<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="JHN" stage="Final" version="B">
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">Yohanis</p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Lii Lolo Be'a nèti Lamatua Yesus<bt>The Lord Yesus' Good Story</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">madhutu sasuri<bt>according to the writing of</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">Yohanis<bt>Yohanis</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yesus èèna, cee?<bt>Who is (this) Yesus?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1" />Dhu uru tèka, abhu mema le Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua.<bt>In the beginning, God's Words/Message (doublet) already was/existed [NOTE: could also be read as ‘pre-existed’].</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Lii Holo-Nori Ama Lamatua ne'e, nuka Dhèu èci.<bt>God's Words/Message (doublet) were a Person. [NOTE: this makes the higher level cohesion of the Prologue hang together.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu ne'e bera-bera dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>That Person was together with God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa Nèngu ne, Ama Lamatua kahèi.<bt>And He is also God. [Message, Source] [NOTE to daughter translations: avoid sense of /sama ke/ meaning ‘is like’.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="2" />Lod'o liru dènge rai-haha dhae j'aj'i mèka,<bt>When the sky and earth had not yet happened/been created/come into being, [EXEG: TH, Deibler; STYLE: ‘sky and earth’ a doublet that represents the whole cosmos.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Dhèu ne'e abhu mema le sama-sama dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>that Person already existed beforehand together with God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="3" />Lamatua paj'aj'i aa'i mèu-mèu, pake Lii Holo-Nori Nèngu ne'e ka.<bt>God2 created/made everything come into being, using that Words/Message (doublet) of His. [EXEG: (Carson): so here: God's Word, understood in the Prologue to be a personal agent, created everything. // Because John is talking about creation, it's better to not force the Person from vs.1, but go back to Word.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Abhu boe ngaa èci sa dhu j'aj'i, ladhe Dhèu ne'e tao boe.<bt>There is not one thing which came into being, if that Person did not make/do it.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="4" />Nèngu ne, kapua mamuri.<bt>He (that one) is the root/source of life.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">De dhèu dhu abhu mamuri dhu lèke,<bt>So (consequently), people who get true/real life,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">rèngu mamuri nèti Nèngu ka.<bt>they live from Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu èci èèna ka dènge Saraa dhu pasaraa,<bt>He is also like Light which shines,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka dhèu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara Saraa ne'e,<bt>so that people who live in that Light,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">bisa rèdhi dènge mèu.<bt>can see clearly (can also imply understand).</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="5" />Saraa ne, heo madhore maroga;<bt>That Light, shines piercing the darkness;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhore"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-01 00:44:38Z" status="Anyone">tembus</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa maroga bisa boe pa'abhe Saraa ne.<bt>and (the) darkness is not able to restrain/hold back/impede that Light.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pahèbe "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-01 00:43:12Z" status="Anyone">pele</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">Te Saraa ne heo taruu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) that Light keeps shining.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Abhu dhèu leo èci, ngara na Yohanis. Ama Lamatua pua-paleha ne kahèi,<bt>There was another/different person, named Yohanis. God also sent/commissioned him, [NOTE: ‘another/different man’ is necessary to distinguish from the person talked about in v1-5.]</bt><note reference="1:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 3:1, Markus 1:4, Lukas 3:1-2</note><v n="7" />sèna ka j'aj'i sakasii ho lole dènge dhèu lula-nèti Saraa ne. Ho sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa parcaya Lamatua, lula lii padhai Yohanis ne.<bt>to be/become a witness who tells people about that Light. So that everyone can believe in God2/the Lord, because of what Yohanis had to say.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Yohanis ne, bukan Saraa èèna. Te ngaa Lamatua pua ne ho la'e peka-padhai dènge dhèu lula-nèti Saraa ne.<bt>This Yohanis was not that Light. But God2 sent/commissioned him to tell people about that Light.</bt><v n="9" />Te Dhèu dhu j'aj'i Saraa tare'a-re'a èèna, neo mai asa rai-haha ne. Saraa ne'e ka dhu d'elo pamèu-mèu j'ara-j'ara hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Cuz (elaboration), that Person who was the real/true Light, was going to come to this world. That Light reveals/makes to become visible true things/matters to everyone/all people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Masi ka Nèngu tao nare aa'i mèu-mèu ngaa-ngaa ètu rai-haha ne, te ngaa dhèu ètu rai-haha tadhe boe Ne, lod'o Na pea ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>Even though He had made everything that is in the world come into being, nevertheless people in this world did not know/recognise Him when he lived in this world.</bt><v n="11" />Masi ka Nèngu mai pea dènge dhèu unu Na, te ngaa dhèu se'e ro'o boe sèmi rare Ne.<bt>Even though He came to live with His own people, nevertheless these people did not want to accept/receive Him.</bt><v n="12" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa ladhe dhèu sèmi rare aa parcaya Ne, Nèngu hia si hak sèna ka j'aj'i ana-ana Ama Lamatua.<bt>Even that being the case, nevertheless everyone who accepts/receives and believes (in) Him, He gives them the right (loan) to be/become God's children. [Mar 2011: revised to better reflect Gk referents.]</bt><v n="13" />Èèna nuka sèmi rara iisi hari rèngu. Te ngaa rara iisi hiu ne, sama boe dènge bhèni rara iisi ana. Aa nèti boe dad'èi dhèu mone dhu neo abhu kolo. Te rèngu j'aj'i ana-ana Ama Lamatua, lula Lamatua pangèd'u si mamuri hiu.<bt>That's the same as if they had been born again. But that new birth of theirs, is not like a woman giving birth to a child. And it is not from one man who wants to get descendants (lit: tips). Cuz (elaboration) they become God2's children, because God2 is the one who grants them new life. [EXEG: Carson, NLT, HCE; NOTE: /turunan/ forces direct biological descent and avoids adoption the /anak/ can carry.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14" />Hèia, &lt;<span class="Italic">Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua</span>&gt; ne,<bt>So, <span class="Italic">&lt;God2's Words/Message&gt;</span> (that I have been referring to),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">rara iisi Ne j'aj'i dhèu rai-haha.<bt>was born as a human.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu mamuri ètu talora aae èdhi.<bt>He lived in our-inc midst.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Èdhi ladhe tèdhi dadedha Na.<bt>We could/were able to see His *glory/high-ness</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dadedha Na sèmi èèna, lula Nèngu ne Ana mesa Ama Lamatua.<bt>His glory like that, was because He was/is God's only Child. [NOTE: here if say Ana Mone mesa, has implications that he is the only son, but there are daughters.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Nèngu d'èi pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na mi èdhi,<bt>He likes to/often shows His goodness/kindness/grace/generosity to us-inc,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula d'ara Na sèmi èèna ka.<bt>because His insides/character/characteristic/nature is really like that.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa aa'i-aa'i dhu Na peka-padhai lula-nèti Ama Lamatua, lèke tare'a-re'a.<bt>And everything which He tells about God is really true.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Yohanis ne, lole lula-nèti Dhèu ne'e ka. Na rodhe, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nanene, ee! Nèngu ne'e ka dhu ja'a lole èèna, peka na, &lt;Bèli-camèd'a Dhèu èci mai. Nèngu ne, kapai risi eele nèti ja'a. Lod'o dhu dhae rara iisi mèka ja'a ne, Nèngu dhu mema-mema le!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>That Yohanis, told about this Person. He shouted out, saying, “Listen, ee! He (this one) is the one I have been telling/narrating, saying, ‘Later a Person is going to come. He is greater/more incredible/ more amazing than I. Before I was born, He already existed before that!’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Yohanis padhai lii sèmi èèna, lula Dhèu ne d'èi titu kèna pad'elo d'ara hua iia Na. Aa Na tao taruu-taruu sèmi èèna hia mi èdhi.<bt>Yohanis spoke like that, because that Person really likes to show His goodness/kindness/grace/generosity. And He keeps doing that over and over to us-inc. [NLT, CEV]</bt><v n="17" />Uru-uru sèra, Musa ka dhu papuru Atora Ama Lamatua mi bèi-baki èdhi. Te ngaa lod'o limuri ne, Dhèu ne, nuka Yesus Kristus ka dhu pad'elo d'ara hua iia Ama Lamatua mi èdhi. Aa aa'i-aa'i dhu Na lole lula-nèti Ama Lamatua, lèke mola-mola.<bt>Long ago, grandfather/forefather Musa is the one who handed down God's Regulations/Law to our-inc ancestors (doublet). But now, that Person (that I have been referring to), who is Yesus Kristus, is the one who show/reveals God's goodness/kindness/grace/generosity to us-inc. And everything that He tells/explains about God, is really true/straight.</bt><v n="18" />Abhu mèka ca dhèu sa hèi dhu rèdhi Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa Ana Pasue Mone mesa Na èèna ka dhu pad'elo mi èdhi, d'ara Ama Lamatua. Ana ne, ètu baboa Ama Na. Te Nèngu ne, nuka Ama Lamatua kahèi.<bt>There has never been one person who has seen God. But His only Child whom He loves, is the one who shows us God's insides/character/heart. That Child is at His Father's side. Cuz (elaboration) He is also God. [NOTE: same as last clause in vs.1, except for connector.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis tuka sarani peka-padhai lula-nèti Lamatua Yesus<bt>Yohanis the Habitual *Baptiser speaks (doublet) about the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 3:1-12; Markus 1:1-8; Lukas 3:1-18)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ca tèka, ama-ama dhèu Yahudi ètu kota Yerusalem pua pèri-pèri ama agama, dènge pèri-pèri dhèu nèti suku Lewi dhu tema lalau-lalo'o ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua. Hèia rèngu lasi asa cabèka loko Yarden<bt>One time, the Yahudi people's fathers/leaders in Yerusalem sent/commissioned several *priests (heads of religion), and several people from the Lewi tribe who normally serve/minister (doublet) in the *Temple (God's Main House of Worship). They went to the other/far side of the Yarden river</bt><note reference="1:19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Era dhu Yohanis sarani dhèu ne, rare nèti ayat 28.<bt>The place where Yohanis was baptising people is taken from verse 28.</bt></note>sèna ka karèi Yohanis tuka sarani, na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne'e ka, Kristus dhu Ama Lamatua padhadha tèke neo hia mai èèna, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>to ask Yohanis the Habitual *Baptiser, saying, “Are you Kristus, who God promised to send?” [NOTE on ‘the Jews’: see Carson, &amp; Terry Schram's dissertation “The use of ‘the Jews’ in the fourth gospel”; DISCOURSE: For background-foreground, location here from verse 28]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia na peka dènge dhèu se, nèngu ne, cee.<bt>So he told them who he was.</bt><v n="20" />Yohanis peka mola-mola, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o. Ja'a ne, Kristus boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yohanis said openly, saying, “No. I am not Kristus.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka ra karèi hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, èu ne, cee? Elia, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>So they asked again/further, saying, “If that's the case, who are you? Gf Elia, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, “Not (him) either.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ra tatu'i hari, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tao-tao èu ne, dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua dhu Na padhadha tèka èèna, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 they asked/interrogated further, saying, “Perhaps/Could it be that you are that *spokesperson of God2's that He promised2 beforehand, right?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tatu'i"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-01 01:52:34Z" status="Anyone">cari-tau tarus-tarus; ondersuuk, interogasi</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, “Not (him) either.”</bt><note reference="1:21" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 18:15, 18, Meliaki 4:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka dhèu se karèi hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, èu ne, cee? Peka ku laa! Te ji'i lèpa, aa hud'i peka ku dènge ama-ama dhu pua ji'i mai!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then1 these people asked further, saying, “If that's the case, then who are you? Tell us [+light imperative]! Cuz (elaboration) we-exc must go back and report to the leaders who sent/commissioned us here!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Hèia na peka madhutu ngaa dhu Yesaya suri tèke, na,<bt>Then2 he spoke according to what Gf Yesaya had previously written, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, nuka dhèu dhu pa'oo-parodha ètu d'ara mamoo, dhu peka na,<bt>“I am that person who shouts out (doublet) in the empty place, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">&lt;Dhèu aa'i-aa'i hud'i pa'èra mema, sèna ka pabe'a j'ara,<bt>‘All people must prepare to make good/fix the way/path,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">ho sèmi mere mamai Lamatua!<bt>to receive the Lord/God2's coming!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Pamera j'ara ho soru Ne.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Make flat/smooth the path to greet Him.’” [Same as Mark 1:3, structured as parallelism.]</bt><note reference="1:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 40:3</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ètu talora aae dhèu dhu mai nèti Yerusalem se'e, abhu kahèi pèri-pèri dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi.<bt>Among those people who came from Yerusalem, there were also several people from the Farisi religious party.</bt><v n="25" />Dhèu se karèi Yohanis, na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ladhe èu ne Kristus boe, Elia boe, aa dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua èèna boe, nga tao ka èu sarani dhèu? Èu abhu hak nèti mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>These people asked Yohanis, saying, “It's like this. If you are not Kristus, not Elia, and not that (known) *spokesperson of God2's, why are you *baptising people? From where do get the right/authority?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ka Yohanis b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, sarani dhèu dhoka pake èi di. Te ngaa abhu le ca Dhèu ètu talora aae miu dhu miu tadhe boe.<bt>So Yohanis responded, saying, “I baptise people just using water. But there already is a Person in your-pl midst whom you do not know/recognise.</bt><v n="27" />Nèngu èèna kapai risi nèti ja'a, masi ka ja'a aj'a-nori uuru dhèu. J'aj'i ènu Na, ja'a nia boe sa hèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>He is greater/more amazing/more incredible than I, even though I began to teach (doublet) people first/before him. To be/become His slave, I am not equal/worthy.” [NOTE to daughter translations: Ftn same as in Mark 1:7, but omitting “stoop to”.]</bt><note reference="1:27" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu lii Yunani dhu uru tèka, peka na, &lt;&lt;lècu dhari salapa na, ja'a nia boe sa hèi.&gt;&gt; Sasoa na Yohanis dhèu haha. Masi ka j'aj'i ènu nèti Lamatua Yesus di, nia boe sa hèi.<bt>The original/oldest Greek language writing says, &lt;&lt;to undo his shoe/sandal strap, I am not worthy.&gt;&gt; It's meaning is that Yohanis was just a low person (social status). Even.if he just became Lord Yesus' slave, he wasn't fitting/appropriate/worthy.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />J'ara se aa'i-aa'i ra j'aj'i ètu Betania, ètu cabèka loko Yarden. Yohanis dènge ana-ana madhutu na aa'i-aa'i, sarani dhèu ètu era èèna.<bt>All these things happened in Betania, on the other side of the Yarden river. Yohanis and his underlings/followers/*disciples were baptising people there. [EXEG: leave open the option of village or region.]</bt><note reference="1:28" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">&lt;Betania&gt; ne, leo nèti rae Betania dhu padètu dènge kota Yerusalem. Te ngaa era èèna, re'a mèu boe ètu mia. Dhèu d'èlu-mèu pangee na Betania ne, nuka rai Basan ètu sebhe dhimu dano Galilea, te Yosefus suri ngara era &lt;Batanea&gt; kahèi. Yosefus ne, dhèu Yahudi dhu suri sejara Isra'el hia dhèu paredha Roma.<bt>This &lt;Betania&gt; is different from the village of Betania which is quite close to the city of Yerusalem. But its location isn't clear. Knowledgable people (=experts) think that it is probably the same as the region of Basan, on the east side of lake Galilea, cuz (elaboration) Yosefus also wrote that that place had the name &lt;Batanea&gt;. This Yosefus (that we are referring to) was a Yahudi person who wrote the history of Israel for the Roma government.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus sama sèmi Ana Kahib'i-kalèbho Ama Lamatua<bt>The Lord Yesus is like God's *Lamb (sheep offspring)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Asa bèli èèna, Yohanis ladhe nèdhi Yesus kako mai asa nèngu. Hèia na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ku Dhèu nèi! Nèngu èèna ka, Ana Kahib'i-kalèbho Ama Lamatua dhu j'aj'i korban, sèna ka saku eele sasala-sasigo dhèu ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>The next day, Yohanis saw Yesus walking towards him. He said, “Have a look at that Person over there (yonder)! He is God's *Lamb (sheep offspring; they have sheep on Rote, the next island over; their word for sheep is a doublet which includes the word for goat) who becomes a *sacrifice (loan) to *wipe away the wrongs (doublet) of the people of this world.</bt><v n="30" />Dhèu ne'e ne ka dhu ja'a peka le dènge miu med'a, na, &lt;Bèli-camèd'a abhu ca Dhèu dhu cèu mai. Nèngu kapai risi nèti ja'a, lula Nèngu karèi uru j'ara nèti ja'a.&gt;<bt>This Person is the one I was telling you-pl about yesterday, saying, ‘Later a Person will appear/come. He is greater/more impressive than I, because He already existed before me.’ [Note to daughter translations: If Gk was /gar/, then it should be KM /te/. But Gk is /hoti/ which is a stronger, asserted reason, so is rendered /tagal/ ‘because’ here.]</bt><v n="31" />Uru èèna, ja'a ke'a mèka, na, Nèngu ne, Kristus. Masi ka sèmi èèna, ja'a ke'a le, na, ja'a hud'i patadhe Ne dènge dhèu Isra'el aa'i-aa'i. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a mai ho sarani dhèu pake èi.<bt>Previously, I did not know that He is/was Kristus. Even that being the case, I already knew I must introduce/make Him known to all the people of Isra'el. Because of that, I came/have come to baptise people using water. [EXEG: (Carson): “does not mean that John did not know Jesus at all, but only that he did not know him as the Coming One.”]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32-33" />Ama Lamatua pua ja'a sèna ka sarani dhèu pake èi. Na peka dènge ja'a kahèi, na, &lt;Èèna na Dhèu èci mai asa èu. Èle èèna, Roh Ja'a puru mai asa Nèngu. Dhèu èèna ka dhu bèli-camèd'a nèti Roh Ja'a dhu Mola-Mèci, sèna ka pangèd'u koasa mi dhèu Ja'a.&gt; Lod'o Dhèu ne mai, ja'a tadhe mèka Ne. Te ngaa ropa ladhe kèdhi Roh Lamatua puru mai nèti sorga nuka sèmi koro j'aha, hèia pea ètu Nèngu, ka ja'a heka tadhe Nèngu, na, &lt;Nèngu èèna, kèna!&gt;<bt>God sent/commissions me to baptise people using water. He also told me, saying, ‘Later a Person is going to come to you-sg. Then My Spirit will descend coming on/to Him. That Person is the one who will bring/bear/carry/deliver My *Holy/Clean/Pure Spirit, to give/grant/present power/authority to My people.’ When that Person came, I didn't yet recognise Him. But when I saw God2's Spirit descend coming from the sky like a dove, then stay on/in Him, only.then did I recognise Him, saying/that, ‘This is Him!&gt; [DISCOURSE: Quote margin in the Greek violates local RL discourse structure. In other books we've also had to get rid of similar quote margins. Quote margins imply a change of speaker here.]</bt><v n="34" />Ja'a kèdhi j'ara se dènge musi madha ja'a unu ku. Ka ja'a lole dènge miu, na, &lt;Dhèu dhu mai èèna, Ana Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>I saw that matter with my very own eyes. [DISCOURSE: High level evidential statement.] So I am telling you-pl, ‘That Person who is coming there, that is God's Child!’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pili nare ana madhutu dhu partama<bt>The Lord Yesus chooses His first *disciples/followers</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Asa bèli èèna, Yohanis dhu titu dènge ana madhutu na, dhèu dua.<bt>The following day, Yohanis was standing with two of his *disciples.</bt><v n="36" />Ropa Yohanis ladhe nèdhi Yesus kako re era èèna, ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ku laa! Te Nèngu ne ka Ana Kahib'i-Kalèbho Ama Lamatua dhu bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i korban!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yohanis saw Yesus walking by there, he told/explained, saying, “Have a look [+light imperative]! Cuz (elaboration) He (there, definite, specific) is God's Lamb who will become a *sacrifice!”</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01660b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Hèia ana madhutu Yohanis dhèu dua dhu tadèngi lii padhai na, tèke eele ne, ho lasi madhutu Yesus.<bt>Then Yohanis' two disciples who heard what he was saying, left him to go following Yesus.</bt><v n="38" />Ka Yesus kabib'a asa kabodho, hèia ladhe nèdhi si, na, rèngu madhutu Ne. Hèia Na karèi si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia? Parluu, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus turned, and saw that they were following Him. So He asked them, saying, “How about it? Do you need something? (=idiomatic way of saying “What do you want?”)”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa dua ra karèi ne, <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Rabi </span>pea ètu mia?&gt;&gt; (Ètu d'ara lii Aram rèngu, <span class="Italic">&lt;Rabi&gt;</span> sasoa na, &lt;Ama Mese&gt;.)<bt>The two of them asked Him, saying, “Where does <span class="Italic">Rabi</span> (=you) live/stay?” (In their Aram language, <span class="Italic">Rabi</span> means, ‘Father Teacher’.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ka Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Mai sèna ka mèdhi unu mi.&gt;&gt; Hèia lasi madhutu Ne, ka rèdhi era pea Na. Rèngu d'ai nèi, pe d'ara hake èpa nihia sa. Ka ra pea dènge Ne toke d'ai lod'o cèna.<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying, “Just come and see for yourselves.” So they followed/accompanied Him, and saw the place where He stayed/lived. When they arrived yonder (remote), it was around 4 o'clock in the afternoon. So/then they stayed with Him until the sun went down. [EXEG: although Morris says “and probably means that they spent the night with him.” which makes good sense the way the verse is constructed and situationally, unfortunately there is not strong additional support, and is by inference. So we take the safer interpretation of just being together through the remaining daylight hours.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Nèti rèngu dua ra dhu tadèngi lii padhai Yohanis, ka lasi dènge madhutu Yesus, èci ngara na Anderias. Nèngu ne, ari Simon Petrus.<bt>From those two people who heard what Yohanis said, and then followed Yesus, one was named Anderias. He was Simon Petrus' younger brother.</bt><v n="41" />Ropa d'ai èmu, ka Anderias la'e dènge tenge a'a na Simon, ka na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'a, ee! Ji'i paraga le dènge <span class="Italic">Mesias!&gt;&gt; </span>(Madhutu lii rèngu, <span class="Italic">&lt;Mesias&gt;</span> sasoa na, &lt;Kristus, nuka Dhèu dhu Lamatua padhadha tèke karèi nèti uru ka, ho neo hia mai.&gt;)<bt>Upon returning home, Anderias (first thing) went to look for his older brother Simon, saying, “Older brother, ee! We-exc have met with the <span class="Italic">Mesias!</span>” (In their language, <span class="Italic">‘Mesias’</span> means, ‘Kristus, that is the Person whom God2 has promised beforehand from long ago to send coming.’)</bt><v n="42" />Ka Anderias lere nèti a'a na asa Yesus.<bt>Then Anderias brought/escorted his older brother to Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus ladhe nèdhi ne, ka Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, Simon. Ama mu, ka Yohanis. Mulai nèti doe ne'e dhèu paroa èu, <span class="Italic">&lt;Kefas&gt;</span>&gt;&gt; (&lt;Kefas&gt;, èci èèna ka dènge &lt;Petrus&gt;, sasoa na &lt;hadhu&gt;.)<bt>And Yesus looked at him, and spoke, saying, “You are Simon. Your father is Yohanis. Beginning now people will call you, <span class="Italic">‘Kefas’”</span> (‘Kefas’ is the same as ‘Petrus’, meaning ‘rock’.)</bt><note reference="1:42" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ngara <span class="Italic">Kefas </span>ne, nèti lii Aram <span class="Italic">kefa</span>. Sasoa na &lt;hadhu&gt;. Ngara <span class="Italic">Petrus, </span>nèti lii Yunani <span class="Italic">petra.</span> Sasoa na &lt;hadhu&gt; kahèi.<bt>The name <span class="Italic">Kefas</span> is from the Aram language <span class="Italic">kefa.</span> It means ‘rock’. The name <span class="Italic">Petrus</span> is from the Yunani language <span class="Italic">petra.</span> It also means ‘rock’.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus paroa nare Pelipus dènge Natanel<bt>The Lord Yesus calls/summons Pelipus and Natanel</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43-44" />Ètu era èèna, abhu dhèu leo èci, ngara na Pelipus. Rae èta-èsu na Betsaida. Petrus dènge Anderias nèti rae èèna kahèi.<bt>There, there was also another person, name Pelipus. His village of origin (doublet) was Betsaida. Petrus and Anderias were also from that village.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Asa bèli èèna, Yesus neo la'e asa propensi Galilea. Hèia Na la'e paraga dènge Pelipus, ka Na gale ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai madhutu Ja'a sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu Ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>The next day, Yesus wanted to go to the province of Galilea. And He went to meet Pelipus, and summoned/invited him, saying, “Come on, follow Me and be/become My person!” [EXEG: NLT, CONNOT, Carson]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ka Pelipus la'e tenge Natanel, hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Angalai, ee! Ji'i paraga le dènge Dhèu dhu Musa suri tèke ètu d'ara Atora Lamatua. Dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua uru-uru sèra suri kahèi lula-nèti Dhèu ne'e ne. Dhèu ne, ngara na Yesus, nèti rae Nasaret. Ama Na, ngara na Yusuf.&gt;&gt;<bt>So/then Pelipus went to look for Natanel, and told him, saying, “Brother/cousin/friend, ee! We-exc have met that Person who Gf Musa has written about in God2's Regulations/Law. God2's spokespeople from long ago also wrote about this Person. His name is Yesus, from the village of Nasaret. His father is named Yusuf.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Te ngaa Natanel dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu Nasaret!? Abhu boe j'ara hua iia èci sa dhu cèu nèti nèi, nga!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Natanel responded, saying, “A Nasaret person!? There is not anything good that comes out of there, nga! [+objection]”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Pelipus lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Baku sèmi èèna. Lati ho mèdhi unu mu!&gt;&gt;<bt>And Pelipus said, “Wee! Don't be like that. Come on and see for yourself!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Ropa Natanel kako mai, Yesus ladhe nèdhi le, ka Na peka, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne dhèu d'ara mola! Te d'ara na dhu ne'a boe pakapod'e. Nèngu ne, dhèu Isra'el tare'a-re'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>When Natanel was walking toward [Him], Yesus saw him straightaway/beforehand, and said, “He here is an honest/straight person! Cuz (elaboration) his insides know no deceit/twisting. He here is a true/genuine/authentic Isra'el person!”</bt><note reference="1:47" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu ne'e Yesus karihu lii. Te lod'o Ama Lamatua hia mèka ngara &lt;Isra'el&gt; mi Yakob, sasoa ngara Yakob èèna, &lt;dhèu monya&gt;. (Ladhe ètu <span class="Italic">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka</span> 27:1-40, 32:22-32.) Madhutu a'abhu Yesus ètu ne'e, na, Natanel ne dhèu Isra'el leko-leo nèti Yakob. Te Natanel ne, dhèu d'ara mola.<bt>Yesus is making a word play here. Cuz (elaboration) when God had not yet given the name ‘Israel’ to Yakob, the name Yakob meant ‘habitual deceiver’. (Look at <span class="Italic">Story of Beginnings</span> 27:1-40, 32:22-32.) Yesus' meaning here is that this Natanel is an Israel person of a different model/type/kind than Yakob. Cuz (elaboration) this Natanel is a straight/righteous/honest person.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Ka Natanel karèi, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka Ama tadhe ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>Natanel asked, “How is it that Father/You knows/recognises me?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ja'a kèdhi le èu, ropa èu dhu ae ètu mamaho aj'u èèna.<bt>Yesus responded2, saying, “It's like this. I already saw you when you were resting/taking a break under (the shade of) that tree.</bt><note reference="1:48" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Idhonesia peka na, &lt;aj'u ara&gt;, madhutu lii Yunani <span class="Italic">sukei.</span> Te ngaa Alkitab peka mi aj'u èci ètu nèi dhu dhèu ra'a hua na. Ètu Idhonesia cabèka dhimu dhèu ra'a boe hua &lt;ara&gt;. De aj'u ara ètu d'ara Alkitab lii Idhonesia sama boe dènge aj'u ara ètu ne'e.<bt>Bahasa Indonesia uses the word ‘ara tree’ for the Yunani term <span class="Italic">sukei.</span> But the Bible designates a tree from there (remote) which people usually eat its fruit. In Indonesia eastern side, people do not eat ‘ara tree's’ fruit. So, ‘ara tree’ in the Indonesian Bible, is not the same as our-inc ara tree here.</bt></note>Lod'o èèna, Pelipus dhae dhiu mèka paroa èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, Pelipus had not yet called/summoned you.” [NOTE to daughter translations: footnote is same as in Mark 11:13.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Hèia Natanel dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese ne, tatu Ana Ama Lamatua! Aa tatu Ama Dhèu Aae ji'i dhèu Isra'el kahèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>So/then Natanel achnowledged/confessed, saying, “Father Teacher, surely (you) are God's Child! And You are also surely the King of the people of Israel!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Yesus karèi ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tao-tao èu ne lèka Ja'a, lula deo na Ja'a peka na, &lt;Ja'a ladhe kèdhi èu, ropa èu dhu ae ètu mamaho aj'u èèna,&gt; si? Sanèd'e, te bèli-camèd'a pe èu mèdhi j'ara-j'ara dhu kapai risi eele hari!<bt>Yesus asked him, saying, “Perhaps you believe Me, because I just said, ‘I already saw you when you resting were under that tree,’ right? Remember, later you will see matters that are even greater/more amazing/more incredible!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />Tare'a! Ja'a peka mema. Bèli-camèd'a miu ladhe mèdhi liru bhoke tèke. Hèia ana-ana pajuu Lamatua ètu sorga ca'e-puru re baboa Ja'a. Te Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>That's right! I'm telling you this directly/beforehand. Later you-pl will see the sky opened. And God2's *angels (underlings in/from heaven) descending-ascending at My side. And I here, am the *Son of Man (Authentic/Ideal Human).” [EXEG: Carson] [DISCOURSE: Quote margin in the Greek violates local RL discourse structure. In other books we've also had to get rid of similar quote margins. Quote margins imply a change of speaker here.]</bt><note reference="1:51" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu <span class="Italic">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka</span> 28:10-17, Yakob dhu nii ètu Betel. Ètu d'ara nii ne'e ladhe nèdhi ana-ana pajuu Ama Lamatua ca'e-puru langa èci dhu Yakob pangare na, &lt;&lt;hèb'a èmu asa sorga&gt;&gt;.<bt>In <span class="Italic">Story of Beginnings</span> 28:10-17, Yakob has a dream at Betel. In his dream, he sees God's *angels descending-ascending on a ladder that Yakob refers to as “the door/gate to heaven”.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Pesta kab'i ètu rae Kana<bt>Wedding feast/festival in the village of Kana</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Asa camèd'a èèna, dhèu tao pesta kab'i ètu rae Kana, propensi Galilea. Aa ina Yesus ètu èèna kahèi.<bt>The day after next [today = 1, tomorrow = 2, day after = 3], there was a wedding feast/festival/celebration in the village of Kana in the province of Galilea. And Yesus' mother went there. [EXEG: ‘third day’ see discussion in Carson. NLT ‘next day’ and CEV ‘three days later’ are both incorrect.]</bt><v n="2" />Ra nèru Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na kahèi, ka rèngu lasi.<bt>Yesus and his *disciples (underlings/followers) also got invited. So they also went.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ètu d'ara pesta kab'i ne, nèbhu boe ka èi anggor èle. Hèia ina Yesus la'e peka dènge Ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Soru-bara si ku laa! Te èi anggor rèngu èle le.&gt;&gt;<bt>But during the wedding celebration, eventually the wine (assimilated loan: liquid of grapes [local tapping of palm tress, this ‘liquid’ can be juice or mildly alcoholic) began to run out. So/then Yesus' mother told Him, saying, “Help (doublet) out! Cuz (elaboration) their wine is already running out.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ina. Nga tao ka ina Ku neo sèna ka Ja'a ka ator? Te lod'o Ja'a dhae d'ai mèka.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus responded, saying, “Mother. Why do you want me to handle it/arrange/ manage/fix/put in order? Cuz (elaboration) My time is not yet arrived.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Te ngaa ina Na peka dènge dhèu sab'a ètu sèra, na, &lt;&lt;Nanene! Ladhe Na pua miu tao ngaa, na, mi tao madhutu laa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But His mother told the workers there, saying, “Listen! Whatever He orders you-pl to do, na, just go along with it/do accordingly.”</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01667b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ètu era èèna, abhu g'ala èna bua dhu dhèu tao nèti hadhu. G'ala cue, isi na pe d'ai pidhu nguru lèmi toke cangasu canguru lèmi liter èi. Dhèu Yahudi tema dhui èi nèti g'ala se ho pamèu ngi'u ra madhutu atora agama ra.<bt>There, there were six jars/jugs/basins, which people made from stone. One of those jugs could liquid.hold about 75-115 liters. Yahudi people normally used water from jugs of that sort to clean/purify themselves according to their religious regulations. [Quantity: NLT note.]</bt><v n="7" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge dhèu sab'a se, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lami mere èi, ho isi papènu g'ala se.&gt;&gt; Ka ra isi toke pènu oe bua eele.<bt>Then Yesus told those workers, saying, “Go fetch water to fill these jugs.” Then2 they filled them until full flat (=to the brim/about to overflow).</bt><v n="8" />Ka Na peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Dhui mere ciki, ho mèti asa lamatua tatao.&gt;&gt; Hèia dhèu sab'a se madhutu kahèi.<bt>Then2 He told them, saying, “Dip/scoop out a little, to take to the master of the feast [NOTE: also a local category here].” Then1 the workers did accordingly.</bt><v n="9" />Ropa lamatua pesta sèmi nare, ka na ngao. Te ngaa re'a rare boe, èi ne dhu j'aj'i le anggor! Dhèu ne malaa, te ne'a boe, na, dhèu se abhu anggor ne nèti mia. (Te ngaa dhèu sab'a se re'a.)<bt>When the master of the feast received it, then he tasted it. But contrary to expectation that water had already become wine! The man was confused, cuz (elaboration) he didn't know where they had gotten that wine from. (But those workers knew.)</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ngao"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-01 04:15:19Z" status="Anyone">cicipi (cair), sip;</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na paroa nare pengantin dhèu mone.<bt>So/then he called/summoned the bridegroom.</bt><v n="10" />Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Dhu tema le, lamatua èmu hia uuru ku anggor dhu be'a risi. Ladhe dhèu rinu ae ku, heka hia anggor dhu ako karehe kèna. Te ngaa èu tao leo. Èu hia uuru anggor dhu ako karehe, heka limuri dhu be'a risi!&gt;&gt;<bt>And he said, “It's like this. Normally the master of the house gives out the best wine first. If/when people have already drunk alot, only.then does he bring out the wine that's a bit not good/not so good. But you-sg have done differently. You gave out the not-so-good wine first, and only later on the best wine!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />J'ara ne j'aj'i ètu rae Kana, propensi Galilea. Ne'e ne heka hiu-hiu kèna Yesus tao tadha malaa dhu dhèu bisa rèdhi dènge musi madha ra. Na pad'elo dadedha Na sèmi èèna, ka ana madhutu Na parcaya Ne.<bt>That event/thing/issue happened in the village of Kana, in the province of Galilea. It was the first time Yesus did an *amazing sign (=miracle) which people could see with their eyeballs. He showed his glory/high-ness like that, and His *disciples believed in/trusted Him. [STYLE: Framed as high-level evidential, validating the event as historical.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus, ina Na, ari dènge ana madhutu Na sèra, puru lasi asa kota Kapernaum. Te ngaa rèngu pea dhoka pèri lod'o di ètu èèna.<bt>After that, then Yesus, His mother, younger siblings and His *disciples descended to the city of Kapernaum. But they only stayed there for several/a few days.</bt><note reference="2:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 4:13</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus babège eele dhèu nèti Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua<bt>The Lord Yesus evicts people from *God's *Temple (Main House of Worship/Prayer)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 21:12-13; Markus 11:15-17; Lukas 19:45-46)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ropa oe dètu dènge lod'o kalela Paska dhèu Yahudi, Yesus ca'e la'e asa kota Yerusalem.<bt>When the Yahudi people's feast day/holiday Paska was very near, Yesus went up to the city of Yerusalem.</bt><note reference="2:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 12:1-27</note><v n="14" />Ètu madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, Yesus ladhe nèdhi dhèu pahia sapi, kahib'i-kalèbho, dènge koro j'aha dhu dhèu hèli ho j'aj'i korban. Ètu era ne'e, abhu kahèi dhèu dhu madhèdi ètu mei ho pasilu doi dhu ra pake hia mi Ama Lamatua ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i èèna.<bt>In the *Temple yard, Yesus saw people were selling cows, sheep (doublet), and doves/pidgeons which people bought to use as *sacrifices (assimilated loan). There, there were also people who sat at tables to exchange money that was used to give to God at that Temple.</bt><v n="15" />Hèia Yesus nare dhari pèri-pèri loa ho Na èpi j'aj'i sèmi gui sa. Ka Na babège-lalèta dhèu se'e aa'i-aa'i ra nèti madha Èmu èèna. Nèngu bhabhoo eele sapi, dènge kahib'i-kalèbho sèra kahèi. Na lege eele mei, aa Na ceb'e eele doi sèra kahèi.<bt>Then Yesus took several strands of rope to make/weave into a whip. And He evicted (doublet) all of those people from that yard. He also shooed away the cows and sheep. He overturned the tables, and poured spilling out the money.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="loa "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-02 00:19:31Z" status="Anyone">urat (tali); èpi = pintal, wind, braid</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lege "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-02 00:24:18Z" status="Anyone">tip over, turn over, upend</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Hèia Na pua dhèu pahia koro j'aha sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mèti sa li'u manu-bhui dènge karogo ra sèra nèti ne'e! Ne'e, era pahia-pahèli boe! Baku tao Èmu Ama Ku, j'aj'i mi era d'aga!&gt;&gt;<bt>And He ordered the people who sold the doves, saying, “Take these birds and their cages away from here! This place here is not a selling-buying place (=market)! Don't make My Father's House become a place of commerce!” [EXEG: things = birds and their cages. Ex.Helps, TRT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ka ana madhutu Na ngee rèdhi Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua dhu suri, peka na,<bt>And His disciples thought about/remembered2 the *Scriptures (God2's Holy/Clean Writings) which wrote/were written, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Ja'a sue Èmu Ama Ku titu kèna.<bt>“I dearly/ deeply/ intensely love My Father's House.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti èèna ka, d'ara Ja'a èra ho j'aga ngara be'a Èmu èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why my insides are strong to guard the good name/reputation of that House.” [EXEG: zeal for the house; make sure it is not phrased as God's reputation.]</bt><note reference="2:17" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 69:9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Hèia ama-ama dhèu Yahudi peka dènge Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Èu dènge hak ho babège-lalèta dhèu sèmi ne'e, na, Mu pad'elo tadha malaa èci hia ji'i, sèna ka j'aj'i mi bukti!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the leaders of the Yahudi people ordered Yesus, saying, “If You-sg have the right to evict (doublet) people like that, na, show us-exc an *amazing sign as proof/evidence!” [NOTE on ‘the Jews’: see Carson, &amp; Terry Schram's dissertation “The use of ‘the Jews’ in the fourth gospel”]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka Yesus b'ala si, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu paguri era mola-mèci ne, pe camèd'a èèna, Ja'a patitu kore hari le èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “If you-pl knock down this clean/holy/pure place here, later the day after next, I will raise it again/rebuild it.” [EXEG: discussion in CONNOT for 2:1 &amp; 2:19 for ‘on the third day’. See Carson on /naos/, not the normal word for ‘temple’ here. TH for command vs. conditional--command doesn't fit in these target lgs. NOTE to daughter translations: word for ‘destroy’ needs to collocate both with buildings and with bodies.]</bt><note reference="2:19" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 26:61, 27:40, Markus 14:58, 15:29</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa ra pab'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Abhu ètu mia? Te dhèu patitu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne èpa nguru èna tèu. Tasamia ka, Èu peka na, Èu parluu dhoka tèlu lod'o di, sèna ka patitu more hari?!&gt;&gt;<bt>But they protested, saying, “Where do you get that (=unbelievable)? Cuz (elaboration) people took 46 years to erect/build this Temple. Why do You think that You only need just three days to rebuild it?!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Te ngaa dhèu se'e re'a rare boe, Yesus peka lula-nèti ngi'u Nèngu unu Na, dhu nuka sèmi era mola-mèci.<bt>But they didn't understand that Yesus was talking about His own body, which is like a clean/holy/pure place.</bt><v n="22" />De d'ai lèpa lod'o limuri, ropa Yesus madhe, hèia mamuri hari, heka ana-ana madhutu Na sanèd'e kèna, ngaa dhu Na peka tèke dènge rèngu. Ka ra parcaya ngaa dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua karèi nèti uru-uru ka, dènge ngaa dhu Yesus peka mema dènge rèngu.<bt>So (consequently), later on, when Yesus had died, and then lived again, His disciples only.then remembered what He had told beforehand to them. And they believed what the Scriptures wrote from long ago, and what Yesus had told them beforehand.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus ne'a mèu d'ara dhèu aa'i-aa'i<bt>The Lord Yesus knows everyone's insides/characters/emotions/values</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka Yesus pea taha ètu kota Yerusalem, ho madhutu kalela Paska ètu èèna. Hèia dhèu ae rèdhi tadha-tadha malaa dhu Na tao, ka ra parcaya Ne.<bt>Then Yesus stayed temporarily in the city of Yerusalem to participate in the Paska holiday/festival there. And many people were able to see the various amazing signs that He did, and so they believed (in) Him. [EXEG: believed in his name = 1) believed in Him, 2) believed in his rank (as Messiah) [NLT]; rank is one common sense of Gk ‘name’.]</bt><v n="24-25" />Te ngaa Yesus lèka boe rèngu, lula ne'a mèu d'ara dhèu aa'i-aa'i. Nèngu parluu boe dhèu ho peka dènge Ne, lula Na ne'a mema le mamuri dènge tatao dhèu rai-haha.<bt>But Yesus did not trust2 them, because He knew/knows everyone's insides. He did not need people to tell/explain to Him, because He himself already knew beforehand/directly humans lives/condition and deeds/character (used as doublet together has sense of human ‘nature’. [EXEG: Gk pantas: 1) all (of them), 2) all (of humanity) here is generic ‘humanity’ (Morris, TRT, NLT, The Source, NRSV, CEV, TB); little support for #1 here.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus padhai lii dènge Nikodemus<bt>The Lord Yesus talks with Nikodemus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Abhu ca dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi, ngara na Nikodemus. Nèngu ne, mese aae nèti dhèu Yahudi.<bt>There was a person from the Parisi religious party, named Nikodemus. He was a leading teacher [Dhao /mese aae/ could also be read as ‘professor’] of the Yahudi people [See Carson].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mese aae"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-02 01:08:03Z" status="Anyone">professor</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ca tèka, na mai paraga dènge Yesus re mèda. Hèia na padhai lii dènge Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ji'i nge'a, na, Lamatua ka dhu pua Ama ho aj'a-nori ji'i. Te tadha-tadha malaa dhu Ama tao sèra, pad'elo, na, Lamatua ka dhu pangèd'u koasa mi Ama. Ladhe sèmi boe èèna, tatu tadha malaa se'e bisa boe j'aj'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>One time, he came at night to meet Yesus. And he said, “Father Teacher! We-exc know that God2 is the one who sent/commissioned You to teach (doublet) us-exc. Cuz (elaboration) the various amazing signs that You do show that God2 is the one who has given You power/authority. If that were not the case, surely those amazing signs wouldn't happen/work.” [NLT]</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01670b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a! Aa Ja'a neo peka sèmi ne'e ku: ladhe dhèu rara iisi hari boe ne, nèngu bisa boe j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “That's true! And I want to tell you this: if a person is not born again, s/he cannot be/become God2's person.” [EXEG: while the Greek word is polysemous (1. again, 2. from above), and Jesus seems to be using it with double meaning, Nicodemus clearly understood the ‘again’ sense of the word (In vs.4 he reflects it back with “second time”). So the rendering in this verse has to set up the dialogue in the next verses.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Hèia Nikodemus karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia dhèu dhu kapai le bisa rara iisi hari ne!? Nèngu tatu bisa boe maso hari asa d'ara kabake ina na, sèna ka ina na nara iisi hari ne. Bisa boe, sina ma!?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Nikodemus asked, saying, “How can a person who is already grown be born again like that!? S/he surely cannot enter again into his mother's womb a second time, so that his mother gives birth again to him. That's not likely, right!?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a! Te ngaa Ja'a peka dènge èu sèmi ne'e: dhèu hud'i rara iisi ku re èi sèna ka j'aj'i mèu, aa re roh ho j'aj'i dhèu hiu. Dènge j'ara ne'e, nèngu heka bisa j'aj'i dhèu unu Lamatua kèna.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “True! But I'll tell you this: a person must be born with/by/via water to be/become clean/pure/holy, and be born with/by/via spirit to be/become a new person. In that way, only.then can s/he enter becoming God2's person. [EXEG: see Carson for extensive discussion of various interpretations of “born of water and spirit”, and concludes “a new birth that cleanses and renews”; NET Bible has a more concise note, summarizing the issue. Note: it is “spirit”, not “the Spirit” (no article). See Message.]</bt><v n="6" />Te dhèu rai-haha ne rara iisi nèti dhèu rai-haha, te ngaa roh dhèu rara iisi hiu nèti Roh Ama Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) humans are born from humans, but a person's spirit is reborn/ born anew/ new birth from God's Spirit. [EXEG: NLT, Carson]</bt><v n="7" />Baku malaa ladhe Ja'a peka, na, &lt;Miu hud'i rara iisi hiu ku, ho abhu mamuri hiu.&gt;<bt>Don't be surprised if I tell you, saying, ‘You-pl must be born anew, to get/obtain new life.’</bt><v n="8" />Èdhi pasoro ku dènge lai ngèlu. Te lai ngèlu g'oro madhutu dad'èi na. Èdhi bisa tadèngi lii na, te ngaa te'a boe mai nèti mia, aa la'e asa mia. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu rara iisi hiu nèti Roh Lamatua sama sèmi èèna kahèi. Te èdhi bisa ladhe tèdhi Roh Lamatua tao dhèu j'aj'i hiu, masi ka te'a boe tasa mera mia j'ara èèna bisa j'aj'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>Let's compare [it] with wind. Cuz (elaboration) wind blows following/according to its will/wishes. We-inc can hear its sound, but we don't know it comes from where, and is going to where. Everyone who is born anew from God2's Spirit is also like that. Cuz (elaboration) we-inc can see God2's Spirit has made a person become new, even though we don't understand how that can happen.” [EXEG: Carson, CONNOT, TRT (Carlton).]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka Nikodemus karèi, na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka j'aj'i sèmi èèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Nikodemus asked, saying, “How can that happen/come to be/work?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Yesus b'ala, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne mese aae dhèu Isra'el. Tasamia ka èu me'a boe j'ara se'e?<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “You are the people of Isra'el's important teacher/professor. How is it that you don't understand these things?</bt><v n="11" />Ja'a peka j'ara dhu lèke mola-mola. Ji'i nge'a j'ara se'e. Te ji'i j'aj'i sakasii lula-nèti j'ara-j'ara dhu ngèdhi unu mi. Te ngaa miu sèmi boe lii padhai ji'i.<bt>I am telling what is true. We-exc understand these things. Cuz (elaboration) we-exc are a witness/testifying of various things we have seen ourselves. But you-pl don't accept what we say. [EXEG: Q: who is we? TRT: “It is not clear who 'we (exclus.)' refers to here and there is much disagreement about this, so it is probably best translate 'we' literally. Many Bible scholars think it refers to Jesus and His disciples or followers (as in Jn 9.4). Some others think this is the editorial 'we' that means 'I' (Jesus). Some others think it refers to Christians who were alive at the time that John wrote this book. However, some others think it refers to Jesus and God's prophets, especially John the Baptizer, and a few think it refers to Jesus and His Father and/or the Holy Spirit (see Jn 8.18). It is very likely that Jesus is echoing/repeating Nicodemus' use of 'we' in verse 2.” See also Carson, TH, CONNOT, Ex.Helps. Our protocol is to preserve the ambiguity of the Gk where all the options are acceptable.]</bt><v n="12" />Miu mo'o boe lèka, ropa Ja'a lole lula-nèti j'ara-j'ara dhu j'aj'i ètu rai-haha ne. Ngaa hari ladhe Ja'a lole j'ara-j'ara dhu j'aj'i ètu dedha-liru nèi. Tatu miu asa lèka boe!<bt>You-pl don't want to believe when I tell about things which happen on earth. Let alone/even less if I tell about things which happen in the sky/heaven above. Surely you-pl would believe even less (Lit: even more not believe)!</bt><v n="13" />Abhu boe dhèu èci sa dhu ca'e la'e paraga dènge Ama Lamatua ètu dedha-liru nèi. Dhodhoka Ja'a di, nuka Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, dhu puru mai nèti Nèngu.<bt>There is not one person who has ascended and met with God in heaven yonder (remote). Only Me, that is *Son of Man (True/Authentic Human), who descended here coming from Him. [EXEG: heaven = Jewish circumlocution for God]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Uru-uru sèra ètu d'ara mamoo, Musa kadhoe mege tabaga ci'u ètu kolo aj'u, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu laladhe ne, rèngu abhu mamuri. J'ara sèmi èèna hud'i j'aj'i ku mi dedha Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne. Bèli-camèd'a ra kadhoe Ja'a ètu aj'u,<bt>Long ago in the lonely place (=wilderness), Musa hung a copper/bronze snake on the end/tip of a wood/tree/pole, so everyone could see it and they could be/get *life/saved/rescued (from bad consequences). A thing/event like that must also happen to Me, the True/Authentic Human. They (non-referential) are going to hang Me on a wood/tree/pole, [EXEG: HCE, CONNOT points out inappropriate to mention cross here.]</bt><note reference="3:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 21:4-9</note><v n="15" />sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu parcaya Ja'a abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe.<bt>so that everyone who believes in Me will get *true/real life that never ends.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Te Ama Lamatua sue seli dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne. Nèti èèna ka, Na pua Ja'a, Ana mesa Na mai, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu parcaya Ja'a, cèri eele boe nèti Lamatua. Dènge j'ara ne, rèngu abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God really loves everyone in this world. That is why He sent/commissioned Me, His only Child, so that everyone who believes (in) Me will not be separated off/cut off (completely) from God2. In that way, they can get *true/real life that never ends. [EXEG: Gk word is not “die”, but more sense of “die spiritually/perish”. Problem: neither believers nor non-believers are “completely destroyed” but get eternal life or eternal punishment. Carlton (TRT) notes, “The translation of ‘perish’ should not mean ‘be completely destroyed/annihilated’. You could say ‘be lost (spiritually)’”; HCE “cut off from God”; NRSV, NLT “perish” (church language--zero meaning), CEV “never really die” (unsatisfactory on several counts), TB binasa “be destroyed, annihilated”.]</bt><v n="17" />Lamatua pua boe Ja'a, Ana Na, mai asa rai-haha ne ho pama'ète hahuku dhèu. Te ngaa Na hia Ja'a mai, sèna ka patabuli dhèu nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra.<bt>God2 did not send/commission Me, His Child, to come to this world to decide people's punishment. But He sent2 Me to *save2/release/rescue people from their wrongs (doublet).</bt><v n="18" />Ama Lamatua huku boe dhèu dhu parcaya Ja'a. Te ngaa Nèngu dhu pama'ète nare le hahuku mi dedha dhèu dhu parcaya boe, <span class="Italic">lula</span> rèngu parcaya boe Ja'a, nuka Ana mesa nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>God does not punish people who believe in Me. But He has already decided beforehand the punishment for people who don't believe, <span class="Italic">because</span> that person doesn't believe (in) Me, that is, in God's only Child. [NOTE: heavy, but reflects the meaning bits and style of Gk]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Nuka sèmi ne'e: Lamatua hia le saraa ho pasaraa rai-haha ne. Te ngaa dhèu d'èi risi mamuri ètu d'ara maroga. Rèngu ro'o boe mamuri ètu d'ara saraa lula tatao rèngu dhu lèke boe. Nèti èèna ka, Ama Lamatua neo huku si.<bt>It's like this (Idiom: think of it like this): God2 has given/sent light to shine in this world. But people preferred to live in the dark. They did/do not want to live in the light, because their deeds/what they do is not right/correct. That is why God is going to punish them.</bt><v n="20" />Te dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tatao ra lèke boe, d'èi boe saraa èèna. Rèngu d'èi boe saraa ne d'elo rèngu, sèna ka saraa ne baku pasabhoka bhabhelu-katub'a ra.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) everyone who does what is not right/correct, hates/dislikes that light. They don't like that light shining on them, so that the light doesn't expose their evil (doublet).</bt><v n="21" />Te ngaa dhu tao lèke, rèngu ara mai sèna ka saraa ne d'elo si. Te saraa ne'e ka dhu pad'elo, na, rèngu dhu tao madhutu dad'èi Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>But those who do according to what is right/correct, they come so that the light shines on them. Cuz (elaboration) that light shows that they are doing according to God2's will.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus dènge Yohanis tuka sarani<bt>The Lord Yesus and Yohanis the *Habitual Baptiser</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka Yesus dènge ana madhutu Na sèra kalua nèti kota Yerusalem, te ngaa rèngu pea taha ètu rai Yudea. Ètu era ne'e rèngu sarani dhèu.<bt>Then Yesus and His disciples left the city of Yerusalem, but they stayed temporarily in the region of Yudea. There they *baptised (method neutral) people. [EXEG: Jn. 4:2 says Jesus himself did not baptise, thus 3p subject here. Jerusalem from high-level context + NLT]</bt><v n="23-24" />Lod'o èèna, Herodes si dhae pamaso mèka Yohanis tuka sarani asa d'ara bèdho. Aa Yohanis sarani dhèu ètu rae Ainon, padètu dènge rae Salim, lula abhu èi ae ètu era èèna. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu ae mai asa Yohanis ho na sarani si.<bt>At that time, Herodes (collective) had not yet put Yohanis the Habitual Baptiser into prison. And Yohanis was also baptising people in the village of Ainon, near the village of Salim, because there was a lot of water there. So people kept coming to Yohanis for him to *baptise them.</bt><note reference="3:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 14:3, Markus 6:17, Lukas 3:19-20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Madhutu ad'a agama Yahudi, ladhe neo sabaj'a, hud'i pamèu uuru ku iisi. Ètu era ne'e abhu dhèu Yahudi ca dhèu dhu patao-palaha dènge ana-ana madhutu Yohanis, lula j'ara èèna.<bt>According to the Yahudi religion, if/when (one) wanted to pray/worship2, (one) must cleanse/purify oneself first. There, there was a Yahudi person who was disputing (doublet) with Yohanis' disciples/followers about that/because of that matter/issue. [EXEG: fungsi dari sarani orang--Message.]</bt><v n="26" />Ka dhèu se mai asa Yohanis, hèia ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Sanèd'e era, do aad'o? Dhèu dhu uru èèna tenge ama ètu sebhe loko Yarden, dhu ama peka na, Nèngu èèna, Kristus. Nèngu sarani dhèu kahèi! Nèti èèna ka, abhu heka dhèu dhu mai asa ji'i! Te lasi aa'i asa Nèngu!&gt;&gt;<bt>So/then they came to Yohanis and spoke, saying, “Father Teacher! Do you still remember or not, that Person who was looking for you on the other side of the Yarden river, who you said that He was Kristus, right? He is also baptising people! That is why nobody is coming to us anymore! Cuz (elaboration) everyone keeps going to Him!” [EXEG: NLT “instead of coming here to us.” Convey speaker attitude.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia Yohanis dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Dhèu bisa boe tao ngaa èci sa, ladhe Ama Lamatua bhoke boe j'ara hia ne.<bt>Then/so Yohanis responded, saying, “It's like this! A person cannot do anything, if God does not open the way for him. [EXEG: Carson, NLT, CEV]</bt><v n="28" />Miu tadèngi dhu ja'a peka le mola-mola dènge miu, na, &lt;Ja'a ne, Kristus boe, dhu èdhi tatae. Te ngaa Lamatua pua uuru ja'a mai, ho oti j'ara hia Kristus. J'ara na sèmi èèna ka!&gt;<bt>You-pl have heard me explaining clearly/forthrightly to you, saying, ‘I here, am not that Kristus whom we have been waiting for. But God2 has sent/commissioned me ahead of time/prior, to open/forge the way for Kristus. That's how it is/That is what's going on!’</bt><note reference="3:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ladhe abhu pengantin dhèu mone, tatu abhu pengantin dhèu bhèni kahèi. Te ngaa sakasii na, dhu titu dènge ne, d'ara na karej'e, ladhe tadèngi lii padhai lii pengantin dhèu mone. Yesus ne, sama sèmi pengantin dhèu mone. Aa ja'a ne, sama sèmi sakasii Na. Nèti èèna ka, limuri ne d'ara ja'a karej'e-karae.<bt>As an example, if there is a bridegroom surely there is also a bride. But his witness [NOTE: Indonesian/Kupang/Dhao technical term for an official companion of the wedding party], who stands with him, is happy if/when he hears the bridegroom talking. This Yesus is like a/the bridegroom. And I here, am like His witness. That is why now my insides are really happy. [EXEG: ‘complete, fulfilled’ carried by ‘now’.]</bt><v n="30" />Dhu lèke ka, Nèngu hud'i asa tabha kapai, aa hud'i laa ja'a asa kura j'aj'i dhèu haha.&gt;&gt;<bt>The important thing is, He must keep increasing in importance/significance/greatness, and may I just keep decreasing becoming insignificant (small person).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu puru mai nèti sorga<bt>The person who descends coming (=comes down) from heaven</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Yohanis tuhu hari lii padhai na, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne mai nèti Ama Lamatua ètu sorga, nèti èèna ka Nèngu kapai risi aa'i. Te ngaa ja'a ne dhoka mai nèti rai-haha, nèti èèna ka ja'a èci èèna ka dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne. Ja'a padhai lii lula-nèti j'ara dhu biasa j'aj'i ètu rai-haha ne. Te ngaa dhu mai nèti Ama Lamatua ètu sorga, tatu Nèngu kapai risi nèti ngaa aa'i-aa'i.<bt>Yohanis continued speaking, saying, “He came from God in heaven, so that is why he is greater than everything/everyone. But I have only come from this world, so that is why I am like everyone in this world. I speak about everyday/common matters that happen in this world. But the one who comes from God in heaven is certainly more amazing/incredible/greater than all/everything. [EXEG: NLT. /dunya/ here is not about sinfulness but about limitations (Carson). STYLE: use /besar/ and /hebat/ to highlight two aspects of the implied status.]</bt><v n="32" />Nèngu peka lula-nèti ngaa dhu nèdhi, dènge ngaa dhu Na tadèngi le. Te ngaa dhèu sèmi boe lii padhai Na.<bt>He tells about what He has already seen and heard. But people don't accept what He has said/says.</bt><v n="33" />Ladhe dhèu sèmi rare ngaa dhu Dhèu nèti dedha-liru ne peka, èèna pad'elo bukti kahèi, na, nèngu parcaya lii padhai Ama Lamatua èèna, lèke tare'a.<bt>If people accepted what that Person from above has already said/told/explained, it would also show evidence/proof that he believes what God says is true.</bt><v n="34" />Dhèu dhu Lamatua pua mai èèna, lole lii moa Ama Lamatua. Te Ama Lamatua hia le Nèngu Roh Na dhu dènge boe too-lane.<bt>That Person whom God sent, tells God's message/instructions. Cuz (elaboration) God has given His Spirit to Him without limit/boundary.</bt><v n="35" />Te Ama ètu sorga sue Ana Na titu kèna. Aa Na pangèd'u aa'i mèu-mèu mi d'ara adhe-aai Ana Na.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) Father in heaven really loves His Child. And He has turned over/entrusted everything into that Child's hand [STYLE: They insist this is natural, not a Hebraism--I've heard a number of these expressions in other non-translation contexts. With /tangan/ implies also giving responsibility/authority for dealing with it according to the giver's wishes.] [EXEG: leave broad ‘everything’ vs. specific ‘power/authority’]</bt><note reference="3:35" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 11:27, Lukas 10:22</note><v n="36" />Ka dhèu dhu parcaya Ana ne, rèngu abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. Te ngaa dhèu dhu parcaya boe Ne, aa tao boe madhutu lii moa Na, rèngu abhu boe mamuri èèna. Tatu Ama Lamatua nasa ka huku si.&gt;&gt;<bt>And/so people who believe in that Child, they will get real life that never ends. But people who don't believe in Him, and don't do according to His message, they don't get that life. Surely God2 will be angry and so punish them.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus padhai lii dènge bhèni ca dhèu ètu Samaria<bt>The Lord Yesus talks with a woman in Samaria</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1-2" />Ladhe pasoro Yohanis dènge Yesus, ana-ana madhutu Yesus mulai sarani dhèu dhu madhutu Ne ae risi nèti Yohanis. Yesus sarani boe dhèu, dhodhoka ana madhutu Na ka dhu sarani si. Ka ropa Yesus ne'a, na, dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi re'a, na, Yesus si sarani dhèu ae risi,<bt>When comparing Yohanis with Yesus, Yesus' disciples began to baptise people who were following Him more (in number) than Yohanis. Yesus did not baptise people, only His disciples were he ones who baptised people. So when Yesus found out that people of the Parisi religious party had heard Yesus (collective) were baptising more people, [DISCOURSE: restructured for background - foreground.]</bt><v n="3" />hèia Nèngu dènge ana madhutu Na tèke eele rai Yudea, lèpa hari asa propensi Galilea.<bt>then He and His disciples left the region of Yudea, to return again to the province of Galilea.</bt><v n="4" />Te ngaa kakako rèngu èèna re propensi Samaria asa propensi Galilea.<bt>But their journey went through/by way of the province of Samaria towards/on the way to Galilea.</bt><v n="5" />Ètu d'ara kakako ra, rèngu d'ai kota èci ètu Samaria, ngara na Sikar, padètu dènge rai dhu Yakob hia ana na Yusuf.<bt>On their journey, they arrived at a city in Samaria, named Sikar, near the land which Yakob had given to his child Yusuf.</bt><note reference="4:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 33:19, Yosua 24:32</note><v n="6-8" />Ètu era ne'e, abhu madha èi èci, ngara na &lt;madha èi Yakob&gt;. D'ai loo nètu ku, Yesus si d'ai era ne'e. Lula j'èra nèti kakako deo na, ka Yesus madhèdi taha ètu madha èi ne'e. Ka ana madhutu Na sèra tèke eele mesa Na, lasi hèli nganga'a ètu d'ara kota.<bt>There, there was a well, named ‘Yakob's well’. In the middle of the day, Yesus (collective) arrived there. Because He was tired from walking/travelling, Yesus He sat temporarily (=took a break) at that well. And His disciples left Him alone there, to go into the city to buy food.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="isi j'èra"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-24 01:20:30Z" status="Anyone">rasa badan manoso (ke flu, gejala demam)</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-06 02:33:03Z">lo-nètu short and normal for lod'o nètu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia bhèni ca dhèu nèti kota èèna, mai usu èi. Ka Yesus manèngi ne èi, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a bisa kinu èi ciki, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then a woman from that city came to fetch water at that well. Yesus asked her, saying, “Can I ask for a drink? (idiomatic)”</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01674b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Te ngaa bhèni ne cag'ag'a, lula dhèu Yahudi tema boe padhai lii dènge dhèu Samaria. Ka bhèni ne karèi Yesus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu dhèu Yahudi. Ja'a ne dhèu Samaria. Sala boe ne, ladhe Èu manèngi ja'a èi ho minu?&gt;&gt;<bt>But that woman was surprised, because Yahudi people normally don't speak with Samaria people. So the woman asked Yesus, saying, “You are a Yahudi person. I'm a Samaria person. Isn't it wrong if You ask me for a drink?”</bt><note reference="4:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Esra 4:1-5, Nehemia 4:1-2</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ladhe èu me'a ngaa dhu Ama Lamatua neo hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i, aa ladhe èu tadhe Ja'a ne cee, dhu manèngi èu èi ne, na, tatu èu manèngi hari èi nèti Ja'a. Pe Ja'a hia èu èi dhu nèti mamuri.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying, “It's like this. If you knew what it was that God wants to give everyone, and if you knew/recognised who I am who is asking for a drink, surely you would ask Me for water in return/instead. And I would give water that brings life.” [EXEG: “God's gift” 1) that He wants to give you (NLT, CEV), 2) that He wants to give everyone (Jews and Samaritans alike) (HCE, context), 3) “gift of God” = Torah (Odeburg, in Carson), 4) eternal life (Carson).]</bt><note reference="4:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yermia 2:13, Sakaria 14:8; Yeheskial 47:9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka bhèni ne b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu dènge boe sabha uusu. Aa madha èi ne marèma. Nèti mia Èu abhu èi dhu nèti mamuri èèna? Èi èèna abhu ètu mia hari?<bt>The woman said, “You have no dipping bucket. And this well is deep. Where are You going to get that water that brings life? Where could that water be?</bt><v n="12" />Abhu ètu mia Èu kapai risi nèti baki èdhi Yakob! Nèngu ka dhu tèke eele madha èi ne hia ji'i. Aa nèngu, ana-ana na, dènge badha-manu na rinu nèti èi ne'e kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>It is surely not possible that You are greater than our-inc grandfather/forefather Yakob! He is the one who left this well for us-exc. And he, His children, and his animals also drank from this well.” [EXEG: cattle = flocks; NRSV, NLT, CEV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Hèia Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e, ee! Dhèu dhu tema rinu nèti madha èi ne, èèna na koko-kamango hari.<bt>So Yesus responded, saying, “Remember, ee! A person who normally/habitually drinks from this well, will later get thirsty again.</bt><v n="14" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu rinu èi dhu Ja'a hia, èèna na koko-kamango heka. Te èi dhu Ja'a hia èèna, nuka sèmi èi madha dhu sabhoka asa li'u. Èi ne, nèti mamuri dhu lèke, dhu ma'ète boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the person who drinks the water that I give, will later not get thirsty again. Cuz (elaboration) the water that I give, is like a spring which bursts out (under pressure)/artesians out. That water brings real life which never ends.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ka aku dhèu bhèni ne, na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, na, Èu hia ku ja'a èi èèna, sèna ka ja'a koko-kamango ia ka! Dènge sèmi èèna, ja'a mai heka pahari-pahari asa ne'e ho usu èi.&gt;&gt;<bt>The woman said, “If that's the case, na, You give me that water [+imperative], so that I don't get thirsty anymore! In that way, I won't have to keep coming here to fetch water anymore.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Hèia Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Èu lèpa, lamu paroa ku dhèu èmu mu, mai asa ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told her, saying, “[Do] like this. You go home, and summon your spouse, then come back here.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-18" />Ka bhèni ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Te ngaa ja'a dènge boe dhèu èmu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the woman responded, saying, “But I don't have a spouse.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a. Èu peka mola-mola èèna. Te èu leo mèdhi le èmu lèmi hari. Aa mone dhu limuri ne, dhèu èmu èu boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yesus said, “True. You speak honestly/straight. Cuz (elaboration) you have had five spouses. And the man who is now, is not your spouse.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka bhèni ne lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Ja'a heka ke'a kèna, Ama ne ca dhèu nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Lamatua.<bt>Then the woman said, “Ira ii! [+amazement] Only.now I know that Father (=You) here, are one of God2's *spokespeople.</bt><v n="20" />De ja'a neo karèi. Bèi-baki ji'i dhèu Samaria pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua ètu ledhe Gerisim.<bt>So (consequently) I want to ask. We-exc Samaria people's ancestors (doublet) worshipped God on the Gerisim mountain.</bt><note reference="4:20" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ledhe Gerisim èèna, padètu dènge rae Sikem ètu propensi Samaria. Ètu sasuri lii Yunani, dhoka suri, na, &lt;&lt;ètu ledhe ne'e&gt;&gt;. Te ngaa dhèu d'èlu-mèu se peka, ngara ledhe ne, nuka &lt;&lt;Gerisim&gt;&gt;.<bt>That Gerisim mountain was near the village of Sikem in the province of Samaria. In the Yunani language writings, it only says, “at this mountain”. But the knowledgeable people say the name of that mountain is “Gerisim”.</bt></note>Te ngaa miu dhèu Yahudi peka na, ladhe neo sabaj'a mi Ama Lamatua, dhèu aa'i-aa'i hud'i lasi ku asa kota Yerusalem. Madhutu Ama, mia ka dhu lèke?&gt;&gt;<bt>But you-pl Yahudi people say, if (you/people) want to worship2 God, everyone must go to the city of Yerusalem. According to you, the truth is which (of choices)?” [NLT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Èu parcaya ku lii Ja'a ne, te dhu lèke sèmi ne'e ku. Dhèu neo pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua ètu ledhe ne'e, do, ètu Yerusalem, pe d'ai lod'o na, dua era se guna heka.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “You should believe what I am telling you, cuz it is true. (Whether) a person wants to worship God on this mountain, or, in Yerusalem, the time will come when both/neither will be of anymore use/value. [EXEG: NLT, Carson “Believe me (pisteuw plus the dative; cf. notes on 2:22), are not an invitation to trust Jesus with saving faith, but a simple asseverative” = conversational device.]</bt><v n="22" />Miu dhèu Samaria me'a mèu boe, mi cee ka miu pahaha iisi. Te ngaa ji'i dhèu Yahudi nge'a mèu, lula-nèti Ama Lamatua dhu ji'i pahaha iisi mi Nèngu. Te Nèngu neo pake ji'i ho bhoke j'ara, sèna ka dhèu bisa abhu mamuri nèti koasa sasala-sasigo rèngu.<bt>You-pl Samaria people don't really understand a lot about who you worship. But we-exc Yahudi people know a lot about God whom we worship. Cuz (elaboration) He wants to use us-exc to open the way so that people can be saved from the power of their sins (doublet). [NLT, CEV]</bt><v n="23" />Pe d'ai lod'o na, nuka mulai ne'e ne, dhèu dhu tare'a-re'a pahaha iisi mi Ama èdhi ètu sorga, na, rèngu pahaha iisi mi Nèngu madhutu Roh Na, aa madhutu ngaa dhu lèke. Te Ama ètu sorga d'èi dhèu sèmi sèra dhu pahaha iisi mi Nèngu.<bt>The time is arriving, that is is has already begun now/is already beginning, (when) people who truly worship our-inc Father in heaven, na, they worship Him according to His Spirit, and according to what is true/correct. Cuz (elaboration) Father in heaven likes people of that sort who worship Him. [EXEG: 23-24 based on plays on multiple senses of spirit; if want to preserve parallels in these well known verses, must go with Spirit, rather than spirit.]</bt><v n="24" />Te Lamatua èèna, roh. De dhèu dhu pahaha iisi mi Nèngu hud'i pahaha iisi madhutu ku Roh Na, aa madhutu ngaa dhu lèke.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God2 is spirit. So (consequently), people who worship Him must worship according to His Spirit, and according to what is true.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ka dhèu bhèni ne lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ke'a le Mesias neo mai èèna, dhu dhèu peka na, &lt;Kristus&gt;. Ama Lamatua padhadha tèke neo hia mai. Ladhe Na mai ka, tatu Nèngu bhoke paled'a aa'i-aa'i mi ji'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>The woman said/told/explained, saying, “I know that the *Mesias (loan) is going to come, the one who people refer to saying ‘Kristus’. God has promised beforehand to send Him coming. When He comes/has come, surely He will explain everything to us-inc.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Hèia Yesus b'ala, na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu èèna, nuka Ja'a dhu padhai lii dènge èu ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “That one is Me who am speaking to you now.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Ropa Nèngu padhai lii era, ana madhutu Na sèra lèpa nèti d'ara kota. Rèngu malaa, lula rèngu rèdhi Yesus dhu padhai lii dènge bhèni Samaria ca dhèu. Te ngaa ca dhèu sa bani boe karèi dhèu bhèni, na, &lt;&lt;Èu parluu ngaa?&gt;&gt; Aa èci sa bani boe karèi Yesus kahèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka Ama padhai lii dènge dhèu bhèni ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>While He was speaking, His disciples came back from the city. They were surprised/amazed, because they saw Yesus speaking with a Samaria woman. But there was no one had the (social) courage to ask the woman, saying, “What do you want/need?” And there was no one who had the courage to ask Yesus either, saying, “Why is Father (=You) speaking to this woman?” [EXEG: Carson]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ka bhèni ne tèke eele g'ala na ètu era èèna, la'e asa d'ara kota. Hèia na lolo dènge dhèu ètu sèra, peka na,<bt>So/then, that woman left her jug behind there, returning into the city. And2 she told/narrated to the people there, saying,</bt><v n="29" />&lt;&lt;Mai lati ladhe ku Dhèu nèi laa! Te Na bhoke patalele aa'i le ngaa-ngaa dhu ja'a ad'u-ue kèdhi. Tao-tao Nèngu ne'e ka, Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua pamoa hia mai!&gt;&gt;<bt>“Come have a look at this Person [+light imperative]! Cuz (elaboration) He has completely revealed/exposed everything I've ever done. What if/could it be/perhaps He is Kristus, who God promised to send!”</bt><v n="30" />Hèia dhèu ae kalua nèti d'ara kota, lasi laladhe Ne.<bt>Then2, the people went out from that city, going to see Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Lod'o bhèni ne la'e asa kota, hèia ana madhutu Na peka dènge Ne, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Mai ka ta'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>When that woman had gone to the city, Yesus' disciples spoke to Him, saying, “Father Teacher! Let's eat!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Te ngaa Na dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a abhu le nganga'a dhu miu me'a boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>But He responded, saying, “I already have food that you-pl don't know (about).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ka ana madhutu Na pakarèi èci dènge èci, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia, ne? Cee ka dhu rèti nganga'a hia Ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>His disciples asked each other, saying, “How is this? Who is it that brought food for Him?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge rèngu, na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ama Lamatua pua Ja'a mai, sèna ka tao madhutu dad'èi Na, aa pakako sasab'a-la'a Na toke d'ai èle. Ne'e ne, nuka sèmi nganga'a-nginu dhu Ja'a abhu.<bt>But Yesus explained to them, saying, “It's like this. God sent/commissioned Me here to do according to His will, and carry out His work until it is done/completed. That is like food (doublet) to/for Me.</bt><v n="35" />Miu ladhe ku asa d'ara oka-tedhe, aa mi kasere sèku, ele boe miu peka na, &lt;Di èpa hèru ka, heka bisa puru are kèna.&gt; Nanene, ee! Ja'a pasanèd'e miu. Ladhe miu laladhe paie-iie, are ètu d'ara oka-tedhe d'ai le lod'o puu-g'ètu. Oka-tedhe sèra nuka sèmi dhèu-dhèu dhu mai asa èdhi. Te rèngu se'e ka dhu sadia le parcaya Ja'a.<bt>You-pl have a good look at a field/the fields, then have a guess/estimate, saying, &lt;Still four more months before [we] can pick/harvest rice/grain.&gt; Listen, ee! I'm reminding you (how it really is). If you look carefully, the grain in the fields are now already ready to pick/harvest (doublet). Those fields are like the people who are coming to us-inc. Cuz (elaboration) they are ready to believe in Me. [EXEG: In consultant check UNS's had difficulty figuring out field = ??; So from Kankanay, Western Bukidnon, Yakan, Tagbanwa BT's, we put in last 2 sentences.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Di èpa hèru"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-24 02:59:16Z" status="Anyone">Tinggal 4 bulan ; lagi 4 bulan</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />Mesa boe sèmi se'e di, te dhèu dhu puu-g'ètu sèra pakaboko hua-hela ètu d'ara gud'a, rèngu mulai sèmi rare rui-j'aj'èra ra. Rèngu se'e, nuka sèmi dhèu pad'elo j'ara sèna ka dhèu parcaya mi Ama Lamatua, ho abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, dhèu sèle hini dènge dhèu puu-g'ètu, bisa sama-sama karej'e-karae.<bt>Not only that, cuz/but the pickers/harvesters who are gathering/collecting their yield/produce in the storehouses/bodegas, have already begun to receive their wages/payment/reward (fruit of their labour; lit: bones from suffering). They are like people who show the way for people to believe in God, and get real life which never ends. In that way, people who plant seeds, and people who pick/ harvest the produce/ result, can be happy together. [EXEG: NLT, Carson.]</bt><v n="37" />Dhèu peka na, &lt;Dhèu èci sèle hini; dhèu leo ka dhu kaboko isi rai.&gt; Èèna, lèke kèna.<bt>People say, ‘One person plants seed; other/another is the one who gathers the crop/result/harvest.’ That's true.</bt><v n="38" />Ja'a pua-paleha miu ho lami kaboko isi rai nèti sasab'a dhèu leo. Mema sasab'a miu boe, te ngaa miu abhu leto nèti rui-j'aj'èra rèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I have sent/commissioned (doublet) you-pl to go gather/collect produce/harvest from the work of other people. It's really not you who did the work, but you get/gain the benefit from their efforts/tiredness.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu ètu d'ara kota Samaria ae ka dhu parcaya Yesus, lula lii padhai bhèni ne, dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Na bhoke patalele aa'i le ngaa-ngaa dhu ja'a ad'u-ue kèdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, there were many Samaria people in that city who believed in Yesus, because of what that woman said, saying, “He has completely revealed/exposed everything I have ever done.” [same as vs.29] [STYLE: “At that time” needed to signal shift in topic.]</bt><v n="40" />Ka ropa dhèu se'e mai d'ai madha Yesus, ra pamako Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama pea ku laa dènge ji'i mi ne'e!&gt;&gt; Hèia Yesus pea dènge dhèu se, dua lod'o.<bt>Then, when these people came before Yesus, they begged/coaxed Him, saying, “Father just stay/live with us here!” And/so Yesys stayed temporarily with those people for two days.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Aa dhèu leo ae kahèi dhu parcaya Ne, lula lii padhai Na.<bt>And many other people also believed in Him, because of what He said.</bt><v n="42" />Hèia dhèu se peka dènge dhèu bhèni ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Med'a na, ji'i nanene dhoka lii èu di. Te ngaa ne'e ne ji'i parcaya Ne, lula ji'i nanene lii padhai Na patoo madha dènge madha. Ji'i nge'a tare'a, na, Dhèu ne'e ne ka dhu bisa patalale èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti, ètu rai-haha ne nèti koasa sasala-sasigo èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they told the woman, saying, “Yesterday, we-exc only heard what you-sg had to say. But now we-exc believe in Him, because we listened to Him face to face. We really know that this Person is the one who can rescue/save/release all of us-inc in this world from the power of our wrongs (doublet).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle papèd'a nèti ana pegawi ca dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) an official's child</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Hèia Yesus si tèke eele era èèna, pakèd'i lasi asa propensi Galilea.<bt>After Yesus (collective) left that place, they continued going/travelling to the province of Galilea.</bt><v n="44" />(Ca tèka Yesus dhu peka nèdhi, na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu d'èi boe pakab'ua dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua nèti rae èta-èsu na.&gt;&gt;)<bt>(One time Yesus had spoken, saying, “People don't like to give/show respect to God's spokesperson in his own home village.”)</bt><note reference="4:44" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 13:57, Markus 6:4, Lukas 4:24</note><v n="45" />Uru èèna, lod'o dhèu dhae tao mèka kalela Paska, dhèu Galilea ae ka dhu lasi asa Yerusalem, sèna ka tao lod'o hua iia ètu nèi. Ka rèdhi aa'i-aa'i kahèi dhu Yesus tao ètu Yerusalem. Nèti èèna ka, lod'o Na lèpa asa Galilea, dhèu sèmi Ne dènge be'a.<bt>Previously, when it was not.yet Paska feast, many Galilea people had gone to Yerusalem to make/do the festival/holiday there. And they saw everything that Yesus did in Yerusalem. That is why when He returned (home) to Galilea, they accepted/received Him well. [CONNECTORS: Carson, Message.]</bt><note reference="4:45" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 2:23</note><v n="46" />Ka Yesus si lasi hari asa rae Kana ètu propensi Galilea. Ètu era ne'e ka dhu Yesus tao nèdhi èi j'aj'i anggor.<bt>So/then Yesus (coll.) continue going and went again to the village of Kana in the province of Galilea. He had (once/ever) made water become wine there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lod'o èèna, abhu pegawi ca dhèu dhu pea ètu kota Kapernaum. Ana mone na dhu pèd'a.<bt>At that time, there was an official (assimilated loan) living in the city of Kapernaum. His son was sick.</bt><note reference="4:46" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 2:1-11</note><v n="47" />Ropa pegawi ne tadèngi, Yesus lèpa le asa Galilea nèti propensi Yudea, hèia ca'e la'e asa rae Kana ho tenge Yesus. Ropa paraga dènge Ne, ka na pamako, sèna ka Yesus puru la'e ho puri-pa'èle ana na nèti papèd'a-tarègu. Te ana ne dhu pèd'a oe madhe.<bt>When that official heard that Yesus had already come back/home to Galilea from the province of Yudea, then he went up (topographical) to Kana to look for Yesus. When he met Him, he begged/coaxed for Yesus to come down to heal (doublet) his child from disease (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) that child was sick near death.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Ka Yesus peka dènge pegawi ne, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu mèdhi boe tadha-tadha malaa dhu Ja'a tao, na, miu mo'o boe lèka Ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus told that official, saying, “If you-pl don't see Me doing various amazing signs, na, you don't want to believe in Me!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Te ngaa pegawi ne dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, lati ku laa. Te aad'o, na, ana ja'a madhe.&gt;&gt;<bt>That official responded, saying, “Father, let's go now. Cuz (elaboration) if not, na, my child is dead (sense of “will surely die”).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Lèpa ka. Te ana mu mamuri.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told him, saying, “Go on home. Cuz (elaboration) your-sg child is alive/lives/will live.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na lèpa dènge ka, lula nèngu parcaya lii padhai Yesus.<bt>So he returned (home) immediately, because he believed/trusted what Yesus had said.</bt><v n="51" />Ropa pegawi ne ètu talora j'ara era, dhèu-dhèu sab'a na mai paraga dènge ne, ka ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama susa ia ka, te ana ama èle le nèti papèd'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>When/while the official was still travelling, his workers came and met him, saying, “Father/you don't need to be troubled anymore, cuz (reason) your child is healed from sickness.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Ka na karèi si, &lt;&lt;Na èle, d'ara hake pèri sa?&gt;&gt;<bt>So he asked them, saying, “He got better/well from what time?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka dhèu se dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Karèi med'a, lod'o titu mera d'ara hake èci sa, maringi-sagoro na èle dènge ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>Those people responded, saying, “Beginning from mid-day yesterday at one o'clock, his fever went down straightaway.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="samuri"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-24 03:43:13Z" status="Anyone">sembuh</Message></Annotation><v n="53" />Hèia pegawi ne ngee nèdhi dènge, na, ana na be'a le, ropa Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Ana ama èle le nèti papèd'a.&gt;&gt; Ka pegawi ne, dènge isi èmu na aa'i-aa'i parcaya Yesus.<bt>Then that official remembered/knew right away that his child had become well, beginning from when/the time Yesus said, “Your child is healed from sickness.” Then the official, and all his household (=family + servants) believed in Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />De ne'e ne, tadha malaa ka dua dhu Yesus tao, lod'o Na kalua nèti Yudea la'e asa Galilea.<bt>So (consequently) this here was the second amazing sign which Yesus did when he came out from Yudea, to go to Galilea.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu karuku èci ètu kolam Batesda<bt>The Lord Yesus heals a paralysed person in/at the pool/pond of Batesda</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Nèbhu boe nèti èèna, abhu lod'o hua iia agama Yahudi. Ka Yesus si lasi asa kota Yerusalem.<bt>After that, there was a Yahudi religious feast/festival/holiday. So Yesus (coll.) went to the city of Yerusalem.</bt><v n="2" />Ètu nèi, abhu kolam cue dhu dènge lèmi teras dhu padètu dènge hèb'a babèdho èci, dhu dhèu peka na, Babèdho Kahib'i-Kalèbho. Dènge lii Aram kolam ne, ngara na <span class="Italic">&lt;Batesda&gt;.</span><bt>There, there was a pool which had five porches/pavilions/terraces quite near a door/gate named Sheep Door/Gate. In their Aram language, that pool's name was <span class="Italic">&lt;Batesda&gt;.</span> [Greek TEXT: TH says Bethzatha reading is “least problematic”, following GNT (but with a doubtful D reading), and this is followed by NRSV, CEV, Source; Carson and Morris favour Bethesda, followed by NIV, NLT, TB, Message; Bethsaida is weakest reading.]</bt><note reference="5:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani cahag'e, suri na, &lt;Betesda&gt;, cahag'e hari &lt;Betsata&gt;, aa abhu kahèi &lt;Betsaida&gt;. Babèdho Kahib'i-Kalèbho abhu kahèi ètu sasuri <span class="Italic">Nehemia </span>3:1,32; 12:39. Kota Yerusalem abhu babèdho ae dhu maso asa d'ara kota. Babèdho dhu leo sèra, gaguna baka-leo. Uru-uru sèra, dhèu pake Babèdho Kahib'i-Kalèbho ne, ho eo kahib'i-kalèbho maso re era èèna.<bt>Some Yunani language writings write ‘Betesda’, some write ‘Betsata’, and some others write ‘Betsaida’. The Sheep Gate is also in <span class="Italic">Nehemia</span> 3:1,32; 12:39. The city of Yerusalem has many doors/gates going into the city. Diffeent gates had different functions. Long ago, they normally/often used this Sheep Gate for sheep to enter via there.</bt></note><v n="3" />Dhèu pèd'a ae-ae dhu tema mate ètu teras se'e. Dhèu pèd'a se nuka sèmi: dhèu bèdhu, dhèu karuku, dènge dhèu bisa boe eso. [Rèngu se mate, ladhe pèri lod'o èi ne mulai dènge gagèb'o.<bt>There were many sick people who normally/often waited at/on those terraces. Those sick people were: blind people, paralysed people [with some movement], and people who couldn't move. [They were waiting for when that water would begin to move/shake.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="gagèb'o"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-24 03:57:22Z" status="Anyone">ripple, move [Lena not know]</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Te ca tèka-tèka, ana pajuu Lamatua nèti sorga maso uru asa d'ara èi ne, ho na gagèb'o èi ne. Ho ladhe cee dhu maso uru asa d'ara èi ne, papèd'a nèngu èle dènge.]<bt>Cuz (elaboration) once in awhile/sometimes, God2's angel/underling from heaven would enter into that water, to move/shake/disturb the water. So that whoever entered the water first, na, his/her sickness would disappear/be healed.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakaj'èb'o"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-24 03:58:20Z" status="Anyone">move</Message></Annotation><note reference="5:4" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii dhu ètu d'ara kurung, abhu boe ètu d'ara sasuri Lii Yunani dhu be'a risi dènge dhu uru-uru tèka.<bt>The words in these parantheses (Indo loan) do not exist in the Yunani language writings which are the best and the oldest.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ètu era ne'e abhu ca dhèu dhu pèd'a tèlu nguru aru tèu le.<bt>There, there was a person who had been sick for 38 years.</bt><v n="6" />Hèia Yesus ladhe nèdhi dhèu ne j'unu ètu èèna. Nèngu ne'a dhèu ne dhu pèd'a nèbhu le, ka Na karèi ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu neo èle nèti papèd'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yesus saw that person laying there. He knew that person had been sick for a long time, so He asked him, saying, “Do (you) want to be healed of your sickness/infirmity?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Hèia dhèu ne dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Ko'o, Ama. Te ngaa ako carui ka, ladhe èi ne mulai gagèb'o, abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu ded'e ja'a ho pamaso asa d'ara èi ne. Ladhe ja'a sèku maso, na, abhu le dhèu leo dhu maso uuru nèti ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>The man responded saying, “I want to, Father. But the difficulty is, if/when the water has begun to move, there is nobody to lift me to put me into the water. If I try to go in, na, there is already someone else who gets in ahead of me.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sa'u"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-24 04:07:51Z" status="Anyone">gendong</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ka Yesus pua ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Titu ka! Lulu dhèpi èu, ho lèpa ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus commanded him, saying, “Stand up! Roll up your mat, and go home.”</bt><v n="9" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii nare, hèia dhèu ne èle dènge ka nèti karuku na. Ka na kèd'i, ded'e nèti dhèpi na, hèia la'e dènge ka.<bt>When Yesus had finished speaking, that person became healed from his paralysis. Then/so he got up, picked up his mat, and left immediately.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">J'ara ne j'aj'i, lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a dhèu Yahudi.<bt>That matter happened on the Yahudi people's day of worship. [DISCOURSE: WHEN it happened is background, but is needed here to introduce basis for following dispute.]</bt><v n="10" />Ka ama-ama dhèu Yahudi jèke dhèu dhu heka èle nèti papèd'a ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Weh! Èu me'a, do aad'o? Doe ne'e ne, lèke dènge lod'o ae sasab'a. Madhutu atora agama èdhi, dhèu bisa boe nedhe dhèpi na, te èèna ngara na, sasab'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>So/then the leaders of the Yahudi people scolded that person who had just been healed of his sickness/infirmity, saying, “Weh! You should really know this. (Lit: do you know, or not?) Today is the day of rest (stopping work). According to our religious regulations, nobody is allowed to carry their mat, cuz that would be categorised as work!” [Productive grammatical construction: cuz that, its name, XX = this would be categorised/ named/ classified as XX] [STYLE: Lu tau, ko sonde? for carrying speaker attitude.]</bt><note reference="5:10" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Nehemia 13:19, Yermia 17:21</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka na dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama-ama! Baku nasa dènge ja'a. Te Dhèu dhu puri-pa'èle ja'a, dhu paredha ja'a peka na, &lt;Lulu dhèpi èu, ho lèpa ka.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, “Fathers! You shouldn't be angry with me. Cuz (elaboration) the Person who healed (doublet) me is the one who commanded me, saying, ‘Roll2 up your mat, and go on home.’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia dhèu se karèi ne, &lt;&lt;Cee ka dhu pua èu nedhe dhèpi èèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they asked him, saying, “Who was it that ordered you to pick up your mat?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu èle nèti pèd'a ne, tadhe boe, na, Yesus ne, cee. Te Yesus dhu kalua le mau-mau, lula dhèu ae ètu èèna.<bt>But that person who had been healed from his disease did not know who Yesus was. Cuz (elaboration) Yesus had gone out quietly/unnoticed, because there were many people there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Nèbhu boe, ka Yesus paraga dènge dhèu ne ètu madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ka Yesus peka dènge ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nanene! Èu èle le nèti papèd'a èu. Baku ad'u-ue hari sasala, sèna ka èu baku abhu hari j'aj'èra dhu bia risi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Soon after that, Yesus met with that person in the *Temple's yard. Then Yesus told him, saying, “Listen! You have been healed of your disease. Don't do wrong/sin anymore, so that you do not experience/get anything that is even worse.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia dhèu ne la'e asa ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se, ka na lolo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhu puri-pa'èle ja'a nèti papèd'a èèna, ngara na Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then that person went to look for the Yahudi people's leaders, and told them, saying, “The one who healed (doublet) me from disease, His name is Yesus.”</bt><v n="16" />Nèti èèna ka, ra mulai paj'èra Yesus, lula Nèngu pa'èle dhèu pèd'a lèke dènge lod'o manèngi-mangaj'i.<bt>That is why they began to cause trouble/suffering/torment Yesus, because He healed a person on the day of worship2.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Te ngaa Yesus peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ama Ku ae boe nèti sasab'a-la'a Na. De Ja'a sab'a taruu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus told them, saying, “It's like this. My Father never (=doesn't know how to) stop working (doublet). So (consequently) I also keep on working.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus mangaku, na, Nèngu ne, Ana Ama Lamatua<bt>The Lord Yesus acknowledges/confesses that He is God's Child</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Lula ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se cap le, peka na, Yesus sisu atora lod'o ae sasab'a rèngu, nèti èèna ka ra tenge-tenge j'ara tasamia, ho pamadhe Ne. Risi-risi hari, Na peka na, Ama Lamatua èèna, Ama Nèngu. Dènge lii padhai sèmi ne'e, Nèngu tao iisi Na sama sèmi Ama Lamatua.<bt>Because the Yahudi people's bosses had already branded/assessed/categorised/judged, saying, Yesus was violating/transgressing their regulation(s) of the day of rest, so that is why they were looking even harder for a way to kill Him. Even more than that, He had said that God was His Father. By speaking like that, He elevated/lifted Himself to be the same as God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Ka Yesus peka dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a! Ja'a peka mema, na, Ja'a bisa boe tao ngaa-ngaa madhutu d'ara Ja'a unu Ku. Te Ja'a ne, Ana Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka Ja'a bisa sab'a dhodhoka madhutu ngaa dhu Ja'a kèdhi Ama Ku sab'a. Ja'a kèdhi Ama Ku tao ngaa, na, Ja'a tao madhutu sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>Then Yesus told them, saying, “True! I'm telling you directly that I cannot do anything from my own self. [CHECK option from MTTs with UNSs] Cuz (elaboration) I (here) am God's Child. That is why I can only do according to what I have seen Father do./I see Father doing. (Whatever) I see My Father doing, na, I also do accordingly.</bt><v n="20" />Ama Ku ètu sorga sue Ja'a, nuka Ana Na. Na pad'elo dènge Ja'a kahèi aa'i-aa'i dhu Nèngu tao. Na neo pad'elo dènge Ja'a j'ara-j'ara dhu kapai risi hari, sèna ka miu mèdhi aa asa tabha malaa!<bt>My Father in heaven loves Me, that is His Child. He also shows Me everything that He does/is doing. Later He is going to show Me things that are even more incredible, so that you-pl will see (them) and be increasingly amazed/awed!</bt><v n="21" />Ama Ku pamamuri hari dhèu madhe. Sèmi èèna kahèi, bèli-camèd'a Ja'a hia mamuri dhu lèke mi cee èèna ka dhu madhutu dad'èi Ja'a.<bt>My Father brings dead people back to life. Like that also, I will give real life to whoever follows My will/desires. [EXEG: Carson, Morris.]</bt><v n="22" />Dhu mola-mola, sèmi ne'e ka: Ama Ku mesa Na pama'ète boe hahuku mi dhèu. Te ngaa Na pangèd'u aa'i hak èèna mi Ja'a, te Ja'a ne, Ana Na. Hèia Ja'a ka dhu pama'ète, na, tatao dhèu lèke, do aad'o.<bt>The truth is like this: My Father himself doesn't decide/judge punishment for people. But He has turned over that right to Me, cuz (elaboration) I am His Child. So, I am the one who decides that/whether (a) person has done what is right, or not.</bt><v n="23" />Ama Ku d'èi sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i pakab'ua Ja'a, sama sèmi rèngu pakab'ua Nèngu kahèi. Te dhèu dhu pakab'ua boe Ja'a, Ana Nèngu ne, èci èèna ka rèngu pakab'ua boe Ama Ku dhu pua Ja'a mai.<bt>My Father likes for everyone to respect/honour Me, just as they also respect/honour Him. Cuz (elaboration) a person who doesn't respect/honour for Me, that is His Child, he also doesn't respect/honour My Father who sent/commissioned Me here.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Tare'a! Ja'a peka mema. Dhèu dhu tare'a-re'a nanene lii padhai Ja'a, aa parcaya Ama Lamatua dhu pua Ja'a mai, na, nèngu abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. Lamatua huku heka nèngu. Te dhèu èèna abhu heka hahuku madhe, te ngaa nèngu j'aj'i le dhèu dhu mamuri taruu dènge Lamatua.<bt>That's right! I'm telling (you) straight. (A) person who truly hears/listens to what I have to say/My message, and believes in God who sent/commissioned Me, na, he has gotten real life which never ends. God2 doesn't/won't punish him anymore/is no longer going to punish him. Cuz (elaboration) that person no longer gets/experiences the death penalty/punishment of death, but s/he has already become a person who lives continually with God2.</bt><v n="25" />Tare'a! Ja'a peka mema dènge miu kèna. Lod'o na dètu le, limuri ne dhu j'aj'i le, nuka dhèu-dhèu madhe nanene lii Ja'a, Ana Ama Lamatua. Te dhèu dhu nanene dènge sèmi nare lii padhai Ja'a, nèngu abhu mamuri dhu lèke.<bt>That's right! I'm telling (you) straight. The time is very near, in fact it has already begun now, for dead people to hear My voice/message, that is the voice/message of God2's Child. Cuz (elaboration) a/the person who hears/listens and accepts what I have to say/My message, will get/obtain real life.</bt><v n="26" />Mamuri aa'i-aa'i kapua na nèti Ama Ku. Nèngu hia Ja'a mamuri dhu lèke kahèi. Te Ja'a ne, Ana Na.<bt>All life is rooted/sourced in My Father. He has also given Me real life. Cuz (elaboration) I am His Child [+obvious (speaker attitude)]. [EXEG: Context: from 5:18ff. “making himself equal with God”, followed by additional qualities that the Son shares with the Father; NRSV, NIV, NLT, Carson, Morris, TB all go to “life-in-himself” (setting the stage for the resurrection, cf. vs.25, 28-29). TEV, CEV, Uma, Yakan, TH go to “power to give life” which is harder to support immediately from the Gk text, both lexically and grammatically (In Gk Jesus is the recipient of “give”), although it resonates with vs.24. From the claims in the Prologue, and John's penchant for using multiple senses of words simultaneously, it is difficult to limit the first clause to just “real/true life” only.]</bt><v n="27" />Ama Ku pangèd'u koasa dènge hak mi Ja'a kahèi, sèna ka pama'ète hahuku mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra, lula Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a.<bt>My Father has also given/gives the right and power/authority to Me to decide/judge everyone's punishment, because I am the *Son of Man (Authentic/Ideal Human).</bt><v n="28" />Miu baku malaa, te ciki oo'e hari dhèu madhe aa'i-aa'i ra tadèngi lii padhai Ja'a.<bt>You-pl should not be surprised, cuz (elaboration) soon all the dead people will hear My voice.</bt><v n="29" />Hèia ra mamuri hari. Ka rèngu kalua nèti d'ara ro'a ra. Dhèu dhu uru sèra tao be'a, abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. Te ngaa dhèu dhu uru sèra ad'u-ue bhabhelu-katub'a, pasae hahuku taruu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they will come back to life/live again. And they will come out from their graves. People who formerly did good, will get/obtain real life which never ends. But people who formerly did evil (doublet), will bear/experience continual punishment.” [EXEG: “eternal life” Carson, Morris, NLT, TB]</bt><note reference="5:29" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Daniel 12:2</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abhu sakasii ae dhu peka lula-nèti Lamatua Yesus<bt>There are many witnesses that tell about the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a bisa boe tao ngaa-ngaa ladhe dhae tadèngi mèka nèti Ama Ku. Ladhe Ja'a tadèngi kore ku, heka Ja'a pama'ète lii langu dhèu kèna. Nèti èèna ka, ngaa dhu Ja'a pama'ète sèra, lèke mola-mola. Te Ja'a ko'o boe madhutu dad'èi Ja'a mesa Ku, te ngaa Ja'a madhutu dad'èi Ama Ku. Lula Nèngu ka dhu pua Ja'a mai!<bt>Yesus continued speaking, saying, “I cannot do anything if I have not yet heard from My Father. If/when I have already heard/finished listening/heard, only then will I decide a person's case. Because of that, what I decide is true/correct/right/just/fair. Cuz (elaboration) I do not want to follow My own will/desire, but follow My Father's will/desire. Because He is the one who sent/commissioned Me [+emphatic]! [NLT]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Lèke iia boe, ladhe Ja'a mesa ku dhu padhue-padhai lula-nèti ngi'u Ja'a.<bt>It is not valid/correct if only I myself am the one to tell/explain (doublet) about My self.</bt><v n="32" />Te ngaa abhu dhèu leo kahèi dhu j'aj'i sakasii lula-nèti Ja'a. Aa Ja'a ke'a lii padhai nèngu lula-nèti Ja'a, lèke tare'a-re'a.<bt>But there is also another person who is a witness about Me. And I know he speak the truth about Me. [EXEG: OT principle--2-3 witnesses; vs.31 I about myself, vs.32 more than just me; vs.33 John TBapt; vs. 36a God the Father; vs.36b the works that I do; vs.38 God's Word; so even though the Gk is singular in vs. 32, it sets up a series of witnesses “in addition to Yesus”]</bt><v n="33" />Miu dhu pua mèdhi dhèu lasi pakarèi dènge Yohanis tuka sarani. Ka na peka lèke lula-nèti Ja'a ne.<bt>You-pl once sent/commissioned people to go ask Yohanis the Habitual Baptiser. And he spoke what is true about Me.</bt><note reference="5:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:19-27, 3:27-30</note><v n="34" />Aa te ngaa Ja'a parluu boe lii sakasii nèti dhèu rai-haha. Te ngaa Ja'a pasanèd'e lii se'e, sèna ka miu bisa pakaj'èu nèti koasa sasala-sasigo miu.<bt>In fact, I don't need a witness [message here, not person] from humans. But I remind (you) of these things, so that you can obtain life/be saved from the power of your *wrongs/sins.</bt><v n="35" />Lii padhai Yohanis ne, nuka sèmi labhu èci dhu heo pasaraa miu. Ropa heo na d'elo miu era, d'ara miu karej'e-karae.<bt>Yohanis' message was like a lingt that shines brightly on you-pl. When his light was still burning/shining, your insides were happy (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="delo"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-25 01:17:19Z" status="Anyone">loti; menyinar, senter</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Aa te ngaa Ja'a abhu Dhèu èci dhu kapai risi eele nèti Yohanis dhu peka mola-mola lula-nèti Ja'a ne. Nèngu, nuka Ama Ku ètu sorga, dhu pangèd'u mi Ja'a sasab'a ae-ae, sèna ka sab'a toke pa'èle. Sasab'a ae se'e ka dhu j'aj'i mi tadha, na, Ama ka dhu pua Ja'a.<bt>But in fact there is a Person who is greater/more incredible than Yohanis who speaks the truth about Me. He is My Father in heaven who has turned over much work/handed over many responsibilities to Me, so that (I will) carry them out until completed. These tasks/responsibilities (that I carry out) are what show sign/evidence that Father is the one who sent/commissioned Me. [EXEG: Carson (totality of Christ's work), NLT “my teachings &amp; my miracles”.]</bt><v n="37" />Lula Nèngu ka dhu pua-paleha Ja'a, Nèngu ka dhu peka mola-mola lula-nèti Ja'a kahèi. Miu mesa mi tadèngi mèdhi mèka lii Nèngu, do, patoo madha dènge madha, aa ladhe mèdhi mèka rèhu Na.<bt>Because He who sent/commissioned Me, also speaks the truth about Me. You-pl yourselves have never heard His voice, or seen Him face-to-face.</bt><note reference="5:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 3:17, Markus 1:11, Lukas 3:22</note><v n="38" />Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua mamuri boe ètu d'ara miu, lula miu parcaya boe Ja'a dhu Nèngu pua mai.<bt>God2's Words/Message (doublet) does not live in your insides, because you don't believe in Me, whom He sent/commissioned.</bt><v n="39" />Miu d'èi parisa toke lutu Sasuri Mola-Mèci Lamatua, lula miu pangee, na, bèli-camèd'a miu abhu j'ara ho abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. Aa te ngaa Sasuri sèra ka dhu lole lula-nèti Ja'a ne.<bt>You like to carefully examine in detail the *Scriptures (God2's Clean/Holy/Pure Writings, because you think that you will find/encounter/obtain the way to get/obtain real life which does not end. In fact, those Writings tell about Me.</bt><v n="40" />Te ngaa miu mo'o boe ara mai asa Ja'a, ho j'aj'i dhèu Ja'a, sèna ka abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe.<bt>But you don't want to approach Me, to become My person, so that you can get/obtain that real life that never ends.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ara mai"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-25 01:24:25Z" status="Anyone">maju ; mendekatkan diri</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Ja'a parluu boe dhèu ded'e kolongara Ja'a padedha-dedha.<bt>I don't need for people to elevate/honour My name-reputation.</bt><v n="42" />Lula Ja'a ke'a mèu d'ara iiki miu. Nèti èèna ka Ja'a ke'a, na, miu sue boe Ama Lamatua.<bt>But I clearly know your inner insides. That is why I know that you do not love God.</bt><v n="43" />Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne, lula Ama Ku dhu nèd'u koasa ka pua Ja'a mai. Te ngaa miu mo'o boe sèmi mere Ja'a. Aa te ngaa ladhe dhèu leo dhu mai pake koasa nèngu, miu sèmi mere ne dènge be'a.<bt>I came to this world, because My Father who holds power/authority was sending/commissioning Me to come. But you did not accept Me. Whereas, if there was another person who came using his own authority, you would accept/receive him well/nicely.</bt><v n="44" />Miu èci dènge èci d'èi sèna ka abhu koa-kad'iri. Te ngaa miu pusi-pahae boe, ladhe Ama Lamatua koa miu, do aad'o. Aa te ngaa Nèngu èèna, Ama Lamatua! Abhu boe dhu leo. De ladhe miu pahae boe Ne, na, tasamia miu bisa parcaya Nèngu?<bt>You each like to get praise (doublet). But you don't care if God praises you, or not. In fact/keep in mind, He is God2! There is no other. So (consequently), if you don't care about Him, how could you believe in Him?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Baku pangee, na, Ja'a pèci sasala mi dedha miu ètu katanga madha Ama Ku. Aad'o. Dhu pèci sasala sa dedha miu nuka Musa. Aa te ngaa, era maena miu ka nèngu, lula nèngu ka dhu hia miu Atora Ama Lamatua.<bt>Don't think that I am the one blaming/accusing you in front of My Father. No. The one who is accusing you, is Musa. Whereas in fact, you-pl are hoping in him, because he is the one who gave (you) God2's Regulations/Law.</bt><v n="46" />De ladhe miu lèka Musa, tatu miu parcaya Ja'a tare'a-re'a. Te nèngu ka dhu suri lula-nèti Ja'a ne.<bt>So, if you believed2 in Musa, surely you would also believe1 in Me. [NOTE: Lexical variety is preferred style over lexical repetition.] Cuz (elaboration) he is the one who wrote about Me.</bt><v n="47" />Te ngaa lula miu parcaya èra boe mi ngaa dhu na suri, tasamia ka miu bisa lèka ngaa dhu Ja'a peka-padhai? Aad'o, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>But because you don't really/truly believe1 what he wrote, how could you/are you going to believe2 what I say/My message (doublet)? (You) won't, right?</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus panga'a dhèu lèmi riho risi<bt>The Lord Yesus feeds more that five thousand people</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 14:13-21; Markus 6:30-44; Lukas 9:10-17)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="6" />
      <v n="1-4" />Lod'o kalela Paska dhèu Yahudi oe dètu. Hèia Yesus si lasi asa cabèka dano Galilea. (Ngara leo dano ne, &lt;dano Tiberias&gt;.) Dhèu ae dhu madhutu Ne, lula rèdhi tadha-tadha malaa dhu Na tao, lod'o puri-pa'èle dhèu-dhèu pèd'a. D'ai cabèka dano, Yesus dènge ana-ana madhutu Na ca'e asa ledhe iiki èci. Hèia ra madhèdi ètu era èèna.<bt>The time of the Yahudi people's festival/feast/holiday ‘Paska’ was nearing. Then Yesus (coll.) went to the other side of lake Galilea. (That lake's other name, is ‘lake Tiberias’.) Many people followed Him there, because they saw the various amazing signs which He had done when He healed (doublet) sick people. Arriving at the other side of the lake, Yesus and His disciples went up a small mountain. Then they sat there. [DISCOURSE: Time frame fronted for target language background-foreground patterns.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ropa Yesus ladhe nèdhi dhèu ae mai pakaboko, hèia Na karèi ana madhutu Na ca dhèu, ngara na Pelipus, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ètu era mia èdhi bisa hèli nganga'a, ho hia dhèu se ra'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus saw there were many people coming gathering (together), He asked one of His disciples, named Pelipus, saying, “Where can we-inc buy food to give these people to eat?”</bt><v n="6" />Yesus ne'a le ngaa dhu Nèngu neo tao. Te ngaa Na peka sèmi èèna, sèna ka neo sèku Pelipus.<bt>Yesus already knew what He was going to do. But He spoke like that to test Pelipus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka Pelipus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Masi ka gaji tuka ca dhèu dua ngasu lod'o èèna ka, d'ai mèka hèli roti ho panga'a dhèu udhu sobhu-sobhu se! Masi ka ca dhèu abhu roti ciki oo'e èèna ka, pad'ai boe hèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>And Pelipus responded, saying, “Waa! [+dismay, annoyance] Even the wages of a craftsman for 200 days, would still not be enough to buy bread to feed these heaps of people (idiomatic)! Even for each person to get a little bit of bread, it would still not be enough!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia, ca dhèu hari nèti ana madhutu Na, ngara na Anderias, ari Simon Petrus, peka dènge Yesus, aku nèngu na,<bt>Then, another one of Yesus' disciples, named Anderias, that is Simon Petrus' younger brother, told Yesus, saying,</bt><v n="9" />&lt;&lt;Ama! Ana iiki èci ètu ne'e nèti roti lèmi bua, dènge i'a dua ngi'u. Te ngaa d'ai dhèu ae-ae se ra'a, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>“Father! There is one child here who brought five loaves (lit: fruit) of bread, and two fish. But it's likely/probably not enough to feed this many people!” [CHECK /batulai/ likely/probably Lena not know]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="batulai"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-25 01:41:14Z" status="Anyone">mungkin [CHECK; Lena not know]</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-09 04:55:00Z">2 UNS not know</Message></Annotation><note reference="6:9" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri uuru lii Yunani peka na, roti sèra tao nèti <span class="Italic">krithinos.</span> Alkitab lii Idhonesia suri na, &lt;jelai&gt;. Lamusi na oe sèmi tarae.<bt>The original Yunani language writings write, saying, they made this bread from <span class="Italic">krithinos.</span> The Indonesian language Bible writes it is &lt;jelai&gt;. It's seeds are very similar to ‘Rote corn’ (a barley/sorghum type of grain).</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ètu era ne'e, j'u'u muri ae-ae. Ka Yesus peka dènge ana madhutu Na, &lt;&lt;Ator si madhèdi.&gt;&gt; Hèia dhèu se madhèdi ka. Lod'o èèna, dhèu ae titu kèna. Dhèu mone di, pe d'ai lèmi riho dhèu sa.<bt>There, there was a lot of living grass [NOTE: grass here defaults to picked/cut grass, for feeding animals]. So Yesus told His disciples, “Arrange for them to all sit down.” And those people sat down. At that time, there were a great many people! Just the men numbered around five thousand.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia Yesus nare roti se, ka Na manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua. Ka Na pangèd'u mi ana madhutu Na sèra. Sèna ka rèngu bagi hia dhèu se aa'i-aa'i ra. Na tao sèmi èèna kahèi dènge i'a sèra. Dhèu se aa'i-aa'i ra'a toke bècu.<bt>Then Yesus took that bread (pl), and He gave thanks to God. Then He handed it out to His disciples. So they went and divided it out to all those people. He did the same with those fish. Everyone ate until full. [EXEG: Gk is “he divided...”, but in 10 and 12 he has the disciples doing the work. So we have it indirect.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa ra'a toke bècu, hèia Yesus peka dènge ana-ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pakaboko mere nganga'a dhu sisa se'e, sèna ka baku core eele iia d'ara.&gt;&gt;<bt>When everyone had eaten until full, Yesus told His disciples, saying, “Gather up the leftover food, so there is nothing wasted needlessly.”</bt><v n="13" />Ka ra pakaboko nganga'a dhu sisa nèti roti lèmi bua deo sa, pènu canguru dua soe.<bt>So they gathered up the leftover food from those five loaves of bread, to the point that they filled full 12 /soe/ baskets.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ropa dhèu ae-ae se ladhe rèdhi tadha malaa dhu Yesus tao ne, hèia ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Nèngu ne, tatu Dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu Na jaji le neo hia mai.&gt;&gt;<bt>When the crowds saw the amazing sign that Yesus had done, they said, “Ira ii! [+amazement] He here, is surely that *Spokesperson that God2 promised to send coming/here.” [DISCOURSE: “into the world” made implicit.]</bt><v n="15" />Yesus ne'a, na, dhèu se neo laka-seti Ne sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu aae. Hèia la'e tèke eele si, ka Na ca'e asa era kaj'èu ètu ledhe iiki èci, sèna ka Nèngu mesa Na ètu era èèna.<bt>Yesus knew that the crowds wanted to force Him to become king. So/then He went leaving them, and went further up on a small mountain, so that He could be alone there.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus kako ètu dedha èi<bt>The Lord Yesus walks on water</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 14:22-33; Markus 6:45-52)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ropa lod'o heka cèna, ana-ana madhutu Yesus puru lasi asa sebhe dano.<bt>When the sun had just set/drowned, Yesus' disciples walked/went down to the edge of the lake.</bt><v n="17" />Yesus mai mèka pa'èci dènge rèngu. Ka ra ca'e koha cue, hèia ra tuku lasi asa kota Kapernaum ètu cabèka dano. Ropa rèngu pakèd'i, lod'o dhu maroga le.<bt>Yesus had not yet come to join with them. Then they embarked on a boat, and began to row to/toward the city of Kapernaum on the other side of the lake. When they left, it was already dark.</bt><v n="18" />Lula ngèlu aae, ka naha mulai kapai.<bt>Then a great wind (blew), resulting in large waves.</bt><v n="19" />Ropa ana madhutu Yesus se'e tuku kaj'èu pe d'ai lèmi kilometer sa, hèia ladhe rèdhi Yesus dhu kako re dedha èi. Na mai padètu-dètu dènge koha rèngu, ka ra madha'u titu kèna.<bt>When Yesus' disciples had rowed about five kilometers, they saw/happened to see Yesus walking on the water. He came very close to their boat, and they were terrified/very afraid.</bt><v n="20" />Te ngaa Yesus lii dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Baku madha'u! Te Ja'a ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus spoke to them, saying, “Don't be afraid! It's Me here.”</bt><v n="21" />Nèti èèna ka, rèngu madha'u heka. Aa ra neo sèna ka Yesus ca'e sama-sama dènge rèngu. Cag'ag'a laa, koha ne d'ai le dae dhu rèngu neo lasi.<bt>Because of that, they weren't afraid anymore. And they wanted Yesus to get into the boat with them. Without being aware of it/Unnoticed, the boat had arrived at the place they were going to.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu ae mai tenge Lamatua Yesus<bt>People kept looking for the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22-24" />Asa bèli èèna, dhèu ae sèra ètu cabèka dano era. Rèngu padètu iiki dènge era dhu med'a na Yesus manèngi makasi mi Ama Lamatua, ropa hia si ra'a. Hèia dhèu se re'a, na, med'a na koha dhoka cue di ètu era èèna. Te ngaa ana madhutu Yesus se pake koha ne, lasi tèke eele era ne'e, aa Yesus dhu ca'e boe dènge rèngu.<bt>The next day, the crowds were still on the other side of the lake. They were near the place where the previous day Yesus had given thanks to God, when (He) fed them. They found out/came to realise that yesterday/the previous day there had only been one boat at that place. But Yesus' disciples had already used that boat to leave that place. And Yesus himself had not embarked with them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa abhu pèri-pèri koha leo nèti kota Tiberias dhu lasi-mai ètu era èèna. Hèia, ropa dhèu ae se re'a, na, Yesus dènge ana-ana madhutu Na dhu aad'o heka, ka ra ca'e koha leo sèra lasi tenge Yesus asa Kapernaum, ètu cabèka dano.<bt>But there were several other boats from the city of Tiberias who often came to-from that place. So, when the crowds found out/came to understand that Yesus and His disciples were no longer there, they got into those other boats, to go look for Yesus in Kapernaum, on the other side of the lake.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus nuka sèmi Roti dhu nèti mamuri<bt>The Lord Yesus is like Bread which brings life</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ka ra paraga dènge Yesus ètu cabèka dano. Hèia ra karèi Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Ama d'ai era ne'e sange mera mia sa?&gt;&gt;<bt>So/then they found/met Yesus on the other side of the lake. And they asked Him, saying, “Father Teacher! When did you arrive here?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Dhu lèke sèmi ne'e: miu se tenge Ja'a lula boe miu mèdhi le tadha-tadha malaa, te ngaa lula Ja'a panga'a miu toke bècu.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “In truth it's like this: you-pl are looking for Me not because you have seen various amazing signs, but because I fed you, to the point that you got full.</bt><v n="27" />Nanene paie-iie! Baku sab'a tenge dhoka nganga'a di dhu bèli-camèd'a ele iie d'ara. Te ngaa be'a risi miu sab'a sèna ka abhu nganga'a dhu taha taruu, dhu nèti mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. Te Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Ja'a ka dhu bisa hia miu mamuri èèna. Te Ama ètu sorga pangèd'u le hak mi Ja'a ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Listen carefully! Don't just work to get food which will disappear. It would be better to work to get food which keeps/perseveres on, which brings real/true life that doesn't stop. Cuz (elaboration) I am the *Son of Man. I am the one who can give you that life. Cuz (elaboration) Father in heaven has given/turned over that right/authority to Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Hèia dhèu se karèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, na, ji'i hud'i tao tasamia, sèna ka bisa pakako sasab'a Ama Lamatua?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they asked, saying, “If that's the case, na, what must we-exc do so that we can carry out God's work?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sasab'a Lamatua, sèmi ne'e ka: miu hud'i parcaya ku Ja'a ne. Te Ama Lamatua ka dhu pua Ja'a mai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “God2's work is like this: you must believe in Me. Cuz (elaboration) God is the one who sent/commissioned Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Hèia dhèu se karèi hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama neo pad'elo tadha malaa sèmi ngaa, ho ji'i ngèdhi aa parcaya Ama? Aa Ama neo tao ngaa hari hia ji'i?<bt>Then they asked again, saying, “What amazing sign are You going to show, so we can see it, and believe in You? And/Furthermore, what else are You going to do for us? [NLT]</bt><v n="31" />Nuka sèmi uru-uru sèra, bèi-baki ji'i ra'a roti <span class="Italic">manna </span>ètu d'ara mamoo. Èèna nuka sèmi dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua, peka na, &lt;Nèngu hia si roti dhu mai nèti dedha-liru, sèna ka ra'a.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>For example, long ago our-inc ancestors ate the <span class="Italic">manna</span> bread in the empty place. That is like what is written in the *Scriptures, saying, ‘He gave them bread which came from the sky/heaven, for them to eat.’”</bt><note reference="6:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 16:4, 15, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 78:24</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ka Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a peka dhu lèke sèmi ne'e: uru èèna, Musa boe ka dhu papuru roti èèna nèti dedha-liru hia mi bèi-baki miu. Te dhu papuru mai roti èèna, nuka Ama Ku ètu sorga. Limuri ne Na sadia hia miu roti nèti liru kahèi. Te ngaa roti ne'e ne, Roti dhu tare'a-re'a taha toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>Yesus responded, “I tell (you) what is true like this: formerly/long ago, it was not Musa who sent down that bread from the sky to your ancestors (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) the one who sent that bread down, was My Father in heaven. Now He is also prepared to give you-pl bread from the sky/heaven. But this bread (that I'm talking about), is the true/real Bread that keeps/perseveres on forever. [NLT, Carson; NOTE to daughter translations: “true bread” should somehow link to vs. 27 “food that lasts for eternal life”.]</bt><v n="33" />Te Roti nèti Lamatua ne, nuka, Dhu puru mai nèti sorga aa nèti mamuri hia mi dhèu ètu rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) this Bread from God2 is the One who descends/comes down from heaven and brings life to people in this world.” [NOTE to daughter translations: if the “yang” construction is difficult in other lgs, try “Dia yang”.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Hèia dhèu se manèngi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Hia taruu ji'i roti èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>So/then the people requested, saying, “Father! Keep giving that bread to us!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ka Yesus peka dènge si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne'e ka, Roti èèna. Te Ja'a ka dhu kèti mamuri dhu lèke. De dhèu dhu j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a, manganga heka! Aa dhèu dhu parcaya Ja'a, koko-kamango heka!<bt>Then Yesus told/explained to them, saying, “I am that Bread. Cuz (elaboration) I am the one who brings real life. So (consequently) people who become My people, will not be hungry anymore! And people who believe in Me, will not be thirsty anymore!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Te ngaa Ja'a peka kèdhi le dènge miu, na, masi ka miu mèdhi le Ja'a, te ngaa miu parcaya mèka Ja'a.<bt>But I have told you that even though you have seen Me, nevertheless you still don't believe in Me.</bt><v n="37" />Aa te ngaa dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama Ku hag'e nare le ho j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a rèngu mai asa Ja'a. Aa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu mai asa Ja'a, tatu Ja'a babège eele boe ne!<bt>Whereas, everyone whom My Father has chosen to be/become My people, they will come to Me. And if/when a person comes to Me, it is not likely/probable that I will evict/kick him out! [+understatement]</bt><v n="38" />Te Ja'a mai nèti dedha-liru. Ja'a mai sèna ka sab'a madhutu dad'èi Ama Ku, lula Nèngu ka dhu pua Ja'a. Ja'a ko'o boe madhutu dhoka dad'èi Ja'a mesa Ku.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I came down from the sky/heaven (doublet). I came to do according to My Father's will/desires, because He is the one who sent/commissioned Me. I don't just want to do My own will.</bt><v n="39" />Dad'èi Ama Lamatua sèmi ne'e: nèti dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu Nèngu hag'e nare le ho j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a, Nèngu d'èi Ja'a oru-kaboko si aa'i-aa'i. Ja'a bisa boe soro tèke ca dhèu sa ele. Te ngaa ladhe lod'o d'ai èle rai-haha ne, Ja'a pamamuri hari si.<bt>And God's will is like this: from all the people whom He has chosen to become My people, He wants Me to gather/collect (doublet) all of them. I am not allowed/ permitted to let one of them disappear/be lost. But later at the end of the world, I must make them live again/ come back to life. [EXEG: NLT, Carson, Morris; NOTE: the vague Gk. phrase “raise up at the last day” occurs in vs. 39, 40, 44, 54. So there needs to be cohesion. MEANING: NRSV “raise up”, NLT “raise from dead”, CEV “raise to life”, HCE “bring back to life”; Carlton (TRT) “raise from the dead”; Carson “This preservation of each individual in the collective of the elect includes resurrection at the last day. ... in clear references to the final resurrection (vv. 39, 40, 44, 54), ... All of this explanation is part of the bread of life discourse. These verses not only contribute to the explanation as to why some believe and some do not, but, culminating in the promise of eternal, resurrection life,...” Morris “a future resurrection.... It is unthinkable that death should blot out forever the life that Christ gives. Because he is what he is, he will assuredly raise up those to whom he gives life.” Compare with similar phrasing “resurrection at the last day” in 11:24. LEX: it doesn't seem the Gk word can support the sense of “take up to heaven”--which is a possible reading of the English. (In Gk the object changes position or state, but not location). Theological PROBLEM: what about those who are not dead, i.e. 1 Thess. 4:14-17? But should views on theology be driving the translation? Or should the text? The translation principles we subscribe to say we have to be guided by the text. Apparently John is not addressing that issue here.]</bt><v n="40" />Nuka sèmi dhu Ja'a peka deo na, Ama Ku d'èi sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tadhe aa parcaya Ja'a, nuka Ana Na, èèna na rèngu bisa abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. Hèia ètu lod'o èle rai-haha, Ja'a pamamuri hari si.&gt;&gt;<bt>It's like I said earlier, My Father wants for everyone who knows and believes in Me, that is His Child (here), they can get/obtain real life that never ends. Then later at the end of the world, I will bring them back to life/make them live again.” [EXEG: “who sent me” made implicit as in NLT to reduce heavy information load. It's in vs.38.; on “raise up at the last day” see note at 6:39.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Ka ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se mulai ka'uu-kamuki, lula Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Roti dhu mai nèti Lamatua èèna, nuka Ja'a dhu mai nèti sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the Yahudi people's leaders began to grumble/complain (doublet), because Yesus said, “That Bread from God2 is Me, who came from heaven.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Ra padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka sèmi ne'e? Dhèu ne'e ne, Yesus ana Yusuf, si? Ji'i tadhe ina-ama Na. De tasamia ka Nèngu ne peka na, &lt;Ja'a mai nèti sorga?&gt; Abhu ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>They talked (reciprocally), saying, “How is this? This Person here, is Yesus, Yusuf's child, right? We-exc know His mother-father. So (consequently) how is it that now He says, ‘I came from heaven’? Where does He get that?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="43" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Eee! Loe eele ku ka'uu-kamuki!<bt>Yesus spoke to them, saying, “Eee! Stop that grumbling there!</bt><v n="44" />Ama Ku ètu sorga ka pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne. Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu bisa mai asa Ja'a, ladhe Ama Ku lere boe ne mai. Aa d'ai lod'o èle rai-haha, Ja'a pamamuri hari si.<bt>My Father in heaven is the one who sent/ commissioned Me to come here to earth. Nobody can come to Me, if My Father does not bring/escort him. So later at the end of the world, I will bring them back to life. [EXEG: NLT; on “raise up at the last day” see note at 6:39.]</bt><v n="45" />Dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua uru-uru sèra suri rèdhi le, peka na, &lt;Ama Lamatua neo aj'a-nori dhèu aa'i-aa'i.&gt; De dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu nanene Ama ètu sorga, aa rèngu abhu aj'a-nori nèti Nèngu, rèngu mai sa Ja'a, sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a.<bt>God2's spokespeople long ago once wrote, saying, ‘God want to teach everyone.’ So (consequently) everyone who listens to/obeys Father in heaven, and learns from Him, they come to Me to become My people.</bt><note reference="6:45" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 54:13</note><v n="46" />Ja'a ne ka dhu puru mai nèti Ama Lamatua. De dhoka Ja'a mesa-mesa Ku kèdhi Ne. Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu patoo madha dènge Ama ètu sorga.<bt>I here and the one who came down from God. So (consequently), I alone am the only one who has ever seen Him. There is not a single other person who has ever faced Father in heaven directly.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Tare'a! Ja'a peka dènge miu kèna! Dhèu dhu parcaya Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe.<bt>That's right! I'm telling you straight! The person/whoever believes in Me, will get real life that never ends.</bt><v n="48" />Te Ja'a ne, nuka Roti dhu nèti mamuri èèna.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I am the Bread that brings that life (that I've been talking about).</bt><v n="49" />Uru-uru sèra, bèi-baki miu ra'a roti <span class="Italic">manna </span>lod'o ra kako rai-reo d'ara mamoo. Masi ka ra'a le roti èèna, te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu madhe kahèi.<bt>Formerly/long ago, your ancestors ate <span class="Italic">manna</span> bread while the walked wandering in the empty place. Even though they ate that bread, nevertheless eventually they also died.</bt><v n="50" />Te ngaa Roti dhu limuri ne puru mai nèti sorga, leko-leo. Te dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa ra'a. Sasoa na, dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu parcaya Ja'a, rèngu cèri eele heka nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>But the Bread which comes down from heaven now is different. Cuz (elaboration) everyone is allowed to eat it. That means that everyone who believes in Me, they will not be separated off/cut off from God anymore. [HCE]</bt><v n="51" />Lula Ja'a ne, Roti dhu nèti mamuri, dhu mai nèti sorga. Pe ladhe Ja'a madhe, Ja'a soro ngi'u Ja'a sèna ka madhe pala dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne, ho ra bisa mamuri. Aa dhèu dhu ra'a Roti ne, rèngu abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I am the Bread that brings life, that comes down from heaven. So, later when I die, I turn over/surrender My body so that everyone in this world can live. And people who eats that Bread, they are the ones who will get/obtain real life that never ends.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Ropa ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se tadèngi rare lii padhai Yesus ne, hèia ra pab'ala èci dènge èci, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Na padhai lii sèmi ngaa ka nèi? Tasamia ka Dhèu ne bisa hia ngi'u Na, èdhi ta'e?&gt;&gt;<bt>Hearing what Yesus said, the Yahudi people's leaders began to argue with each other, saying, “What's He saying/talking about? How can this Person give His body for us-inc to eat?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="53" />Hèia Yesus peka dènge si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a padhai lii dhu mola-mola dènge miu kèna. Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. Dhèu dhu neo mamuri lèke, hud'i pa'èki ku dènge Ja'a. De ladhe miu mi'a boe ngi'u Ja'a, aa minu boe raa Ja'a, na, miu abhu boe mamuri dhu lèke.<bt>And Yesus told/explained to them, saying, “I'm telling the truth to you. I am the *Son of Man (Authentic/Ideal Human). The person who wants real life must be bound/linked to Me. So (consequently) if you-pl do not eat My body, and do not drink My blood, na, there is no real life in you. [EXEG for ftn: Carson notes that there are significant problems with interpreting this as primarily a reference to the Eucharist, and favours vs.53-54 as a metaphorical repetition of vs. 40, where it is “see and believe”; Morris agrees it is not primarily about the Eucharist but about belief and relationship. “Eating and drinking Christ’s flesh and blood thus appears to be a very graphic way of saying that people must take Christ into their innermost being. ... a challenge to enter the closest and most intimate relation with him.”]</bt><note reference="6:53-54" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ropa Yesus peka na, ta'e ngi'u Nèngu dènge tinu raa Na, sasoa na, dhèu hud'i parcaya Nèngu aa mamuri pa'èki dènge Ne taruu. Pakasame dènge <span class="Italic">Yohanis </span>6:40.<bt>When Yesus spoke about eating His body, and drinking His blood, the meaning is that people must believe in Him and live bound/linked with Him continually. Compare with <span class="Italic">Yohanis</span> 6:40.</bt></note><v n="54" />Te dhèu dhu ra'e ngi'u Ja'a, aa rinu raa Ja'a, rèngu abhu le mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. D'ai lod'o èle rai-haha, Ja'a pamamuri hari ne.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the person who eats My body, and drinks My blood, has already gotten/obtained real life that never ends. So later at the end of the world, I will bring him back to life. [EXEG: on “raise up at the last day” see note at 6:39.]</bt><v n="55" />Te nganga'a dhu lèke, nuka ngi'u Ja'a. Aa nganginu dhu lèke, nuka raa Ja'a.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the real food is My body. and the real drink is My blood.</bt><v n="56" />De dhèu dhu ra'a ngi'u Ja'a, dènge rinu raa Ja'a, mamuri ra dhu pa'èki dènge Ja'a. Aa Ja'a pa'èki dènge rèngu.<bt>So (consequently) the person who eats My body, and drinks My blood, is living bound/linked to Me, And I am also bound/linked with him.</bt><v n="57" />Ama ètu sorga dhu pua Ja'a, Nèngu mamuri tare'a-re'a. Aa Ja'a abhu mamuri dhu lèke nèti Nèngu kahèi. Nèti èèna ka dhèu dhu na'e ngi'u Ja'a, nèngu unu mamuri dhu lèke nèti Ja'a kahèi.<bt>Father in heaven who sent/commissioned Me, He really lives/is alive. And I also get/obtain real life from Him. That's why the person who eats My body, he will also later get real life from Me.</bt><v n="58" />Uru-uru sèra, bèi-baki miu ra'a roti <span class="Italic">manna </span>nèti dedha-liru. Masi ka rèngu ra'a, te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu rèngu madhe kahèi. Te ngaa Roti dhu mai nèti sorga ne, leko-leo. Te dhèu dhu ra'a Roti ne, bèli-camèd'a abhu mamuri dhu lèke&gt;&gt;.<bt>Formerly/long ago, your ancestors ate that <span class="Italic">manna</span> bread from heaven. Even though they ate (it), nevertheless eventually they also died. But the Bread that comes from heaven now, is different. Cuz (elaboration) the person who eats this Bread will get real life.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="59" />Yesus aj'a j'ara se'e ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a dhèu Yahudi cue ètu kota Kapernaum.<bt>Yesus taught this issue/matter in one of the Yahudi people's house of worship in the city of Kapernaum.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu ae tèke eele Lamatua Yesus<bt>Many people leave/abandon the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="60" />Dhèu ae dhu madhutu Yesus. Ropa rèngu tadèngi lii padhai Na sèmi èèna, hèia abhu dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;A'aj'a Na, bia! Cee ka dhu bisa sèmi rare a'aj'a èèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>[There were] many people who followed Yesus. When they heard Him teach like that, there were those that spoke, saying, “That teaching of His is heavy/difficult/hard! Who can accept that teaching?” [EXEG: (Carson, Morris, Carlton) not hard to understand, but hard to accept, offended their sensibilities [also NRSV, NLT, NIV] See also context of vs.61-66.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="61" />Te ngaa Yesus dhu ne'a le lii padhai rèngu se, hèia Na karèi si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'aj'a ne tao miu susa, do?<bt>But Yesus found out/came to know they were grumbling (among themselves) like that, so He asked them, saying, “Does this teaching cause difficulty for you-pl?</bt><v n="62" />Tasamia hari, ladhe miu mèdhi Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, ca'e hari asa era pea Ja'a uru èèna?<bt>How about if/when you see Me, the Son of Man, ascend back up there, to My former place of residence?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="63" />Roh Lamatua ka dhu nèti mamuri dhu lèke. Mamuri dhu lèke mai boe nèti ngi'u dhèu. Te ngaa Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a kapua na nèti Roh Ama Lamatua. De Lii Holo-Nori ne'e bisa hia mamuri dhu lèke mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i kahèi.<bt>God2's Spirit is the one that brings real/true life. Real/true life does not come/originate from a person's body. But My Words/Message (doublet) are rooted/sourced in God's Spirit. So (consequently) those Words/Message can also bring real life to all people.</bt><v n="64" />Te ngaa abhu nèti miu cahag'e dhu lèka boe Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>But there are some of you who don't believe2 (in) Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yesus peka sèmi ne'e, lula Nèngu dhu ne'a le karèi nèti uru j'ara, cee dhu parcaya boe, aa cee ka dhu èèna na pahie eele Nèngu.<bt>Yesus spoke like that, because He already knew from the beginning who it was that didn't believe, and who it was that would later sell Him off (=betray Him).</bt><v n="65" />Hèia Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a peka mema le dènge miu, na, Ama Ku ètu sorga hud'i bhoke uuru ku j'ara hia dhèu, heka dhèu ne bisa mai j'aj'i dhèu unu Ja'a kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>And He spoke further, saying, “That is why I have told you that My Father in heaven must open the way for people first, only then can that person come (and) become My person.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="66" />Karèi nèti lod'o èèna, ana madhutu Na ae ka dhu tèke eele Ne, lula rèngu ro'o heka madhutu Nèngu.<bt>Beginning from that time, there were many of His disciples who pulled left/abandoned Him, because they didn't want to follow Him anymore.</bt><v n="67" />Ka Yesus karèi ana madhutu Na dhèu canguru dua sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aa miu tasamia? Neo tèke eele Ja'a kahèi, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked his twelve disciples, saying, “And how about you-pl? Do you also want to leave/abandon Me?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="68" />Te ngaa Simon Petrus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i patai-patapa mi cee hari? Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu bisa lole dènge ji'i, j'ara tasamia ji'i bisa abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. Dhoka Èu mesa Mu di!<bt>But Simon Petrus responded, saying, “Father! Who else would we lean on (doublet) [put our hope in]? There is nobody else who can tell/explain to us-exc, how we can get/obtain that real life that never ends. Only You alone!</bt><v n="69" />Aa ji'i lèka Ama. Lula ji'i dhu nge'a le, na, Èu ne, nuka Dhèu Mola-Mèci nèti Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>And we believe2 in You. Because we know that You here are God's Holy/Clean/Pure Person.”</bt><note reference="6:68-69" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:16, Markus 8:29, Lukas 9:20</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="70" />Ka Yesus peka dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a hag'e kore le miu dhèu canguru dua. Te ngaa sanèd'e! Nèti miu se'e, abhu ca dhèu nuka sèmi nidhu!&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus told them, saying, “I have chosen the twelve of you. But remember! There is one of you people who is like an evil spirit!”</bt><v n="71" />Dhu Na peka ne, nuka Yudas, ana Simon Iskariot. Yudas ne, ca dhèu nèti ana madhutu Na dhèu canguru dua sèra. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu èèna na pahie Yesus.<bt>The one He was meaning was Yudas, Simon Iskariot's child. That Yudas was one of His twelve disciples. He is the one who would later sell off Yesus (=betray).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus dènge ari Na sèra<bt>The Lord Yesus and His younger siblings</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="7" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna, hèia Yesus si kako palème propensi Galilea. Nèngu neo boe kako palème propensi Yudea, lula abhu ama-ama dhèu Yahudi dhu neo pamadhe Ne.<bt>After that, Yesus (coll.) walked/went around/throughout the province of Galilea. He didn't want to go around in the province of Yudea, because there were leaders of the Yahudi people there who wanted to kill Him.</bt><v n="2" />Lod'o èèna, dètu le dènge lod'o kalela puu-g'ètu dhu ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Kalela Paleo&gt;&gt;.<bt>At that time, approached the Yahudi people's harvest festival that they called “Canopy Festival”.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Pesta Teng"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-09 07:59:20Z" status="Anyone">èmu maa = ruma jaga kebun</Message></Annotation><note reference="7:2" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">&lt;Kalela Paleo&gt; ne, d'ai aru lod'o kateme. Pesta ne rame titu kèna. Lod'o kalela puu-g'ètu ne era, dhèu Isra'el pea ètu d'ara paleo dhu rèngu patitu ètu èmu ra. Paleo ne pasanèd'e rèngu, lod'o uru èèna bèi-baki si dhu pea ètu d'ara paleo ètu d'ara mamoo. Paleo ne èci èèna ka dènge èmu maa dhu dhèu patitu ètu d'ara oka, lod'o hèru puu-g'ètu. Baca ètu sasuri <span class="Italic">Kalua nèti Masir </span>23:16; <span class="Italic">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama</span> 23:33-36, 39-43; <span class="Italic">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri </span>16:13-15; aa sasuri <span class="Italic">Sakaria </span>14:16-19.<bt>[Adapted from Carlton TRT] The ‘Canopy Festival’ ran for 8 days. That festival was very festive. While that harvest festival was going, the people of Isra'el lived temporarily under canopies2/tents/temporary shelters which they erected at their houses. Those canopies2/temporary shelters reminded them that long ago their ancestors had also lived under canopies2 when they were going around in the empty place. That canopy2 was also like the garden huts people erected in their fields during the harvest season. Read about it in <span class="Italic">Going out from Egypt</span> 23:16; <span class="Italic">Regulations of the Priests</span> 23:33-36, 39-43; <span class="Italic">Retelling about the Life Way</span> 16:13-15; and <span class="Italic">Sakaria</span> 14:16-19.</bt></note><v n="3" />Ka ari Yesus sèra peka dènge Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a risi, Èu pakeso nèti ne'e, lamu asa Yudea. Sèna ka dhèu dhu madhutu Èu ètu nèi, bisa ladhe rèdhi j'ara-j'ara dhu Èu tao.<bt>Then Yesus' younger siblings told Him, saying, “It would be better if You get out of here and go to Yudea. So that the people who follow You there (remote) can also be able to see the various things that You are doing.</bt><v n="4" />Te ladhe cee dhu neo sèna ka dhèu ae rèdhi kolo-karisi nèngu, na, nèngu baku tao pahuni-pahuni. Lula Èu dhu tao tadha malaa rupa-rupa, be'a risi hari, ladhe dhèu ae-ae bisa ladhe rèdhi ngaa dhu Èu tao sèra!&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if a person wants many people to see what he excels at (doublet), na, he shouldn't do it in secret. Because You are doing various sorts of amazing signs, it would be even better if many people could be able to see those things You are doing!”</bt><v n="5" />Ari Na sèra peka sèmi èèna, lula rèngu dhu lèka Nèngu èra iia boe.<bt>His younger siblings spoke like that, because they themselves didn't have much confidence/trust in Him. [EXEG: episteuon: here ‘trust, reliance, have confidence in’; (LN, Carson) they did not understand the significance of what they saw, nor his real identity, so they didn't trust/have confidence in him to do what made sense on their terms.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Lod'o Ja'a dhae d'ai mèka. Te ngaa ladhe miu neo lami, sad'i lake mere.<bt>And Yesus responded, saying, “It's like this. At this time, My time has not yet arrived. But if you-pl want to go, you can go whenever/at any time.</bt><v n="7" />Dhèu ètu rai-haha ne tèka boe d'ara dènge miu. Te ngaa rèngu tèka d'ara dènge Ja'a, lula Ja'a bhoke patalele aa'i tatao rèngu. Te d'ara ra bhelu-katub'a.<bt>People in this world don't resent you. [NOTE: No good word for hate.] But they really resent Me, because I expose openly all the things that they are doing Cuz (elaboration) their insides are evil (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="udhi "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-25 04:36:05Z" status="Anyone">1) dendam ; 2) bagian ujung besi (piso ato parang) yg maso asa dara gagang-nya</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Lod'o kalela agama èdhi dètu le. De miu ka laa lami asa Yerusalem. Ja'a neo mèka laku, te dhae d'ai mèka lod'o.&gt;&gt;<bt>Our-inc religious holiday is very near. So (consequently) just let it be you-pl who go up to Yerusalem now. I don't want to go yet, cuz (elaboration) the time is not yet right.” [TEXT: see Carson for discussion of variants in Gk text between ‘not’ and ‘not yet’. NOTE to daughter translations: The translation of this verse needs to be faithful, but also not clash horribly with vs.10, where he “changes” his mind and goes anyway.]</bt><v n="9" />Na peka nare, hèia Na pea ètu propensi Galilea.<bt>When He finished speaking, He stayed on in the province of Galilea.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus madhutu kalela agama Yahudi<bt>The Lord Yesus participates in a/the Yahudi religious festival</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Te ngaa ropa ari Na si lasi madhutu kalela agama dhèu Yahudi ètu Yerusalem, Yesus madhutu kahèi. Te ngaa la'e pahuni-pahuni, sèna ka dhèu baku rèdhi Ne.<bt>But when His younger siblings had left to go participate in the Yahudi people's holiday/festival in Yerusalem, Yesus also followed (later). But he went secretly, so that people wouldn't see Him.</bt><v n="11" />Ètu Yerusalem, lod'o kalela agama dhèu Yahudi, ama-ama dhèu Yahudi patangi-tenge Yesus. Ra pakarèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu èèna, ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>In Yerusalem, during the festival, the Yahudi people's leaders kept looking for Him. They were asking each other, saying, “Where is that Person?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Dhèu ae dhu paka'uu lula-nèti Nèngu. Cahag'e peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne, dhèu be'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Many people were whispering (to each other) about Him. Some said, “He is a good person.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Cahag'e hari peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Nèngu ne dhu kapod'e-kabèli dhèu ae-ae.&gt;&gt;<bt>Some others said, “No! He likes to/often deceive (doublet) many people/the crowd.”</bt><v n="13" />Te ngaa abhu boe dhu pacèu lii padhai lula-nèti Yesus, te rèngu madha'u dènge ama-ama se.<bt>But there was nobody who dared talk openly/clearly/plainly about Yesus, because they were afraid of those leaders.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Pas ètu talora kalela ne, Yesus maso la'e asa Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ka Na aj'a dhèu ètu era èèna.<bt>Right in the middle of that festival (time), Yesus went into the Temple. And He taught people there.</bt><v n="15" />Hèia ama-ama dhèu Yahudi malaa, ka ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne sakola nèdhi boe sèmi èdhi. Te ngaa tasamia ka ne'a aa'i mèu j'ara se'e?&gt;&gt;<bt>The Yahudi people's leaders were surprised/amazed, saying, “This Person has never been schooled like we-inc have. But how is it that He knows so many things like this?” [EXEG: LN, Carson, NLT] [CHECK UNS get this as ‘learn’, or ‘teach’? In some ways it doesn't matter, because of last sentence.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka Yesus peka dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nanene. J'ara-j'ara dhu Ja'a lole, kapua boe nèti Ja'a mesa ku, te ngaa nèti Nèngu dhu pua Ja'a mai.<bt>Yesus told them, saying, “Listen! The things/matters that I say, are not rooted/sourced from Me myself, but from Him who sent/commissioned Me.</bt><v n="17" />Dhèu dhu tare'a-re'a neo madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua, nèngu èèna na ne'a mèu, a'aj'a Ja'a ne, tare'a-re'a mai nèti Ama Lamatua, do nèti dhoka Ja'a mesa ku.<bt>A person who really wants to do according to God's will/desires, he will be able to know/come to know clearly, (if) My teaching really comes from God, or only comes from Me myself.</bt><v n="18" />Te dhèu dhu padhai lii pake mamèu unu na, nèngu tenge dhoka kolongara di. Te ngaa dhèu dhu neo ded'e kolongara nèti dhèu dhu pua-paleha na, tatu lii padhai lèke mola-mola. Aa lii padhai nèngu koe-kapengo boe.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) a person who only speaks using his own knowledge/cleverness, s/he is only just trying to make a name/reputation for himself. But a person who wants to elevate/promote the good name/reputation of the person who sent/commissioned him, is surely speaking the truth. And what he says has no deceit/distortion (doublet).</bt><v n="19" />Musa pangèd'u le miu Atora Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa miu mo'o boe tao madhutu. De tasamia ka miu tenge j'ara ho neo pamadhe Ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>Musa already gave/presented to you-pl God's Regulations/Law. But you don't do accordingly/obey. So (consequently) why is it that you keep trying to find a way to kill Me?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Hèia dhèu ae se karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu peka ngaa, ne? Ele boe nidhu tao Èu, do? Cee ka dhu tenge j'ara neo pamadhe Èu?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then many people asked, saying, “What are you-sg talking about here? It seems/probably you have been possessed/affected by an *evil spirit, or what? Who is looking for a way to kill you?” [CHECK batulai, Lena not know.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ka Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e ka. Ja'a heka tao tadha malaa èci ètu lod'o manèngi-mangaj'i, te ngaa miu aa'i-aa'i mi kacèki le.<bt>And Yesus responded, saying, “It's like this. I just did one *amazing sign on a day of worship, but [contrary to expectation] you are all annoyed/upset (lit: constricted). [EXEG: NLT, CEV-note; higher-level context; NRSV “astonished”, CEV “amazed”, NLT “offended”, both LN &amp; BAGD say of Gk word “whether the reaction is favorable or unfavorable depends on the context”; Carson “astonishment-not the astonishment that leads to praise”; Carlton (TRT) “negative connotations ... surprised/ shocked/ upset”.]</bt><v n="22" />Te ngaa ca tèka-tèka, miu sab'a kahèi ètu d'ara lod'o sabaj'a, nuka sèmi: Musa hia le atora suna, dhu peka na, ladhe dhèu rara iisi ana mone ca dhèu, na, ètu d'ara lod'o ka aru, miu hud'i suna ku ana ne. Masi ka lod'o ne, lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a, miu hud'i suna ku nèngu. (Te ngaa madhutu mola-mola na, atora ne uru tèka nèti Musa. Te Ama Lamatua dhu hia uru le atora ne mi Abraham.)<bt>But every once in awhile you-pl also work on the day of worship, such as this: Musa has handed down the *regulation of *circumcision (assimilated loan), saying, if a person gives birth to a son, na, on his eighth day, you must circumcise that child. Even if that day falls on a day of worship, you must circumcise him. (But in actual fact/truth, that regulation is older than Musa. Cuz (elaboration) God had already given that regulation before that to Abraham.) [NLT]</bt><note reference="7:22" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 17:10, Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 12:3</note><v n="23" />De ladhe suna ana iiki èci lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a sisu boe atora Musa, nga tao ka miu nasa dènge Ja'a, lula Ja'a puri-pa'èle dhèu karuku lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a? Maso boe d'ara ngangee, sina ma!?<bt>So (consequently) if circumcising a child on the day of worship itself does not violate/transgress Musa's regulation, na, why is it that you-pl are angry with Me because I healed (doublet) a paralysed person on the day of worship? It doesn't make sense, right!?</bt><note reference="7:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 5:9</note><v n="24" />Baku pasale dhèu lula j'ara-j'ara dhu miu mèdhi dènge musi madha di. Dadoo uuru ku dènge d'ara be'a, heka pama'ète dhu lèke.&gt;&gt;<bt>Don't criticise/judge people on account of things/matters/issues that you-pl see with your eyes. Weigh/evaluate everything carefully first, and only then decide what is right/correct.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dadoo "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-28 00:47:47Z" status="Anyone">weigh, evaluate, extended to thinking; similar to babenu (archaic, balanced scales, but less widely known and not extended to thoughts</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus ne, nuka Kristus, do?<bt>Is the Lord Yesus, the Kristus, or (what)?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia pèri-pèri dhèu nèti kota Yerusalem pakarèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne ka dhu ra patangi-tenge ho neo pamadhe Ne, do?<bt>After that, there were several people from the city of Yerusalem who were asking each other, saying, “This Person here, isn't He the one they keep looking for to kill, or (what)?</bt><v n="26" />Ladhe ku laa! Na padhai lii pahuni boe ètu madha dhèu ae-ae. Te ngaa abhu boe dhu kai Ne ho hutu hèb'a Na. Madhutu miu, tasamia? Ele boe dhèu dhu rèd'u koasa sèra re'a le, peka na, Dhèu ne'e ne, nuka Kristus, dhu Lamatua pajaji tèke ho neo pua mai èèna, si?<bt>Have a look! Cuz (elaboration) He is speaking openly in front of lots of people. But nobody is forbidding Him (telling Him) to shut His mouth. According to you-pl, how is it? Do you think perhaps that those who hold power/authority already know, that this Person is Kristus, whom God2 promised to send, or (what)? [EXEG: Are they praising or criticising him here? Morris clearly falls on side of praise; HCE]</bt><v n="27" />Te ngaa j'aj'i mi lii langu, sèmi ne'e: ladhe Lamatua pua ka Kristus mai, abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu re'a Nèngu nèti mia. Te ngaa èdhi te'a le Dhèu ne nèti mia.&gt;&gt;<bt>But there's a problem, like this: later, if/when God2 sends Kristus coming, nobody knows where He is from. But we-exc already know where this Person is from.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Lod'o èèna, Yesus aj'a dhèu era ètu madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ropa tadèngi dhèu se peka sèmi èèna, hèia Na karèi si dènge lii mèdhu, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu pangee, na, miu se tadhe Ja'a, aa me'a mèu Ja'a mai nèti mia, do? Ja'a ne, mai boe asa ne'e madhutu dad'èi Ja'a mesa ku. Te dhu pua Ja'a èèna, abhu tare'a-re'a. Aa miu tadhe boe Nèngu.<bt>At that time, Yesus was still teaching people in the Temple's yard. When [He] heard people talking like that, He asked them using a loud voice, saying, “You-pl think that you know/recognise Me, and you know exactly where I come from, right? I did not come here according to My own desires/will. Cuz (elaboration) that one who sent Me, really/truly is/exists. And you don't know/recognise Him. [EXEG: ‘real’ (Carson) he really is the one who sent Jesus; the Jews would not doubt that God is real; =the one who sent me really exists. EXEG: although “the one who sent me” is a common way that John uses to refer to God, translating that as “God” here would destroy the coherence of the veiled reference in this passage.]</bt><v n="29" />Te ngaa Ja'a tadhe Ne, lula Ja'a mai nèti Nèngu, aa Nèngu ka dhu pua Ja'a mai.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I know Him, because I came from Him, and He is the one who sent/commissioned Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ka dhèu se'e neo kèpe Ne. Te ngaa abhu boe dhu bisa kèpe Ne, te d'ai mèka lod'o Na.<bt>Then they tried to catch/arrest Him. But there was nobody who was able to grab Him (successfully), cuz (elaboration) His time was not yet right.</bt><v n="31" />Nèti dhèu ae-ae dhu ètu èèna, abhu ae kahèi dhu parcaya Ne. Dhèu se padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne tao tadha malaa ae le. Pe bèli-camèd'a, ladhe Kristus mai, tatu boe Na tao tadha malaa risi nèti Dhèu ne'e, si?&gt;&gt;<bt>From/Among those many people there, there were also many who believed in Him. They spoke (with each other), saying, “This Person has done/made many amazing signs. So later, if/when Kristus comes, it's not likely/probable that He will do more than this Person, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Rèngu pua dhèu lasi kèpe Lamatua Yesus<bt>They (non-referential) order people to go catch/arrest the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="32" />Ètu talora aae dhèu ae se, abhu pèri-pèri dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi kahèi. Rèngu tadèngi dhèu ae se pakanucu j'ara-j'ara lula-nèti Yesus. Hèia, dhèu se, dènge kètu agama Yahudi se pua pèri-pèri dhèu j'aga Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i sèna ka lasi kèpe Yesus.<bt>Among those many people, there were several people from the Parisi religious party also. They had heard the many people/crowds whispering those things about Yesus. So/then they, and the *chief priests (Yahudi priests' heads) sent several Temple guards to go catch/arrest Yesus.</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01737b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ka Yesus peka, na, &lt;&lt;Lod'o Ja'a pa'èci dènge miu di ciki oo'e ka, nare heka nèbhu. Te nèbhu heka, Ja'a laku hari asa Nèngu dhu pua Ja'a.<bt>Then Yesus told (people), saying, “My time to be together with you-pl, just remains a little longer. Cuz (elaboration) soon/in near future, I am going back to Him who sent/commissioned Me. [NOTE to daughter translations: if you use ‘God’ here, then the confusion of the next verses doesn't work. It is a deliberately veiled reference.]</bt><v n="34" />Pe èèna na, miu tenge Ja'a, te ngaa mèdhi boe Ja'a. Te Ja'a neo laku asa era èci dhu miu bisa boe madhutu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then later, you-pl will look for Me, but you won't find Me. Cuz (elaboration) I am going to a place that you cannot go/follow.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ka ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se pakarèi iisi-aanga ra, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne neo la'e mia? La'e asa era mia, dhu èdhi bisa boe paraga dènge Ne? Nèngu la'e lu'u asa dhèu Yahudi dhu bali ètu rai kaj'èu, do? Neo la'e aj'a-nori dhèu-dhèu dhu pake lii Yunani ètu nèi, do? Do, tasamia?<bt>Then the leaders of the Yahudi people asked each other, saying, “Where is this Person going to go? He is going to what place that we-exc can't find/encounter Him? Is He going to go hide among the Yahudi people who live scattered abroad (outside the country), or (what)? Is He going to go teach (doublet) the people who speak the Yunani language there (remote), or (what)? Or how is it?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lu'u "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-28 01:19:53Z" status="Anyone">sembunyi</Message></Annotation><v n="36" />A'abhu Na tasamia, ka Na peka, na, &lt;Miu neo tenge Ja'a, te ngaa paraga boe.&gt; Aa, &lt;Ja'a laku asa era èci dhu miu bisa boe madhutu.&gt;?&gt;&gt;<bt>What does He mean when He says, ‘You-pl will look for Me, but you won't find (Me).’ And, ‘I am going to a place that you cannot follow’?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Èi dhu nèti mamuri<bt>Water that brings life</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />D'ai lod'o oe èle kalela, dhu j'aj'i lod'o kapai risi èèna, hèia Yesus kèd'i titu, ka Na rodhe, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nanene, ee! Cee ka dhu koko-kamango, na, hud'i laa na mai asa Ja'a ho ninu!<bt>On the (very) last day of the feast, which was the most important/prominent day, Yesus stood and shouted out, saying, “Listen, ee! Whoever is thirsty, na, let him come to Me to/for a drink!</bt><note reference="7:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 23:36</note><v n="38" />Cee dhu parcaya Ja'a, na, mai sèna ka minu! Te ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua, dhu suri tèke le, peka na, &lt;Èi dhu nèti mamuri, èèna na hae mai nèti d'ara dhèu-dhèu parcaya.&gt; Ka rèngu abhu mamuri dhu lèke. Dènge j'ara ne, rèngu bisa soru-bara dhèu leo, sèna ka ra abhu mamuri dhu lèke kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Whoever believes in Me, na, just come and drink! Cuz (elaboration) in the Scriptures it has been written, saying, ‘Water that brings life will flow/burst out (under pressure) from the insides/heart of the believers.’ So, they will get real life. In that way, they can also help (doublet) other people to get that real life.” [NLT, HCE--water doesn't just flow out and go down the drain, but it does some good.]</bt><note reference="7:38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yeskial 47:1-12, Sakaria 14:8, Nehemia 9:15,19-20</note><v n="39" />Yesus padhai lii lula-nèti Roh Ama Lamatua, lula dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu parcaya Yesus abhu Roh èèna. Te ngaa lod'o Yesus padhai lii sèmi èèna, rèngu dhae sèmi rare mèka Roh èèna, lula Ama Lamatua dhae hia mèka. Ama Lamatua mema hia mèka, lula Na ded'e mèka padedha-dedha Yesus.<bt>Yesus was speaking about God's Spirit, because everyone who believes in Yesus will/would get/obtain/receive that Spirit. But when Yesus was speaking like that, they had not yet received that Spirit, because God had not yet given [it]. God really had not yet given [it], because He had not yet *glorified (elevated/promoted very high/exalted) Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu se mulai pahag'a lula Lamatua Yesus<bt>People began to be divided/split (in factions) because of the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Dhèu ae-ae ètu sèra nanene lii padhai Yesus ne. Hèia abhu dhu peka, na, &lt;&lt;Tatu Dhèu ne, Dhèu nèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua, dhu Na padhadha mema karèi nèti uru ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Many people there heard Yesus talk like that. And there were those who said (to each other), “Surely this Person is God's Spokesperson, whom He had promised beforehand from long ago!”</bt><note reference="7:40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 18:18-19</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Abhu cahag'e dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Nèngu ne, nuka Kristus dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u karèi nèti uru ka mai!&gt;&gt;<bt>There were some others, who said, “No! This one, is Kristus, whom God designated from long ago!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa cahag'e hari pab'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Bisa boe! Te Kristus èèna, dhèu Galilea boe. Tare'a, si?<bt>But there were still others who protested, syaing, “That cannot be! Cuz (elaboration) that Kristus, is not a Galilea person, right?</bt><v n="42" />Te Sasuri Ama Lamatua suri, na, Kristus èèna, ana-èpu nèti dhèu aae Daud. Ètu d'ara sasuri leo kahèi dhu suri, peka na, Nèngu ne, dhèu Betlehem, rae dhèu aae Daud. Sèmi èèna ka, si?&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the *Scriptures write that the Kristus is king David's descendant. In another writing it is also written, saying, that He is a person from Betlehem, that is king David's village. That's how it is, right? [NOTE to daughter translations: Cross ref. Indonesian TB gives Bethlehem info in Micah 5:1 (as do BHS and LXX). Most English sources put it in 5:2 as in our cross ref. below, and don't even seem to be aware there is a discrepency. NRSV has a footnote noting there is different versification in the Hebrew. TH has some discussion. OT versification is slightly different between the Hebrew and the English. The reference is memorised for catechism and Sunday school. So don't be surprised if someone makes an issue. It's not as simple as just saying “TB got the versification wrong.” I've asked around and I'm trying to get a copy of the TNIV, which apparently is the only recent resource dealing with the mismatch in versification.]</bt><note reference="7:42" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Samuel 7:12, Mika 5:2</note><v n="43" />Ka dhèu se mulai pahag'a lula Yesus.<bt>So the people began to become divided/split/factioned because of Yesus.</bt><v n="44" />Abhu pèri-pèri dhèu dhu neo kèpe Ne, te ngaa ca dhèu sa goi boe Ne.<bt>There were several people who wanted to catch/arrest Him. But nobody was able to grab/hold (successfully) Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama-ama dhèu Yahudi parcaya boe Lamatua Yesus<bt>The leaders of the Yahudi people don't believe (in) the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Èle ka, dhèu-dhèu madhenga Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i dhu mai neo kèpe Yesus, lèpa asa kètu agama Yahudi dènge dhèu Parisi sèra. Hèia dhèu kapai se karèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka miu mèti boe Ne mai?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, the Temple guards who had come to catch/arrest Yesus, returned back to the *chief priests and the Parisi people. So/then those important people asked, saying, “Why didn't you-pl bring Him here?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="46" />Hèia dhèu se dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Ji'i dhae paraga ngèdhi mèka dènge dhèu èci sa dhu padhai lii sama sèmi Dhèu nèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>They responded, saying, “Ira ii! [+amazement] There has never been a person who spoke like that Person (remote)!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Ka dhèu Parisi se karèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Heh! Miu se lèke le tipu, si?<bt>The Parisi people asked, saying, “Heh! Have you also been deceived/tricked?</bt><v n="48" />Sanèd'e! Te nèti ji'i dhèu-dhèu Parisi, do, ama-ama abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu lèka Ne. Tare'a, si? Ladhe dhèu kapai parcaya boe, na, tasamia ka miu se lèka Nèngu?<bt>Think/remember! Cuz (elaboration) there is nobody from our Parisi people, or, from the leaders who believe2 in Him. That's right, right? If those big/important/prominent people don't believe, na, why do you-pl want to believe2 in Him? [NOTE: Last sentence added, because at consultant check, UNS's couldn't get the ellipsed proposition, i.e. why they were saying this vs.48.]</bt><v n="49" />Te ngaa dhèu ae dhu neo parcaya Ne, re'a boe Atora Ama Lamatua. Bèli-camèd'a rèngu dui rare huku dhu bia nèti Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>But these many people/crowds who are wanting to believe in Him, don't know God's Regulations/Law. God is going to punish them heavily/severely!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="50" />Te ngaa ètu era ne'e, abhu kahèi dhèu Parisi ca dhèu, ngara na Nikodemus. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu la'e asa Yesus re mèda, ho padhai lii dènge Ne. Ka na karèi dhèu se'e, peka na,<bt>But there, there was also a Parisi person, named Nikodemus. He was the one who once came at night to speak with Yesus. So/then he asked them, saying,</bt><note reference="7:50" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 3:1-2</note><v n="51" />&lt;&lt;Tasamia? Madhutu atora agama, èdhi pama'ète uru ku lii langu dhèu, do? Do, èdhi hud'i nanene uuru ku lii lolo na, sèna ka te'a mèu dhèu ne tao ngaa, heka pama'ète lii langu na kèna?&gt;&gt;<bt>“How is it? According to our-inc religious regulations, do we-inc first decide beforehand a person's case? Or, must we listen to he has to say first, to find out what he has done, (and) only then decide his case?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Hèia ra jèke ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, dhèu Galilea èci èèna ka dènge Nèngu, do? Parisa paie-iie uuru ku Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua! Baca paie-iie sèna ka me'a mèu, na, abhu boe dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu mai nèti Galilea!&gt;&gt;<bt>And they spoke angrily at him, saying, “Are you-sg here a Galilea person like Him, or (what)? Make a careful examination of the *Scriptures! Read it carefully so you know that there is not a single *spokesperson of God's who comes from Galilea!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu bhèni èci dhu tao j'ara makae<bt>A woman who did a shameful thing (euphemism)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="53" />[Ka ra pacèri, èci-èci lèpa asa èmu ra.<bt>[Then they dispersed, and everyone went home.</bt><note reference="7:53-8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">11: Alkitab lii Yunani dhu uru tèka, suri boe lii lolo ne. Abad ka canguru ku, heka cèu lii lolo ne ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani.<bt>11: The oldest Yunani language Bibles don't write this story. It was the 10-th century (loan) before this story appeared in the Yunani language writings.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="8" />
      <v n="1" />Te ngaa Yesus la'e asa ledhe Saitun.<bt>But Yesus went to Saitun (Olives-loan) mountain.</bt><v n="2" />Asa bèli mad'ae aae èèna, Nèngu la'e asa madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Dhèu ae mai pakaboko ètu madha Nèngu. Ka Na madhèdi aj'a-nori si.<bt>Early the next morning, He entered into the Temple yard. Many people came to gather (around/in front of) Him. Then He sat and taught them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Lod'o èèna, kèpe rare bhèni ca dhèu dhu talora na ad'u-ue j'ara makae. Ka pèri-pèri mese agama dènge dhèu Parisi ère rèti bhèni ne asa Yesus. Hèia ra laka-seti bhèni ne titu ètu madha rèngu aa'i-aa'i.<bt>At that time, there was a woman who had been caught while she was doing a shameful thing [CHECK euphemism]. And several religious teachers and Parisi people brought the woman (implies force/compelled) to Yesus. And they forced the woman to stand in front of all of them.</bt><v n="4" />Ka ra peka dènge Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese. Kèpe ngare bhèni ne dhu talora nèngu dhu ad'u-ue j'ara makae.<bt>Then they told Yesus, saying, “Father Teacher. This woman was caught while she was doing a shameful thing.</bt><v n="5" />Ètu d'ara atora Musa, abhu paredha èci dhu peka na, &lt;Dhèu dhu ad'u-ue j'ara makae dènge dhèu èmu na boe, hud'i abhu hahuku pèci toke madhe.&gt; De madhutu Ama Mese, na, tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>According to Musa's regulations/law, there is a command that says, ‘A person who does a shameful thing with someone who is not their spouse must be punished by throwing (stones) until dead.’ According to Father Teacher, how is it/should it be?”</bt><note reference="8:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 20:10, Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 22:22-24</note><v n="6" />Dhèu se sèku Ne, sèna ka abhu j'ara ho pèci sasala asa Yesus ho pamanahu Ne.<bt>They wanted to test Him, so they could accuse/blame Yesus to bring Him down.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yesus lii boe, te ngaa madhèdi pasaboti suri rai, pake suu kolo ai Na.<bt>Yesus did not speak3, but He squatted to write on the ground, using the end/tip of his finger.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhèdi pasaboti"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-28 02:31:34Z" status="Anyone">dudu jongko</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Dhèu se loe boe karèi Nèngu. Hèia Na titu, ka padhai lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ladhe nèti miu abhu dhu tao mèdhi mèka sasala, na, nèngu ka dhu bisa pèci uuru ku, sèna ka huku bhèni ne'e.&gt;&gt;<bt>They kept asking Him. Then He stood, and spoke, saying, “Like this. If there is among you-pl someone who has never done wrong/sinned, na, he is the one who can throw first to punish this woman.”</bt><v n="8" />Ka Na madhèdi pasaboti hari, hèia suri hari rai.<bt>Then He squatted again, and wrote more on the ground.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ropa dhèu se tadèngi lii padhai Na, rèngu j'aj'i makae. Lula rèngu re'a ètu d'ara ra, rèngu ad'u-ue sasala kahèi. Ka lasi ka èci-èci, mulai nèti dhèu heka toke d'ai ana ngèru, tèke eele dhodhoka Yesus dènge bhèni ne ètu era èèna.<bt>When these people heard what He said, they became ashamed. Because they knew in their insides had also done wrong. So/then they left one by one, beginning from the oldest person to the youngest, leaving only Yesus and that woman there by themselves.</bt><v n="10" />Hèia Yesus titu hari, ka Na karèi, &lt;&lt;Eea! Mia lasi? Abhu heka ca dhèu sa ètu ne'e ho pèci sasala mi èu, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus stood up again, and asked, saying, “Eea? Where have they gone? Isn't there anyone here who is going to blame/accuse2 you, or (what)?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia bhèni ne dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o, Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>The woman responded, saying, “No, Father.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus lii dènge dhèu ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a neo boe huku èu kahèi. Lèpa ka, te ngaa sanèd'e. Tao ia ka sasala!&gt;&gt;]<bt>So/then Yesus told her, saying, “I also am not going to punish you. Go on home. But remember. Don't do wrong/sin again/anymore!”]</bt><note reference="7:53-8" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">11: Alkitab lii Yunani dhu uru tèka suri boe lii lolo ne. Abad ka canguru ku, heka cèu lii lolo ne ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani.<bt>11: The oldest Yunani language Bibles don't write this story. It was the 10-th century before this story appeared in the Yunani language writings.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus nuka sèmi saraa hia dhèu ètu rai-haha ne<bt>The Lord Yesus is like light for the people of this world</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ka Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai dènge dhèu ae se, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, nuka sèmi saraa hia dhèu ètu rai-haha ne. Dhèu dhu madhutu Ja'a mamuri boe ètu d'ara maroga, te ngaa na pea ètu d'ara saraa dhu nèti mamuri dhu lèke.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus spoke again with the many people, saying, “I am like light for the people of this world. A/the person who follows Me does not live in darkness, but s/he lives2 in the light that brings real life.”</bt><note reference="8:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:14, Yohanis 9:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Abhu pèri-pèri dhèu Parisi dhu pab'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Weh! Èu mesa mu neo j'aj'i sakasii nèti ngi'u Èu unu mu, do? Bisa boe sèmi èèna! Te madhutu atora èdhi, hud'i dhèu leo ku dhu j'aj'i sakasii hia dhèu èci, bisa boe nèngu unu na. De ji'i ngo'o boe sèmi, aa ngo'o boe parcaya.&gt;&gt;<bt>There were several Parisi people who protested, saying, “Weh! You-sg want to be a witness about Your own self, huh? [+confirmative tag question] That can't be! Cuz (elaboration) according to our-inc regulations, it must be someone else who is a witness for a person, not that person themself. So (consequently), we-exc are not going to accept [it], and are not going to believe.”</bt><note reference="8:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 5:31</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ka Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Hud'i laa Ja'a j'aj'i sakasii mi ngi'u Ja'a mesa ku, te lii padhai Ja'a ne, lèke. Lula Ja'a mesa ku ke'a mola-mola Ja'a ne mai nèti mia, aa neo laku asa mia. Miu me'a boe Ja'a mai nèti mia, aa me'a boe neo laku asa mia kahèi.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “It's like this. Even if I am a witness for Myself, nevertheless what I have to say is true. Cuz (elaboration) I myself am the one who knows precisely where I came from, and where I am going. You-pl don't know where I come from, and also don't know where I'm going to go.</bt><v n="15" />Miu nile dhèu madhutu a'abhu dhèu rai-haha. Te ngaa Ja'a madhutu boe a'abhu dhèu rai-haha ho nile dhèu èci sa.<bt>You assess/evaluate people using human standards/measurements/opinions. But I don't use human standards/measurements to assess/evaluate anyone. [EXEG: Carson points out that to ‘pass judicial sentence’ here would directly contradict Jesus' other sayings in John. He favours ‘assess’ from the lexicon and context.]</bt><v n="16" />Ladhe Ja'a nile dhèu, a'uku dhu Ja'a pake, lèke mola-mola. Te Ja'a mesa ku boe dhu nile dhèu, te ngaa Ja'a tao aa'i-aa'i sama-sama dènge Ama Ku dhu pua Ja'a mai.<bt>If I assess/evaluate a person, the measurement that I use is correct. Cuz (elaboration) I don't assess alone/by myself, but I do everything together with My Father who sent/commissioned Me.</bt><v n="17" />Baku bhèlu. Te dhu suri tèke ètu Atora agama miu, peka na, &lt;Ladhe abhu dhèu dua j'aj'i sakasii dhu padhue j'ara dhu sama, èèna lèke tare'a.&gt;<bt>Don't forget. Cuz (elaboration) it is written in your-pl religious Regulations/Law, saying, ‘If there are two witnesses who say the same thing, it is valid/legal.’</bt><v n="18" />De Ja'a mesa ku boe dhu j'aj'i sakasii mi ngi'u Ja'a unu ku. Te Ama Ku dhu pua Ja'a, j'aj'i sakasii kahèi dhu padhai lii lula-nèti Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), I am not the only one who is a witness about Myself. Cuz (elaboration) My Father who sent/commissioned Me is also a witness who speaks about Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Hèia dhèu se karèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Te Ama Èu èèna, ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>They asked, saying, “So this Father of Yours, where is He?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu se tadhe iie boe Ja'a. Miu tadhe boe kahèi Ama Ku. Te ladhe miu tadhe iie Ja'a, tatu miu tadhe Ne kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “You-pl don't really know/recognise Me. You also don't know/recognise My Father. Cuz (elaboration) if you really knew/recognised Me, you would certainly also know/recognise Him.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Aa'i-aa'i se, Yesus peka-padhai lod'o Nèngu aj'a-nori dhèu ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, padètu dènge era rèngu kaboko doi kolete. Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu kèpe Ne, lula d'ai mèka lod'o na.<bt>All this/these things, Yesus explained/told (doublet) when He was teaching (doublet) in the Temple, near the place which they used to gather the collection money (loan). There was nobody who caught/arrested Him, because the time was not yet right.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">&lt;&lt;Èèna na Ja'a laku asa era èci dhu miu bisa boe madhutu&gt;&gt;<bt>“I will go to a place where you-pl can't follow”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Yesus padhai lii tabha hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Bèli-camèd'a Ja'a tèke eele miu, ho laku asa era leo. Miu èèna na patangi-tenge Ja'a, te ngaa mèdhi boe, te miu dhu dènge boe hak sèna ka lami asa era èèna. Aa ladhe miu madhe, miu pasae sasala miu era.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus continued speaking to them, saying, “Later I will leave you-pl behind, to go to another/different place. You will keep looking for Me, but you will not find/get [Me], cuz (elaboration) you have no right/authority to go to that place. Then when you die, you will still be bearing/shoulder carrying your wrong/sin.” [EXEG: ‘sin, wrong’ here is singular in the Gk. Carson and Morris both say it refers to the sin of rejecting Jesus as Messiah, and not believing in Him.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Hèia ama dhèu Yahudi sèra pakarèi iisi-aanga ra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Na padhai lii ngaa, nèi? Neo pamadhe iisi Na, do? Te Na peka, na, &lt;Miu bisa boe lami asa era èèna.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the leaders of the Yahudi people asked each other, saying, “What's He talking about there? Is He going to kill himself? Cuz (elaboration) He said, ‘You cannot go to that place.’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka Yesus peka dènge dhèu se'e, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu nèti rai-haha. Te ngaa Ja'a mai nèti dedha-liru. Miu dhèu nèti rai-haha ne, te ngaa Ja'a nèti boe rai-haha ne.<bt>Then Yesus told them, saying, “You-pl are from the earth below. But I am from the sky above. You-pl are people from this world, but I am not from this world.</bt><v n="24" />Nèti èèna ka, deo na Ja'a peka dènge miu, na, bèli-camèd'a ladhe miu madhe, miu pasae sasala-sasigo miu era. De ladhe miu parcaya boe, na, Ja'a ne, Kristus, dhu Ama Lamatua pua mai, ladhe miu madhe, tatu miu pasae sasala miu era.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why I said to you just now, that, later when you die, you will still be carrying your sins (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) if you do not believe, that I am the Kristus, whom God has sent here, when you die, surely you will still be carrying your sins.” [EXEG: ‘sins’ here is PL.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ka ra karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Weeh! Te Èu ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>So they asked, saying, “Weeh! So who are You-sg?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a dhu peka mema karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “I have already told you beforehand from the beginning.</bt><note reference="8:25" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani ètu ne'e bisa abhu dua sasoa. Sasoa èci nuka: &lt;Ja'a dhu peka tèke le karèi nèti uru j'ara ka.&gt; Sasoa ka dua nuka: &lt;Nga tao ka Ja'a neo padhai lii dènge miu?&gt;<bt>The Yunani language here can have two meanings. The one meaning is: ‘I have already told you beforehand from the beginning.’ The other one is: ‘Why do I bother to speak to you?’</bt></note><v n="26" />Abhu j'ara ae dhu Ja'a bisa peka lula-nèti miu. Sasala miu ae kahèi. Te ngaa Ja'a pad'elo boe j'ara sèra. Te Dhu pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne, ladhe Na padhai lii, ne'a dhoka peka dhu mola di. Aa Ja'a peka dènge dhèu ètu rai-haha ne, dhoka j'ara-j'ara dhu Ja'a tadèngi nèti Nèngu di.&gt;&gt;<bt>There are many things/matters that I can say/tell/explain about you-pl. Your wrongs/sins are also many. But I am not going to show/reveal those things. Cuz (elaboration) the One who sent/commissioned Me to come here to this world, if/when He speaks, He only knows how to tell the truth. And I tell people in this world only things which I have heard from Him.”</bt><v n="27" />(Dhu Nèngu padhue-padhai, nuka Ama Na ètu sorga. Te ngaa dhèu se re'a rare boe sasoa lii padhai Na.)<bt>(What He was talking about was His Father in heaven. But they didn't (fully/really) catch the meaning of what He said.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ka Yesus padhai lii tabha hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Pe ladhe miu ded'e ka Ja'a, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a ne, ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha, heka miu me'a kèna, na, Ja'a ne, Kristus. Aa Ja'a bisa boe tao ngaa-ngaa madhutu dad'èi Ja'a mesa ku, te ngaa Ja'a aj'a-nori dhoka j'ara-j'ara dhu Ama ètu sorga aj'a-nori le Ja'a.<bt>Then Yesus spoke further, saying, “Later when you-pl have already nailed Me, the *Son of Man (Authentic/Ideal Human) on a *cross, only then will you (fully) understand that I am the Kristus. And I don't do anything from My own desires/will, but I teach (doublet) only the things which Father in heaven has taught Me. [NLT]</bt><v n="29" />Dhu pua-paleha Ja'a bera-bera dènge Ja'a taruu. Nèngu tèke eele nèdhi boe Ja'a mesa-mesa ku, lula Ja'a loe boe sab'a madhutu dad'èi Na.&gt;&gt;<bt>The one who sent/commissioned (doublet) Me is continually with/accompanying Me. He has never left Me alone, because I always do according to His will/desire.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ropa Yesus peka j'ara se'e, dhèu ae parcaya Nèngu.<bt>When Yesus explained/told these things, there were many people who believed in Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">&lt;&lt;Miu se, ana-èpu Abraham&gt;&gt;<bt>“You-pl are Abraham's descendants (doublet)”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus peka dènge dhèu-dhèu Yahudi dhu parcaya Nèngu, na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu mamuri pa'èki taruu dènge Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a, aa aj'a taruu nèti Ja'a, na, miu bisa j'aj'i ana madhutu Ja'a dhu lèke.<bt>After that, Yesus told those Yahudi people who believed in Him, saying, “If you-pl live bound/linked to My Words/Sayings/Teachings (doublet), and you continue to learn from Me, na, you are/become my true/real *disciples. [EXEG: HCE, and unpacking meaning of Gk /matetheis/ as ‘learner, being instructed, getting training’.] [EXEG: Gk in next 2 passages is wordplay on ‘father’ and children: 1) biological, 2) genealogical, 3) character. In Timor region, sense #1 works, but not #2 and #3.]</bt><v n="32" />Miu bisa me'a mèu j'ara-j'ara dhu lèke. Dènge j'ara-j'ara dhu lèke sèra ka dhu patabuli miu, sèna ka miu j'aj'i ia ka ènu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then you can (come to) know things that are true. And those things that are true, are what will free/release you, so you no longer need to be slaves anymore.” [EXEG: larger context of dialogue.] [NOTE to daughter translations: Don't flesh out meaning of “slave” here as in vs.36, because reaction in verse 33 shows they are taking Jesus literally.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ka dhèu se pab'ala, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hee! Ji'i se, j'aj'i boe ènu dhèu! Te ji'i se, ana-èpu Abraham! De, nga tao ka Èu peka, na, èèna na ji'i bebas?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they protested, saying, “Hee! We-exc here are not a person's slaves! Cuz (elaboration) we are Abraham's descendants! So (consequently) why is it that You-sg say that we will become free?”</bt><note reference="8:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 3:9, Lukas 3:8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhu Ja'a peka ne, lèke. Te dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri ètu d'ara sasala, j'aj'i sama sèmi ènu dhu dhoka madhutu dad'èi sasala di.<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying, “What I said is true. Cuz (elaboration) everyone who lives doing wrong, has become like a slave who follows/goes along with only the desires/will of wrong/sin.</bt><v n="35" />Te ngaa dhu tema, sèmi ne'e: ènu se abhu boe pala nèti lamatua èmu na. Te dhoka ana lamatua èmu di dhu abhu pala taruu ètu èèna.<bt>But the norm is like this: slaves don't normally get/obtain a portion/share/inheritance from the house of his master/owner. Cuz (elaboration) it's only the master/owner of the house's children who get/obtain a portion/share/inheritance there.</bt><v n="36" />De Ja'a, nuka Ana Ama Lamatua ne, ladhe saku eele sasala-sasigo miu, na, miu bebas, aa j'aj'i heka ènu nèti koasa sasala-sasigo. Dènge j'ara ne, miu madhutu heka dad'èi sasala, aa tare'a-re'a bebas!<bt>So (consequently) I, that is God2's Child, if [I] wipe away your wrongs/sins (doublet), na, you are free, and are no longer a slave to the power of sin. In that way, no longer follow the will/desires of wrong/sin, and are truly free! [HCE, unpack higher level context.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ka'i-beko"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-02-28 03:52:03Z" status="Anyone">ta'ika (not widely known)</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-10 03:39:50Z">kalili = soft skin of a turtle, not the shell. pea kalili = tinggal menetap</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Ja'a ke'a le miu se, ana-èpu Abraham. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa miu loe boe patangi-tenge j'ara ho pamadhe Ja'a, lula mo'o boe sèmi mere a'aj'a Ja'a. Te ètu d'ara miu, abhu heka era tatèka Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a.<bt>I already know that you-pl here, are Abraham's descendants. Even that being the case, nevertheless you keep looking for ways to kill Me, because you don't want to accept My teaching. Cuz (elaboration) in your hearts (insides), there is no longer any place for you to keep/store/put away My Words/Message (doublet).</bt><v n="38" />Ja'a peka-padhai j'ara-j'ara dhu Ja'a kèdhi le, dhu Ama Ku paj'uj'u le dènge Ja'a. Aa miu tao madhutu j'ara-j'ara dhu miu tadèngi le nèti ama-ama miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I tell the things which I have seen, which My Father has shown Me. And you-pl do according to the things which you have heard from your fathers.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">&lt;&lt;Ama miu, nuka dhèu aae nidhu&gt;&gt;<bt>“Your-pl father is the king of the evil spirits”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Dhèu se dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i se, ana-èpu Abraham!&gt;&gt;<bt>These people responded, saying, “We are Abraham's descendants!” [EXEG: Gk is wordplay on ‘father’ 1) biological, 2) genealogical, 3) character. In Timor region, sense #1 works, but not #2 and #3.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus peka dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu j'aj'i tare'a-re'a ana-èpu Abraham, miu hud'i madhutu j'ara mamuri nèngu.<bt>And Yesus told (them), saying, “If you were Abraham's real descendants, you-pl must/would be obliged to follow his example.</bt><v n="40" />Te ngaa Abraham tao boe bhabhelu sama sèmi dhu miu tao! Te miu loe boe tenge j'ara ho neo pamadhe Ja'a. Aa te ngaa Ja'a ne, dhu peka dènge miu j'ara-j'ara dhu lèke, dhu Ja'a tadèngi nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>But Abraham never did evil like what you-pl do/are doing! Cuz (elaboration) you keep looking for a way to kill Me. When in fact, I am the one who tells you things that are true, which I heard from God.</bt><v n="41" />Tatao miu se mema beda boe nèti tatao ama miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>What you do, really is not really any different from the deeds of your fathers.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa rèngu pab'ala, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Heh! Ji'i se, ana d'èlu! Baku peka na ji'i se, ana ama aad'o! Te Ama ji'i, èci di, nuka Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>But they protested, saying, “Hee! We are legitimate/birth children! Don't say that we here are illigitimate children (lit: child without a father)! Cuz (elaboration) we-exc have only one Father, and that is God!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Hèia, aku Yesus na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ama Lamatua tare'a-re'a j'aj'i Ama miu, tatu miu sue Ja'a. Te Ja'a mai nèti Nèngu, nèti èèna ka Ja'a ka ne'e ne. Ja'a mai ne madhutu boe dad'èi Ja'a mesa ku. Te ngaa Ja'a mai, lula Nèngu ka dhu pua Ja'a.<bt>Yesus told them, saying, “But if God were really your Father, surely you-pl would love Me. Cuz (elaboration) I come from Him, and I am here. I didn't come following My own will. But I came, because He is the one who sent/commissioned Me.</bt><v n="43" />Nga tao ka miu dhane mere boe lii padhai Ja'a? Ele boe, lula miu mema mo'o boe nanene!<bt>Why is it that you can't understand what I am saying? Perhaps/Probably it is because you don't want to hear!</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Miu se, ca ropa dènge dhèu aae nidhu. Te miu d'èi madhutu dad'èi na! Karèi nèti uru j'ara ka, nèngu d'èi dhoka pamadhe dhèu. Nèngu lab'a j'ara dhu lèke, lula na tule eele j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu lèke! Ladhe na kapod'e-kabèli, mema sasab'a na kèna. Te nèngu ne, tuka kapod'e-kabèli, aa baki nèti leko-monya!<bt>You here are the same model/type/kind as the king of the evil spirits. Cuz (elaboration) you like to do according to his will/desires! From the beginning, he was (characterised as) a murderer/killer of people. He opposes things that are true, cuz because he has rejected everything that is true. When he deceives (doublet), that really is his work/job. Cuz he is a habitual liar, and the grandfather of b.s. (idiom)(doublet)!</bt><v n="45" />Ja'a ne'e ka dhu lole j'ara dhu lèke. Te ngaa miu parcaya boe Ja'a.<bt>I am the one who tells what is true. But you-pl don't believe2 (in) Me.</bt><v n="46" />Pangee sèku! Nèti miu se, cee ka dhu bisa pad'elo bukti, peka na, Ja'a ne ad'u-ue sasala? Malaa, nga! Ladhe Ja'a peka lèke, nga tao ka miu mo'o boe lèka Ja'a?<bt>Try to think (=have a think about this)! Who among you can show proof/evidence that I have done wrong/sin? That's surprising, nga [+unexpected]! If I speak truth, why is it that you don't want to believe2 (in) Me?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Dhèu dhu j'aj'i nèti Ama Lamatua nanene Lii Holo-Nori Na. Te ngaa miu se j'aj'i boe nèti Ama Lamatua, nèti èèna ka miu mo'o boe nanene Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>A/the person who originates from God listens to/obeys His Words/Message (doublet). But you here do not originate from God, so that is why you don't like to listen to Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">&lt;&lt;Dhae rara iisi mèka Abraham, Ja'a dhu mema-mema le&gt;&gt;<bt>“Before Abraham was born, I was already before-before that”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="48" />Ama-ama dhèu Yahudi b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lii padhai ji'i lèke tare'a-re'a. Te ji'i dhu peka le, na, Èu ne, dhèu Yahudi boe, te ngaa dhèu Samaria. Èu ne nidhu tao!&gt;&gt;<bt>The Yahudi people's leaders responded, saying, “We-exc have told the truth. Cuz (elaboration) we said that You are not a real/genuine Yahudi, but you are a Samaria person. And You have also been possessed by/adversely affected by an evil spirit!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a nidhu tao boe. Ja'a pakab'ua Ama Ku ètu sorga, te ngaa miu mo'o boe pakab'ua Ja'a.<bt>So Yesus responded, saying, “I have not be possessed by an evil spirit. I respect/honour to My Father in heaven, but you do not respect/honour Me.</bt><v n="50" />Ja'a padedha boe iisi ho pad'elo kolo-karisi Ja'a. Te ngaa abhu Èci dhu neo pad'elo dadedha Ja'a. Hud'i laa Nèngu ka dhu pama'ète, na, lii padhai Ja'a ne lèke, do aad'o.<bt>I don't elevate/promote myself to show how great/superior (doublet) I am. But there is One who wants to/is going to show my glory/high-ness. Let Him be the one to decide (whtehr) what I say is true, or not. [EXEG: NLT, Uma, Deibler. context.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="51" />Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a, lèke tare'a. De dhèu dhu nanene aa tao madhutu Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a, madhe boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>My Words/Message (doublet) really is true! So (consequently), the person who hears and does according to My Words/Message is not going to die.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="52" />Ropa tadèngi rare lii ne, hèia ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se peka dènge Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Limuri ne ji'i nge'a le Èu dhèu huj'u, lula nidhu tao le Èu. Te Abraham, madhe. Dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua uru-uru sèra, madhe le kahèi. Te ngaa aku Èu, na, &lt;dhèu dhu nanene dènge madhutu Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a, madhe boe.&gt; Mema Èu ne tare'a-re'a huj'u le!<bt>Hearing that, the leaders of the Yahudi people told Him, saying, “Now we-exc know that You are a crazy person, because You have been possessed by an evil spirit. Cuz (elaboration) Abraham died. God's *spokespeople long ago also died. But You say, ‘the person who hears and does according to My Words/Message is not going to die.’ You really are are crazy!</bt><v n="53" />Do, Èu ne pangee, na, Èu ne kapai risi nèti Abraham dhu madhe le? Do, Èu kapai risi nèti dhèu-dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua dhu madhe sèra? Èu ngee, na, Èu ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Or, do You think You are greater than Abraham who died? Or, are You greater than God's spokespeople who died? Who do you think you are?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ja'a ka dhu padedha iisi, dhèu ro'o boe sèmi rare. Madhutu iia-iia, na, Ja'a boe ka dhu ded'e padedha-dedha iisi, te ngaa dhu ded'e Ja'a padedha-dedha nuka Ama Ku. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu miu mangaku, na, Nèngu j'aj'i Ama Lamatua miu.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “If I elevate/promote Myself, people will not accept (it/me). Whereas in fact, it is not Me who is elevating Myself, but My Father who is *glorifying (elevating way up high) Me. He is the one you-pl acknowledge, saying He is your God.</bt><v n="55" />Te ngaa miu tadhe boe Ne. Dhu tadhe mèu ka Ja'a ne. Ladhe Ja'a peka na Ja'a tadhe boe Ne, Ja'a leko-monya, sama sèmi miu. Te ngaa Ja'a tadhe mèu Ne, aa Ja'a tao madhutu Lii Holo-Nori Na kahèi.<bt>But you don't know/recognise Him. I know/recognise Him well. If I said I didn't know/recognise Him, I would be a liar (doublet), just like you. But I know/recognise Him well, and I also do according to His Words/Message (doublet).</bt><v n="56" />D'ara baki miu Abraham karej'e titu kèna, lod'o na tatae neo nèdhi mamai Ja'a. Nèngu mema nèdhi le, ka na karej'e-karae.&gt;&gt;<bt>Your Gf/Ff Abraham was really happy, when he was eagerly awaiting to see My coming. He really has already seen (it), and so he is happy (doublet).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="57" />Ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se b'ala Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Umur Èu dhae d'ai mèka lèmi nguru tèu sa hèi! Te ngaa Èu peka na, mèdhi le Abraham. Tare'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>The Yahudi people's leaders responded, saying, “You are not yet 50 years old! But You say You have already seen Abraham. Is that right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="58" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a! Te dhae rara iisi mèka Abraham, Ja'a dhu mema-mema le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded2, “That's right! Cuz (elaboration) before Abraham was born, I was already before-before that (I already existed prior to that).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="59" />Ka dhèu se rare hadhu ho neo pèci Ne, lula Na tao iisi sama sèmi Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa Yesus kako mau-mau kalua nèti madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i.<bt>So/then those people picked up stones to throw at Him, because He had made Himself to be the same as/equal (status) with God. [NOTE: same wording as in Jn. 5:18; added because UNS's at consultant check couldn't make the link with vs. 58 as to why they wanted to stone him.] But He went secretly/quietly out from the Temple yard.</bt><note reference="8:59" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 5:18</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus puri-pa'èle dhèu bèdhu ca dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus heals (doublet) a blind person</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="9" />
      <v n="1" />Hèia Yesus si kako taruu. Ka Na ladhe nèdhi dhèu bèdhu ca dhèu, dhu bèdhu karèi nèti ina na nara iisi nèngu.<bt>Then Yesus (coll.) continued walking/their journey. And He saw a blind person who had been blind from birth.</bt><v n="2" />Hèia ana-ana madhutu Na karèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Cee ka tao sasala, ka dhèu ne bèdhu? Nèti nèngu mesa na, do, nèti ina-ama na?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then His disciples asked, saying, “Father Teacher! Who is it that did wrong/sin, with result that this person became blind like this? Is it he himself, or, from his mother-father?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu bèdhu ne tao boe sala. Aa ina-ama na aad'o kahèi. Rara iisi na sèmi ne'e, ho hud'i laa dhèu aa'i-aa'i ra ladhe rèdhi tatao Ama Lamatua dhu be'a mi dedha nèngu.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “This blind person did not do wrong. And his mother-father also did not either. He was born like that, so that everyone would be able to see God's good deed for him.</bt><v n="4" />Ama Lamatua ka dhu pua Ja'a. De èdhi hud'i tenge j'ara, sèna ka pakako sasab'a Na, lod'o saraa era. Te ladhe maroga mai, dhèu bisa heka sab'a.<bt>God is the one who sent/commissioned Me. So (consequently) we-inc must look for ways to carry out His work while there is still light/the day is still light. Cuz (elaboration) when the darkness has come, people won't be able to work anymore.</bt><v n="5" />Ropa Ja'a ètu rai-haha ne era, Ja'a nuka sèmi saraa dhu d'elo hia mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>While I am still in this world, I am like light which shines/reveals on/for everyone.” [EXEG: NRSV, NLT, Carson; STYLE: having ‘world’ twice is heavy in KM.]</bt><note reference="9:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 5:14, Yohanis 8:12</note></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01739b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii nare, ka Na paru'e ilu mi rai. Hèia Na madhèdi pasaboti, ho pakihu rai ne j'aj'i kabheca. Ka Na lame musi madha dhèu ne dènge kabheca deo na.<bt>After Yesus finished speaking like that, He spat spittle on the ground. Then He squatted, to mix it into mud. Then He smeared the mud on that blind person's eyes.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paru'e"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-02 03:21:17Z" status="Anyone">spit</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabheca"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-02 03:22:50Z" status="Anyone">mud ; lub'u = lumpur alus yg itam (untuk mewarnai tenun dulu)</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Hèia Na peka, na, &lt;&lt;Lamu asa kolam Siloam, sèna ka riu rèhu èu.&gt;&gt; (Ètu d'ara lii Ibrani, <span class="Italic">Siloam</span>, sasoa na, &lt;nèti mai&gt;.) Ka dhèu bèdhu ne la'e, ka riu rèhu na. Ropa na lèpa hari mai, nèngu bisa nèdhi le!<bt>Then He said, saying, “Go to the Siloam pool, to wash your face there.” (In the Ibrani language, <span class="Italic">Siloam</span> means ‘bring coming’.) Then that blind person went there, and he washed his face. When he came back he was already able to see! [EXEG: not sure of basis for NIV ‘went home’; ‘came back’ seems to have stronger lexical and contextual support, NRSV, NLT (note CEV loses it altogether); “Hebrew” from Carson. NOTE to daughter translations: Siloam = bilingual word play between Hebrew "water sent" and Greek Jesus sent"= MC (channeling of water, sent through conduit), CEV (One who is Sent); TB (yg diutus); LN (send someone, apostelw), Carson (“received its water through a channel which carried (or 'sent') it from the spring of Gihon in the Kidron valley.” also “The suitability of drawing attention to Siloam may have depended simply on its name. As it was called 'Sent', so Jesus was supremely the sent one (cf. notes on 20:21). Moreover, in Isaiah 8:6 the Jews reject the waters of Shiloah; here they reject Jesus.”); Morris (“Originally the name will have had to do with the fact that this water was “sent” into the pool by a channel; the Hebrew is active and in the first place will have referred to this channel, the “sender.” But the pool was given the name quite early (Neh. 3:15; Isa. 8:6). For John such a name has obvious spiritual significance and is not to be overlooked. So he draws attention to the meaning. In this Gospel the thought of being sent is very prominent. Again and again John refers to Jesus as having been “sent” by the Father.”) In KM, “bawa” works for water, but not for Christ. “Utus” works for Christ and reflects the Greek, but doesn't work for water, and doesn't reflect the Hebrew, which is what we're saying here. “Kirim datang” (send coming) works for both, and beautifully resonates with phrasing that we have been using in many books about the coming of the Messiah.]</bt><note reference="9:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 49:10; 2 Dhèu Aae sèra 20:20; Yesaya 8:6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia rae lesa dènge dhèu dhu rèdhi ne, dhu tema manèngi ngaa-ngaa nèti dhèu, ra pakarèi èci dènge èci, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne, dhèu bèdhu dhu tema madhèdi ho kanata ai manèngi ngaa-ngaa nèti dhèu, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, his neighbours, and those who had seen him begging from people, asked each other, saying, “This one here, is the blind person who used to sit around stretching out his hand begging, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Dhèu cahag'e dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Oo! Nèngu ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Some people said, “Oo! [=affirmation] That's him!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dhèu cahag'e hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Nèngu ne, rèhu na oe sèmi dhèu èèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>Some other people said, “No! His face only just resembles that person!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa dhèu ne dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Ja'a èèna ka, ne'e ne! Dhu uru èèna bèdhu!&gt;&gt;<bt>But that person himself told them, saying, “No! This is me! That one who used to be blind!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka dhèu se karèi ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka èu bisa ladhe mèdhi?&gt;&gt;<bt>So they asked him, saying, “How is it that you are able to see?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia na peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Dhèu dhu ngara Yesus èèna, pakihu kabheca ka lame mi musi madha ja'a. Ka Na pua ja'a, aku Nèngu na, &lt;Lamu asa kolam Siloam, ho riu rèhu èu ètu nèi.&gt; Hèia ja'a tao madhutu sèmi èèna. Nèti èèna ka, ja'a bisa ladhe kèdhi le!&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, “It's like this! That Person named Yesus mixed mud, then rubbed/smeared it in my eyes. And He ordered me, saying, ‘Go to the Siloam pool, to wash your face there (remote).’ So I did accordingly. That is why I am able to see!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Èle ka dhèu se karèi ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu èèna, ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they asked him, saying, “So where is that Person?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ke'a boe, mia la'e!&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, “I don't know where he's gone!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Parisi parisa dhèu dhu uru èèna bèdhu<bt>Parisi people examine/interrogate the person who had previously been blind</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13-14" />Lod'o èèna, ropa Yesus pakihu rai j'aj'i kabheca, ka puri-pa'èle dhèu bèdhu ho bisa ladhe nèdhi èèna, lèke dènge lod'o a'ae sasab'a dhèu Yahudi. Ka lere rèti dhèu dhu uru èèna bèdhu, asa madha dhèu-dhèu partei agama Parisi.<bt>That day, when Yesus mixed dirt into mud, and healed (doublet) the blind person so he could be able to see, fell on the Yahudi people's day of rest/stopping work. And they (non-referential) took/led that person who had once been blind, to before the people from the Parisi religious party.</bt><v n="15" />Ka dhèu Parisi se karèi ne, &lt;&lt;Èu lolo ku laa! Tasamia ka èu bisa ladhe mèdhi?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then those Parisi people asked him, saying, “Narrate to us! Why is it that you-sg now are able to see?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dhèu ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Dhèu èèna tao kabheca mi musi madha ja'a. Ka laku riu rèhu. Hèia limuri ne, ja'a bisa kèdhi le.&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, “It's like this. That Person put mud on my eyes. Then I went and washed my face. Now I am able to see.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka abhu dhèu Parisi cahag'e, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu puri-pa'èle èu èèna, mai boe nèti Ama Lamatua. Ji'i nge'a, lula Nèngu sisu atora nèti lod'o a'ae sasab'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>There were some of the Parisi people who said, “That Person who healed (doublet) you, did not come from God. We-exc know, because He has violated/transgressed the regulation(s) about the day of rest.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Aa abhu cahag'e hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia ka dhèu dhu ad'u-ue sasala bisa tao tadha-tadha malaa sèmi sèra?&gt;&gt; Ka rèngu patao-palaha èci dènge èci toke ra pahag'a.<bt>There were some others who said, “How could it be that a person who does wrong/sin could do various amazing signs like that?” So they argued (doublet) among themselves to the point that they were divided/factioned.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Hèia ra karèi hari dhèu dhu uru èèna bèdhu, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu a'abhu èu, Dhèu dhu puri-pabe'a musi madha èu ne, Dhèu sèmi ngaa sa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they again asked the person who had previously been blind, saying, “According to your opinion, that Person who restored your eyes, is what model/type/kind of person?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Dhèu ne b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu a'abhu ja'a, Dhèu èèna ca dhèu nèti dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, “According to my opinion, He is one of God's *spokespeople.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Te ngaa ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se ro'o boe lèka, na, dhèu ne uru èèna bèdhu, ka limuri ne bisa nèdhi le. Hèia ra pua dhèu lasi paroa ina-ama na mai.<bt>But the leaders of the Yahudi people did not want to believe2 that this person had ever been blind, and now was able to see. So they ordered people to summon his mother-father to come.</bt><v n="19" />Ropa ina-ama na mai d'ai madha si, hèia ama-ama se karèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne, ana miu, do? Tare'a, do aad'o, nèngu ne dhu bèdhu mema karèi nèti mera iisi ne? Tasamia ka limuri ne nèngu bisa ladhe nèdhi?&gt;&gt;<bt>When his mother-father had come before them, those leaders asked, saying, “This one here, is your child, right? Is it true or not, that he was blind from birth? And how is it that now he is able to see?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ka ina-ama dhèu ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu ne, mema ana ji'i. Aa na bèdhu karèi nèti ngara iisi ne.<bt>His mother-father responded, saying, “He here really is our-exc child/offspring. And he has been blind from birth.</bt><v n="21" />Te ngaa ji'i nge'a boe, na pake ngaa ka musi madha na bisa nèdhi sèmi ne'e. Cee ka dhu puri-pa'èle musi madha na, ji'i nge'a boe kahèi. Nèngu kapai le, de karèi ne, te nèngu bisa lolo unu na!&gt;&gt;<bt>But we don't know what he used so that now he is able to see. Who it was that healed (doublet) his eyes, we also don't know. He is big/grown, so (consequently) just ask him, cuz (elaboration) he is able to tell/narrate (for) himself!”</bt><v n="22" />Dua ra padhai lii sèmi èèna, lula rèngu madha'u dènge ama-ama dhèu Yahudi. Lula re'a, na, ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se dhu rare le lii èci, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe abhu dhèu mangaku, na, Yesus ne, nuka Kristus, na, babège eele dhèu sèra nèti d'ara èmu sabaj'a èdhi dhèu Yahudi.&gt;&gt;<bt>They spoke like that, because they were afraid of the Yahudi people's leaders. Because they knew that those Yahudi leaders had already conspired/plotted among themselves, saying, “If there is a person who acknowledges/confesses that Yesus is Kristus, na, we-exc must evict those people our-inc Yahudi houses of worship.”</bt><v n="23" />Nèti èèna ka, ina-ama dhèu ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèngu kapai le. De karèi ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>That is why that person's mother-father responded, saying, “He is already grown. So (consequently) just ask him.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Hèia ra paroa hari dhèu dhu uru èèna bèdhu. Ka ra karèi ne, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Èu hud'i peka ku mola-mola ètu madha Ama Lamatua, sèna ka j'aga paie kolongara Na. Te ji'i nge'a, na, Yesus ne, dhèu bhelu-katub'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then they summoned back that person who had previously been blind. And they asked him, “It's like this! You-sg must speak honestly before God to guard His good name/reputation. Cuz (elaboration) we-exc know, that this Yesus (known referent) is an evil (doublet) person.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ka dhèu ne dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama si baku nasa! Te ja'a ke'a boe, na, Nèngu èèna, dhèu bhelu, do aad'o. Dhu ja'a ke'a mola-mola, nuka, uru èèna ja'a bèdhu, te ngaa limuri ne ja'a bisa kèdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>That person responded, saying, “I apologise if I'm out of line here (Lit: Fathers (coll.) don't be angry!) Cuz (elaboration) I don't know if He is an evil person, or not. What I know for sure is that, I used to be blind; but now I am able to see.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Hèia ra karèi ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Te Na tao èu tasamia? Tasamia Na bhoke musi madha èu?&gt;&gt;<bt>They asked him, saying, “So what did He do to you? How did He open your eyes?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Dhèu ne dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Eee! Te deo na ja'a lole le, te ngaa miu mo'o boe nanene. Tasamia ka miu neo ja'a lolo hari? Ele boe ama si neo j'aj'i ana madhutu Na, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>The person responded, saying, “Eee! I already told you-pl just now, but you didn't/don't want to listen. Why is it that you want me to tell it again? Perhaps you (fathers) also want to become His disciples, or (what)?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ka ra padhai pa-aape ne, hèia ra peka, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa èu ka j'aj'i ana madhutu Na! Te ji'i se, ana madhutu Musa.<bt>So/then they cursed/swore at/verbally abused him, and they said, “Leave it at just you being His disciple! Cuz (elaboration) we-exc here, are Musa's disciples.</bt><v n="29" />Ji'i nge'a Ama Lamatua ka dhu padhai lii dènge Musa. Te ngaa nge'a boe Dhèu èèna bhodho nèti ro'a mia.&gt;&gt;<bt>We know that God spoke with Musa. But we don't know what hole that Person appeared from [+derogatory].”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ka dhèu dhu uru èèna bèdhu na, dhaa, &lt;&lt;Ja'a malaa, nga! Miu me'a boe Nèngu mai nèti mia. Aa te ngaa Nèngu ka dhu bhoke pamèu musi madha ja'a, ka ja'a bisa kèdhi.<bt>The person who had previously been blind responded, saying, “I'm amazed, [+contrary to expectation]! You-pl don't know where He came from. Whereas in fact, He is the one who opened my eyes so now I am able to see.</bt><v n="31" />Èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti te'a, na, Ama Lamatua parluu boe nanene lii dhèu bhelu, si? Te ngaa Ama Lamatua nanene dhèu d'ara mola, dhu mamuri madhutu dad'èi Na.<bt>All of us-inc know that God doesn't listen to evil people, right? But God listens to people with straight/honest/righteous insides, who live according to His will/desires.</bt><note reference="9:31" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 66:18,19</note><v n="32" />Karèi nèti Ama Lamatua paj'aj'i liru dènge rai-haha toke d'ai sange ne'e, abhu mèka lii lolo èci sa hèi, lula-nèti dhèu dhu puri-pabe'a dhèu bèdhu karèi rara iisi ne, ho nèngu bisa nèdhi.<bt>Beginning from God making the sky and earth (STYLE: doublet associated with the whole of creation) up until now, there has not yet been a story about a person who healed a person who had been blind from birth so that he was able to see.</bt><v n="33" />De ladhe Yesus mai boe nèti Ama Lamatua, tatu Nèngu bisa boe tao ngaa-ngaa, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), if Yesus did not come from God, surely He wouldn't be able to do anything, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Hèia ra b'ala, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Èu ne, dhèu bhelu karèi ina mu nara iisi èu! Èu ngee, na, èu bisa aj'a hari ji'i, do?&gt;&gt; Ka ra babège eele dhèu ne nèti èmu sabaj'a rèngu.<bt>And they responded, saying, “Wee! You here are an evil person from (the time) your mother gave birth to you! Do you think you are able to teach us-exc?” So/then they evicted him from their houses of worship. [EXEG: Carson, Morris, NLT, CEV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu d'ara bèdhu<bt>People whose insides are blind</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Ropa Yesus tadèngi rèngu babège eele dhèu dhu uru èèna bèdhu nèti èmu sabaj'a ra, hèia Na la'e tenge dhèu ne, toke abhu. Ka Na peka, &lt;&lt;Tasamia! Èu parcaya Dhèu Rai-haha tare'a-re'a ne, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus (happened to) hear that they had evicted that person who had previously been blind from their houses of worship, He went to look for that person, until (He) found (him). And He said, “How about it! Do you beleive in the Son of Man (Authentic/Ideal Human)?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ka dhèu ne karèi hari Ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, te Nèngu èèna cee? Peka ku laa, sèna ka ja'a bisa parcaya Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>He asked back, saying, “So who is He, father? Please tell me, so that I can believe in Him.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Hèia Yesus peka, na, &lt;&lt;Èu paraga le dènge Ne. Nèngu èèna, nuka Ja'a ne, dhu padhai lii dènge èu ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yesus told (him), saying, “You have already met Him. He is Me, who is now speaking with you.” [NOTE to daughter trans: ‘see’ resonates nicely with ‘blind’; but it may be more natural in the context to say ‘met’.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Ka dhèu ne dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ja'a parcaya!&gt;&gt; Hèia na patitu kètu urutuu pahaha iisi mi Yesus.<bt>So/then that person said, “Father, I believe!” And he bowed to worship Yesus. [EXEG: Carson notes that the physical sense of ‘bow before’ is unambiguous, but observes that the Evangelist probably used it at two levels to include the sense of ‘worship’; Implication: translating ‘worship’ as primary is missing the action, whereas translating ‘bow down’ is safe. both is OK, but may be heavy/overtranslation.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mamai Ja'a asa rai-haha ne, sèna ka pad'elo sasala-sasigo dhèu, ho dhèu bèdhu bisa ladhe rèdhi, aa dhèu dhu rèdhi bisa j'aj'i bèdhu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told him, saying, “My coming to this world was to show people's wrongs/sins (doublet), so that blind people can see, and people who can see become blind.” [NOTE: If you spiritualise too much in this verse, the reactions in the next verse don't make sense.] [NOTE: yes they can nominalise ‘come’ and possess it as ‘my coming’.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ètu era èèna abhu dhèu Parisi pèri-pèri, dhu tadèngi lii padhai Yesus. Hèia ra karèi Ne, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia! Ji'i se bèdhu boe, sina ma?&gt;&gt;<bt>There, there were several Parisi people who heard what Yesus was saying. So they asked Him, saying, “How is this? We-exc are not blind, right?” [NOTE: Set up question so expected answer is confirmation of their assumption.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ladhe musi madha miu bèdhu, abhu boe dhu pasala miu. Te ngaa lula miu peka, na, miu bisa mèdhi, nèti èèna ka miu pasae sasala miu era.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “It's like this. If your eyes were blind, na, nobody would fault/blame/accuse you. But because you say that you are people who are able to see, that is why you still carry your wrong/sin.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii pakasame lula-nèti dhèu madhenga badha dènge kahib'i-kalèbho na<bt>*Illustration/comparison/parable about a shepherd and his sheep (doublet)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="10" />
      <v n="1" />Yesus padhai lii pake lii pakasame, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhu Ja'a peka dènge miu ne, lèke tare'a. Abhu kahib'i-kalèbho dènge oka ra. Ladhe dhèu maso boe re hèb'a oka, te ngaa ca'e re kolo oka, na, te'a le, nèngu ne, dhèu mana'u.<bt>Yesus spoke using an illustration/parable/comparison, saying, “What I am telling you-pl here/now is true. Sheep have their pens/corrals. If a person doesn't enter by/via the door/gate, but climbs up to get in over the fence, na, it's clear that he is a thief. [STYLE: Information load: Trying to force “thief and robber” is too heavy in KM. One is seen as reinforcing the other, not adding info.]</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00014c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Te ngaa ladhe maso re hèb'a oka, nuka dhèu madhenga dhu piara kahib'i-kalèbho sèra.<bt>But if one enters through the door/gate, s/he is the *shepherd who cares for/raises the *sheep's.</bt><v n="3" />Dhèu j'aga hèb'a oka, tadhe dhèu madhenga kahib'i-kalèbho, hèia na bhoke babèdho hia nèngu. Kahib'i-kalèbho se tadhe lii dhèu madhenga badha kahèi. Ka ropa dhèu madhenga ne paroa ngara ra èci-èci, kahib'i-kalèbho se madhutu ne asa li'u.<bt>The guard/watchman at the door/gate knows/recognises that shepherd of the sheep, and so opens the door/gate for him. The sheep also know/recognise that shepherd's voice. So, when the shepherd calls each of their names, the sheep follow him outside.</bt><v n="4" />Ladhe dhèu madhenga ne neo nèti si asa mia, nèngu kako uuru. Kahib'i-kalèbho se madhutu ne re limuri, lula ra tadhe lii na.<bt>When the shpeherd wants to take them somewhere, he walks in front. The sheep follow from behind, because they know/recognise his voice.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="eo "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-03 00:23:54Z" status="Anyone">menghalau, mengembalakan; KM foo, kasi kumpul</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kako uuru"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-03 00:26:47Z" status="Anyone">go in front ; vs. kako uru = go first, then the others come later</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu kahib'i-kalèbho tadhe boe, na, rèngu madhutu boe ne. Te ngaa ra rai pakaj'èu, lula rèngu tadhe boe lii dhèu leo.&gt;&gt;<bt>If there is a person who the sheep don't know/recognise, na, they don't follow him. But they run off/distance themselves, because they don't know/recognise the other person's voice.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Masi ka Yesus lole lii pakasame ne hia dhèu se'e, te ngaa re'a boe sasoa na.<bt>Even though Yesus told that illustration to these people, nevertheless they didn't understand His meaning.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus sama sèmi dhèu madhenga badha dhu be'a<bt>The Lord Yesus is like a good shepherd</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka Yesus peka tabha hari dènge dhèu sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhu Ja'a lole dènge miu ne, lèke tare'a. Ja'a ne nuka sèmi hèb'a oka kahib'i-kalèbho.<bt>Then Yesus spoke further to them, saying, “What I am telling you is true. I am like the door/gate in the sheep's pen/corral.</bt><v n="8" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mai uuru nèti Ja'a, rèngu sama sèmi dhèu mana'u. Masi ka rèngu loe boe paroa, te ngaa kahib'i-kalèbho se nanene boe lii rèngu.<bt>Everyone who came before Me are like thieves. Even if they kept calling on and on, nevertheless the sheep don't listen to those their voice/message.</bt><v n="9" />Aa Ja'a ne èci èèna ka dènge hèb'a oka èèna. Ladhe abhu dhèu neo maso re Ja'a, Ama Lamatua neo patabuli ne nèti koasa sasala-sasigo na. Èèna sama sèmi nèngu la'e asa era Ama Lamatua, maso re Ja'a dhu j'aj'i hèb'a oka. Aa dhèu dhu maso re Ja'a, nèngu neo asa mia èèna ka, ngaa-ngaa tao boe, dènge abhu na'a-ninu dhu be'a.<bt>And, I am like that door/gate. If there is someone who wants to enter by/via Me, God is going to save/rescue him from his wrongs/sins (doublet). That is like he goes to God's place, entering by/via Me who is its door/gate. And the person who enters by/via Me, he wants to go wherever, there is no problem, and get/obtain real/true food-drink. [EXEG: (Morris) “We should not attempt to find some esoteric meaning for ‘come in and go out.’ It is simply an expression to indicate free and secure movement (cf. Knox, ‘he will come and go at will’).”; NLT = wherever they go.]</bt><note reference="10:9" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 118:20</note><v n="10" />Dhèu mana'u re'a dhoka tao maruru di, te rèngu mai ho mana'u, pamadhe dhèu, aa pa'ele iie mamuri dhèu. Te ngaa Ja'a kèti mamuri dhu hua iia titu kèna, te mamai Ja'a ne, sèna ka dhèu bisa mamuri mera-milu, aa unu mamuri dhu lèke.<bt>Thieves only bring chaos/disorder/disruption, cuz (elaboration) they come to steal, kill/murder people, and ruin/destroy a person's life. But I bring the best life, cuz (elaboration) I come so that a person can live calmly/safe, and have real/true life. [Carson]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ja'a kahèi nuka sèmi dhèu madhenga badha dhu be'a. Te dhèu madhenga dhu be'a, sadia saraka ngi'u na toke madhe, sèna ka kahib'i-kalèbho na bisa mamuri.<bt>I am also like a good shepherd. Cuz (elaboration) a good shepherd is ready/prepared to turn over/surrender/give up himself to the point of death, so that his sheep can live. [EXEG: (Carson): means no more than that he is prepared to do so. He is willing to risk his life for the sheep.]</bt><v n="12" />Te ngaa dhèu sab'a dhu lamatua boe nèti kahib'i-kalèbho sèra, ropa nèdhi busa hui mai, na rai pakaj'èu, tèke eele kahib'i-kalèbho se. Hèia busa hui ne kadhi nare kahib'i-kalèbho, ka rèngu cahag'e rai paceb'a.<bt>But a worker who is not the master/owner of those sheep, when he sees a wild dog come, he runs off/distances himself, and abandons the sheep there. Then the wild dog catches the sheep, and the other sheep run away scattering (in all directions).</bt><v n="13" />Dhèu sab'a èèna rai, lula nèngu dhoka sab'a tenge doi di. Na pusi-pahae boe j'aga paie-iie kahib'i-kalèbho sèra.<bt>That worker runs, because he is only working looking for money. He doesn't care (doublet) to guard the sheep carefully.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Lèke tare'a! Ja'a ne nuka sèmi dhèu madhenga badha dhu be'a. Ja'a tadhe hua iia kahib'i-kalèbho Ja'a sèra. Aa rèngu tadhe Ja'a kahèi.<bt>That's true! I'm like a good shepherd. I fully know/recognise My sheep. And they also know/recognise Me.</bt><v n="15" />Èèna, èci èèna ka dènge Ama Ku ètu sorga tadhe Ja'a, aa Ja'a tadhe Nèngu kahèi. Ja'a sadia kore le ho soro iisi Ja'a toke madhe, sèna ka kahib'i-kalèbho Ja'a bisa mamuri.<bt>It's like Father in heaven knows/recognises Me, and I also know/recognise Him. I am ready/prepared to turn over/give up Myself to the point of death, so that My sheep can live.</bt><note reference="10:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 11:27, Lukas 10:22</note><v n="16" />Abhu kahib'i-kalèbho Ja'a dhu leo era, dhu dhae kaboko kore mèka sèna ka pa'èci dènge kahib'i-kalèbho ètu se'e se. Ja'a hud'i eo pa'oru kore si mi ca era kahèi. Ropa rèngu tadèngi lii Ja'a, rèngu tadhe dènge. Hèia ra mai pa'èci, sèna ka j'aj'i mi ca kaboko dhu dènge dhèu madhenga èci.<bt>I have other sheep, who have not yet joined/united with My sheep here. I must go gather/herd them together. Later when they have heard My voice, they will know/recognise (Me) immediately. So then they will come and join into one gathering/flock that has one shepherd. [EXEG: building on higher level context with 10:3-5]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Nèti èèna ka, Ama Ku ètu sorga sue Ja'a. Te Ja'a dhu sadia le soro iisi Ja'a toke madhe, sèna ka Ja'a bisa mamuri hari.<bt>Because of that, My Father in heaven loves Me. Cuz (elaboration) I am ready/prepared to give up Myself to the point of death, so I can live again/come back to life. [EXEG: Carson, HCE]</bt><v n="18" />Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu laka-seti Ja'a ho madhe, te ngaa Ja'a mesa ku soro iisi la'a toke madhe. Ja'a dènge hak ho soro ngi'u Ja'a, aa dènge hak kahèi sèna ka kore hari. Paredha ne, dhu Ja'a sèmi kore le nèti Ama Ku ètu sorga.&gt;&gt;<bt>There is nobody who forces Me to die, but I myself am the one who is prepared to give up Myself to the point of death. I have the right to give up Myself. I also have the right to take it back. This command here, I have received from My Father in heaven.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Lula dhèu se tadèngi lii padhai Yesus sèmi èèna, ka dhèu Yahudi se pab'ala hari isi-aanga ra.<bt>Because they heard Yesus talking like that, the Yahudi people were arguing again with each other.</bt><v n="20" />Abhu dhèu ae nèti rèngu dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne, huj'u! Aa nidhu tao Ne! Nga tao ka miu d'èi nanene Ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>There were many of the who said, “This person here is crazy! And He has been done (=possessed) by an evil spirit. Why is it that you want to listen to Him?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Te ngaa abhu cahag'e peka na, &lt;&lt;Ne'e ne nèti boe lii padhai dhèu huj'u, sina ma? Lii padhai sèmi se'e se, kalua boe nèti d'ara hèb'a nidhu! Aa nidhu sèra bisa boe kahèi puri-pa'èle musi madha dhèu bèdhu, si?&gt;&gt;<bt>But there were some others who said, “This is not the talk of a crazy person, right? Words like that have never come out of an evil spirit's mouth! And evil spirits also don't heal the eyes of blind people, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ama-ama dhèu Yahudi ro'o boe sèmi Lamatua Yesus<bt>The leaders of the Yahudi people don't want to accept the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu Yahudi neo tao kalela agama rèngu. Lod'o be'a ne, lèke dènge hèru pacuhi. Pesta ne, pasanèd'e dhèu Yahudi lod'o dhu dhèu leo mai pakaj'alu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i Ama Lamatua ètu kota Yerusalem, ka ra pamèu ne sèna ka ringi hari ca tèka.<bt>At that time, the Yahudi people were about to do/make one of their religious festivals/holidays. That holiday fell on/during the cold season. This feast reminded the Yahudi people (about) when other people/foreigners had defiled/made dirty God's Temple in the city of Yerusalem, and then they had made it clean/purified it to consecrate/ordain it again.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ringi"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-03 01:02:38Z" status="Anyone">(acara) bekin dingin</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:22" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Limuri ne dhèu Yahudi peka kalela ne, <span class="Italic">Hanuka, </span>dhu padètu dènge hari Natal. Lii lolo na sèmi ne'e ka: ètu tèu 167 (cangasu èna nguru pidhu--lod'o Kristus dhae mai mèka), jedheraa dhèu Siria èci, ngara na Antiokus Epifanes, paguri eele kota Yerusalem. Nèngu pakaj'alu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i kahèi, dènge j'ara na hake palaho mei korban, ka tao era sogo-tagu na ètu èèna. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu Yahudi maruru. Ka tanggal 25 hèru <span class="Italic">Kislef, </span>tèu 164 (cangasu èna nguru èpa--lod'o Kristus dhae mai mèka), ra pamèu hari Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne, hèia ra tao acara sèna ka ringi hari Èmu ne.<bt>These days the Yahudi people refer to that holiday/festival saying, <span class="Italic">Hanuka,</span> which falls quite near to Natal (Christmas). It's story is like this: in the year 167 (before Kristus had come), there was a Sirian general, named Antiokus Epifanes, who destroyed the city of Yerusalem. He also defiled/made dirty the Temple, by breaking up/destroying the *altar (sacrifice table) there, and he erected/set up his objects of traditional worship there. Because of that, the Yahudi people rebelled. Then on the 25th day of <span class="Italic">Kislef</span> in the year 164 BC, they made clean/purified the Temple again, and they made a ceremony to consecrate/ordain the Temple again.</bt></note><v n="23" />Yesus kako palème ètu madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i ne, ètu era dhu ra pangare na, &lt;Paleo Dhèu Aae Soleman&gt;.<bt>Yesus was walking around inside the Temple yard, in the place they refer to as ‘King Soleman's Canopy/Pavilion’ (=large, open-sided).</bt><v n="24" />Hèia ama-ama dhèu Yahudi mai lingu rare Ne, ka ra peka, &lt;&lt;Eeh! Ji'i se mate toke d'ai pèri lod'o hari, ho nge'a? Ladhe Èu ne, nuka Kristus, na, peka mola-mola.&gt;&gt;<bt>And the leaders of the Yahudi people came and crowded around Him, saying, “Eeh! How long will we-exc have to keep waiting, before we can find out? If You here are Kristus, na, tell us straight/plainly/openly.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Yesus b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a dhu peka mema le, te ngaa miu mo'o boe lèka. Aa te ngaa j'ara-j'ara dhu Ja'a tao, aa'i-aa'i madhutu paredha Ama Ku di. J'ara se'e se ka dhu pad'elo, na, Ja'a ne, cee.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “I have already told you (before this), but you don't want to believe2. Whereas in fact, the things that I do, are all just following My Father's commands. Those are the things which show who I am.</bt><v n="26" />Te ngaa miu mo'o boe lèka Ja'a, lula miu se kahib'i-kalèbho Ja'a boe.<bt>But you don't want to believe in Me, because you are not My sheep.</bt><v n="27" />Te kahib'i-kalèbho Ja'a dhu tare'a sèra, tadhe lii Ja'a. Rèngu madhutu Ja'a, aa Ja'a tadhe rèngu kahèi.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) My real/true sheep know/recognise My voice. They also follow/obey Me. I also know/recognise them.</bt><v n="28" />Ja'a hia si mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe, aa rèngu cèri eele boe nèti Ama Lamatua kahèi. Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu bisa parame rare si nèti Ja'a.<bt>I give them real life that never ends, and they also are not separated off/cut off from God. There is not one person who can snatch them (successfully) from Me. [EXEG: on “perish” see note at 3:16.]</bt><v n="29" />Ama Ku ètu sorga ka dhu pangèd'u rèngu mi Ja'a. Nèngu èra risi aa'i mèu-mèu. Nèti èèna ka, abhu boe ca dhèu sa hèi, dhu bisa parame rare si nèti Nèngu.<bt>My Father in heaven is the one who handed them over/entrusted them to Me. He is greater/more powerful than everything. That is why there is nobody who can snatch them from Him.</bt><v n="30" />Te Ama Ku dènge Ja'a ne, èci.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) My Father and I are one/united.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ropa tadèngi rare, hèia ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se rare hari hadhu, neo pèci pamadhe Yesus.<bt>Hearing that, the leader of the Yahudi people picked up stones once again, wanting/intending to throw killing Yesus. [EXEG: Carson, NLT, CEV.]</bt><v n="32" />Ka Yesus padhai lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a pad'elo le j'ara dhu be'a ae-ae nèti Ama Ku. Miu pake j'ara be'a mia, ho neo pèci pamadhe Ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus spoke, saying, “I have shown (you) many good thing from My Father. Which of these good things are you-pl using to stone Me to death?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Hèia dhèu se dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i pèci boe èu lula èu tao j'ara be'a. Te ngaa ji'i huku èu dènge j'ara pèci pake hadhu, lula èu pahahe Ama Lamatua. Te èu dhoka dhèu rai-haha di, te ngaa tao iisi mu nuka sèmi Ama Lamatua! Seli-kolane, nga!&gt;&gt;<bt>They responded, saying, “We-exc are not stoning you, because you do good things. But we are punishing you by stoning, because you have *blasphemed/slandered/insulted God! Cuz (elaboration) you are only human, but you elevate yourself to be like God. That's way beyond (what's acceptable) [+objection]!”</bt><note reference="10:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Atora nèti Ama-ama Agama 24:16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ka Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia? Ètu d'ara Atora agama dhu miu mèd'u, dhu suri na, &lt;Ja'a peka mema, na, miu ama-ama se, dewa&gt;.<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying, “How's that? In those Religious Regulations that you hold, it is written, saying, ‘I have told (you) beforehand, saying, you-pl leaders/bosses here, are god(s) [loan]’. [EXEG: Carson, Morris, TRT, favour interpretation that this is about leaders, not about all of God's people. NOTE to daughter translations: In Kupang we tried ‘dewa’ here instead of ‘tuhan’, but it broke the logic of Jesus' argument thru vs. 36.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lamatua"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-03 01:31:33Z" status="Anyone">Lamatua rai-haha 1) tuan yg berdosa (kuasa gelap), ke dewa ; 2) bapa-mama sbg lamatua rai-haha</Message></Annotation><note reference="10:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 82:1,2,6</note><v n="35" />Èdhi te'a le, na, aa'i-aa'i dhu suri ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, lèke, aa bisa boe core eele. Ama Lamatua mesa Na dhu peka le dhèu sèra, na, rèngu se, &lt;dewa&gt;.<bt>We-inc already know that everything that is written in the Scriptures is true, and cannot be thrown away/discarded/annulled. God himself refers to those people saying they are ‘gods’.</bt><v n="36" />De tasamia ka miu bisa peka, na, Ja'a ne pahahe Ama Lamatua lula Ja'a peka, na, Ja'a ne Ana Ama Lamatua? Maso boe asa d'ara kahadhu, si! Te Ama ètu sorga ka dhu paj'uj'u Ja'a aa pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne.<bt>So (consequently), how is it that you can say I am blaspheming because I said I am God's Child? That doesn't make sense (Lit: doesn't enter into the brain)! Cuz (elaboration) Father in heaven is the one who designated Me and sent/commissioned Me to come to this world.</bt><v n="37" />Sèmi ne'e. Ladhe Ja'a pakako boe sasab'a-la'a Ama Ku, na, miu baku parcaya Ja'a.<bt>It's like this. If I do not continue to carry out My Father's work. na, you shouldn't believe in Me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madha mèu "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-03 01:37:56Z" status="Anyone">tidak usa</Message></Annotation><v n="38" />Te ngaa Ja'a pakako taruu sasab'a Ama Ku. De masi ka miu lèka boe Ja'a, te ngaa miu hud'i sèmi mere ku tadha malaa dhu Ja'a tao. Dènge sèmi èèna, miu bisa me'a kahèi, na, Ama Ku dhu pa'èki dènge Ja'a. Aa Ja'a pa'èki dènge Nèngu kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I do carry out My Father's work continually. So (consequently) even though you don't believe in Me, nevertheless you must accept the amazing signs that I do/have done. In that way you can also understand that My Father is bound/linked with Me. And I am also bound/linked with Him” [EXEG: “the works that I do” = ??; first group of UNS's got it no problem, but UNS's in consultant check didn't; NIV, Morris, Carson “miracles” (but not limited to).]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Ka dhèu se sèku kèpe Ne hari, te ngaa Na tabhèli eele nèti kacui-aai rèngu.<bt>Then they tried again to catch/arrest Him, but He slipped through/escaped from their hands.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tabhèli "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-03 01:49:13Z" status="Anyone">slipped through</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Hèia Yesus la'e hari asa cabèka loko Yarden, ètu era dhu uru èèna Yohanis sarani dhèu. Ka Na pea taha ètu nèi.<bt>Then Yesus went again to the other side of the Yarden river, to that first place where Yohanis had previously baptised people. Then2 He stayed there (remote) temporarily.</bt><note reference="10:40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:28</note><v n="41" />Dhèu ae mai tenge Ne. Hèia ra peka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis tao nèdhi boe tadha malaa. Te ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu nèngu lole lula-nèti Yesus ne, lèke tare'a-re'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Many people came looking for Him. And they spoke, saying, “Yohanis never did amazing signs. But everything he said about this Yesus here is true!”</bt><v n="42" />Ka dhèu ae ètu nèi parcaya Yesus.<bt>And many people there believed in Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mamadhe Lasarus<bt>The death of Lasarus (implies an internally complex event)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="11" />
      <v n="1-2" />Abhu dhèu èci, ngara na Lasarus. Nèngu pea ètu rae Betania, sama-sama dènge a'a na bhèni dhèu dua, Maria dènge Marta. (Maria ne'e, ka dhu pakose haga Lamatua Yesus dènge èi hèu mèngi, ka pamèu pake rèu kètu na.) Ca lod'o, ka Lasarus pèd'a aae.<bt>There was a person named Lasarus. He lived in the village of Betania, together with his two older sisters, Maria and Marta. (This Maria here, is the one who poured the Lord Yesus' feet with aromatic oil, and then wiped/cleaned it using her own hair.) One time, Lasarus became severely ill. [EXEG: (Morris) It seems that Martha was the elder of the two; (TRT) For some languages it is necessary to specify/say whether Mary and Martha were older or younger than Lazarus. We do not know for sure who was oldest, but some Bible scholars think that Martha was oldest and Lazarus was youngest, based on the order of their names in verses 5 and 19. In the Bible the names of brothers and sisters are often listed according to their ages. All three were adults,]</bt><note reference="11:1-2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 10:38-39; Yohanis 12:3</note><v n="3" />Ka ana hèni na dhèu dua se pa'adhu lii moa hia Yesus, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lasarus, angalai Ama èèna, pèd'a aae.&gt;&gt;<bt>So his two sisters sent a message to Yesus, saying, “Lasarus, Father's (=Your) friend, is severely ill.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ropa Yesus tadèngi lii moa ne, hèia Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èi papèd'a ne nèti boe mamadhe. Ama Lamatua neo pake j'ara ne'e ho pad'elo dadedha Na. Sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i ded'e padedha-dedha Ja'a, nuka Ana Ama Lamatua ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus heard that message, He spoke, saying, “This sickness will not bring death. God is going to use this matter to show His glory/high-ness. So that people will *glorify (elevate way up high) Me, that is, God's Child.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Yesus sue Marta, Maria, dènge ari ra Lasarus.<bt>Yesus loved Marta, Maria, and their younger sibling Lasarus. [EXEG: see note on vs. 1]</bt><v n="6" />Lod'o Na tadèngi, na, Lasarus dhu pèd'a, Yesus pea dua lod'o era ètu cabèka loko Yarden.<bt>When He heard that Lasarus was sick, Yesus still stayed another two days on the other side of the Yarden river.</bt><v n="7" />Ka Na peka dènge ana madhutu Na sèra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai lati hari asa era pea Lasarus ètu propensi Yudea.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, He told His disciples, saying, “Let's go back again to Lasarus' place in the province of Yudea.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa ana madhutu Na pab'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese. Lai-lai ne, ama-ama dhèu Yahudi sèra neo pèci pamadhe Ama ètu nèi. Te ngaa Ama neo lamu hari asa nèi?&gt;&gt;<bt>But His disciples protested, saying, “Father Teacher. Just recently the leaders of the Yahudi people wanted to stone you to death there (remote). But now You want to go back there again?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Baku madha'u! Bèli-bèli, nèti lod'o rea toke lod'o cèna, canguru dua jam, si? Ladhe kako ètu d'ara saraa, dhèu kadhunu boe. Te saraa pasaraa rai-haha ho dhèu bisa ladhe rèdhi dènge be'a.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “Don't be afraid! Every day, from sun up to sun down, (there are) 12 hours, right? If/when walking in the light, a person doesn't stumble. Cuz (elaboration) the light shines on the earth/world so people can see well. [EXEG: IF we spiritualise too much in this verse to identify the light at two levels, then 9-10 don't hang together very well.]</bt><v n="10" />Te ngaa ladhe dhèu kako ètu d'ara maroga, na kadhunu pahari-pahari, te dènge boe saraa.&gt;&gt;<bt>But if a person walks in the dark, he stumbles repeatedly, cuz (elaboration) he has no light.”</bt><note reference="11:9-10" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu a'abhu Yesus, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a nuka sèmi saraa. De lod'o-lod'o Ja'a dènge miu era, na, miu ngaa-ngaa tao boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus meant, saying, “I am like the light. So (consequently), as long as I am still together with you-pl, na, you are safe/nothing will happen to you.”</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Yesus padhai lii èle, ka Na peka, &lt;&lt;Angalai èdhi Lasarus bhèj'i le. Te ngaa pe Ja'a laku parèi ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus finished speaking like that, He told (them), saying, “Our-inc friend Lasarus has gone to sleep. But I will go get/wake him up.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia ana madhutu Na peka, na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ladhe nèngu bhèj'i di, sasoa na, èèna na nèngu èle nèti papèd'a, si?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then His disciples said, “Father. If he is only sleeping, that means he will get well from his sickness, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ra peka sèmi èèna, lula rèngu ngee, na, Yesus padhai lii lula-nèti bhèj'i dhu biasa di. Aa te ngaa, Yesus lole lula-nèti mamadhe Lasarus.<bt>They spoke like that because they thought Yesus was talking about normal sleep. Whereas in fact, He was talking about Lasarus' death.</bt><v n="14" />Hèia Yesus peka mola-mola dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Lasarus madhe le.<bt>Then Yesus explained clearly to them, saying, “It's like this. Lasarus has died.</bt><v n="15" />Aa te ngaa Ja'a karej'e lula Ja'a aad'o ètu nèi lod'o dhu na madhe mèka, sèna ka miu baku susa. Te, ngaa dhu j'aj'i ne'e, èèna ka dhu tao miu bisa parcaya Ja'a. Mai lati ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>In actual fact, I'm glad because I was not there (remote), before he died, so that you-pl would be troubled/in strife/upset. Cuz (elaboration) what is going to happen now, will make you able to believe in Me. Come on, let's go!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Hèia Tomas, dhu dhèu paroa, na, &lt;&lt;ana kembar,&gt;&gt; peka dènge ana madhutu dhu leo sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai ka! Be'a risi aa'i-aa'i ti lati, sèna ka madhe palere-lere dènge Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Tomas, who they called, “Twin (loan),” told the other disciples, saying, “Let's go! It's better for all of us to go, so that we-inc die together with Him.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus la'e asa Betania, ka pa'èra d'ara Marta<bt>The Lord Yesus goes to Betania, and comforts/encourages Marta</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17-19" />Ka Yesus si lasi asa rae Betania.<bt>So/then Yesus (coll.) went to the village of Betania.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Rae ne, kaj'èu nèti Yerusalem tèlu kilometer di. Ka dhèu Yahudi nèti nèi, ae ka dhu mai beke, sèna ka pa'èra d'ara Marta dènge Maria.<bt>That village was only 3 kilometers distance from Yerusalem. And many Yahudi people came from there to stay awake (cultural term = sit with grieving family) and comfort Marta and Maria.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Yesus si d'ai nèi, heka re'a, na, dhèu padhane le Lasarus èpa lod'o kèna.<bt>When Yesus (coll.) arrived there, they just found out that people had already buried Lasarus four days ago.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ka lod'o Marta tadèngi, na, Yesus mai le, hèia la'e paraga dènge Yesus. Te ngaa Maria mate ètu èmu.<bt>So/then when Marta heard that Yesus had come, she went to/and met Yesus. But Maria waited in/at the house.</bt><v n="21" />Hèia Marta lii dènge Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama, ee! Ladhe Ama ètu ne'e, tatu ari ja'a madhe boe.<bt>Then Marta told Yesus, saying, “Father, ee! If You were here, surely my younger sibling would not have died.</bt><v n="22" />Te ngaa ja'a parcaya kahèi, sad'i Ama manèngi ngaa èèna ka nèti Ama Lamatua, tatu abhu.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I am also confident/believing/sure, whatever You request from God, na, (You) will certainly get it.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka Yesus lii dènge ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Marta! Èèna na, Ari mu mamuri hari.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yesus told her, saying, “Marta! Your younger sibling will live again.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Marta padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ke'a, pe d'ai lod'o èle rai-haha ne, ladhe Ama Lamatua pamamuri hari dhèu madhe aa'i-aa'i, Nèngu pamamuri hari kahèi ari ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Marta acknowledged, saying, “I know/understand, later at the end of the world, when God makes all dead people come back to life, He will also bring back to life my younger sibling.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Hèia Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ka dhu hia dhèu madhe mamuri hari. Ja'a ka dhu hia dhèu, mamuri dhu lèke kahèi. De dhèu dhu parcaya Ja'a, abhu mamuri èèna, masi ka nèngu madhe.<bt>Then Yesus told (her), saying, “I am the one who makes dead people come back to life. I am also the one who gives real life to people. So (consequently) the person who believes in Me will get/obtain that life, even if/though he dies. [NOTE to daughter translations: Be careful about ambiguous renderings. Avoid implication of 1) coming into belief after dying /biar dia su mati/, 2) a person who has ever/once believed (but later didn't) /yang parná parcaya sang Beta/]</bt><v n="26" />Ka dhèu dhu unu mamuri dhu lèke èèna, aa parcaya Ja'a, bèli-camèd'a madhe boe, te ngaa mamuri taruu. Marta, èu parcaya lii padhai Ja'a ne, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>And the person who gets that real life, and believes in Me, will not die, but live continually. Marta, do you believe what I'm saying, or (what)?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia Marta dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Oo, Ama! Ja'a parcaya, na, Èu ne, nuka Kristus, Dhèu dhu Ama Lamatua paj'uj'u mema karèi nèti uru ka. Aa Èu ne, Ana Ama Lamatua dhu Na padhadha tèke hia mai asa rai-haha ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Marta responded, saying, “Oo [+affirmative], Father! I believe that You are Kristus, the Person who God has designated from long ago. And You are God's Child, whom He has promised to send into this world.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus tangi<bt>The Lord Yesus cries</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Ropa Marta padhai lii nare, hèia na lèpa asa èmu na. Ka na paroa ari na Maria, sèna ka dua ra mesa-mesa ra. Ka na peka, na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese mai le. Nèngu neo paraga dènge èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Marta finished speaking like that, she went home. And she called her younger sibling Maria, so the two of them were alone. She told (her), saying, “Father Teacher has come. He is wanting to meet with you.”</bt><v n="29-31" />Ropa tadèngi sèmi èèna, hèia Maria la'e dènge ka tenge Yesus. Ropa dhèu Yahudi dhu beke dènge Maria ètu d'ara èmu, rèdhi nèngu kèd'i sahèka, ka rai li'u la'e, hèia lasi madhutu ne re limuri. Te rèngu pangee, na, Maria la'e tangi asa ro'a Lasarus.<bt>Hearing that, Maria left quickly to look for Yesus. When the Yahudi people who were staying awake with Maria in the house, saw her get up quickly and rush out, they followed her from behind. Cuz (elaboration) they thought that Maria was going to go cry at Lasarus' grave.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lod'o èèna, Yesus si d'ai mèka d'ara rae. Nèngu ètu era dhu Marta paraga dènge Ne.<bt>At that time, Yesus (coll.) had not yet arrived in the village. He was still at that place where Marta had met with Him.</bt><v n="32" />Ropa Maria la'e d'ai era èèna, ka ladhe nèdhi Yesus. Hèia na patitu kètu urutuu ètu madha Yesus. Ka na lii, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Sèmi Ama ètu ne'e, tatu ari ja'a madhe boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Maria arrived at that place, she saw Yesus. Then she knelt before Yesus. And she said, “Father! If You had been here, certainly my younger sibling would not have died.” [NOTE to daughter trans: same wording as vs. 21]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ropa Yesus nèdhi Maria tangi, aa dhèu Yahudi dhu madhutu ne tangi kahèi, ka Yesus nasa aa d'ara Na susa.<bt>When Yesus saw Maria crying, and those Yahudi people who had followed her was also crying, He was angry, and His insides were troubled/upset. [EXEG: NLT: he was moved with indignation and was deeply troubled. (Carson) ‘he was outraged in spirit, and troubled’ (see his extended discussion, also Morris).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ta'u'a"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-11 01:27:07Z" status="Anyone">fed up</Message></Annotation><v n="34" />Hèia Na karèi, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu padhane ne ètu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He asked, saying, “Where did you-pl bury him?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mai, Ama! Sèna ka mèdhi unu mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>They responded, saying, “Come [invite], Father! To see for yourself.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Hèia Yesus tangi.<bt>Then Yesus wept.</bt><v n="36" />Ka dhèu Yahudi se papeka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ku laa. Na sue Lasarus titu kèna!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 those Yahudi people spoke among themselves, saying, “Look at that. He really loved Lasarus!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Te ngaa abhu cahag'e dhu papeka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne ka dhu hia dhèu bèdhu bisa nèdhi. Nga tao ka Nèngu bisa boe tenge j'ara, sèna ka Lasarus baku madhe?&gt;&gt;<bt>But there were some others who spoke among themselves, saying, “This Person here is the one who made a blind person so he could see. Why is it that He is not able to find a way so Lasarus didn't die?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lasarus mamuri hari<bt>Lasarus lives again</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Ka d'ara Yesus susa. Hèia la'e padètu-dètu asa ro'a dhu ra padhane Lasarus. Ro'a ne dhu ra katange le dènge hadhu aae cue.<bt>Then Yesus' insides were troubled (=upset, sad). And He went close to the hole/cave/grave which they used to bury Lasarus. They had closed that cave with a large stone.</bt><v n="39" />Hèia Yesus pua dhèu ètu sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Loli eele ku hadhu nèti hèb'a ro'a ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus ordered people there, saying, “Roll away this stone from the opening/door of this cave!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Marta, ana hèni dhèu madhe ne, peka, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Irii, Ama! Na madhe èpa lod'o kèna! Tatu hèu le.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Marta, the dead person's sister, said, “Irii, [+dismay] Father! He's been dead for four days already! Surely (he) smells (bad).”</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01769b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ka Yesus pasanèd'e ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sanèd'e lii Ja'a deo na, si? Ja'a dhu peka mema le, na, ladhe èu tare'a-re'a parcaya Ja'a, pe mèdhi dadedha Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 Yesus reminded her, saying, “(You) remember what I said earlier, right? I already told you that if you really believe (in) Me, you will see God's glory/high-ness.” [EXEG: in vs. 23-26 it is ‘believe in Me’.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Hèia pèri-pèri dhèu loli eele hadhu nèti hèb'a ro'a ne. Ka Yesus ladhe asa dedha-liru, hèia Na peka, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ja'a manèngi makasi, lula Ama nanene Ja'a.<bt>Then there were several people who (re)moved that stone from the opening/door of the cave/grave. Then Yesus faced (up) toward the sky, and said, “Father! I give thanks, because Father listens to Me.</bt><v n="42" />Ja'a ke'a karèi nèti uru ka, na, Ama nanene taruu Ja'a. Te ngaa doe ne Ja'a peka sèmi ne'e, sèna ka dhèu-dhèu dhu titu ètu ne'e, bisa re'a, na, Ama ka dhu pua Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>I already know from before, saying, Father always listens to Me. But I am saying that now, so that the people standing here can know that Father is the one who sent/commissioned Me.”</bt><v n="43" />Ropa peka nare, hèia Na paroa dènge lii mèdhu, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lasarus! Kalua ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>When He had finished speaking, then He shouted with a loud voice, saying, “Lasarus! Come out [+imperative]!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Ka dhèu madhe ne kalua nèti d'ara ro'a. Kacui-aai dènge haga na pa'èki era dènge bèla hutu dhèu madhe. Aa abhu bèla dhu pahutu rèhu na kahèi. Yesus pua dhèu ètu sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Bhoke eele bèla hutu se, sèna ka na kako!&gt;&gt;<bt>And the dead person came out of the cave/grave. His hands and feet were bound with dead people's cloth. And there was also a cloth that covered his face. Yesus ordered people there, saying, “Undo that cloth so he can walk!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra tenge j'ara ho neo pamadhe Lamatua Yesus<bt>They look for a way to kill the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:1-5; Markus 14:1-2; Lukas 22:1-2)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="45" />Ropa laladhe rèdhi tatao Yesus ne, dhèu Yahudi dhu beke dènge Maria, ae ka dhu parcaya Yesus.<bt>When they saw what Yesus had done, many of the Yahudi people who came to stay awake (=sit with famliy of dead) with Maria, believed in Yesus.</bt><v n="46" />Te ngaa abhu cahag'e kahèi dhu lasi paraga dènge dhèu nèti partei Parisi, sèna ka peka tatao Yesus ne dènge rèngu.<bt>But there also were some others who went to meet with people of the Parisi party, to tell them what Yesus had done.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="47" />Èle èèna, hèia kètu agama Yahudi sèra, dènge dhèu Parisi pakaboko ho padhue. Ra pakarèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu ne'e ne, tao tadha malaa rupa-rupa! De èdhi tao Ne tasamia hari?<bt>After that, the *chief priests (heads of the priests), and the Parisi people gathered to confer/discuss a matter. They asked each other, saying, “That Person has done many sorts of amazing signs! So (consequently) what else should we-inc be doing? [EXEG: Carson, Morris on “what have we accomplished?”]</bt><v n="48" />Te ladhe èdhi soro tèke Ne, bèli-camèd'a dhèu aa'i-aa'i sanao-maena Nèngu j'aj'i dhèu aae rèngu. Dènge j'ara ne'e, èèna na sordad'u Roma sèra mai paguri eele Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i èdhi dènge palaho isi kabarai èdhi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if we-inc just let Him be, then everyone will be hoping (doublet) in Him as (if) He were their king. If that happens, then the Roma soldiers will come and destroy/ruin/tear apart our Temple and destroy2 our people/citizens (not government).” [EXEG: not “believe in” in spiritual sense of salvation, but “put their hopes in” in the sense of a political deliverer and rallying point. Note following sentence about Romans.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="49" />Tèu èèna, Kayafas dhu j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi. Na peka, na, &lt;&lt;Goa, ee! Miu me'a boe ngaa-ngaa!<bt>That year, Kayafas is the one who was *high priest (highest head of priests). He spoke, saying, “That's dumb, ee! You-pl don't know anything!</bt><v n="50" />Te ladhe dhèu èci madhe pala dhèu aa'i-aa'i, èèna be'a risi hia miu. Te ladhe aad'o, na, sordad'u Roma mai, pamadhe aa'i mèu-mèu isi kabarai èdhi dhèu Yahudi ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if there is only person who dies for everyone, that is better for you. Cuz (elaboration) if not, then the Roma soldiers will come and kill off our entire Yahudi citizenry!”</bt><v n="51" />Lii Kayafas ne mai boe nèti d'ara nèngu unu na. Te Ama Lamatua pake hèb'a na, lula nèngu ka kètu kapai risi agama d'ara tèu èèna. Nèti èèna ka, Kayafas peka tèke, na, bèli-camèd'a Yesus madhe pala dhèu Yahudi aa'i-aa'i ra.<bt>What Kayafas said did not come from his own insides. Cuz (elaboration) God was using his mouth, because he was *high priest that year. That is why Kayafas foretold that Yesus would die for all Yahudi people.</bt><v n="52" />Aa te ngaa, dhu lèke ka, Yesus madhe boe hia dhèu Yahudi mesa ra di, te ngaa pala dhèu unu Ama Lamatua aa'i-aa'i dhu pale-lème ètu rai-haha ne. Nèngu èèna na oru nare si j'aj'i mi suku ca nau-ca nadha.<bt>Whereas in fact, in truth He would not only die for the Yahudi people/nation alone, but for all of God's people who are scattered around this world. He would make/gather them become like one tribe/race/people/nation (doublet).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="53" />Lula lii padhai Kayafas ne'e ka, karèi nèti lod'o èèna, ama-ama dhèu Yahudi tenge j'ara ho neo pamadhe Yesus.<bt>Because of what Kayafas said, beginning from that time, the leaders of the Yahudi people looked for ways to kill Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="54" />Nèti èèna ka, Yesus la'e heka asa madha dhèu ae ètu talora ama-ama dhèu Yahudi. Nèngu dènge ana-ana madhutu Na lasi asa d'ara kota èci, ngara na Efraim, padètu dènge d'ara mamoo. Ka ra pea taha ètu èèna.<bt>That is why Yesus did not go openly anymore among the leaders of the Yahudi people. He and His disciples went to a city named Efraim, which was near the/an empty place. And they stayed there temporarily.</bt><note reference="11:54" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sensus 9:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="55" />Lod'o èèna, dètu le dènge lod'o kalela Paska agama Yahudi. Dhu tema le, d'ai lod'o sèmi èèna, dhèu ae nèti rae-rae mai pakaboko ètu kota Yerusalem ho madhutu kalela Paska ètu èèna. Dhèu se d'ai uru, ho pamèu iisi madhutu atora agama.<bt>At that time, the Yahudi religious festival Paska was very near. The norm/custom was for many people from the villages to come and gather together in the city of Yerusalem to participate in the Paska feast there. These people (would) arrive ahead of time, to clean/purify themselves according to religious regulations.</bt><v n="56" />Ae ka nèti rèngu patangi-tenge Yesus ètu èèna. Ropa ra titu ètu madha Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i, ka ra pakarèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Madhutu a'abhu miu, tasamia? Yesus mai madhutu pesta kalela Paska ne, do aad'o?&gt;&gt;<bt>Many people who came to Yerusalem were looking (all over) for Yesus there. When they stood in the Temple yard, then they asked each other, saying, “According to your-pl opinion, how is it? Do you think that Yesus is going to come participate in this Paska religious feast, or not?”</bt><v n="57" />Te ngaa kètu agama Yahudi sèra, dènge dhèu Parisi paredha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu re'a Yesus ètu mia, na, peka dènge ji'i!&gt;&gt; Aa te ngaa rèngu neo kèpe Ne.<bt>But the *chief priests (heads of the priests), and the Parisi people had ordered, saying, “If there is anyone who knows where Yesus is, na, tell us!” Whereas in fact, their intention was to catch/arrest Him.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Maria pakose haga Yesus dènge èi hèu mèngi<bt>Maria pours aromatic oil on the Lord Yesus' feet</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:6-13; Markus 14:3-9)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="12" />
      <v n="1" />Di èna lod'o ka, d'ai lod'o kalela Paska, ka Yesus si mai hari asa rae Betania. Lasarus si pea ètu èèna. Nèngu ka dhu madhe, dhu Yesus pamamuri hari le.<bt>Then, when there were still six days before the Paska day, Yesus (coll.) came back to the village of Betania. Lasarus (coll.) lived there. He is the one who died, who Yesus had brought back to life.</bt><v n="2" />Hèia rèngu pananasu, sèna ka mèda none Yesus na'a-ninu dènge rèngu. Marta lalau mei. Aa Lasarus madhèdi na'a-ninu mei èci dènge Yesus.<bt>So they cooked so in the evening Yesus could eat-drink with them. Marta was serving table. And Lasarus was sitting eating-drinking/feasting at the same table with Yesus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="none"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-11 03:05:38Z" status="Anyone">nanti, sebentar</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Hèia Maria nare èi hèu mèngi asli ca boto dhu kab'ua. Ka na pasuti mi haga Yesus. Hèia na roso haga Yesus pake rèu kètu nèngu. Ka hèu mèngi ne pale-lème aa'i d'ara èmu èèna.<bt>Then Maria took a bottle of pure (loan) aromatic oil whcih was expensive. And she poured it out on Yesus' feet. Then2 she used her hair to wipe Yesus' feet. And that entire house had a fragrant smell.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roso "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-11 02:57:21Z" status="Anyone">roso = wipe ; pakose = rub</Message></Annotation><note reference="12:3" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu Alkitab lii Yunani, peka èi hèu mèngi ne, <span class="Italic">&lt;nardos&gt;,</span> dhu uru èèna dhèu tao nèti amo aaj'u hèu mèngi. Alkitab lii Idhonesia peka na, &lt;narwastu&gt;. Alkitab lii Yunani peka isi boto ne, ca <span class="Italic">&lt;litra&gt;,</span> nuka tèlu ngasu dua nguru lèmi gram, ele boe d'ai ca tenga liter.<bt>The Yunani language Bible says the name of that oil was <span class="Italic">&lt;nardos&gt;</span>, which they used to make from an aromatic tree root. The Indonesian language Bible calls it ‘narwastu’. The Yunani language Bible also says the size of that bottle was one <span class="Italic">&lt;litra&gt;</span>, that is 325 grams, or around half a liter.</bt></note><note reference="12:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 7:37-38</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Te ngaa ana madhutu Yesus èci, ngara na Yudas Iskariot, dhu èèna na pahie Yesus, ka'ugu aku nèngu na,<bt>But one of Yesus' disciples, named Yudas Iskariot, who would later sell off (=betray) Yesus, complained, saying,</bt><v n="5" />&lt;&lt;Wee! Nga tao ka nèngu pahie boe èi hèu mèngi ne? Te kab'ua na nuka sèmi gaji dhèu èci d'ara ca tèu. Be'a risi pahie, sèna ka kab'ua na pabagi mi dhèu unu aad'o sèra!&gt;&gt;<bt>“Wee! Why didn't she just sell that aromatic oil? Cuz (elaboration) its price/value is the same as a person's wages for a year. It would be better to sell (it) so its money (could be) given/divided out to the poor people!” [NOTE to daughter translations: Gk is passive in last clause (no subject identified). If need subject, use “Lebe bae lu/dia jual...” using Mary as referent.]</bt><note reference="12:5" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Alkitab lii Yunani peka kab'ua èi hèu mèngi ne, tèlu ngasu <span class="Italic">&lt;denari&gt;.</span> Ca <span class="Italic">denari </span>èèna, sama sèmi gaji tuka ca lod'o.<bt>The Yunani language Bible says the value of that oil was 300 <span class="Italic">&lt;denari&gt;</span>. One <span class="Italic">denari</span> was the same as a craftsman's wage for a day.</bt></note><v n="6" />Aa te ngaa Yudas peka sèmi ne'e ne lula boe nèti nèngu sue dhèu-dhèu unu aad'o. Te ngaa lula nèngu, dhèu mana'u. Nèngu ne dhu tèke doi Yesus si, te ngaa ae ka dhu huni nare nèti d'ara kas.<bt>Whereas in fact, Yudas spoke like that, not because he loved/pitied poor people. But because he was a thief. He was the person who kept/stored money for Yesus (coll.), but much/some of it he kept taking secretly from the till/cash(box)/kitty (loan).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka Yesus b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa bhèni ne tao sèmi ne'e. Te nèngu dhu tèke èi hèu mèngi ne, sèna ka lalau ngi'u aae Ja'a ho ra padhane Ja'a.<bt>And Yesus responded, saying, “Let this woman alone/be. Cuz (elaboration) she has saved this aromatic oil, to prepare/look after My corpse for them (non-referential) to bury Me.</bt><v n="8" />Dhèu unu aad'o dhu bera-bera dènge miu. Te ngaa Ja'a ne bèli-camèd'a aad'o heka ètu talora miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Poor people are always with/accompanying you. But later I will no longer be in your-pl midst.”</bt><note reference="12:8" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lole Hari J'ara-j'ara Mamuri 15:11</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kètu agama sèra tenge j'ara ho neo pamadhe Lasarus<bt>The chief priests look for a way to kill Lasarus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Èle èèna, dhèu Yahudi ae ka dhu re'a, na, Yesus ètu rae Betania. Ka dhèu se mai neo rèdhi Ne, aa neo rèdhi Lasarus kahèi. Te rèngu tadèngi le, na, Yesus pamamuri hari le Lasarus nèti mamadhe.<bt>After that, many Yahudi people found out that Yesus was in the village of Betania. So they came wanting to see Him, and also wanting to see Lasarus. Cuz (elaboration) they had heard that Yesus had made Lasarus live again from his death.</bt><v n="10" />Te ngaa kètu-kètu agama padhue ho neo pamadhe Lasarus.<bt>But the *chief priests conferred/connived to kill Lasarus too.</bt><v n="11" />Te dhèu Yahudi ae dhu tadèngi le lii palolo lula-nèti Lasarus ne, ka dhèu se parcaya Yesus. Rèngu se ro'o heka nanene ama-ama dhèu Yahudi.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) many Yahudi people had heard about Lasarus' story, so they believed in Yesus. They didn't want to listen to/obey the leaders of the Yahudi people anymore. [NOTE to daughter translations: watch out for ambiguity “dengar Lasarus pung carita” can be 1) story about Lazarus, or 2) story that Lazarus told. In KM using /so'al/ ‘about’ forces the first reading.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus maso asa d'ara kota Yerusalem sama sèmi dhèu aae-dhèu kapai<bt>The Lord Yesus enters the city of Yerusalem like a big/important person (doublet)</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 21:1-11; Markus 11:1-11; Lukas 19:28-40)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Asa bèli èèna, dhèu ae dhu mai madhutu kalela Paska ètu kota Yerusalem, tadèngi, na, Yesus neo mai asa era ne'e kahèi.<bt>The next day, many people/crowds had come to participate in the Paska feast in the city of Yerusalem, [when they] heard that Yesus was going to come there too.</bt><v n="13" />Ka lasi pare rèu palam ho pake soru mamai Yesus, sama sèmi Nèngu ne, dhèu aae-dhèu kapai. Hèia ra pa'oo aa'i-aa'i ra, aku rèngu na,<bt>So they went and cut palam leaves/fronds [a kind of frond used for funerals and other ceremonies] to use to greet/welcome (formally, fanfare) Yesus' coming, like He was a big/important person (doublet). And they all shouted (festively), saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;<span class="Italic">Hosana!</span> Ji'i koa-kio Ama Lamatua!<bt>“<span class="Italic">Hosana!</span> We-inc praise (doublet) God!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Te Lamatua paj'uj'u d'ara hua iia Na mi Dhèu Aae Isra'el,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God2 has shown His goodness/kindness/grace to the King of Isra'el,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">dhu nèti kolongara Lamatua!&gt;&gt;<bt>who comes bearing God2's name!”</bt><note reference="12:13" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 118:26</note></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01782b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ka Yesus abhu badha keled'ei èni ci'u, hèia Na manya'e. Se'e se j'aj'i nuka sèmi dhu suri tèke le ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, na,<bt>Then Yesus found a juvenile keledai (loan-donkey) animal, and He mounted (it). That is like was written in the *Scriptures, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="15" />&lt;&lt;Miu dhèu kota Yerusalem, baku madha'u!<bt>“You-pl people of the city of Yersusalem, don't be afraid!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Miu dhèu kota &lt;Sion&gt; se, ladhe ku asa nèi!<bt>You-pl people of the city of ‘Sion’ here, look yonder [=imperative]!</bt><note reference="12:15" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Kota Sion, ngara leo nèti kota Yerusalem.<bt>That city of Sion, is another name for the city of Yerusalem.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te Dhèu Aae miu nuka mai nèi!<bt>Cuz (elaboration) your King is coming!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèngu mai manya'e keled'ei èni ci'u.&gt;&gt;<bt>He is coming mounted on a juvenile donkey.”</bt><note reference="12:15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 9:9</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Lod'o èèna, ana madhutu Yesus re'a mèka sasoa nèti j'ara se'e se. Te ngaa bèli-camèd'a, ropa Yesus mamuri hari nèti mamadhe Na, aa Ama Lamatua ded'e Ne padedha-dedha, rèngu heka sanèd'e j'ara-j'ara dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci lula-nèti Nèngu ne. Rèngu sanèd'e kahèi tatao dhèu ae se mi dedha Yesus.<bt>At that time, Yesus' disciples did not understand the meaning of these things/matters. But later on, when Yesus had come back to life from His death, and God *glorified Him (elevated Him very high), only then did they remember the things which were written in the Scriptures about Him. They also remembered what these many people/crowds had done to/for Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Lod'o Yesus pamamuri hari Lasarus nèti mamadhe, hèia Na paroa ne kalua nèti ro'a dhèu madhe èèna, abhu dhèu ae dhu sama-sama dènge Yesus. De limuri ne rèngu lolo palème lula-nèti ngaa dhu uru èèna rèngu rèdhi dènge musi madha ra.<bt>When Yesus brought Lasarus back to life from his death, and called him out from that grave, there were many people together with Yesus. So (conseuqently) now, they were telling/narrating to each other all over (the place) about what they had seen with their own eyes.</bt><v n="18" />Nèti èèna ka, ropa Yesus padètu dènge Yerusalem, dhèu ae mai soru Ne lula rèngu tadèngi le, na, Nèngu ka dhu tao tadha malaa èèna.<bt>That is why many people came to greet Yesus close to Yerusalem, because they had heard that He had done that amazing sign.</bt><v n="19" />Ka dhèu-dhèu Parisi peka, na, &lt;&lt;Peeh! Ladhe ku laa! Dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne, parai-oru ho neo madhutu Ne! Bèli-camèd'a èdhi ka dhu j'èra! Ladhe j'aj'i ka sèmi èèna, èdhi tao tasamia hari?&gt;&gt;<bt>So/then the Parisi people spoke (with each other), saying, “Peeh! [+disgust] Look there! Everyone in this world is acting like a busy-body to follow Him! Later, we-inc are the ones who will be in difficulty/strife/trouble! When it happens like that, what else can we do?” [EXEG: (NIV): See, this is getting us nowhere; (NLT) We've lost!; (CEV) There is nothing that can be done!]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parai-oru "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-11 04:17:24Z" status="Anyone">batasibu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Pèri-pèri dhèu Yunani neo mai paraga dènge Yesus<bt>Several Yunani people who want to meet with Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Abhu dhèu Yunani pèri-pèri dhu mai asa kota Yerusalem palere-lere dènge dhèu leo, ho neo madhutu kalela Paska ètu èèna. Ètu èèna, rèngu neo pahaha iisi mi Ama Lamatua kahèi.<bt>There were several Yunani (Greek) people who came to the city of Yerusalem together with the other people, wanting to participate in the Paska festival there. They also wanted to worship God there.</bt><v n="21" />Hèia dhèu se mai paraga dènge Pelipus, dhu rae nèngu ka Betsaida ètu propensi Galilea. Ra manèngi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i neo paraga dènge Yesus.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they came and met with Pelipus, whose origins were from the village of Betsaida in the province of Galilea. They requested, saying, “We are wanting to meet with Yesus.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ka Pelipus la'e peka dènge Anderias. Hèia dua ra lasi peka dènge Yesus.<bt>So Pelipus went and told Anderias. And the two of them went to speak with Yesus.</bt><v n="23-24" />Ka Yesus peka dènge si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lod'o Ja'a d'ai kèna. Ja'a hud'i madhe ku, heka Ama Lamatua neo ded'e padedha-dedha Ja'a kèna. Tare'a sèmi èèna! Èdhi pakasame ku dènge hini èci. Ladhe èdhi sèle hini ca lamusi, na, hini ne ele iie uuru ku dènge j'ara boho ètu d'ara rai, heka na muri mai, hèia na hia hua-hela ae-ae kèna. Ladhe sèmi boe èèna, hini èèna cue dhoo-dhoo di.<bt>Then Yesus told them, saying, “My time has come. I must die first, before God is going to *glorify (elevate very high) Me. That's right! We-inc could compare it with a seed (for planting). If/when we plant one seed (for planting), na, the seed must swell and soften in the ground first, and disappear/get lost before it comes alive, so it can put out a lot of yield/produce (doublet). if it doesn't do that, it just keeps staying/being just a grain seed. [EXEG: Carson on “germination”, plus discussions with Crofts: Problem: agriculturally the seed doesn't die, it transforms to a different stage. People here say that if the seed had “died”, then it couldn't sprout. Also few other cultures would describe what the seed does as “die”. So the challenge is to find something that both makes sense (the English doesn't) and carries the parallel with Christ's death.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boho"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-04 01:14:54Z" status="Anyone">bengkak; seed softens, outer part decays, *swells prior to sprouting, forcing the secayed outer shell to burst</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bèb'a"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-04 01:33:08Z" status="Anyone">bertambah banyak</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nibhu dhoo"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-04 01:33:26Z" status="Anyone">hanya</Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Dhèu dhu pahae boe dad'èi Ama Lamatua, lula nèngu sue ae mamuri na ètu rai-haha ne, èèna na mamuri na ele iie d'ara. Te ngaa dhèu dhu sadia tèke eele mamuri rai-haha na, bèli-camèd'a nèngu abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe.<bt>A person who doesn't care about God's will (=the things of God), because s/he excessively loves his life in this world, later that life will be lost/disappear (completely) [NOTE: lexical cohesion with above]. But a person who is prepared to (completely) give up/abandon his life in this world, later will get/obtain real life that never ends. [EXEG: (Carson on hate = fundamental preference, not hatred on some absolute scale. On “love his life” he says “to love one's life is a fundamental denial of God's sovereignty, of God's rights, and a brazen elevation of self to the apogee of one's perception, and therefore an idolatrous focus on self, which is the heart of all sin.” “shameless focus on self”. Morris “The verb translated ‘lose’ often means ‘destroy’.”]</bt><note reference="12:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:39, 16:25, Markus 8:35, Lukas 9:24, 17:33</note><v n="26" />Dhèu dhu neo sab'a hia Ja'a, nèngu hud'i madhutu Ja'a taruu. Ja'a ètu mia, na, dhèu pajuu-paleha Ja'a ètu èèna kahèi. Te ladhe abhu dhèu dhu sab'a hia Ja'a, èèna na Ama Ku ètu sorga pakab'ua nèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>The person who wants to work for Me, [NOTE: Dhao word for ‘serve’ is a problem in this context--long discussion and the MTTs have convinced me.] he must follow Me continually. That is, wherever I am, na, My servant (doublet) is also there. Cuz (elaboration) if there is a person who works for Me, My Father in heaven respects/honours him.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ladhe-leru "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-04 01:47:32Z" status="Anyone">look after (position of strength and responsibility/authority); so a parent can l-l small kids, but small kids and lowly servants cannot l-l their parents or bosses</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka mema lula-nèti mamadhe Na<bt>The Lord Yesus foretells about His death</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai Na, peka na, &lt;&lt;D'ara Ja'a susa titu kèna. Te ngaa Ja'a neo peka ngaa hari? Ja'a hud'i manèngi ku, peka na, &lt;Ama! Patabuli Ja'a, sèna ka Ja'a baku madhe ku d'ara lai-lai ne,&gt; do? Bisa boe! Ja'a manèngi boe sèmi èèna, lula Nèngu pua Ja'a mai sèna ka madhe.<bt>Yesus spoke further, saying, “My insides are very troubled/stressed/in strife. But, what else could/should I say? Should I request, saying, ‘Father! Release/spare Me, so that I don't have to die soon,’ or (what)? No! I do not request like that, because He sent/commissioned Me to come so I could/would die.</bt><v n="28" />De dhu Ja'a manèngi ka, &lt;Ama. Hud'i laa Ja'a madhutu dad'èi Ama Ku, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i ded'e padedha-dedha kolongara Ama.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) what I request is: ‘Father. Just let/allow Me to follow/obey Father's will/desire, so that everyone can *glorify (elevate very high) Father's name/reputation.’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia lii èci nèti dedha-liru peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ded'e padedha-dedha le kolongara Ja'a. Aa Ja'a neo ded'e padedha-dedha hari kolongara Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then there was a voice from the sky (doublet), saying, “I have *glorified (elevate very high) My name/reputation. And I am going to *glorify (elevate very high) My name/reputation again.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ka dhèu ae dhu titu ètu sèra sa, tadèngi lii ne'e kahèi, hèia ra peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! D'oro nga!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then those many people who were standing there also heard that voice, and said, “Ira ii! [+amazed] There's thunder!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Cahag'e hari peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o! Ana pajuu Lamatua èci nèti sorga padhai lii dènge Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>There were some other people who spoke, saying, “No! One of God2's *angels from heaven is speaking with Him.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Te ngaa Yesus padhai lii dènge rèngu, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lii deo na, lii hia miu, hia boe Ja'a.<bt>But Yesus told them, saying, “That voice just now, was for you-pl, not for Me.</bt><v n="31" />Limuri ne, dhèu ètu rai-haha ne hud'i lasi asa madha Ama Lamatua, sèna ka Na pama'ète lii langu rèngu. Lamatua neo babège eele kahèi Dhèu Bhelu dhu paredha ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>Now people in this world must go before God, for Him to decide their cases. He is also going to evict that Habitual Evildoer who rules/governs in this world.</bt><v n="32" />Ladhe dhèu ded'e ka Ja'a ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha, pe Ja'a ère kore dhèu aa'i-aa'i, sèna ka ra parcaya Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>If/when people lift Me up on a *cross (crossed wood/pole (doublet)), I will pull/draw inward all people so they believe in Me (purpose, irrealis).” [EXEG: NLT; While language sounds like it refers to the ascencion, vs.33 emphatically ties it with crucifixion; previous context links it to glorification/resurrection. Carson believes John is deliberately using it for multiple meanings.]</bt><v n="33" />(Na padhai lii sèmi ne'e, ho peka j'ara mamadhe Na.)<bt>(He spoke like that, to show what way He would die.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Ka dhèu ètu sèra karèi, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i tadèngi ngèdhi le nèti atora Lamatua, dhu peka na, èèna na Kristus mamuri taruu. Kristus dènge Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a, èci èèna ka, do? De, nga tao ka Èu peka na, &lt;Bèli-camèd'a dhèu neo paca'e Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a èèna ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha?&gt; Te Nèngu ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then people there asked, saying, “We-exc have heard from God2's Regulations/Law, that, later Kristus will live continually. Kristus and the Son of Man are the same, right? So (consequently) why do You say, ‘Later they will hang the Son of Man from a cross?’ So who is that Son of Man?”</bt><note reference="12:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 110:4, Yesaya 9:6, Yeskial 37:25, Daniel 7:14</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Nèbhu heka saraa Ja'a, d'elo heka miu. De lod'o Ja'a dènge miu era, miu hud'i mamuri mola ku, sèna ka bhabhelu-katub'a baku hutu nare saraa dhu ètu d'ara miu. Te dhèu dhu kako ètu d'ara maroga, ne'a boe la'e asa mia.<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying, “It won't be much longer (=soon) that My light doesn't shine on you-pl anymore. So (consequently), while I am still with you, you must live straight (=morally pure), so that evil (doublet) does not cover/shut out that light that is in your insides. Cuz (elaboration) a person who walks in the dark, does not know where he is going. [EXEG: Carson, NLT, HCE, Morris.]</bt><v n="36" />Lod'o saraa Ja'a ne era, miu hud'i parcaya ku Ja'a, sèna ka miu j'aj'i mi dhèu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara saraa, ho me'a, na, miu neo lami mia.&gt;&gt;<bt>While My light is still here, you must believe in Me, so that you are/become people who live in the light, so you know where you are going to go.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa Yesus padhai lii nare, hèia la'e tèke eele dhèu se'e, sèna ka Nèngu mesa-mesa na.<bt>After Yesus finished speaking like that, then He left/withdrew from those people/crowds, so that He could be alone.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu Yahudi ro'o boe parcaya Lamatua Yesus<bt>Yahudi people don't believe in the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Masi ka Yesus tao le tadha malaa ae-ae ètu madha dhèu ae, te ngaa ro'o boe parcaya Ne.<bt>Even though Yesus had already done many amazing signs in front of those many people, nevertheless they didn't want to believe in Him.</bt><v n="38" />Ne'e ne palèke dènge lii Yesaya, ca dhèu nèti lii padhai Lamatua, dhu suri peka na,<bt>That was like what God2's spokesperson Yesaya had said, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Lamatua! Abhu boe dhèu dhu parcaya lii padhai ji'i!<bt>“Lord/God2! There is nobody who believes what we-exc say!</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Te masi ka Lamatua pad'elo le koasa,<bt>Cuz (elaboration) even though You have already shown Your power/authority,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">te ngaa dhèu sèra ladhe rèdhi boe ngaa-ngaa!&gt;&gt;<bt>nevertheless people don't see anything at all!” [STYLE: changed RQ to statement; HCE]</bt><note reference="12:38" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 53:1</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Nèti èèna ka, limuri ne dhèu Yahudi cahag'e parcaya boe Lamatua, lèke sèmi dhu Yesaya suri tèke ètu era leo d'ara sasuri na, peka na,<bt>That is why some of those Yahudi people could not believe in Lord/God2 now, like Yesaya wrote in a different place, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="40" />&lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua pabèdhu le d'ara ra,<bt>[DISCOURSE STYLE: unravel chiasmus] “God has blinded their insides, [Yes, Dhao can make this a transitive verb.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka baku rèdhi ngaa-ngaa.<bt>so that they are not able to see anymore/anything.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Na soro tèke d'ara ra adhu sèmi hadhu,<bt>He has allowed their insides to become hard/stiff, (=1) hard hearted, 2) void of compassion),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka baku re'a mèu.<bt>so that they don't truly understand.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Soro tèke si sèmi èèna,<bt>Just let them be like that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">sèna ka baku ra lèpa tenge Ja'a,<bt>so they don't need to turn (back) and look for Me,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa Ja'a tao boe pabe'a si.&gt;&gt;<bt>and I don't need to heal them.” [Style: irony, cynical]</bt><note reference="12:40" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yesaya 6:10</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Yesaya peka sèmi ne'e, lula nèdhi le dadedha Yesus, ka na lole mema lula-nèti Yesus ne.<bt>Yesaya spoke like that, because he had already seen Yesus' *glory/high-ness, and so he foretold about Yesus. [EXEG: Carson on Jesus' glory as complement of ‘see’;]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="42" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa abhu kahèi dhèu ae dhu parcaya Yesus. Mesa boe dhèu biasa di, te abhu kahèi ama-ama dhèu Yahudi dhu parcaya Ne. Te ngaa rèngu mangaku boe Yesus ètu madha dhèu ae, lula ra madha'u, mage dhèu Parisi babège eele si nèti d'ara èmu sabaj'a ra.<bt>Even that being the case, nevertheless many people believed in Yesus. Not just common people, cuz there were also some leaders of the Yahudi people who believed in Him. But they did not acknowledge Yesus in front of many people/the crowds, because they were afraid, lest the Parisi people would evict them out from their houses of worship.</bt><v n="43" />Ama-ama Yahudi se pusi-pahae boe ho Lamatua koa si, lula rèngu d'èi risi abhu koa-kad'iri nèti dhèu rai-haha.<bt>Those leaders did not care if God2 praised them, because they were more interested in receiving praise (doublet) from humans.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua Yesus pad'elo tatao dhèu<bt>The Lord Yesus' Words/Message shows a person's behaviour/nature/character</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="nanèu"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-04 03:06:38Z" status="Anyone">bahan ; sifat (but 1st sense more widely known); 2 MTTs don't like it here</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="44" />Ka Yesus padhai lii dènge lii mèdhu, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu parcaya Ja'a, nèngu parcaya boe Ja'a mesa ku, te ngaa nèngu parcaya kahèi Dhèu dhu pua Ja'a mai.<bt>Then Yesus spoke with a loud voice, saying, “The person who believes in Me, he does not just believe in Me alone, but he also believes in the Person who sent/commissioned Me. [NOTE to daughter translations: our lgs vary whether God can be referred to as a ‘Person’ or not. If there is not a general ‘being’ word that works for God try ALT: parcaya sang Yang utus sang Beta // parcaya sang Dia yang utus sang Beta.]</bt><v n="45" />Te dhèu dhu ladhe nèdhi Ja'a, na, nèngu ladhe nèdhi kahèi Dhèu dhu pua-paleha Ja'a.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if a person has (ever) seen Me, na, s/he also has seen the Person who sent/commissioned Me.</bt><v n="46" />Ja'a mai sèna ka j'aj'i nuka sèmi saraa ètu rai-haha ne. Ho hud'i laa dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu parcaya Ja'a mamuri boe ètu d'ara maroga.<bt>I came to be like a light to this world. So that everyone who believes in Me will not live in the dark/darkness.</bt><v n="47" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu nanene Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a, te ngaa madhutu boe, na, Ja'a pama'ète boe hahuku na. Te mamai Ja'a asa rai-haha ne, neo boe pama'ète hahuku dhèu, te ngaa Ja'a neo patabuli si nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra.<bt>If there is a person who hears/listens to My Words/Message (doublet), but doesn't obey/do according to (them), na, I don't decide his punishment. Cuz (elaboration) My intent/purpose for coming into this world, is not to decide people's punishment, but I want to *save/release/rescue people from the power of their wrongs/sins (doublet).</bt><v n="48" />Te ngaa dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tule eele Ja'a, aa d'èi boe sèmi Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a, pe na paraga dènge hakim. Te d'ai èle rai-haha ne, Lii Holo-Nori dhu Ja'a lole kèdhi sèra, ka dhu pama'ète hahuku mi dedha rèngu èci-èci.<bt>But everyone who rejects (lit: push away) Me, and doesn't want to accept My Words/Message, will meet with the judge (loan). Cuz (elaboration) if/when the end of the world comes, the Words/Message(s) which I have spoken, are what will decide their punishment.</bt><v n="49" />Lula Ja'a dhae padhai lii kèdhi mèka pake kolongara Ja'a mesa ku. Te ngaa Ja'a padhai lii kèti kolongara Ama Ku ètu sorga. Te Nèngu ka dhu pua Ja'a. Aa Nèngu ka dhu paredha Ja'a, sèna ka Ja'a padhai lii ngaa.<bt>Because I have never spoken bearing My own name/authority. But I have spoken bearing My Father in heaven's name/authority. Cuz (elaboration) He is the one who sent/commissioned Me. And He is the one who commanded Me (telling Me) what I must say.</bt><v n="50" />Ja'a ke'a kahèi, na, lii paredha Na hia mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe. Nèti èèna ka, lii padhai Ja'a madhutu mola-mola ngaa dhu Ama Ku pua Ja'a padhai lii.&gt;&gt;<bt>I also know that His commands bring real life that never ends. That is why what I say follows exactly what My Father orders Me to say.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus rase haga ana madhutu Na<bt>The Lord Yesus washes His disciples' feet</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="13" />
      <v n="1" />Lod'o kalela Paska dhae d'ai mèka, Yesus ne'a le, na, d'ai le lod'o ho Nèngu tèke eele rai-haha ne, aa la'e hari asa Ama Na ètu sorga. Nèngu sue titu kèna dhèu unu Na ètu rai-haha ne, toke Na saraka mamuri Na kateme aae hia mi rèngu.<bt>When the Paska festival/holiday had not yet begun, Yesus already knew that His time had arrived, for Him to leave behind this world, and go back to His Father in heaven. But He really loved His people who were/are in this world, to the point that He turned over/gave up/surrendered His whole/entire life for them. [EXEG: “to the end” 1) temporally, 2) fully, totally, completely (See Carson, NLT)]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Lod'o èèna, dhèu aae nidhu dadugu-rariu le Yudas, ana Simon Iskariot, sèna ka pahie eele Yesus. Ka Yudas dhu pama'ète le, sèna ka ad'u-ue madha j'ara èèna, ropa Yesus si madhèdi ra'a-rinu ètu d'ara kalela Paska.<bt>At that time, the king of the evil spirits had incited/pursuaded/goaded (doublet) Yudas, that is Simon Iskariot's child, for him to sell off (=betray) Yesus. So/then Yudas had already decided to do that thing/matter, when Yesus (coll.) were sitting eating (doublet) that Paska feast.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Yesus ne'a mema le, na, Ama Lamatua pua-paleha Nèngu mai asa rai-haha ne, de nèbhu heka Nèngu lèpa hari la'e asa Ama Lamatua. Aa Nèngu ne'a kahèi, na, Ama Na ètu sorga pangèd'u aa'i le ngaa-ngaa mi Nèngu.<bt>Yesus already knew that God is the one who sent/commissioned (doublet) Him to come into this world, and in a little while/soon He must go back (home) to God. And He also knew that His Father in heaven had turned over/entrusted everything to Him.</bt><v n="4" />Hèia Yesus kèd'i nèti mei, ka Na tao eele kodho li'u Na. Nare bèla èci, ho èki mi lalole na.<bt>So/then Yesus got up from the table, and took off His outer shirt/clothes. Then He took a towel, to tie around His waist.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tapuka "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-04 03:31:35Z" status="Anyone">handuk</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-11 06:13:08Z">young UNSs not know</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lalole "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-04 03:31:57Z" status="Anyone">pinggang</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Ka Na bhori èi asa d'ara bokor iiki cue. Hèia Na rase haga ana madhutu Na sèra. Ropa Na rase pamèu nare haga dhèu èci, Na seka pamango pake bèla dhu pa'èki ètu lalole Na.<bt>Then He poured water into a small basin. And He washed His disciples' feet. After finishing washing the feet of one person, He wiped it dry using the towel tied around His waist. [NOTE to daughter translations: look at Cook cn01799B.tif and 1800B.tif to discuss “basin”.]</bt><v n="6" />Na rase haga si èci-èci. Ropa d'ai Simon Petrus, ka Simon Petrus karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama neo rase haga ja'a kahèi, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>He washed each of their feet. When He arrived at Simon Petrus, Simon Petrus asked, saying, “Are You (Father) also going to wash my feet?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Deo ne'e ne, èu dhae me'a mèka ngaa dhu Ja'a tao ne. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu, èu heka me'a kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “Now you-sg do not yet know/understand what I am doing here. But eventually you will understand.” [NOTE: Gk uses 2 different words for understand here, not able to be reflected in Dhao, but reflected in Kupang.]</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01799b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Te ngaa Petrus pasisu, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama baku tao sèmi èèna! Ja'a ko'o boe Ama rase haga ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>But Petrus protested, saying, “Father shouldn't do like that! I don't want You to wash my feet.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ja'a rase pamèu boe haga èu, na, èu bisa boe pa'èki dènge Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then/so Yesus responded, saying, “If I do not wash making clean (fixed phrase) your feet, na, you cannot be bound/linked with Me.” [EXEG: see discussion in Carson; NOTE to daughter trans: don't force the “wash you” if that carries undesirable baggage--use “wash your feet”.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ka Simon Petrus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, mesa boe haga di. Te ngaa Ama rase kacui-aai dènge kètu ja'a kahèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Simon Petrus responded, saying, “If that's the case, don't just wash my feet. But wash my hands and head too!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu diu le èi, parluu dhoka rase haga di. Te ngi'u na mèu le. Mema tare'a d'ara miu mèu le, te ngaa miu aa'i mi boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told him, saying, “A person who has finished bathing, only needs to wash his feet. Cuz (elaboration) his body is already clean. It's true that your-pl insides are clean/pure, but not all (of you) are clean/pure.” [EXEG: see Carson. Gk “all of you” is referring to number of people, not “entire body” TB is vague here.]</bt><v n="11" />(Yesus peka sèmi ne'e, lula ne'a le cee ka dhu neo pahie Ne. Nèti èèna ka, Na peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu aa'i mi boe dhu mèu.&gt;&gt;)<bt>(Yesus spoke like that, because He already knew who it was who was going to sell Him off (betray). That's why He told (them), saying, “Not all (of you) are clean/pure.”)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ropa Yesus pamèu nare haga si, hèia Na silu hari kodho Na, ka madhèdi hari asa mei. Ka Na karèi ana madhutu Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tasamia? Ropa Ja'a rase haga miu, miu me'a sasoa nèti dhu Ja'a tao ne, do aad'o?<bt>When Yesus had finished washing their feet, He put His shirt/clothes back on, and sat at the table again. Then He asked His disciples, saying, “How is it? When I washed your-pl feet, did you understand the meaning/significance of what I was doing, or not?</bt><v n="13" />Miu tema paroa Ja'a ne, &lt;Ama Mese&gt; aa &lt;Lamatua&gt;. Èèna lèke kèna, lula mema hud'i sèmi èèna ku.<bt>You-pl often refer to Me as ‘Father Teacher’ and ‘Master/Lord’. That's appropriate, because that's what I really am.</bt><v n="14" />Te ngaa ladhe Mese dènge Lamatua miu ne, rase le haga miu nuka sèmi ana pua-paleha sa, na, tasamia hari dènge miu? Miu hud'i lalau-lalo'o isi-aanga mi èci dènge èci; conto nuka: miu hud'i èci dènge èci rase haga mi.<bt>But if your Teacher and Master here, has washed your feet like a lowly servant, na, how about you? You-pl also must serve (doublet) each other; for example: you must also wash each other's feet.</bt><v n="15" />Te Ja'a tao le j'ara ne, sèna ka miu madhutu. Ladhe Ja'a tao tasamia, na, miu hud'i tao sèmi èèna kahèi.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I have done this so you will follow. Whatever I do, na, you-pl must also do like that.</bt><note reference="13:12-15" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 22:27</note><v n="16" />Ja'a peka tare'a-re'a dènge miu. Ca dhèu ènu bisa boe risi nèti lamatua na. Aa ca dhèu pajuu-paleha bisa boe risi nèti dhèu dhu pua nèngu.<bt>I'm telling you the truth. A lowly servant cannot be greater than his master/owner. And an *apostle (commissioned one) cannot be greater than the person who sent/commissioned him.</bt><note reference="13:16" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:24, Lukas 6:40, Yohanis 15:20</note><v n="17" />Lula miu dhu me'a le j'ara se'e, miu oto ladhe miu tao madhutu.<bt>Because you know these things, you are fortunate if you do accordingly.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ja'a padhai lii boe lula-nèti miu aa'i-aa'i mi. Ja'a tadhe mèu dhèu dhu Ja'a hag'e kore. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa j'ara ne hud'i j'aj'i ku, sama sèmi dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, na, &lt;Dhèu dhu madhèdi na'a-ninu pa'èci dènge Ja'a, soro kabodho mi Ja'a le.&gt;<bt>I am not talking about all of you. I really know/recognise the people whom I have chosen. Even that being the case, nevertheless it must happen like what has been written beforehand in the *Scriptures, saying, ‘The person who sits to eat-drink together with me, has turned his back on me.’ (also implies rejection in Dhao.) [EXEG: “lifted his heel against me” = idiom; Carson says, “The most likely is that it means ‘has given me a great fall’ or ‘has taken cruel advantage of me’ or ‘has walked out on me’”; TH discussion on Middle Eastern custom really relates more to ‘sole’ than ‘heel’.]</bt><note reference="13:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 41:10</note><v n="19" />Ja'a peka mema dènge miu, ho ladhe abhu dhèu dhu la'e tèke eele Ja'a, na, miu bisa parcaya kèna, na, Ja'a ne, Kristus.<bt>I'm telling this to you beforehand, so later when a person has abandoned Me like that, na, you can believe that I am Kristus.</bt><v n="20" />Ja'a peka dènge miu tare'a-re'a kèna, dhèu cee dhu bhoke d'ara na ho sèmi nare dhèu dhu Ja'a pua, na, nèngu kahèi sèmi nare Ja'a. Aa cee ka dhu sèmi nare Ja'a dènge be'a, na, nèngu sèmi nare kahèi Dhèu dhu pua-paleha Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>I'm telling you the truth, that whoever opens his insides to receive/accept the people that I send/commission, na, s/he also receives/accepts Me. And whoever accepts Me well, na, s/he also accepts the Person who sent/commissioned (doublet) Me.” [NOTE to daughter translations: our lgs vary whether God can be referred to as a ‘Person’ or not. If there is not a general ‘being’ word that works for God, try ALT: tarima sang Yang utus sang Beta // tarima sang Dia yang utus sang Beta.]</bt><note reference="13:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:40, Markus 9:37, Lukas 9:48, 10:16</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka mema, na, bèli-camèd'a abhu dhèu dhu pahie eele Ne<bt>The Lord Yesus foretells that there is a person who will betray Him</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:20-25; Markus 14:17-21; Lukas 22:21-23)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Yesus padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, hèia d'ara Na mulai susa. Ka Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Dhu Ja'a peka ne, lèke tare'a. Ca dhèu nèti miu, èèna na pahie eele Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus finished talking like that, His insides began to feel disturbed/unsettled/troubled. So He told (them), saying, “What I'm saying here is true. One of you will sell Me off (=betray).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa tadèngi sèmi èèna, hèia ana-ana madhutu Na palaladha èci dènge èci, te rèngu malaa. Re'a boe na, cee ka dhu Nèngu peka.<bt>Hearing that, His disciples looked around at each other, cuz (elaboration) they were confused. They didn't know who He was talking about.</bt><v n="23" />Ètu era ne'e abhu ca dhèu dhu Yesus sue (nuka ja'a, Yohanis dhu suri sasuri ne).<bt>There, there was also a person whom Yesus loved (that is me, Yohanis, who is writing this book).</bt><note reference="13:23" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Madhutu tradisi gareja dènge a'abhu dhèu d'èlu-mèu sèra, na, &lt;ana madhutu dhu Yesus sue&gt; èèna, nuka Yohanis.<bt>According to church tradition and knowledgable people, ‘the disciple whom Yesus loved’ was Yohanis.</bt></note>Ja'a dhu madhèdi ètu baboa Yesus.<bt>I was sitting beside Yesus. [NOTE: Local style/sociolinguistics a person can occasionaly use his full name to refer to himself, but not 3rd person pronoun.]</bt><v n="24" />Hèia Simon Petrus pangètu kètu, ho ja'a karèi Yesus, cee ka dhu Na peka èèna.<bt>And Simon Petrus gave a sign with his head, so I would ask Yesus who He was talking about.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pakahu'u musi madha"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-04 04:08:31Z" status="Anyone">maen mata; pangètu kètu = nods in affirmation, angguk</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-11 06:51:40Z">nods, give a sign</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ka ja'a eso padètu dènge Yesus, ho karèi Ne, &lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu Ama peka ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then I scooted my body closer to Yesus, to ask, saying, “The person that you are talking about is who?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ja'a neo kore roti ca'èta, ho cèb'u asa d'ara mago ne. Èèna na Ja'a hia mi dhèu dhu Ja'a peka deo na.&gt;&gt; Ka Yesus cèb'u nare roti ne asa d'ara mago, hèia Na j'ole asa Yudas, ana Simon Iskariot.<bt>And Yesus responded, saying, “It's like this. I'm going to take a piece of bread, to dip into the bowl. Then I will give it to the person I mentioned just now.” After Yesus dipping that bread into the bowl, then He stretched His hand out giving it to Yudas, that is Simon Iskariot's child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="roti cakadeka"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-04 04:19:31Z" status="Anyone">bread (sliced by knife)</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Ropa sèmi nare roti ne, hèia dhèu aae nidhu maso asa d'ara Yudas. Ka Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Èu neo tao ngaa, na, tao ka lai-lai. Pamata ia ka.&gt;&gt;<bt>Upon receiving that bread, the *king of the evil spirits entered into Yudas. Then Yesus told him, saying, “What you are going to do, na, do it quickly. Don't wait any longer.”</bt><v n="28" />Te ngaa dhèu leo dhu madhèdi ètu sèra re'a rare boe, nga tao ka Yesus padhai lii sèmi èèna.<bt>But the other people sitting there didn't understand why Yesus spoke like that.</bt><v n="29" />Lula Yudas dhu tèke doi-dhari, ka abhu dhu pangee, na, Yesus pua Yudas, peka na, &lt;&lt;Lamu hèli ngaa dhu èdhi parluu, sèna ka tao pesta Paska.&gt;&gt; Aa abhu kahèi dhu pangee, na, Yesus pua Yudas, &lt;&lt;Lamu hia doi d'ai ciki sa, mi dhèu unu boe ngaa-ngaa sèra.&gt;&gt;<bt>Because Yudas was their treasurer (storer of money), there were those who thought Yesus had ordered Yudas, “Go buy what we-inc need to eat the Paska feast.” And there were also those who thought that He meant, “Go give a little money to the poor people.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Ropa Yudas sèmi nare roti ne, hèia la'e dènge ka. Lod'o nèngu kalua èèna, dhu mèda le.<bt>After Yudas had accepted that bread, he went out quickly/immediately. When he went out, it was already night.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lii paredha dhu hiu<bt>A new command</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ropa Yudas la'e, hèia Yesus padhai lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, Dhèu Rai-haha Tare'a-re'a. D'ai lod'o kèna, ho Ama Lamatua ded'e Ja'a padedha-dedha. Aa nèti j'ara ne'e, dhèu rèdhi dadedha Ama Lamatua kahèi.<bt>When Yudas had gone out, Yesus spoke, saying, “I here am the *Son of Man (Authentic/Ideal Human). Now the time has arrived for God to *glorify (elevate way up high) Me. And that will also make/cause people to see God's *glory/high-ness.</bt><v n="32" />Lula Ja'a pa'èki dènge Ama Lamatua, aa pad'elo dadedha Na, nèti èèna ka Na ded'e padedha-dedha Ja'a. Na pamata heka.<bt>Because I am bound/linked with God, and show His glory/high-ness, that is why He will glorify Me. He will not delay anymore.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Ana aa'i-aa'i! Masi ka Ja'a sue miu titu kèna, te ngaa nèbhu heka Ja'a pa'ana-lalu eele miu. Èèna na miu patangi-tenge Ja'a, te ngaa mèdhi boe. Lii dhu Ja'a peka dènge miu ne, èci èèna ka dènge dhu Ja'a lole dènge ama dhèu Yahudi sèra, na, &lt;Ja'a laku asa era èci dhu miu bisa mèka madhutu.&gt;<bt>Children/underlings! Even though I really/dearly love you, nevertheless soon I will orphan you (idiom = not be together with you anymore to look after you). You will look for Me, but not see/find. I am telling you, just like what I have already told the leaders of the Yahudi people, saying, ‘I am going to a place where you-pl cannot yet follow.’ [Cf. 7:34; 8:22-23.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'analalu"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-30 00:33:08Z" status="Anyone">bekin jadi anak yatim-piatu</Message></Annotation><note reference="13:33" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 7:34, 8:22-23</note><v n="34" />Ja'a hia miu lii paredha hiu èci, nuka: <span class="Italic">miu hud'i pasue ku èci dènge èci, sama sèmi Ja'a sue miu.</span> De miu hud'i pasue ku èci dènge èci kahèi.<bt>I am giving you-pl a new commandment, like this: <span class="Italic">you must love each other, just like I love you.</span> So (consequently), you also must love each other.</bt><note reference="13:34" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 15:12, 17, 1 Yohanis 3:23, 2 Yohanis 5</note><v n="35" />Ladhe miu pasue sèmi èèna, dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa re'a, na, miu se, ana madhutu Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>If you love each other like that, everyone can know that you-pl here are My disciples.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus peka tèke, na, Petrus èèna na pasili Nèngu<bt>The Lord Yesus foretells, that Petrus is going to deny (knowing) Him</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasili "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-30 00:45:29Z" status="Anyone">1) menyangkal, 2) menghindar</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:31-35; Markus 14:27-31; Lukas 22:31-34)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ka Simon Petrus karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Te Ama neo lamu mia?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Simon Petrus asked Him, saying, “So where are You (Father) going to go?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a laku asa era èci dhu èu bisa mèka lamu. Te ngaa lod'o limuri ku, heka èu lamu kèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then2 Yesus responded, saying, “I'm going to a place where you-sg can not yet go. But in the end/last day/time you will also go there.” [NOTE: Gk here is different from vs.33.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Petrus karèi hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Nga tao ka ja'a bisa mèka laku hèi? Te ja'a dhu pa'èra iisi le ho madhe pala Ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>Petrus asked, saying, “Father! Why is it that I cannot yet go now? Cuz (elaboration) I am ready to die for You (Father)!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Yesus dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a, do? Èu neo soro mamuri èu sèna ka madhe pala Ja'a? Dhu lèke ka sèmi ne'e: manu dhae kokotoo mèka, te ngaa èu pasili le tèlu hari, peka na, èu tadhe boe Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded2, saying, “Is that right/true? Are you going to/willing to give up/surrender your life to die for Me? The truth is like this: before chicken/rooster crows, you will have already denied (knowing) Me three times.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Abhu boe j'ara leo ho pabe'a dènge Ama; dhodhoka re Yesus di<bt>There is no other way/path to be in a right relationship with Father; only by/via Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="14" />
      <v n="1" />Yesus padhai lii tabha hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;D'ara miu baku susa. Parcaya mi Ama Lamatua, aa parcaya mi Ja'a kahèi.<bt>Yesus spoke further, saying, “You-pl should not worry/be troubled/disturbed. Believe in God. And believe in Me too. [EXEG: Gk can be taken as indicative or imperative; see discussion in Carson.]</bt><v n="2" />Ètu èmu Ama Ku abhu kama ae-ae. Ladhe era d'ai boe, tatu Ja'a peka le dènge miu. Ne'e ne, Ja'a neo laku sadia tèke era hia miu ètu nèi.<bt>In/at My Father's house, there are many-many rooms. If there weren't enough places, surely I would already have told you-pl. Now, I'm going to go prepare (ahead of time) a place(s) for you there (remote). [EXEG: Carson.]</bt><v n="3" />Ladhe Ja'a laku aa sadia kore era pea hia miu, pe Ja'a lèpa hari mai kore miu ho lati pea asa nèi. Dènge j'ara ne'e, ladhe Ja'a ètu mia, na, miu ètu èèna kahèi.<bt>If/when I have gone and have finished preparing your places to stay/live, I will come back again to get you so we-inc can go stay there (remote). In that way, whereever I am, na, you-pl are also there.</bt><v n="4" />Miu me'a le j'ara asa era dhu Ja'a neo laku.&gt;&gt;<bt>Cuz (elaboration) you already know the way which goes to that place where I am going.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Te ngaa Tomas karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Ji'i nge'a boe Ama neo lamu mia. De tasamia ka ji'i nge'a j'ara ho la'a asa nèi?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Tomas asked Him, saying, “Father! We-exc don't know where You are going. So (consequently) how could we be able to know the way there?”</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01735b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Hèia Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Abhu boe j'ara leo dhu bisa nèti dhèu asa Ama ètu sorga. Dhodhoka re Ja'a mesa-mesa ku. Te Ja'a ne ka j'ara asa Ama Lamatua. Ja'a ne ka kapua mamola. Aa Ja'a ne'e ka dhu hia dhèu mamuri dhu lèke.<bt>Then Yesus responded, saying, “There is no other way to bring people to Father in heaven. Only (exclusive) by/via Me alone. Cuz (elaboration) I here am the road/path/way to God. I here am the root/source/base of straightness/truth. And I here am the one who gives people real life. [NOTE: BIS leaves out ‘truth’ in this verse. Middle bit, adjusted Apr 2011 to remove weak simile.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ja'a ne ka dhu kèpe ngaa dhu lèke."><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-30 01:23:12Z" status="Anyone">ss</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Ladhe miu tadhe mèu Ja'a, na, miu tadhe Ama Ku kahèi. De karèi nèti deo ne'e ne, miu tadhe Nèngu le, dènge mèdhi Ne kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>If you-pl really knew/recognised Me, na, you would also know/recognise My Father. So (consequently) beginning from now, you already know/recognise Him and have also seen Him.” [EXEG: see discussion in Carson.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Pelipus manèngi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Mese! Pad'elo ku Ama Mu dènge ji'i! Te èèna d'ai le.&gt;&gt;<bt>Pelipus requested, saying, “Father Teacher! Please show us Your Father! Cuz (elaboration) that is/would be enough.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Hèia Yesus peka dènge ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Pelipus. Ja'a sama-sama dènge miu nèbhu nare sange ne'e, te ngaa miu tadhe iia mèka Ja'a, do? Te dhèu dhu nèdhi le Ja'a, èèna sama sèmi nèngu nèdhi le Ama Ku. De, nga tao ka deo na èu peka na, &lt;Pad'elo ku Ama Mu dènge ji'i&gt;?<bt>Then Yesus told him, saying, “Pelipus! I have been together with you-pl for this long, but you still don't really know/recognise Me, or (what)? Cuz (elaboration) the person who has seen Me, that is like s/he has also already seen My Father. So (consequently), why is it that just now you-sg were saying, ‘Show the Father to us’?</bt><v n="10" />Tasamia kèna? Lod'o Ja'a peka na, Ja'a pa'èki dènge Ama, aa Ama pa'èki dènge Ja'a, èu parcaya Ja'a, do aad'o? Lii padhai dhu Ja'a peka dènge miu sèra, mai boe nèti Ja'a mesa ku, te ngaa mai nèti Ama Ku. Aa Na pake Ja'a sèna ka sab'a taruu sasab'a-la'a Na.<bt>How about it? When I say I am bound/linked to Father, and Father is also bound/linked to Me, do you-sg believe (in) Me, or not? The Words/Message that I have spoken to you-pl, do not come from Me alone, but they come from My Father. And He is using Me to keep carrying out His work.</bt><v n="11" />Parcaya la mi Ja'a ropa Ja'a peka na, Ja'a dhu pa'èki dènge Ama Ku, aa Nèngu pa'èki dènge Ja'a kahèi. Te ngaa ladhe miu bisa boe parcaya sèmi èèna, na, parcaya la Ja'a, lula miu mèdhi le j'ara-j'ara dhu Ja'a tao.<bt>Believe Me when I say, I am bound/linked to/with My Father, and He is also bound/linked with Me. But if you-pl cannot believe like that, na, just believe in Me because you have seen those things that I do/have been doing. [NOTE to daughter translation: CHECK: is this interpreted as ‘miracles’?]</bt><v n="12" />Lii padhai Ja'a se, lèke! Te dhèu dhu parcaya Ja'a, èèna na nèngu bisa tao j'ara dhu Ja'a tao kahèi. Te ngaa, lula Ja'a laku asa Ama Ku, ka ngaa dhu dhèu tao sèra, kapai risi nèti dhu Ja'a tao.<bt>What I am/have said is true! Cuz (elaboration) the person who believes in Me, later s/he will also do the things I have done. But, because I go to My Father, what it is that person does (pl), will be greater/more amazing that what I have done. [EXEG: see discussion in Carson --because after Jesus death, resurrection, and exaltation, the role of these acts in history and theology will be much clearer.]</bt><v n="13" />Miu dhu pa'èki dènge Ja'a, unu hak pake kolongara Ja'a. De ladhe miu sabaj'a sad'i manèngi ngaa èèna ka, pake la kolongara Ja'a,<bt>You who are bound/linked with Me, have the right to bear My name. So (consequently), if/when you-pl are praying to request something/whatever, using My name,</bt><note reference="14:13" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sabaj'a &lt;&lt;pake kolongara Ja'a&gt;&gt; sasoa na, èdhi sabaj'a madhutu dad'èi Yesus. Èdhi dènge hak ho &lt;&lt;pake kolongara Yesus&gt;&gt; ladhe èdhi j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, ladhe èdhi mamuri pa'èki taruu dènge Ne, ladhe èdhi nanene Nèngu, dènge parcaya, na, Nèngu madhe ho saku eele sasala-sasigo èdhi. De &lt;&lt;pake ngara Yesus&gt;&gt; èèna, sama boe dènge sad'i &lt;&lt;ale ngara Yesus&gt;&gt; di.<bt>Praying “using My name” means that we-inc pray according to Yesus' will. We have the right to “use Yesus' name/reputation/authority” if we are His person/people, if we live bound/linked with Him continually, if we keep listening/obeying Him, and if we believe that He died to wipe away our sins (doublet). So (consequently), “using Yesus' name” is not the same as merely “mentioning Yesus' name”.</bt></note>pe èèna na Ja'a tao hia miu. Dènge j'ara ne, Ja'a ded'e Ama Ku padedha-dedha, sèna ka hud'i laa dhèu aa'i-aa'i re'a.<bt>I will do it for you. In that way, I am *glorifying (elevating way up high) My Father, so that everyone will know.</bt><v n="14" />Ja'a peka hari ca tèka: miu sabaj'a ho sad'i manèngi ngaa èèna ka, pake kolongara Ja'a, èèna na Ja'a tao hia miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I'll tell (you) again: you-pl pray to request something/whatever, using My name/reputation/authority, I will do it for you.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus padhadha neo hia mai Roh Ama Lamatua<bt>The Lord Yesus promises to send coming God's Spirit</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Yesus peka tabha hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe miu sue Ja'a, na, miu tao madhutu lii paredha Ja'a sèra.<bt>Yesus spoke further/continued speaking, saying, “If you-pl love Me, na, you will do according to/obey My commands.</bt><v n="16-17" />Ja'a manèngi Ama Ku, sèna ka, lod'o Ja'a dènge heka miu, na, Nèngu hia miu ca Dhèu Era Sarai-Maena, sèna ka pad'elo j'ara hia miu. Nèngu ne, nuka Roh Lamatua, dhu aj'a-nori miu ngaa dhu lèke. Dhèu cahag'e ètu rai-haha ne ro'o boe sèmi rare Ne, lula rèngu bisa boe ladhe rèdhi Nèngu, aa tadhe boe Nèngu. Te ngaa miu tadhe Ne, lula Na pa'èki dènge miu. Aa Na muri ètu d'ara miu. Èèna na, Nèngu dènge miu taa-taa.<bt>I have requested My Father, so that when I am no longer with you anymore, na, He will give/send you an *Advisor/Mentor/Go-To Person (lit: person who is the place of your hopes (doublet); = your go-to person who looks out for your welfare, advises, guides, helps develop, etc.) to show the way for you-pl. He is God2's Spirit, who teaches/will teach (doublet) you what is true. Some people in this world don't want to accept/receive Him, because they can't see Him, and don't know/recognise Him. But you know/recognise Him, because He is bound/linked with you. He lives/will live in your insides. And He will also be together with you continually. [Key Term: mentor, guide, comforter (too narrow), encourager (too narrow), advocate (too narrow, too much baggage), helper (too broad) see discussion in LN.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Oti J'ara"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-30 02:00:09Z" status="Anyone">rintis jalan ; era sarai ; era patai-patapa ; era maena = tempat sandaran</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dènge sèmi èèna, Ja'a tèke eele boe miu mesa mi, nuka sèmi ana lalu-eela. Te ngaa sanèd'e, te bèli-camèd'a Ja'a lèpa hari mai asa miu.<bt>In that way, I am not abandoning/leaving you behind alone/by yourselves, like an orphan. But remember, cuz (elaboration) I will come back again to you.</bt><v n="19" />Nèbhu heka, dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne rèdhi heka Ja'a. Te ngaa miu mèdhi Ja'a. Lula Ja'a mamuri hari, miu abhu mamuri dhu lèke kahèi.<bt>Soon/in a little while, other people in this world will not see Me anymore. But you-pl will later see Me. Because I will live again/come back to life, you will also get/obtain real life.</bt><v n="20" />Aa ladhe lod'o Ja'a mamuri hari, miu me'a mèu, na, Ja'a pa'èki dènge Ama Ku; miu pa'èki dènge Ja'a; aa Ja'a pa'èki dènge miu kahèi.<bt>And later, when I have already come back to life, you will really know that I am bound/linked to My Father; you-pl are bound/linked to Me; and I am bound/linked to you as well.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Dhèu dhu sèmi rare, aa tao madhutu lii paredha Ja'a sèra, na, nèngu ka dhu sue Ja'a. Aa Ama Ku sue kahèi dhèu dhu sue Ja'a. Ja'a sue dhèu èèna kahèi, aa pad'elo iisi Ja'a dènge ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>The person who accepts and does according to/obeys My commands, na, s/he is the one who loves Me. And My Father also loves the person who loves Me. I also love that person, and show/reveal Myself to him/her.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ètu era ne, abhu dhèu èci, ngara na Yudas. Nèngu ne, Yudas Iskariot boe. Ropa na tadèngi lii padhai Yesus, hèia na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama neo pad'elo iisi mi ji'i. Te ngaa tasamia ka Ama pad'elo boe iisi mi dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne?&gt;&gt;<bt>There, there was a person named Yudas. He was not Yudas Iskariot. When he heard what Yesus was saying, he asked, saying, “You (Father) are going to show/reveal yourself to us-exc. But why is it that You (Father) don't want to show yourself to other people in this world?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Yesus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Dhèu dhu sue Ja'a, nuka dhèu dhu tao madhutu Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a. Ama Ku sue nèngu kahèi. Ka Ja'a dènge Ama Ku mamuri d'ara èci dènge ne.<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “It's like this. The person who loves Me, is the person who does according to/obeys My Words/Message (doublet). My Father (will) also loves him. And I and My Father (will) live one insides (in harmony, one accord, same purpose) with him.</bt><v n="24" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu sue boe Ja'a, nèngu madhutu boe Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a kahèi. Aa'i-aa'i dhu miu tadèngi nèti Ja'a, mai boe nèti Ja'a, te ngaa mai nèti Ama Ku dhu pua Ja'a.<bt>But the person who doesn't love Me, s/he also doesn't do according to/obey My Words/Message either (doublet). Everything that you-pl have heard from Me, did not come from Me, but came from My Father who sent/commissioned Me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ne'e ne Ja'a bera-bera dènge miu era. Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a peka tèke j'ara se'e dènge miu.<bt>Now I am still together with you-pl. That is why I am telling you beforehand (about) these matters.</bt><v n="26" />Te ngaa èèna na, Ama Ku pua mai ca Dhèu Era Sarai-Maena, nuka Roh Mola-Mèci Na. Roh ne'e ka dhu gati Ja'a ètu rai-haha ne. Sasab'a Na, nuka: aj'a-nori miu madha j'ara aa'i-aa'i ra, dènge pasanèd'e miu j'ara-j'ara dhu Ja'a padhue-padhai le dènge miu.<bt>But later, My Father is going to send here an Advisor/Mentor/Go-To Person, that is His *Clean/Holy/Pure Spirit. that Spirit will take My place in this world. His work/responsibilities/job is this: teach all things to you-pl, and remind you of everything that I have ever told/explained to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Pe, ladhe d'ai lod'o Ja'a laku, Ja'a tao d'ara miu ho mamuri padame dènge mera-milu. Dhoka Ja'a mesa ku dhu bisa tao d'ara mera-milu sèmi èèna. Aa'i-aa'i dhu ètu rai-haha ne bisa boe tao rare d'ara miu mera-milu sèmi èèna. De miu baku susa, aa baku madha'u.<bt>Later, when I have gone, I will make it so you-pl can live in mutual good relations (peace #2), and stability (peace #1/3). I am the only one who can give you stable/calm insides of that sort. Every (one/thing) in this world is not able to make your insides stable/calm like that. So (consequently), don't let/allow yourselves to be troubled/worry and be fearful.</bt><v n="28" />Miu tadèngi mèdhi le, dhu Ja'a peka dènge miu, na, &lt;Ja'a tèke eele miu, te ngaa èèna na mai hari.&gt; D'ara miu baku susa. Te ladhe miu sue Ja'a, na, d'ara miu karej'e-karae, lula Ja'a laku asa Ama Ku. Ama Ku kapai risi nèti Ja'a ne.<bt>You-pl have heard Me tell/explain to you-pl, saying, ‘I am leaving you-pl, and later will come back again.’ (You) don't need to be troubled in your insides/upset. Cuz (elaboration) if you-pl love Me, na, your insides will be happy (doublet), because I go/am going to My Father. My Father is greater/more amazing than Me. [CHECK that last sentence doesn't evoke physical size, but greatness.]</bt><v n="29" />Sanèd'e, te Ja'a dhu peka mema le dènge miu. Dènge j'ara ne'e, ladhe j'ara se j'aj'i ku, na, miu bisa parcaya Ja'a.<bt>Remember that I have already told you beforehand. In that way, when these things happen later, na, you can believe (in) Me.</bt><v n="30" />Nèbhu heka, Ja'a padhai lii heka dènge miu. Te dhèu aae nidhu dhu mai le. Nèngu nèd'u paredha ètu rai-haha ne, te ngaa koasa na lèke boe Ja'a.<bt>Soon/in a little while, I will not speak with you anymore. Cuz (elaboration) the king of the evil spirits will have come. He holds rule/government in this world, but his power/authority does not hit/effect Me. [EXEG: Gk is /gar/ ‘for’ which normally equates with KM /te/ and has a similar range of functions. Some translations use a stronger connector equivalent to /tagal/, but that is not appropriate here.]</bt><v n="31" />Masi ka nidhu ne mai, te ngaa Ja'a sab'a taruu madhutu paredha Ama Ku. Ne'e ne ka dhu pad'elo dènge dhèu ètu rai-haha ne, na, Ja'a sue Ama Ku titu kèna.<bt>Even though he comes, nevertheless I keep doing according to/obeying My Father's commands. That shows the people in this world that I dearly love My Father.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">De mai lati ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) let's go now!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus sama sèmi aj'u anggor<bt>The Lord Yesus is like a grape plant/tree/vine</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="15" />
      <v n="1" />Yesus padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nanene! Miu dhu pa'èki dènge Ja'a. Ja'a ne sama sèmi aj'u anggor ca kapua. Te ngaa Ja'a ne, aj'u anggor dhu lèke!<bt>Yesus spoke, saying, “Listen! You-pl are bound/linked to Me. I am like a grape tree/vine. But I here, am the real/true grape vine!</bt><note reference="15:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Ètu d'ara Sasuri <span class="Italic">Lii Pajaji Uru Tèka,</span> dhèu dhu suri sèra d'èi pasoro suku Isra'el dènge aj'u anggor ca kapua, do, oka anggor èci. (Ladhe Sasuri <span class="Italic">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio</span> 80:8-16; <span class="Italic">Yesaya</span> 5:1-7; <span class="Italic">Yermia</span> 2:21; <span class="Italic">Yeskial</span> 15:1-8, 19:10-14; <span class="Italic">Hosea</span> 10:1; dènge sasuri dhu leo kahèi.) Te ngaa suku-suku Isra'el piku eele nèti j'ara Lamatua dhu lèke. Nèti èèna ka, ètu ne'e Yesus pakasame iisi Na dènge &lt;aj'u anggor dhu lèke&gt;, lula Nèngu sero eele boe j'ara Lamatua.<bt>In the Book <span class="Italic">Old/Previous Promise</span>, the people who wrote liked to/often compared the people of Isra'el with a grape vine/tree, or a grape orchard. (See <span class="Italic">Praise Songs</span> 80:8-16; <span class="Italic">Yesaya</span> 5:1-7; <span class="Italic">Yermia</span> 2:21; <span class="Italic">Yeskial</span> 15:1-8, 19:10-14; <span class="Italic">Hosea</span> 10:1; and other writings as well.) But the tribes of Isra'el strayed from God2's true path. That is why here Yesus compares himself, saying, that He is the ‘true/real grapevine’, because He does not stray from God2's way/path.</bt></note>Aa Ama Ku nuka sèmi dhèu sab'a oka.<bt>And My Father is like the gardener.</bt><v n="2" />De ladhe dhèu peka na, nèngu dhu pa'èki dènge Ja'a, te ngaa sab'a boe ngaa-ngaa, Ama Ku core eele ne, sama sèmi dhèu sab'a oka dhu pare eele aa'i dadana dhu hua boe. Te ngaa dhèu dhu pa'èki pa'èra dènge Ja'a, Ama Ku pamèu kaj'alu ètu d'ara dhèu èèna, nuka sèmi dhèu sab'a oka poro pabab'a dadana, sèna ka hua na asa ae.<bt>So (consequently), if a person says s/he is bound/linked to Me, but doesn't do anything, My Father will get rid of him, like a gardener cuts off &amp; gets rid of all the branches that don't bear fruit. But the person who is truly/strongly/tightly bound/linked to Me, Father cleanses/purifies the dirt/filth/crud (used both literally and figuratively in everyday speech) from his insides, just like a gardener prunes/cuts short a branch so it will bear more fruit.</bt></p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\Hk00112c.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right">Aj'u anggor<bt>Grape vine</bt></fig>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a se'e, bisa le pamèu d'ara miu, èci èèna ka dènge dhèu sab'a oka dhu pamèu dadana anggor.<bt>My Words/Message (doublet) are already able to cleanse/purify a person's insides, just like a gardener cleans off the branches of his grape (trees).</bt><v n="4" />Miu hud'i pa'èki taruu ku dènge Ja'a, sama sèmi Ja'a pa'èki dènge miu. Te dadana dhu pare eele le nèti laa na, bisa boe hua. Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge miu. Miu bisa boe tao ngaa èci sa dhu be'a, ladhe miu pa'èki taruu boe dènge Ja'a.<bt>You-pl must be bound/linked continually with Me, just like I am bound/linked to you. Cuz (elaboration) a branch that is cut/separated off from its trunk cannot bear fruit. It's the same way with you-pl. You are not able to do anything good at all, if you are not bound/linked continually with Me.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="laa "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-30 03:51:11Z" status="Anyone">batang, pohon</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ja'a sama sèmi aj'u anggor ca kapua. Miu nuka sèmi dadana nèngu. De dhèu dhu pa'èki taruu dènge Ja'a, aa Ja'a pa'èki dènge nèngu kahèi, na, nèngu èci èèna ka dènge dadana dhu hua ae-ae. Te, ladhe miu pa'èki taruu boe dènge Ja'a, miu bisa boe tao ngaa-ngaa dhu be'a.<bt>I here am like a grape tree/vine. You-pl are like its branches. So (consequently) a person who is bound/linked continually with Me, and I am also bound/linked continually with him, s/he is like a branch that bears a lot of fruit. Because, if you are not bound/linked continually with Me, you are not able to do anything good.</bt><v n="6" />Dhèu dhu pa'èki boe taruu dènge Ja'a, nèngu cakaraa dadana èci dhu guna heka. Dadana sèmi èèna, dhèu poro eele, sèna ka pamango eele ne. Hèia pakaboko ho core asa d'ara ai, tunu pakèpu si.<bt>A person who is not bound/linked continually with Me, s/he is like a branch that has no use. A branch of that sort, people would lop/chop off and throw away, leaving it to dry out. Then people would gather up those branches, and throw them in the fire, burning them up.</bt><v n="7" />Te ngaa ladhe miu pa'èki pa'èra-èra dènge Ja'a taruu, aa Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a pea taruu ètu d'ara miu, na, ngaa dhu miu manèngi mi Ama Lamatua, Na tao hia miu.<bt>But if you-pl are bound/linked firmly/continually with Me, and My Words/Message (doublet) also lives/stays continually in your insides, na, whatever you request of God, He will do it for you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ladhe miu tao j'ara dhu be'a ae-ae, sama sèmi dadana èci dhu hua ae-ae, èèna ka dhu ded'e padedha-dedha Ama Lamatua. Dènge j'ara ne'e, miu pad'elo kahèi, na, miu ana madhutu Ja'a.<bt>If you do many good things, like a branch puts out a lot of fruit, that *glorifies God. In that way, you are also showing that you are My *disciples.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Sèmi mia Ama sue Ja'a, sèmi èèna kahèi Ja'a sue miu. Miu hud'i pa'èki ku pa'èra-èra dènge Ja'a, sèna ka Ja'a bisa pad'elo dènge miu sasue Ja'a.<bt>However it is that the Father loves Me, it is in the same way also I love you-pl. You must be bound/linked firmly/continually with Me, so that I can show/reveal My love to you.</bt><v n="10" />Ladhe miu tao madhutu lii paredha Ja'a sèra, na, miu pa'èki taruu dènge Ja'a, hèia Ja'a bisa pad'elo sasue Ja'a mi dedha miu. Èèna nuka sèmi Ja'a tao madhutu lii paredha Ama Ku, hèia Na pad'elo sasue Na taruu mi dedha Ja'a.<bt>If you do according to /obey My commands, na, you are bound/linked continually with Me, and I can show/reveal My love to you. That is like I do according to/obey My Father's commands, and He shows His love to Me continually.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Karèi nèti uru ka, Ja'a peka dènge miu j'ara se aa'i-aa'i ra, sèna ka d'ara miu karej'e-karae, sama sèmi d'ara Ja'a. Te madhutu dad'èi Ja'a, d'ara miu hud'i karej'e dhu dènge boe too-lane!<bt>Beginning from long ago, I have told/explained all these things to you-pl, so that your insides can be happy/joyous (doublet) just like My insides. Cuz (elaboration) My will/desire is for your-pl insides to have joy without limit/boundaries!</bt><v n="12" />Lii paredha Ja'a sèmi ne'e ka: miu hud'i pasue ku èci dènge èci, sama sèmi Ja'a sue miu.<bt>My command is like this: you-pl must love each other, just like I also have loved you. [Cf. 13:34-35]</bt><note reference="15:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 13:34, 15:17, 1 Yohanis 3:23, 2 Yohanis 5</note><v n="13" />Ladhe dhèu èci sadia madhe sèna ka angalai na bisa mamuri, nèngu tatu sue tare'a-re'a angalai na. Abhu boe sasue dhu risi eele hari sèmi èèna.<bt>If one person is prepared to die so that his friends can live, he really/truly loves his friends. There is no love (nominalised) which is greater/more amazing than that.</bt><v n="14" />Ladhe miu madhutu paredha Ja'a taruu, miu j'aj'i angalai Ja'a.<bt>If you do according to/obey My commands continually (=keep doing), you are My friends.</bt><v n="15" />Ja'a paroa heka miu, na, &lt;ana pua-paleha&gt; Ja'a. Te ana pua-paleha èci, ne'a iia boe dad'èi lamatua na. Te ngaa Ja'a paroa miu, na, &lt;angalai&gt; Ja'a, lula Ja'a bhoke patalele le aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama Ku peka le dènge Ja'a.<bt>I don't want to refer to you as My ‘lowly servants’ anymore. Cuz (elaboration) a lowly servant does not truly understand his master's wishes/desires/plans/values. But I refer to you, as My ‘friends’, because I have revealed plainly everything that My Father has told Me.</bt><v n="16" />Miu pili boe Ja'a. Te ngaa Ja'a ka dhu pili kore aa ded'e miu ho pakako sasab'a ne. De miu hud'i lami tao j'ara be'a ae-ae dhu taha nare nèbhu. Èèna nuka sèmi aj'u anggor ca kapua dhu hua na be'a taruu. Ladhe miu tao ka sèmi èèna, na, ngaa dhu miu manèngi mi Ama Ku pake ngara Ja'a, tatu Na tao hia miu.<bt>You-pl did not choose Me. But I am the one who chose and appointed/elevated you to carry out this work/responsibility/mission. So (consequently) you must go do many good things that endure/last/keep/persevere. That is like a grape tree/vine which keeps putting out good fruit on and on. If you do like that, na, you can request whatever from My Father using My name, and He will do it for you.</bt><v n="17" />De dhu Ja'a paredha miu sèmi ne'e ka: miu hud'i pasue ku èci dènge èci.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently) what I am commanding you here is like this: you must love each other.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu rai-haha d'èi boe dhèu unu Lamatua Yesus<bt>People in this world don't like (~hate) the Lord Yesus' people</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Yesus lii tabha hari, na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe dhèu ètu rai-haha ne d'èi boe miu, na, sanèd'e, te karèi nèti uru ka rèngu d'èi boe Ja'a.<bt>Yesus spoke further, saying, “If people in this world don't like you-pl, na, remember that they didn't like Me first/before (you). [NOTE: no good word for hate.]</bt><v n="19" />Ladhe miu sama sèmi dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne, tatu ra sue miu. Te ngaa miu sama boe dènge rèngu. Te Ja'a dhu hag'e kore le miu, sèna ka cèri eele miu nèti rèngu. Nèti èèna ka rèngu d'èi boe miu.<bt>If you are like other people in this world, surely they would love you. But you are not the same as them. Cuz (elaboration) I have already chosen/selected you to separate you from them. That is why they don't like you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Baku bhèlu dhu Ja'a peka kore le dènge miu, na, &lt;Ca dhèu ana pua-paleha risi boe nèti lamatua na.&gt; De ladhe rèngu paj'èra Ja'a, tatu ra paj'èra miu kahèi. Ladhe rèngu nanene ka Lii Holo-Nori Ja'a, na, rèngu nanene miu kahèi.<bt>Don't forget what I already told you, saying, ‘A servant (doublet) is not greater/more than his master/owner.’ So (consequently), if/when they torment/cause suffering/misery to Me, surely they will also torment/cause suffering/misery to you-pl. If they listened to/obeyed My Words/Message (doublet), na, they should/would also listen to you. [NOTE to daughter translations: Compare wording in Jn. 13:16.]</bt><note reference="15:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 10:24, Lukas 6:40, Yohanis 13:16</note><v n="21" />Èèna na ra paj'èra miu, lula miu dhu pa'èki dènge Ja'a. Te rèngu tadhe boe Nèngu dhu pua Ja'a kahèi.<bt>They will torment/cause suffering/misery to you, because you are bound/linked to Me. Cuz (elaboration) they also don't know/recognise Him who sent/commissioned Me. [NOTE: Gk ‘but’ here is contrary to expectation, not a contrast with what comes before, so /ma/ here would be awkward in Kupang. UNS's at Consultant check couldn't get the leap-frogging deixis of what the broader “do these thngs to you” referred to.]</bt><v n="22" />Ladhe Ja'a dhae padhai lii kèdhi mèka dènge rèngu, aa pad'elo j'ara mamuri dhu lèke mi rèngu, na, ra pangee taruu, na, rèngu dènge boe sala ngaa-ngaa. Te ngaa Ja'a mai le, aa padhai dènge rèngu sèmi èèna. De ladhe rèngu tao sala, na, rèngu abhu boe j'ara ho peka na, &lt;Wee! Ji'i se nge'a boe, na, dhu ji'i tao sèra, sala.&gt;<bt>If I had never come and spoken with them, and/then shown the true way of life to them, na, they would keep thinking, that, they have no wrong/sin whatsoever. But I have come, and have spoken with them like that. So (consequently), if/when they do wrong/sin, na, they have no way/basis/excuse anymore to speak, saying, ‘Wee! We-exc didn't know what we were doing was wrong/sin.’</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Dhèu dhu d'èi boe Ja'a, nèngu d'èi boe Ama Ku kahèi.<bt>The person who doesn't like Me, he also doesn't like My Father.</bt><v n="24" />Ja'a tao kèdhi le tadha malaa rupa-rupa ètu katanga madha ra, dhu dhèu leo tao rèdhi mèka. Ladhe Ja'a tao boe j'ara sèra sa, rèngu sala boe kahèi ladhe ro'o boe sèmi rare Ja'a. Aa te ngaa rèngu dhu rèdhi le tadha malaa dhu Ja'a tao sèra. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa rèngu d'èi boe Ja'a, aa d'èi boe Ama Ku ètu sorga kahèi.<bt>I have done a variety of amazing signs in front of them, that other people have never done. If I hadn't done those things, they also wouldn't be wrong/at fault if they didn't want to accept Me. Whereas in fact, they have seen those amazing signs which I have done. Even that being the case, nevertheless they still don't like Me and don't like My Father in heaven. [EXEG: Carson, NLT, CEV. The sin is the rejection of Christ.]</bt><v n="25" />Te ngaa j'ara se'e se dhu j'aj'i le, sèna ka madhutu ngaa dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Atora Ama Lamatua, dhu peka na, &lt;Rèngu d'èi boe Ja'a. Aa te ngaa nanasa rèngu se'e dènge boe kolo-kapua.&gt;<bt>But all these things happened, to do according to/to fulfill what was written in God's Regulations/Law, saying, ‘They didn't like Me. Whereas in fact their anger has no basis/foundation (doublet) whatsoever.’</bt><note reference="15:25" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 35:19, 69:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Te ngaa Dhèu Era Sarai-Maena èèna neo mai. Nèngu èèna, nuka Roh dhu tao miu me'a mèu ngaa dhu lèke. Na mai nèti Ama Ku. Ladhe Ja'a laku le asa Ama Ku, pe Ja'a hia Roh Na mai asa miu. Na lole dènge miu lula-nèti Ja'a.<bt>But later that Advisor/Mentor/Go-To Person is going to come. He is the Spirit who makes you-pl understand clearly what is true. He comes from My Father. If/when I have gone to My Father, I will send coming His Spirit to you. He will tell/explain to you about Me.</bt><v n="27" />Èèna na miu peka dènge dhèu lula-nèti Ja'a kahèi, lula miu bera-bera dènge Ja'a karèi nèti uru j'ara ka.<bt>You will also tell people about Me, because you have been together with Me from the beginning.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="16" />
      <v n="1" />Ja'a peka le j'ara se'e dènge miu, sèna ka miu baku pakaj'èu nèti Ja'a.<bt>I have told you these things, so that you will not retreat/withdraw/distance yourselves from Me.</bt><v n="2" />Èèna na dhèu Yahudi sèra babège eele miu nèti d'ara èmu sabaj'a ra. Mesa boe j'ara ne'e di, te bèli-camèd'a d'ai lod'o na, ladhe dhèu pamadhe miu, ra pangee, na, rèngu tao j'ara dhu lèke hia Ama Lamatua.<bt>Later the Yahudi people will evict you from their houses of worship. Not only that, (but) later there will also be an age/long time period in which if/when people kill you, they will think they are doing something good for God.</bt><v n="3" />Rèngu tao miu sèmi èèna, lula rèngu tadhe iia boe Ja'a. Aa rèngu tadhe boe Ama Ku kahèi.<bt>They do that to you, because they don't really know/recognise Me. They also don't know My Father.</bt><v n="4" />Te ngaa Ja'a peka le j'ara se'e dènge miu, sèna ka lèpa lod'o limuri ladhe j'aj'i, miu bisa sanèd'e, na, Ja'a dhu peka mema le. Te ngaa Ja'a peka uuru mèka dènge miu, lula Ja'a bera-bera dènge miu era.&gt;&gt;<bt>But I have told you these things, so that later, if/when these things happen, you can remember, that, I already foretold (them) from beforehand/previous time. Because (now) I am still together with you, that is why I didn't tell you previously.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Cahari nèi,"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-31 00:46:08Z" status="Anyone">Tempo hari</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sasab'a-la'a Roh Lamatua<bt>The work (doublet) of God2's Spirit</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Yesus aj'a tabha hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Limuri ne, Ja'a neo lèpa asa Nèngu dhu pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne. Te ngaa abhu boe nèti miu ca dhèu sa dhu karèi, na, &lt;Ama neo lamu mia?&gt;<bt>Yesus taught further, saying, “Now, I am going to return/home to Him who sent/commissioned Me to come to this world. But there aren't any of you-pl who ask, saying, ‘Where are You (Father) going?’</bt><v n="6" />Lula Ja'a dhu peka le dènge miu, nèti èèna ka d'ara miu susa.<bt>Because I have told you these things, that is why your insides are distressed/troubled.</bt><v n="7" />Te ngaa, ngaa dhu Ja'a peka dènge miu ne, lèke tare'a. Ladhe Ja'a laku, na, miu abhu babe'a na. Te ladhe Ja'a laku boe, Dhèu Era Sarai-Maena èèna mai boe pad'elo j'ara hia miu. Te ngaa ladhe Ja'a laku, na, Ja'a hia Ne mai dènge miu.<bt>But what I have told/am telling you is true. If/when I go, that is better for you/you get the goodness. Cuz (elaboration) if I don't go, that Advisor/Mentor/Go-To Person will not come and show the way to you. But if I go, na, I will send Him coming to you.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Pe ladhe Na mai, Na bhoke ngangee dhèu ètu rai-haha ne, ka re'a, na, d'ara dènge tatao ra, sala. Na pamako si, sèna ka rèngu madhutu j'ara mamuri dhu lèke. Aa Na pasanèd'e rèngu, na, ladhe Lamatua pama'ète lii langu ra, peka na, rèngu se sala, do sala boe.<bt>[EXEG for vs 8-11: see discussion in Carson] Later if/when He comes, He will open the thinking/understanding of/for/to people in this world, that, their insides and their deeds/character are wrong. He will persuade/coax/entice them to follow the true way of life. And He will also remind them that God2 is going to decide their cases, whether they are wrong, or not wrong/innocent.</bt><v n="9" />Dhèu Era Sarai-Maena èèna pad'elo sasala ra, lula rèngu lèka boe Ja'a.<bt>That Advisor/Mentor shows/reveals their wrong/sin, because they do not believe in Me.</bt><v n="10" />Nèngu pad'elo j'ara mamuri dhu lèke kahèi. Lula Ja'a lèpa asa Ama Ku, èèna na miu mèdhi heka Ja'a. Nèti èèna ka, Dhèu Era Sarai-Maena ne mai gati Ja'a.<bt>He also shows the true way of life. Because I return to My Father, you will not see Me anymore. That is why that Advisor comes to replace Me. [Discourse: context from vs. 7.]</bt><v n="11" />Nèngu peka kahèi, na, Ama Lamatua pama'ète lii langu dhèu dènge mola, lula Lamatua dhu pama'ète nare le lii langu dhèu aae nidhu, dhu paredha rai-haha ne.<bt>He also shows/tells/conveys that God will decide/s people's cases correctly, because God2 has already decided the case of the king of the evil spirits, who governs/rules in this world.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Abhu j'ara ae era dhu Ja'a neo peka dènge miu, te ngaa ne'e ne miu dhae bisa mèka me'a.<bt>There are many things which I still want to tell/explain to you, but you are not yet able to understand (them) now.</bt><v n="13" />Te ngaa ladhe Roh dhu pad'elo j'ara-j'ara dhu lèke èèna mai ka, Nèngu pad'elo j'ara sèna ka miu bisa me'a j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu lèke. Nèngu padhai lii boe nèti d'ara Na mesa, te ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu Na tadèngi sèra mai nèti Ama Ku. Nèngu neo peka dènge miu kahèi, ngaa dhu bèli-camèd'a j'aj'i.<bt>But if/when the Spirit who shows/reveals the things that are true has come, na, He will show/reveal the way so that you are able to understand everthing that is true. He does not speak from His own self, but everything which He hears from My Father. He also is going to tell/explain/convey to you what will eventually happen later.</bt><v n="14" />Nèngu neo ded'e Ja'a padedha-dedha, lula Na neo bhoke patalele aa'i hia miu, j'ara dhu lèke lula-nèti Ja'a.<bt>He is going to *glorify (elevate very high) Me, because He is going to reveal/unveil to you-pl everything that is true about Me.</bt><v n="15" />Aa'i-aa'i dhu unu Ama Ku, unu Ja'a kahèi. Nèti èèna ka, Ja'a peka deo na, Roh Lamatua èèna na bhoke patalele aa'i mèu-mèu j'ara dhu lèke lula-nèti Ja'a, aa pad'elo dènge miu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Every(thing/one) that is My Father's possession, is also My possession. That is why I said earlier, that, God2's Spirit will reveal everything that is true about Me, and show it to you.” [CHECK grammar of 1st sentence wUNSs.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">D'ara miu hud'i susa uru ku, heka abhu karej'e kèna<bt>Your-pl insides must be troubled/in difficulty first, then later will get happiness</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Yesus tuhu hari lii padhai, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nèbhu heka, miu mèdhi heka Ja'a. Te ngaa nèbhu boe kahèi, miu mèdhi hari Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus continued speaking, saying, “Soon/not much longer, you will no longer see Me. But not long, you will see Me again.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Ka ana madhutu Na cahag'e papeka èci dènge èci, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;A'abhu Ama èèna, ngaa kèna? Ka peka na, &lt;Nèbhu heka, miu mèdhi heka Ja'a. Te ngaa nèbhu boe kahèi, miu mèdhi hari Ja'a.&gt; Aa, nga tao ka Na padhai lii, na, &lt;Lula Ja'a neo laku asa Ama Ku&gt;?&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, some of His disciples spoke among themselves, saying, “What does Father mean, by saying, ‘Soon/not much longer, you will not see Me. But not long, you will see Me again.’ And, why is it that He says, ‘Because I am going to My Father’?”</bt><v n="18" />Hèia ra pakarèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;A'abhu Na ngaa, dhu peka na, &lt;nèbhu heka&gt;? Èdhi te'a boe sasoa na.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they asked each other, saying, “What does He mean, saying, ‘Soon/not much longer’? We-inc don't understand the meaning.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Te ngaa Yesus dhu ne'a rèngu neo karèi Ne ca j'ara. Hèia Na karèi, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Deo na Ja'a peka na, &lt;Nèbhu heka, miu mèdhi heka Ja'a. Te ngaa nèbhu boe, miu mèdhi hari Ja'a kahèi.&gt; Miu pakarèi sèmi èèna, si?<bt>But [contrary to expectation] Yesus already knew that they wanted to ask Him something. So He asked, saying, “Earlier I spoke, saying, ‘Soon/not much longer, you will not see Me. But not long, you will see Me again.’ That is what you're asking each other (about), right?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Be'a kahèi, ladhe miu neo me'a sèmi èèna. Ja'a neo peka dènge miu kahèi sèmi ne'e: èèna na miu tangi dènge d'ara susa, te ngaa dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne karej'e-karae. Masi ka d'ara miu susa, te ngaa èèna na d'ara miu karej'e-karae hari.<bt>It is also good if you are wanting to find out/understand like that. I also want to tell you this: you will cry with troubled/sad insides, but other people in this world will be happy (doublet). Even though your insides are troubled like that, nevertheless your insides will later be happy again.</bt><v n="21" />J'ara ne sama sèmi bhèni ca dhèu kabake pèd'a d'ai lod'o neo nara iisi. D'ara na rasa bia, lula d'ai lod'o j'aj'èra na kèna. Te ngaa ladhe nara iisi nare, na, j'aj'èra na ele. Te d'ara na karej'e, lula abhu dhèu hiu èci dhu mai asa rai-haha.<bt>That is like a woman who feels pain about to give birth. Her insides are heavy/worried/sad/depressed first, because her time of difficulty/suffering has arrived. But then when she has finished giving birth, her suffering disappears/disapates. Cuz (elaboration) her insides are happy, because there is a new person who has been born into this world.</bt><v n="22" />Sèmi èèna kahèi dènge miu. Ne'e ne miu tangi dènge d'ara susa. Te ngaa nèbhu-nèbhu Ja'a mai paraga hari dènge miu, ka d'ara miu j'aj'i hari karej'e-karae. Aa ladhe j'ara ne j'aj'i, abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu bisa bhabhae rare d'ara karae miu.<bt>It's the same way with you-pl. Now, you cry/weep with troubled insides. But eventually I will come back and meet up with you again, and then your insides will return to happiness (doublet). And when that matter has happened, there is not one person who can hold back/restrain your happy insides.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Aa ladhe j'ara sèmi sèra j'aj'i, miu pakarèi heka ngaa-ngaa dènge Ja'a. Tare'a! Ja'a peka hari dènge miu kèna, na, sad'i miu manèngi ngaa èèna ka nèti Ama Ku, pake kolongara Ja'a, èèna na Nèngu tao sèmi èèna hia miu.<bt>And when those things have happened, you will not be asking Me anything else anymore. That's right/true! I'm telling you further, that, if you request anything/whatever from My Father, using My name/reputation, He will do like that for you-pl.</bt><note reference="16:23" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sabaj'a &lt;&lt;pake kolongara Ja'a&gt;&gt; sasoa na, èdhi sabaj'a madhutu dad'èi Yesus. Èdhi dènge hak ho &lt;&lt;pake kolongara Yesus&gt;&gt; ladhe èdhi j'aj'i dhèu unu Na, ladhe èdhi mamuri pa'èki taruu dènge Ne, ladhe èdhi nanene Nèngu, dènge parcaya, na, Nèngu madhe ho saku eele sasala-sasigo èdhi. De &lt;&lt;pake ngara Yesus&gt;&gt; èèna, sama boe dènge sad'i &lt;&lt;ale ngara Yesus&gt;&gt; di.<bt>Praying “using My name” means that we-inc pray according to Yesus' will. We have the right to “use Yesus' name” if we are His person/people, if we live bound/linked with Him continnually, if we keep listening/obeying Him, and believe that He died to wipe away our sins (doublet). So (consequently), “using Yesus' name” is not the same as merely “mentioning Yesus' name”.</bt></note><v n="24" />Toke d'ai sange ne'e, miu dhae manèngi mèka ngaa-ngaa pake kolongara Ja'a. De manèngi la, sèna ka miu abhu. Dènge j'ara ne, d'ara miu bisa karej'e tare'a-re'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Until now, you have not yet requested anything using My name/reputation. So (consequently) just request, so that you can/will receive. In that way your insides can be truly happy.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus segi aa'i le koasa ètu rai-haha ne<bt>The Lord Yesus has defeated all powers/authorities in this world</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Yesus padhai lii tabha hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Toke d'ai sange ne'e, Ja'a tema aj'a-nori miu pake lii pakasame. Te ngaa bèli-camèd'a d'ai lod'o na, Ja'a aj'a miu pake heka lii pakasame. Te Ja'a neo peka mola-mola lula-nèti Ama Ku.<bt>Yesus spoke further, saying, “Until now, I usually teach you using *illustrations/parables. But later there arrives a time for Me to teach without using illustrations/parables anymore. Cuz (elaboration) I am going to speak clearly/openly about My Father.</bt><v n="26" />Ladhe lod'o èèna d'ai, na, miu mesa mi dhu sabaj'a ho manèngi mi Ama Ku pake kolongara Ja'a. Baku dhoka Ja'a mesa Ku di dhu sabaj'a hia miu.<bt>When that time has come, na, you yourselves are the ones who will pray to request directly from My Father, using My name. It is no longer just Me alone who prays for you. [NLT, CEV]</bt><v n="27" />Te Ama Ku sue miu, lula miu sue Ja'a. Aa miu me'a mèu, na, Ama Lamatua ka dhu pua Ja'a.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) My Father loves you, because you love Me. And you also know clearly/are assured/confident that God is the one who sent/commissioned Me.</bt><v n="28" />Uru èèna, Ja'a tèke eele Ama Ku, ho mai pea taha ètu rai-haha ne. Te ngaa limuri ne, Ja'a neo tèke eele rai-haha ne, ho laku pea pa'èci hari dènge Ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>Previously, I left My Father, to come stay temporarily in this world. But now, I am going to leave this world, to go back and live/stay united/joined again with Him.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Tadèngi rare sèmi ne'e, hèia ana madhutu Yesus se lii, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;De ne'e ne, Ama padhai lii mola-mola kèna, aa aj'a-nori pake heka lii pakasame.<bt>Hearing that, then Yesus' disciples said, “So (consequently) now You (Father) are speaking clearly/openly, and teaching (doublet) without using illustrations/parables anymore.</bt><v n="30" />Ji'i nge'a, na, Ama dhu me'a aa'i mèu j'ara-j'ara. Dhèu parluu heka sèku Ama dènge karèi ngaa-ngaa, lula Ama dhu me'a uru le ngaa dhu ra neo karèi, aa lii dhaa na tasa mera mia. J'ara ne peka dènge ji'i, na, Ama mai nèti Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>We-exc know/are sure/confident that You (Father) know everything/thoroughly understand everything. Nobody needs to ask You anything anymore (to test you), because You already know beforehand what they are going to ask, and what the answer is/how to answer. That shows us that You came from God.” [EXEG: HCE (NLT &amp; CEV still confused, unclear).]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Hèia Yesus karèi, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a, do? Limuri ne, miu lèka Ja'a, do?<bt>Yesus asked them, saying, “Is that true? Now you believe in Me, right?</bt><v n="32" />Sèmi ne'e. Nèbhu boe, mulai ciki-diki ne, miu aa'i-aa'i mi rai paceb'a. Ca dhèu-dhèu ka rai tèke eele Ja'a mesa-mesa ku, ho la'e lu'u. Masi ka sèmi èèna, Ja'a mesa ku boe, lula Ama Ku bera-bera dènge Ja'a.<bt>It's like this. Soon, beginning now, all of you will run scattering. Each person will run off leaving Me alone, to go hide. Even that being the case, nevertheless I will not be alone, because My Father is together with/accompanies Me.</bt><v n="33" />Ja'a peka tèke le j'ara se dènge miu, sèna ka d'ara miu mera-milu, lula miu dhu pa'èki dènge Ja'a. Te bèli-camèd'a dhèu ètu rai-haha ne pasusa dènge paj'èra miu. Te ngaa pa'èra d'ara miu, lula Ja'a segi aa'i le koasa aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne!&gt;&gt;<bt>I have told these things to you-pl, so that your insides may be calm (doublet), because you are bound/linked to Me. Cuz (elaboration) in the future people in this world will cause suffering and strife to you. But, be encouraged (strengthen your insides), because I have already caused defeat to all the powers/authorities in this world!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus manèngi-mangaj'i hia Nèngu unu Na<bt>The Lord Yesus prays (doublet) for Himself</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="17" />
      <v n="1-2" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii nare, hèia Na ladhe asa dedha-liru, ka sabaj'a, peka na:<bt>When Yesus finished speaking, He faced the sky, and prayed2, saying: [EXEG &amp; STRUCTURE: see Carson]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">&lt;&lt;Ama Pasue. Lod'o d'ai kèna ho Ama ded'e Ja'a padedha-dedha. Ja'a ne, Ana Ama. Ama dhu pangèd'u Ja'a hak, sèna ka lalau-lalo'o dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne. Ama hia hak ne, sèna ka Ja'a hia mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama pangèd'u mai ho j'aj'i dhèu Ja'a. De ne'e ne, Ja'a manèngi sèna ka Ama ded'e Ja'a padedha-dedha ho pad'elo dadedha Ama.<bt>“Dear Father. My time has arrived for Father to *glorify Me. I am Father's Child. You (from ‘Father’ throughout) are the one who has handed over/entrusted to Me the right/authority to oversee/arrange/control/put in order everyone in this world. You gave that right, so that I give real life that never ends to everyone whom You have turned over/entrusted to be My people. So (consequently) now, I request that You *glorify (elevate way on high) Me, so that I can show Your *glory (high-ness. [EXEG: “the hour has come” Carson “the appointed time for Jesus' death/exaltation, for his glorification.” CEV “the time has come for you to bring glory to your Son,” Morris “Now with the cross in immediate prospect Jesus can speak of the hour as having come. This is that to which the whole ministry of Jesus has led up. ... To human view the cross was an instrument of shame. To Christ it was the means of true glory.”]</bt><v n="3" />J'ara abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe, sèmi ne'e: dhèu hud'i tadhe Ama Ku, nuka Ama Lamatua dhu lèke. Dhu leo aad'o. Aa rèngu hud'i tadhe ku Ja'a kahèi, nuka Yesus Kristus, dhu Ama pua mai asa rai-haha ne.<bt>The way to get/obtain that real life that never ends is like this: a person must know/recognise You, that is the true/real God. There is no other. They must also know/recognise Me, that is Yesus Kristus, whom You have sent/commissioned to come to this world. [NLT; EXEG: Apr 2011 changed ‘no other way’, to ‘no other’, Gk is ‘only true God’, not ‘only way’. OV was skewed focus.]</bt><v n="4" />Ja'a pad'elo le dadedha Ama ètu rai-haha ne. Ja'a pa'èle le sasab'a dhu Ama pangèd'u mi Ja'a.<bt>I have shown Your glory/high-ness in this world. I have finished/completed that work/mission/responsibility that You turned over/entrusted to Me.</bt><v n="5" />Uru èèna, lod'o Èdhi paj'aj'i mèka rai-haha ne, Ja'a bera-bera le dènge Ama. Lod'o èèna, dadedha Ja'a èci èèna ka dènge dadedha Ama. Ne'e ne Ja'a neo lèpa hari asa Ama. De Ja'a manèngi ho Ama ded'e Ja'a padedha-dedha, sèna ka dadedha Ja'a sama sèmi uru èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Previously, when We-inc had not yet created/brought into being this world (=before we made), I was together with You. At that time, My glory was also the same as Your glory. Now I am going to return to You. So (consequently) I request You to *glorify Me, so that My glory returns to be the same as previously.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus sabaj'a hia ana madhutu Na [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus prays2 for His *disciples [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Yesus tuhu hari lii sabaj'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama hia le dhèu ètu rai-haha ne, j'aj'i dhèu Ja'a. Ja'a aj'a-nori si, ho rèngu tadhe Ama. Rèngu j'aj'i dhèu Ama, hèia Ama pangèd'u si j'aj'i unu Ja'a kahèi. Ka ra tao madhutu Lii Holo-Nori Ama.<bt>Yesus prayed further, saying, “You (=Father; throughout) have given/allowed people in this world to be/become My people. I have taught (doublet) them, so they know/recognise You. They are/became Your people, and then You turned them over/entrusted them to become My possession as well. So they do according to/obey Your Words/Message (doublet).</bt><v n="7" />Limuri ne re'a le, na, j'ara aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama pangèd'u mi Ja'a sèra, kapua ra nèti Ama.<bt>Now they already understand that everything that You have turned over/entrusted to Me, their roots/source/origin are from You.</bt><v n="8" />Te Ja'a aj'a kore le rèngu Lii Holo-Nori dhu Ama hia mi Ja'a. Rèngu sèmi rare kahèi Lii Holo-Nori se'e. Re'a kahèi, na, Ja'a mai nèti Ama. Ka ra parcaya, na, Ama ka dhu pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) I have (completely/thoroughly) taught them the Words/Message (doublet) which You have given to Me. They also accepted/received those Words/Message. They also know that I came from You. So they believe that You are the one who sent/commissioned Me to come to this world.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ja'a sabaj'a hia rèngu. Ne'e ne, Ja'a sabaj'a boe hia dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne. Te ngaa Ja'a sabaj'a hia dhèu-dhèu dhu Ama pangèd'u mi Ja'a, te rèngu se unu Ama.<bt>I pray2 for them. Right now I'm not praying2 for everyone who is in this world. But I'm only praying for the various people You have turned over/entrusted to Me, cuz (elaboration) those ones are Your possession.</bt><v n="10" />Te aa'i-aa'i unu Ja'a, sèra sa unu Ama kahèi. Aa aa'i-aa'i unu Ama, sèra sa unu Ja'a kahèi. Ka dhèu unu Ja'a se, dhu ded'e Ja'a padedha-dedha.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) every (thing/one) that is My possession, is also Your possession. And every (thing/one) that is Your possession, is also My possession. So/and My people are the ones who *glorify Me (lift up highest).</bt><v n="11" />Ja'a pea boe taruu ètu rai-haha ne, lula nèbhu heka Ja'a lèpa hari asa Ama Ku. Te ngaa dhèu se hud'i pea taruu ètu rai-haha ne. Ama dhu mola-mèci. Ja'a manèngi sèna ka Ama ladhe-leru si pake koasa dhu Ama pangèd'u le mi Ja'a. Ja'a manèngi kahèi ho rèngu pa'èki j'aj'i mi èci, nuka sèmi Ja'a pa'èki j'aj'i mi èci dènge Ama.<bt>I'm not going to keep staying/remaining/living in this world, because soon/not much longer I am going to return (home) to My Father. But these people must continue to remain/stay/live in this world. You (Father) are really/truly clean/pure/holy (doublet). I request that You guard/watch over (doublet) them, using your power/authority that You have given/entrusted to Me. I also request that they are bound/linked becoming one/united, like I am bound/linked as one/united with You.</bt><v n="12" />Karèi nèti Ja'a ètu rai-haha ne bera-bera dènge rèngu, Ja'a leru si, lula rèngu j'aj'i le dhèu Ama. Ja'a j'aga aa sanoro si, sèna ka rèngu pa'èki taruu dènge Ama. Abhu boe dhu ele. Dhodhoka Yudas di dhu cèri eele, madhutu ngaa dhu suri ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua karèi nèti uru èèna.<bt>As long as I am/was in the world together with them, I cared for/raised them because they were already Your possession. I guarded/watched/raised (doublet) over them well/carefully so they they would be bound/linked with You continually. There aren't any who disappeared/were lost. Only just Yudas was separated off/cut off [i.e, from God and from group], according to what the Scriptures had already written beforehand from long ago. [EXEG: sense #4 of Gk “name” (affiliation, association).] [CHECK s-s doublet w younger gen]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sariha-sanoro"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-12 04:46:04Z" status="Anyone">bhs tinggi, 1st part not known;</Message></Annotation><note reference="17:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 41:9, Yohanis 13:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Limuri ne, Ja'a neo lèpa hari asa Ama. Ja'a peka le j'ara se'e lod'o Ja'a ètu rai-haha ne era. Dènge sèmi ne'e, dhèu unu Ja'a se d'ara rèngu bisa karej'e-karae taruu, sama sèmi d'ara Ja'a.<bt>Now, I'm going to come back home to You. I am telling/explaining these things while I am still in this world. In that way, My people's insides can continue to be happy (doublet), like my insides are happy.</bt><v n="14" />Ja'a dhu peka-padhai le dènge rèngu Lii Holo-Nori Ama. Dhèu leo ètu rai-haha tèka d'ara dènge dhèu unu Ja'a, lula mamuri dhèu Ja'a, sama boe dènge mamuri rèngu. Ja'a sèmi èèna kahèi, te Ja'a sama boe sèmi dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>I have already told (doublet) Your Words/Message (doublet) to them. Other people in this world are resentful/veangeful toward My people, because the lives of My people are not like their lives. I am also like that, cuz (elaboration) I am not the same as other people in this world.</bt><v n="15" />Ladhe Ja'a sabaj'a, Ja'a manèngi boe ho Ama more si nèti rai-haha ne. Aad'o! Te ngaa Ja'a manèngi, ho Ama j'aga si, sèna ka ra pakaj'èu nèti bhabhelu.<bt>If/when I pray2, I do not request You to pull out/take out/pluck them out from this world. No! But I request You to guard/watch over them, so they are far/distanced/separated from what is evil. [EXEG: 1) remove from world (like Jesus returning to Father), or 2) separate from people in the world (from vs.14); seems translations and commentaries favour #1 // NOTE to daughter translations: preserve ambiguity between “evil/evil one” if possible.]</bt><v n="16" />Rèngu sama boe dènge dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne, èci èèna ka dènge Ja'a dhu sama boe kahèi dènge dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>They are not the same as other people in this world, like I also am not like other people in this world.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Pake ngaa dhu lèke, sèna ka pamèu d'ara ra. Te dhu lèke ka, Lii Holo-Nori Ama.<bt>Use what is true to make their insides clean/pure/holy. Cuz (elaboration) Your Words/Message (doublet) is true.</bt><v n="18" />Ama ka dhu pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne. Ka Ja'a pua-paleha rèngu kahèi sèmi èèna, sèna ka rèngu mamuri pale-lème ètu talora aae dhèu rai-haha.<bt>You are the one who sent/commissioned Me to come to this world. So/and I also send/commission (doublet) them like that, so that they will live scattered/dispersed in the midst of people of the world.</bt><v n="19" />Ja'a j'aga ngi'u Ja'a ho mola-mèci taruu hia mi Ama. Dènge j'ara ne'e, dhèu unu Ja'a j'aga mamuri ra kahèi sèna ka mola-mèci hia mi Ama. Te Lii Holo-Nori Ama dhu lèke, dhu tao si ho ra saraka mamuri rèngu kateme mi Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>I guard Myself to stay clean/pure/holy (doublet) for You. In that way, My people also guard/watch their lives so they stay clean/pure/holy (doublet) for You. Cuz (elaboration) Your Words/Message (doublet) that are true, are what makes them surrender/turn over/dedicate their entire selves/being/lives to You.” [NOTE: NLT &amp; CEV seem to have missed the grammar and force of the last clause; HCE better.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus manèngi-mangaj'i hia dhèu parcaya aa'i-aa'i [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus prays (doublet) for all believers [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Yesus tuhu hari lii manèngi-mangaj'i Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a sabaj'a, mesa boe hia mi dhèu limuri ne'e di, te ngaa hia rèngu dhu lod'o limuri dhu parcaya Ja'a kahèi, lula lii padhai dhèu se'e.<bt>Yesus prayed (doublet) further, saying, “I pray2 not only just for ththe people of now. But also for those who will believe in Me at a later time, because of what these people (have to) say.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ama, Ja'a manèngi sèna ka rèngu aa'i-aa'i ra bisa pa'èki j'aj'i mi èci, sama sèmi Èdhi pa'èki j'aj'i èci. Ja'a manèngi sèna ka rèngu j'aj'i èci dènge Èdhi, ho hud'i laa dhèu rai-haha ne bisa parcaya, na, Ama ka dhu pua-paleha Ja'a.<bt>Father, I request that all of them can be bound/linked as one/united, like We-inc are also bound/linked as one/united. I also want for them to be bound/linked as one/united with Us, so that other people in this world can believe that You yourself are the one who has sent/commissioned (doublet) Me.</bt><v n="22" />Ama pad'elo le dadedha Ja'a mi dhèu sèra. Ka Ja'a ded'e le rèngu padedha-dedha sama sèmi Ja'a. Dènge jara ne'e, rèngu pa'èki j'aj'i èci, sama sèmi Èdhi kahèi j'aj'i èci.<bt>You have already shown My *glory/high-ness to those people. So/and I have *glorified them, the same as Me. In that way, they are bound/linked as one/united, like We are also bound/linked as one/united.</bt><v n="23" />Ja'a pa'èki dènge rèngu. Ama kahèi pa'èki dènge Ja'a. Rèngu hud'i pa'èki j'aj'i èci sèmi èèna ku, toke ra mamuri d'ara èci dènge be'a. Te ladhe rèngu mamuri d'ara èci sèmi èèna, dhèu leo ètu rai-haha ne re'a, na, Ama dhu sue si, nuka sèmi Ama sue Ja'a. Dènge j'ara ne, rèngu re'a kahèi, na, Ama ku dhu pua Ja'a.<bt>I am bound/linked with them. You are also bound/linked with Me. They must be bound/linked as one/united like that, to the point that they truly live one insides (united, one accord, same purpose). Cuz (elaboration) if they live one insides like that, other people in this world will know/come to know that You are the one who loves them, like You love Me. In that way they will also know that You are the one who sent/commissioned Me. [STYLE: order shifted for information load.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ama, Ja'a d'èi sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama pangèd'u le mi Ja'a, bera-bera dènge Ja'a. Te Ja'a neo, sèna ka rèngu bisa ladhe rèdhi Ama ded'e Ja'a padedha-dedha. Te Ama sue Ja'a mema-mema le, lod'o Èdhi dhae paj'aj'i mèka rai-haha ne.<bt>Father. I want/desire for everyone who You have handed over/entrusted to Me, be together with Me. Cuz (elaboration) I want for them to be able to see You *glorify Me. Cuz (elaboration) You have already loved Me beforehand, when We-inc had not yet made/created/brought into being this world.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ama Pasue dhu d'ara mola. Te ngaa dhèu ètu rai-haha ne tadhe boe Ama. Ja'a tadhe Ama. Aa dhèu unu Ja'a re'a kahèi, na, Ama ka dhu pua Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne.<bt>Dear Father has a straight/honest/righteous insides. But people in this world don't know/recognise You. I know/recognise You. And My people also know that You are the one who sent/commissioned Me to come to this world.</bt><v n="26" />Ja'a dhu peka le dènge rèngu, Ama ne, Cee. Aa èèna na Ja'a loe boe peka dènge rèngu sèmi èèna, lula Ja'a d'èi ho rèngu re'a mèu sasue Ama. Te sasue dhu rèngu re'a rèdhi ne'e ne, èci èèna ka dènge sasue Ama mi dedha Ja'a, sèna ka hud'i laa Ja'a pa'èki taruu dènge rèngu.&gt;&gt;<bt>I have already told/explained to them Who You are. And I will not stop telling them like that, because I want for them to be able to truly/really know Your love. Cuz (elaboration) that love that they experience, is the same as Your love for Me, so that I may be bound/linked continually to them.” [EXEG: Gk “name” in sense #3 (reputation) &amp; #5 (authority); NLT.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra kèpe Lamatua Yesus<bt>They (non-referential) catch/arrest the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:47-56; Markus 14:43-50; Lukas 22:47-53)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="18" />
      <v n="1" />Ropa Yesus manèngi-mangaj'i nare, hèia la'e palere-lere dènge ana madhutu Na. Lasi asa d'ara oka cue ètu sebhe loko Kidron.<bt>When Yesus had finished praying (doublet), He went out together with His disciples. They went into a garden/orchard on the other side of the Kidron river/stream.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2-3" />Lod'o èèna, kètu agama Yahudi sèra dènge dhèu-dhèu nèti partei agama Parisi saraka mi Yudas, sordad'u dènge dhèu j'aga pèri-pèri. Te nèngu neo pahie eele Yesus. Yudas ne'a oka ne kahèi, lula Yesus pakaboko dènge ana madhutu Na ètu era ne'e pèri-pèri hari le. Ka Yudas si lasi asa oka ne rèti dènge ob'o, labhu lantera dènge rèka.<bt>At that time, the *chief priests (heads/leaders of the Yahudi priests), and (various) people from the Parisi religious party had handed over/turned over several soldiers and guards to Yudas. Cuz (elaboration) he was going to sell off (betray) Yesus. Yudas also knew that garden/orchard, because Yesus had gathered many/several times there with His disciples. So/and Yudas (collective) went to that garden/orchard, taking torches, lamps/lanterns, and sharp weapons (category: swords, spears, etc. in contrast with firearms).</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Aa te ngaa Yesus dhu ne'a uru le aa'i-aa'i dhu èèna na j'aj'i. Hèia ara la'e asa madha rèngu, ka Na lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Miu tenge cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Whereas in fact, Yesus already knew everything that was going to happen. So He moved forward to them, and spoke, saying, “Who are you-pl looking for?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />Ka ra b'ala, na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i tenge dhèu èci, ngara na Yesus, nèti rae Nasaret.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they responded, saying, “We-exc are looking for a person, named Yesus, from the village of Nasaret.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ka ne'e.&gt;&gt; Lod'o èèna, Yudas dhu titu dènge dhèu se'e. Nèngu ne'e ka dhu pahie Yesus.<bt>Then Yesus responded2, saying, “That's Me.” At that time, Yudas was standing with those people. He (this one) was the one who solld off (betrayed) Yesus.</bt><v n="6" />Ropa Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ka ne'e,&gt;&gt; hèia dhèu se hari kabodho, ka ra bèbha.<bt>When Yesus spoke, saying, “That's Me,” those people moved backwards, and fell down.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ka Yesus karèi hari, na, &lt;&lt;Miu tenge cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked them again, saying, “Who are you looking for?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia dhèu se dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Yesus, dhèu Nasaret.&gt;&gt;<bt>So they responded2, saying, “Yesus, the Nasaret person.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Hèia Na peka dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Deo na Ja'a peka kore le, na, Nèngu ka Ja'a ne. De ladhe miu tenge Ja'a, na, baku kèpe dhèu leo. Hud'i si lasi.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yesus spoke, saying, “I already told (you) earlier, saying, He is Me. So (consequently), if you are looking for Me, na, don't catch/arrest the other people. Just let them go.”</bt><v n="9" />(Nèngu padhai lii sèmi èèna, sèna ka pamèci dènge ngaa dhu Nèngu peka nèdhi le, na, &lt;&lt;Ama. Aa'i-aa'i dhu Ama pangèd'u le mi Ja'a, abhu boe èci sa dhu ele.&gt;&gt;)<bt>(He spoke like that to make come into being/fulfill what He had once said, saying, “Father. Everyone whom You (Father) have turned over/entrusted to Me, there is not one who has been lost/disappeared.”) [NOTE to daughter translations: compare with 17:12.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Lod'o èèna, Simon Petrus nèti dènge samala iiki èci. Ka na bete ho neo pare dhèu. Kabèdhi laa, na pare pama'ète rèu dhilu g'ana nèti dhèu èci. (Dhèu ne ngara na Malkus. Nèngu ne, ana pua-paleha nèti kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi.)<bt>At that time, Simon Petrus was carrying/bearing a small sword. And he pulled it out, to cut people/someone. Unexpectedly he cut off a person's right ear. (That person was named Malkus. He was the Yahudi *high priest's servant.)</bt><v n="11" />Ka Yesus pua Petrus, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;We, Petrus! Pasaluu hari samala èu èèna asa d'ara sope la'e. Te Ama Ku dhu peka le, na, Ja'a hud'i paraga ku dènge j'aj'èra sèmi ne'e ne. De hud'i laa! Èèna nuka sèmi Nèngu hia Ja'a galaa èci dhu isi na pèd'u-èd'u. Hud'i laa Ja'a kinu toke èle.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus ordered Petrus, saying, “We, Petrus! Put your sword back into it's sheath. Cuz (elaboration) My Father already said I must get/encounter suffering of this sort. So (consequently), just let it be! It's like He has given Me a glass filled with bitterness/bile. Let Me drink it all up.”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sope"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-31 04:09:14Z" status="Anyone">sarong</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pèd'u-èd'u"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-03-31 04:11:48Z" status="Anyone">sepahit empedu</Message></Annotation><note reference="18:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 26:39, Markus 14:36, Lukas 22:42</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lere rèti Lamatua Yesus asa madha kètu kapai risi agama<bt>They take/escort the Lord Yesus before the *high priest</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01814b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Hèia komedhaa, sordad'u dènge dhèu j'aga aa'i-aa'i ra kèpe Yesus, ka ra èki Ne.<bt>Then the commander, the soldiers, and the guards, caught/arrested Yesus, and tied/bound Him.</bt><v n="13" />Ka lere rèti uuru Ne asa Anas. Anas ne, ama dhèu èmu Kayafas. Tèu èèna, Kayafas dhu j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi.<bt>Then2 they took/escorted/led Him first to Anas. That Anas was the father of Kayafas' spouse. That year, Kayafas was the one who was the *high priest of the Yahudi religion.</bt><v n="14" />Kayafas ne'e ka dhu peka nèdhi le dènge ama-ama dhèu Yahudi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Be'a risi hia miu, ladhe dhèu èci madhe pala dhèu aa'i-aa'i.&gt;&gt;<bt>This is the Kayafas who had once told the leaders of the Yahudi people, saying, “It's better for you-pl, if only one person dies for everyone.”</bt><note reference="18:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 11:49-50</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus pasili, peka na, nèngu tadhe boe Lamatua Yesus<bt>Petrus denies, saying, he doesn't know/recognise the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:69-70; Markus 14:66-68; Lukas 22:55-57)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Simon Petrus dhu madhutu Yesus re limuri palere-lere dènge ana madhutu Yesus èci, nuka ja'a, Yohanis ne. Lula kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi tadhe ja'a, nèti èèna ka ja'a bisa maso kahèi palere-lere dènge Yesus asa madha èmu na.<bt>Simon Petrus was following Yesus from behind, together with one of Yesus' other disciples, that is me, Yohanis. Because the high priest of the Yahudi religion knew/recognised me, that is why I was able to enter into his yard, together with Yesus. [EXEG: Carson, Morris, HCE // Explicit to Implicit: “the High priest's palace courtyard”. Implied by his position that he would have had a fancy house or a house complex. Heavy information load.]</bt><v n="16" />Te ngaa Petrus titu ètu li'u, padètu dènge hèb'a tedhe. Hèia ja'a laku asa li'u, ho peka dènge dhèu bhèni èci dhu j'aga hèb'a tedhe ne, sèna ka kèti Petrus asa d'ara.<bt>But Petrus stood outside, near the fence door/gate. So I went out, and spoke to a woman who was guarding/watching that gate, so that I could bring Petrus inside.</bt><v n="17" />Hèia bhèni ne karèi Petrus, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Wee! Èu ne, ca dhèu ana madhutu Dhèu nèi, si?&gt;&gt;<bt>And that woman asked Petrus, saying, “Wee! You-sg here, are one of that Person's disciples, aren't you?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Petrus dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Petrus responded, saying, “No!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Lod'o èèna lèke dènge hèru pacuhi. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu madhenga dènge ana pua-paleha sèra dhu titu manyiru ai. Ka Petrus la'e manyiru ai sama-sama dènge rèngu kahèi.<bt>At that time it was cold season/month. That is why the guard/watchers and the servants were standing warming (themselves) over the fire. So Petrus went to warm (himself) over the fire together with them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Kètu kapai risi agama parisa Lamatua Yesus<bt>The *high priest examines/interrogates the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:59-66; Markus 14:55-64; Lukas 22:66-71)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Lod'o èèna, kètu kapai risi dhui nèti agama Yahudi parisa Yesus lula-nèti a'aj'a Na, aa lula-nèti ana madhutu Na.<bt>At that time, the former *high priest of the Yahudi religion was examining/interrogating Yesus about His teaching, and about His disciples.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Ka Yesus peka dènge nèngu, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a peka paled'a, sèna ka dhèu aa'i-aa'i bisa tadèngi. Ja'a tema aj'a ètu era dhu biasa dhèu Yahudi èdhi pakaboko, nuka ètu d'ara èmu sabaj'a èdhi, dènge ètu Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i. Ja'a padhai lii pahuni kèdhi boe.<bt>And Yesus told (him), saying, “I spoke clearly/openly so everyone could hear. I always taught in places where we-inc Yahudi people normally gather, such as in our-inc houses of worship, and in the *Temple. I have never spoken in hiding/secret.</bt><v n="21" />Nga tao ka èu karèi Ja'a? Karèi la dhèu-dhèu dhu nanene lii padhai Ja'a. Te, tatu re'a ngaa dhu Ja'a peka-padhai.&gt;&gt;<bt>Why do you-sg ask Me? Just ask the people who listened to Me speak/listened to what I had to say. Cuz (elaboration) surely they know what I have said.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Ropa Na padhai lii sèmi èèna, dhèu j'aga èci dhu titu ètu èèna, tèb'e Yesus, ka na peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu baku padhai lii sèmi èèna dènge kètu kapai risi.&gt;&gt;<bt>When He spoke like that, one of the guards who was standing there slapped (open-handed to the face) Yesus, saying, “You-sg shouldn't talk like that to the high priest.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ka Yesus b'ala, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe Ja'a padhai lii sale, na, pad'elo mia dhu sale nèti lii padhai deo na. Te ngaa ladhe Ja'a peka lèke, nga tao ka èu tèb'e Ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus told him, saying, “If I have spoken wrong/incorrectly, na, point out what was wrong/sin/fault with what was said. But if I spoke what is true, why do you slap Me?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Èle ka, Anas pua dhèu lere Ne asa Kayafas dhu j'aj'i kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi. Lod'o lere rèti Ne, Yesus dhu ra èki era.<bt>After that, Anas ordered them to escort/lead Him to Kayafas, who was the *high priest of the Yahudi religion. While they were leading Him, Yesus was still bound/tied.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Petrus pasili hari, peka na, nèngu tadhe boe Lamatua Yesus<bt>Petrus again denies, saying he does not know/recognise the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 26:71-75; Markus 14:69-72; Lukas 22:58-62)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Lod'o èèna, Simon Petrus titu manyiru ai era. Ka dhèu leo dhu ètu èèna, karèi ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, ca dhèu nèti ana madhutu Dhèu nèi, si?&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, Simon Petrus was still standing to warm (himself) over the fire. And the other people who were there asked him, saying, “You-sg here, are one of that Person's disciples, right?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa Petrus pasili, peka na, &lt;&lt;Aad'o!&gt;&gt;<bt>But Petrus denied (it), saying, “No!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ètu era ne'e, abhu kahèi dhèu sab'a èci nèti kètu kapai risi agama Yahudi. Nèngu ne, pa'a'ari kahèi dènge dhèu dhu Petrus pare pama'ète rèu dhilu na. Hèia dhèu ne karèi Petrus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Waa! Deo na, èu ne ètu d'ara oka nèi, si? Te ja'a kèdhi èu ètu nèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>There, there was also one of the *high priest's of the Yahudi religion's servants/workers. He was also a relative/family of that person whom Petrus had cut off his ear. So he asked, saying, “Waa! Earlier you-sg were in that (remote) garden/orchard, right? Cuz (elaboration) I saw you there!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Te ngaa Petrus pasili hari, hèia manu kokotoo dènge.<bt>But Petrus denied (it) again, and the chicken crowed immediately/straightaway.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus ètu madha gubernur Pilatus<bt>The Lord Yesus before gubernur Pilatus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:1-2, 11-14; Markus 15:1-5; Lukas 23:1-5)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />D'ara mad'ae aae era, lere rèti Yesus nèti Kayafas asa èmu jabatan gubernur ètu benteng sordad'u Roma.<bt>Then still early in the morning, they took Yesus from Kayafas, going to the gubernur's official residence in the Roma soldier's fort [loan, but there is an old stone one on Ndao island].</bt><note reference="18:28" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Benteng era pea sordad'u Roma, madhutu lii Latin na, <span class="Italic">praetorium.</span><bt>The Roma soldiers' place, they called in the Latin language, saying, <span class="Italic">praetorium</span>.</bt></note>Dhèu Yahudi se maso boe asa èmu dhèu Roma, te èèna pakaj'alu rèngu. Te ladhe ra maso, na, rèngu bisa boe ra'a pesta Paska.<bt>The Yahudi people themselves did not enter into the place of the Roma people, cuz (elaboration) that would make them filthy/defiled. Cuz (elaboration) if they entered, they couldn't eat the Paska feast. [EXEG: see Carson on time frame.]</bt><v n="29" />Hèia gubernur Pilatus la'e asa li'u paraga dènge dhèu Yahudi se. Ka na karèi, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Miu pèci sasala ngaa mi dedha Dhèu ne'e?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, gubernur Pilatus went out to meet with those Yahudi people. And he asked, saying, “What are you-pl accusing this Person of?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Hèia ra b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, ama. Ladhe Nèngu ne dhèu bhelu-katub'a boe, na, tatu ji'i mai boe asa madha ama. Ngaa hari ji'i mai saraka Ne asa kacui-aai ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>And they responded, saying, “It's like this, father (appropriate to officials). If He here were not an evil (doublet) person/criminal, surely we-exc would not come before you (father). Let alone turn Him over to your hands.” [NOTE: They insist this is not a Hebraism, and I have encountered it in texts.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Ka gubernur peka dènge dhèu se, na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Hud'i laa miu ka dhu uri lii langu Na, madhutu atora miu dhèu Yahudi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the gubernur told them, saying, “It's like this. Just let you-pl be the ones who handle/deal with/take care of His case/matter, according to your Yahudi regulations/law.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ama-ama dhèu Yahudi se, peka na, &lt;&lt;Bisa boe ama. Ji'i dhèu Yahudi dènge heka hak ho pama'ète hahuku madhe. Dhoka miu dhèu paredha Roma di dhu dènge hak èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>The leaders of the Yahudi people told (him), saying, “That can't be, father. We-exc Yahudi people don't have the right anymore to decide the death penalty/punishment. It is only you-pl Roma government that has that right.”</bt><v n="32" />(Lii padhai lii rèngu èèna, palèke dènge lii padhai dhu uru èèna Yesus peka nèdhi le. Te Nèngu dhu peka le dènge dhèu unu Na sèra, na, Nèngu madhe madhutu j'ara paredha Roma, nuka ra paku Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha.)<bt>(When/while they spoke like that, what Yesus had once said before, happened/came into being/fulfilled. Cuz (elaboration) He had already told His people that He would later die according to the Roma government's way/method, that is they would nail Him on a *cross (doublet).)</bt><note reference="18:32" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 3:14, 12:32-33</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="33" />Hèia gubernur maso hari asa d'ara benteng sordad'u. Ka na paroa Yesus, hèia na karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, dhèu aae dhèu Yahudi, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the gubernur went back into the soldiers' fort. Then2 he summoned Yesus, and he asked, saying, “You-sg here are the Yahudi people's king, or (what)?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="34" />Te ngaa Yesus karèi ne, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama ka peka sèmi èèna, do abhu dhèu leo ka dhu peka dènge ama lula-nèti Ja'a?&gt;&gt;<bt>But Yesus asked him, saying, “Are you (father) asking this yourself, or, are there other people who have told you about Me?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />Hèia gubernur dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Eee! Ja'a ne dhèu Yahudi boe. Ana kabarai Èu mesa Mu ka dhu saraka Èu. Ngaa hari kètu agama Yahudi sèra. Èu ne, tao sala ngaa? Èu peka sèku!&gt;&gt;<bt>The gubernur responded, saying, “Eee! [+annoyance] I here am not a Yahudi person. Your-sg own race/people/ethnic group/citizens are the ones who turned you over. Even the *chief prests. So what wrong/offence have you done? Come on and tell me [+imperative]!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="36" />Ka Yesus peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ne, dhèu aae boe nèti rai-haha ne. Te ladhe Ja'a j'aj'i dhèu aae sama sèmi èèna, tatu dhèu-dhèu Ja'a palab'a le, ka dhèu Yahudi kèpe boe Ja'a. Tare'a, Ja'a ne Dhèu Aae. Te ngaa ca dhèu sa ètu rai-haha ne ded'e boe Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus told (him), saying, “I am not a king from this world. Cuz (elaboration) if I was a king of that sort, surely My people would have rebelled/revolt/riot, so the Yahudi people wouldn't have (been able to) catch/arrest Me. I really am a King. But there is nobody in this world who appointed Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="37" />Hèia gubernur karèi hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;De Èu ne, Dhèu Aae, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then, the gubernur asked again, saying, “So (consequently), are you a King, or (what)?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus dhaa, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama unu mu ka dhu peka, na, Ja'a ne Dhèu Aae. Dhu lèke ka, rara iisi Ja'a ne, sèna ka j'aj'i Dhèu Aae. Ja'a mai asa rai-haha ne ho j'aj'i Dhèu Aae, sèna ka Ja'a peka-padhai j'ara-j'ara dhu lèke. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu kèpe pa'èra j'ara-j'ara dhu lèke, rèngu sèra ka dhu nanene Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Yesus responded, saying, “Father yourself is the one who said I was a King. What is true is that I was born to be/become a King. I came to this world to become a King, so that I could tell/explain the things that are true. Everyone who holds firmly to true things/matters/issues, na, they listen to Me.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38a" />Ka gubernur karèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhu lèke èèna, sèmi ngaa sa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the gubernor asked (Him), saying, “What is true, is what?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra pama'ète hahuku madhe mi Lamatua Yesus<bt>They decide the punishment of death for the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:15-31; Markus 15:6-20; Lukas 23:13-25)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38b" />Ropa gubernur Pilatus padhai lii nare, hèia kalua hari la'e asa dhèu Yahudi sèra. Ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Ja'a parisa le Nèngu, te ngaa abhu boe sasala Na èci sa.<bt>When gubernur Pilatus finished speaking, he went back out to the Yahudi people. He spoke, saying, “I have examined/interrogated Him, but I have not found/encountered any fault/wrong/sin with/in Him/of His.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="39" />Te ngaa miu dhu tema le, tèu mai-tèu mai lod'o d'ai pesta Paska sèmi ne'e, ja'a patabuli ana bèdho ca dhèu hia miu. De tèu ne'e mo'o sèna ka ja'a patabuli dhèu aae Yahudi miu, do tasamia?&gt;&gt;<bt>But your-pl custom/norm, is that each year at the Paska feast, I release one prisoner to you. So (consequently) this year, do you want me to release your-pl king of the Yahudis, or how is it?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="40" />Ka aa'i-aa'i ra pa'oo-parodha, peka na, &lt;&lt;Baku patabuli Dhèu èèna! Patabuli Barabas di!&gt;&gt; Barabas ne, ca dhèu dhu bhelu titu kèna.<bt>All of them shouted noisily (doublet), saying, “Don't release this Person! Just release Barabas!” That Barabas was an incredibly evil person.</bt><note reference="18:40" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">&lt;&lt;Dhèu dhu bhelu titu kèna&gt;&gt; ètu lii Yunani abhu dua sasoa, nuka: 1) parapo dhu mana'u mèdha-panyau dhèu dènge j'ara laka-seti, aa 2) dhèu dhu pake rèka ho babèga eele dhèu paredha Roma. Ètu <span class="Italic">Lukas </span>23:19 peka na, Barabas ne, pamadhe dhèu, dènge lab'a dhèu paredha Roma kahèi.<bt>“An incredibly evil person” in the Yunani language word has two meanings, which are: 1) a robber who steal things by porce, and 2) a person who uses weapons to try to get rid of the Roma government. <span class="Italic">Lukas</span> 23:19 says that this Barabas had murdered people and opposed the Roma government too.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="19" />
      <v n="1" />Èle èèna ka, gubernur Pilatus pua sordad'u na lasi kalabhe Yesus pake gui.<bt>After that, gubernur Pilatus ordered his soldiers to go whip Yesus using a whip (verb &amp; noun different lexemes).</bt><note reference="19:1" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sordad'u Roma pake gui dhu èpi nèti ka'uri badha, pèri-pèri loa. Hèia ra èki dènge rui dhu mariu, do tamèru dhu padhudhu ètu suu dhari se. Ladhe hake pahari-pahari, ka'uri dhèu bisa laho mae-mae. Dhèu Yahudi ladhe hake dhèu, dhoka èpa nguru hari di. Te ngaa sordad'u Roma se hake dhu dènge boe too.<bt>The Roma soldiers used a whip that was made from the skin/leather rope several strips. Then they tied sharp bones or sharp lead on the ends of the ropes. If/when whipped over and over, peoples' skins can peal.off throw.away. The Yahudi people used a limit of whipping only just 40 times. But the Roma soldiers whipped without a limit/boundary.</bt></note><v n="2-3" />Aa sordad'u se'e rare kalai aj'u padhudhu kahèi, ho ènyu tao solo. Ka ra lalilu solo ne mi kètu Yesus, nuka sèmi rèngu neo ded'e dhèu aae hiu dhu pake solo dhèu aae. Aa te ngaa sasoa na, ra neo pahahe Ne di. Hèia ra papake Yesus kodho madhera èci dhu mea sanama mangèru, nuka sèmi dhèu aae biasa pake. Aa ra sasei Ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Tabea, dhèu aae Yahudi!&gt;&gt; Sordad'u se tèb'e Ne g'ana-kariu kahèi.<bt>Those soldiers also took the small branches of a thorn tree to weave into a hat. Then they pressed (down) that hat of thorns on Yesus head, like they were appointing/installing a new king with an king's hat. Their meaning/intention was to humiliate/mock Him. Then they put on Yesus a long clothes purple in colour like kings normally wear. [NOTE: red blending blue, a term checked with the weavers and tested w/UNSs.] Then2 they mocked/scoffed at Him, saying, “Respectful greetings, king of the Yahudi people!” The soldiers also slapped Him right-left.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lalilu "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-01 01:18:09Z" status="Anyone">tendes</Message><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-12 07:01:32Z">lalangu = hina ; sasei = olok, ejek, sindir</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ka gubernur la'e hari catèka peka dènge dhèu ae sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e! Ja'a kèti Ne asa li'u hia miu. Te ngaa miu hud'i me'a ku, na, ja'a parisa kore le, te ngaa abhu boe sasala Na èci sa.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the gubernur went out once again, to tell those many people/crowds, saying, “It's like this! I am bringing Him outside to you-pl. But you must understand, that I have (throughly/finished) examined/interrogated Him, but I do not find any wrong in/at/of Him.” [NLT]</bt><v n="5" />Ropa rèti Yesus asa li'u, Nèngu dhu pake era solo padhudhu dènge kodho madhera dhu mea sanama mangèru. Hèia gubernur lii dènge dhèu ae se, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ku, Dhèu ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>When Yesus came out, He was still wearing that hat of thorns, and the long purple clothes. Then the gubernur told those many people, saying, “Have a look! Here is that Person.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ropa kètu agama dènge dhèu madhenga Èmu Kapua Manèngi-Mangaj'i sèra ladhe rèdhi Yesus, hèia ra pa'oo-parodha palere-lere, peka na, &lt;&lt;Pamadhe Ne! Paku ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha!&gt;&gt;<bt>When the *chief priests and the Temple guards saw Yesus, they shouted noisily (doublet) together, saying, “Kill Him! Nail Him on a cross!” [NOTE to daughter translations: if ‘guards’not clear, then say ‘*Temple guards’ (cf. NLT, CEV).]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Te ngaa gubernur peka dènge ra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa miu ka dhu mèti Ne, lami pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Te ja'a abhu boe sasala Na èci sa, dhu palèke dènge hahuku madhe.&gt;&gt;<bt>But the gubernur told them, saying, “Let you-pl be the ones who take Him to kill Him on a cross. Cuz (elaboration) I haven't found any wrong of His worthy/appropriate to punish Him with death.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Dhèu Yahudi dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ji'i dènge Atora nèti Ama Lamatua. Madhutu Atora ne, Dhèu ne hud'i madhe ku, lula Na ded'e iisi Na j'aj'i Ana Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Yahudi people responded, saying, “We-exc have Regulations/Law from God. According to that Regulation/Law, this Person must die, because he has elevated himself to be God's Child.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ropa gubernur tadèngi lii padhai ra, hèia asa na madha'u.<bt>When the gubernur heard what they were saying, he became more afraid.</bt><v n="9" />Ka la'e hari asa d'ara benteng, hèia na karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu ne, dhèu mia?&gt;&gt; Te ngaa Yesus bhoka boe hèb'a.<bt>So he went back into the fort, and asked Yesus, saying, “You here, are a person from where?” But Yesus didn't resond to him. [Lit: didn't open his mouth. (They say it's not a Hebraism.)]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="10" />Ka gubernur jèke Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Eeh! Nga tao ka Èu b'ala boe ja'a? Èu dhu me'a, si? Ja'a ne, dènge koasa pamadhe Èu, do, patabuli Èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the gubernur spoke angrily to Yesus, saying, “Eeh? [+frustration] Why is it that you-sg won't respond to me. Surely you already know, right? I here am the one who has the power/authority to kill You, or, release You.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Hèia Yesus b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e, ama. Ladhe ama dhu dènge koasa sèmi èèna, na, lula ama abhu koasa nèti Ama Lamatua ètu sorga. Te dhodhoka Nèngu di dhu hia ama koasa èèna, sèna ka tao ngaa èci sa hia mi Ja'a ne. Te ngaa dhèu dhu saraka Ja'a asa ama, rèngu sèra ka dhu pasae sasala bia risi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded, saying, “It's like this, father. If you had that power/authority, na, that is because you got/obtained that authority from God in heaven. Cuz (elaboration) only He is the one who gives that power to you, to do whatever to Me. But the people who turned Me over to you, they are the ones who carry a much heavier wrong/sin.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Karèi nèti èèna ka, gubernur tenge j'ara ho patabuli Yesus. Te ngaa dhèu Yahudi se pa'oo palere-lere, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ama patabuli Dhèu ne, tatu ama dhu pa'angalai boe dènge dhèu aae kapai, Keser. Te dhèu dhu ded'e ngi'u na j'aj'i dhèu aae, nèngu èèna lab'a Keser.&gt;&gt;<bt>Beginning from that (time/event/exchange), the gubernur kept looking for a way to free/release Yesus. But the Yahudi people kept shouting together, saying, “If you release this Person, it is clear that you are not the big king Keser's friend. Cuz (elaboration) a person who elevates himself as king is opposing Keser.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ka ropa gubernur tadèngi lii padhai dhèu se, hèia na pua rèti Yesus asa li'u. Ka gubernur madhèdi ètu kadera pama'ète lii, ètu era èci dhu ra pangare na, &lt;&lt;Tana Lapang nèti Hadhu Kabela&gt;&gt;. (Madhutu lii Aram, ngara na <span class="Italic">Gabata.</span>)<bt>So when the gubernur heard them talking like that, he ordered Yesus to be brought out. Then he sat in the judging seat, in a place they named, “(Muster) Field of Flat Stones”. (In the Aram language its name is <span class="Italic">Gabata</span>.) [NOTE: Carson says: “An area paved with stones, originally about 3000 square feet in size, has been discovered in a building identified as the Fortress of Antonia.”]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Lod'o èèna, lèke dènge Lod'o Sadia Kalela Paska. Pe d'ara lod'o titu mera sa, gubernur peka dènge dhèu Yahudi sèra, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe ku laa! Nèngu ne, dhèu aae miu!&gt;&gt;<bt>That day was the Day of Preparing for the Paska Feast. Around noon/mid-day, the gubernur told the Yahudi people, saying, “Have a look! He here is your-pl king!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Te ngaa rèngu asa hoe pa'oo-parodha peka na, &lt;&lt;Mèti Ne, asa li'u mai! Pamadhe Ne! Paku Ne asa aj'u palolo-palèbha!&gt;&gt;<bt>But they shouted (doublet) with increasing flow, saying, “Bring/Take Him out from here! Kill Him! Nail Him on a cross!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia gubernur papane si, peka na, &lt;&lt;De tasamia? Miu d'èi, ladhe ja'a pamadhe dhèu aae miu ne, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>The gubernur goaded/stirred them up, saying, “So (consequently), how about it? Do you desire that I kill your king here, or (what)?”</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="papane "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-12 06:53:09Z" status="Anyone">bekin panas</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka kètu agama Yahudi se b'ala, peka na, &lt;&lt;Dhèu aae ji'i dhodhoka ca dhèu di, nuka Keser! Dhèu leo aad'o!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then the *chief priests responded, saying, “We-exc only have one king, that is Keser! There is no other person!”</bt><v n="16a" />Hèia gubernur hia Yesus asa sordad'u sèra, sèna ka ra paku pamadhe Ne ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha.<bt>So then the gubernur turned Yesus over to the soldiers, for them to nail Him to death on a cross (irrealis).</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra paku Lamatua Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha<bt>They nail the Lord Yesus on a cross</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:32-44; Markus 15:21-32; Lukas 23:26-43)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16b" />Hèia sordad'u se sèmi rare Yesus.<bt>Then, those soldiers accepted/received Yesus.</bt><v n="17" />Ka Yesus pasae aj'u palolo-palèbha Na la'e asa li'u kota. Lasi asa era èci dhu ngara na, &lt;&lt;Era Rui Kètu&gt;&gt;. (Madhutu lii Aram, era ne ngara na, <span class="Italic">Golgota.</span>)<bt>And Yesus shoulder carried His cross going outside the city. They went to a place named, “Skull Place”. (In their Aram language, the name of that place is, <span class="Italic">Golgota</span>.)</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />D'ai era èèna, ra paku Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha èci. Dhèu se paku kahèi dhèu leo dhèu dua. Èci re sebhe g'ana, aa ca dhèu hari re sebhe kariu Yesus. Ka Yesus ètu talora rèngu dua ra.<bt>Arriving there, they nailed Yesus to a cross. They also did that to two other people. One on the right side, and the other on the left side of Yesus. And Yesus was in their middle/in between the two of them.</bt><v n="19" />Ka gubernur paredha sordad'u na sèra, suri ètu papa èci, ho paku re dedha kètu Yesus. Ètu papa ne ra suri, peka na,<bt>The gubernur ordered his soldiers to write on a board, then nail it above Yesus' head. On that board they wrote, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line Centered" usfm="qc">
      <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Yesus, dhèu Nasaret. Nèngu ne, Dhèu Aae dhèu Yahudi&gt;&gt;</span>
      <bt>
        <span class="Italic">“Yesus, a Nasaret person. He is the King of the Yahudi people”</span>
      </bt>
    </p>
    <fig path="HK-LB\LB00327C.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Rèngu suri ètu papa ne pake tèlu lii, nuka: lii Aram, lii Yunani, dènge lii Latin. Dhèu Yahudi ae ka dhu baca sasuri ne, lula era mamadhe Yesus ne, padètu dènge kota Yerusalem.<bt>They wrote on that board using three languages. That is: the Aram language, the Yunani language, and the Latin language. Many Yahudi people read that writing, because the place of Yesus' death was close to the city of Yerusalem. [EXEG: Carson, etc.]</bt><v n="21" />Te ngaa kètu agama Yahudi sèra ro'o boe. Ka lasi peka dènge gubernur, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Baku suri &lt;Dhèu Aae nèti dhèu Yahudi&gt;! Be'a risi suri laa peka na, &lt;Dhèu ne peka na, nèngu dhèu aae nèti dhèu Yahudi.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>But the *chief priests of the Yahudi religion did not like it. So they went and told the gubernur, saying, “Father! Don't write ‘King of the Yahudi people’! It would be better to write, saying, ‘This person says he is king of the Yahudi people.’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Te ngaa gubernur dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a ka dhu pua si suri sèmi èèna. De hud'i ka laa!&gt;&gt;<bt>But the gubernur responded, saying, “I am the one who told them to write like that. So (consequently), just let it be!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Ropa sordad'u paku rare Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha, hèia ra pabagi mèdha-papake Na mi èpa pala. Ca dhèu sordad'u abhu ca pala. Hèia rare kodho li'u Na, dhu j'au boe, dhu manènu kateme nèti dedha.<bt>When the soldiers had nailed Yesus on the cross, they divided His clothes in four places/parts. One part for each soldier. And they took His outer clothes that had no sewing/stitching, which was woven whole from the top.</bt><v n="24" />Ka ra papeka, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi baku ciu eele kodho Na. Be'a risi ère lot, sèna ka te'a, na, cee ka dhu abhu.&gt;&gt; Èèna j'aj'i madhutu sèmi dhu suri tèke ètu d'ara Sasuri Ama Lamatua, dhu peka na,<bt>Then they spoke with each other, saying, “We-inc shouldn't tear up His clothes. It would be better if we draw lots, to find out who gets it.” This happened according to what had been written in the Scriptures, saying,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">&lt;&lt;Rèngu pabagi mèdha-papake ja'a,<bt>“They divided up my clothes,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ka ra ère lot ho abhu kodho ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>and they drew lots to get my shirt/clothes2.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia sordad'u se tao madhutu sèmi èèna ka.<bt>Then those soldiers did that. [TEXT: versification on this last sentence varies. AGNT, TB, CEV, Carlton, have it in vs.24. NRSV and NLT have it is vs.25. I can't find any discussion on why the difference.]</bt><note reference="19:24" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 22:19</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pua Yohanis ladhe-leru ina Na<bt>The Lord Yesus orders Yohanis to look after (doublet) His mother</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Ètu era ne'e, abhu kahèi dhèu bhèni pèri-pèri dhu titu. Rèngu se, nuka: ina Yesus, ina iiki Yesus, Maria dhèu èmu Klopas, dènge Maria nèti rae Magdala.<bt>There, there were also several women standing. They were: Yesus' mother, Yesus' aunt [MZ], Klopas' wife Maria, and Maria from the village of Magdala. [EXEG: see Carson, NRSV, NLT, CEV.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teto"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-01 03:15:32Z" status="Anyone">FZ</Message></Annotation><v n="26" />Yesus ladhe nèdhi ina Na dhu titu ètu èèna, sama-sama dènge ja'a, Yohanis, nuka ana madhutu dhu Nèngu sue. Ka Yesus lii dènge ina Na, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ina. Nèngu ne, ana mu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus saw His mother was standing there, together with me, Yohanis, that disciple whom He loved. Then He told His mother, saying, “Mother. He here, is your child.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="27" />Hèia Yesus lii dènge ja'a, peka na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis. Nèti deo ne'e, tao laa nèngu sèmi ina èu!&gt;&gt; Ka karèi nèti lod'o èèna, ina Yesus pea dènge ja'a.<bt>And He told me, saying, “Yohanis. From now, consider her your-sg mother [+imperative, urging]!” So beginning from that day/time, Yesus' mother lived with me.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Mamadhe Lamatua Yesus<bt>The Lord Yesus' death</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:45-56; Markus 15:33-41; Lukas 23:44-49)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus ne'a le, na, Nèngu sab'a nare aa'i le sasab'a-la'a Na. Se'e se pamèci dènge aa'i-aa'i dhu suri ètu d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua karèi nèti uru ka. Hèia Yesus peka, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a koko-kamango.&gt;&gt;<bt>After that, Yesus knew that He had finished/completed all of His work/responsibilities/mission. That was in accord with everything the *Scriptures had written beforehand from long ago. Then Yesus said, “I'm thirsty.”</bt><note reference="19:28" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 69:22, 22:16</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ètu era ne'e abhu èi anggor manyilu ètu d'ara g'ala iiki cue. Ka sordad'u sèra rare ula ho cèb'u asa èi anggor, hèia èki<bt>There, there was sour (grape) wine in a small (clay) jug. So/and the soldiers took sea-sponge</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ula"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-01 03:24:23Z" status="Anyone">sea sponge</Message></Annotation><note reference="19:29" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani peka na, dhèu se lui ula ne ètu suu aj'u <span class="Italic">hussopos.</span> Aj'u <span class="Italic">hussopos</span> ne, dhèu Yahudi tema pake ètu d'ara acara ad'a, lula aj'u ne hèu mèngi. Aj'u ne madhera na pe dua nguru toke èpa nguru cm sa. Baca lula-nèti <span class="Italic">hussopos</span> buli <span class="Italic">Kalua nèti Masir</span> 12:22; <span class="Italic">Atora nèti Kètu Agama sèra</span> 14:4, 6, 49-52; <span class="Italic">Sensus</span> 19:2-6; (banding dènge <span class="Italic">Ibrani</span> 9:19); <span class="Italic">Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio</span> 51:7.<bt>The Yunani language says people poked that psonge on the tip of a <span class="Italic">hussopos</span> stick. <span class="Italic">Hussopos</span> is an aromatic wood that the Yahudi people normally use in several adat ceremonies. It's length is around 20-40cm. Read about <span class="Italic">hussopos</span> in <span class="Italic">Exit from Masir</span> 12:22; <span class="Italic">Priests Regulations</span> 14:4, 6, 49-52; <span class="Italic">Census List </span>19:2-6; (compare with <span class="Italic">Hebrews</span> 9:19); <span class="Italic">Praise Songs</span> 51:7.</bt></note>mi suu aj'u ca laa, ka j'ole asa hèb'a Na.<bt>and dipped it into that wine, and put/tied it on the end/tip of a stick/piece of wood, and stretched it up to His lips/mouth. [NOTE to daughter translations: it's really a sea sponge. Some lgs have a word for it that everybody knows. Use it. Picture of hyssop HK00114C.tif.]</bt><v n="30" />Ropa Yesus camuci nare, hèia Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Èle kèna.&gt;&gt; Hèia kètu Na loe, ka ma'ète a'ae.<bt>When Yesus had sucked (it), He spoke, saying, “It's done/finished/complete/accomplished.” Then His head drooped, and He stopped breathing. [NOTE: one standard euphemism for die]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="cud'u"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-01 03:29:52Z" status="Anyone">tondok</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sordad'u kèj'i Yesus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha [\s2]<bt>A soldier pierces Yesus on the cross [\s2]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhob'e "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-01 03:49:21Z" status="Anyone">lambung</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="31" />Lod'o èèna lèke hari Jumat. Madhutu atora agama, dhèu Yahudi hud'i sadia mema d'ara lod'o èèna, sèna ka bèli èèna rèngu soru lod'o sabaj'a ra. Nèti èèna ka, ro'o boe tèke eele ngi'u aae dhèu madhe, kadhoe tèke ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha lèke dènge lod'o sabaj'a. Te lod'o sabaj'a èèna, lod'o be'a. De ama-ama dhèu Yahudi manèngi gubernur, sèna ka pua dhèu lasi hake papadhe haga dhèu ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Dènge j'ara sèmi ne'e, rèngu madhe malai, ho dhèu bisa papuru ngi'u aae ra nèti aj'u palolo-palèbha ako lod'o aae era.<bt>That day fell on Friday. According to religious regulations, Yahudi people must prepare on that day, for the next day they greet their day of worship. That is why they don't want people's corpses to keep hanging on crosses on their day of worship. Cuz (elaboration) that day of worship is a special/good day. So (consequently) the leaders of the Yahudi people requested the gubernur to order people to hit/beat breaking the leg bones of the people on the crosses. In that way, they w/could die quickly, so that people could bring down their corpses from the cross while the sun still shone/still daylight.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="papadhe"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-01 03:52:25Z" status="Anyone">kasi patah</Message></Annotation><v n="32" />Hèia sordad'u se lasi asa era èèna. Ka ra hake papadhe uru haga dhèu dua sèra, dhu paku sama-sama dènge Yesus.<bt>So the soldiers went to that place. And they hit/beat breaking first the two people's leg bones, who they had nailed together with Yesus.</bt><v n="33" />Te ngaa ropa ra d'ai Yesus, rèdhi, na, Yesus dhu madhe le. Nèti èèna ka, rèngu hake papadhe boe haga Na.<bt>But when they arrived at Yesus, they saw He was already dead. That's why they did not hit breaking His leg bones.</bt><v n="34" />Te ngaa sordad'u ca dhèu nare kapoke na, hèia kèj'i d'ara karasa Yesus. Ka raa kalua, aa èi kalua kahèi.<bt>But one soldier took his spear, and pierced it into Yesus' side/ribs. Then3 blood came out, and water/liquid came out from Yesus' body. [NOTE to daughter translations: TB “lambung” (stomach) seems to have no support from Gk text, lexicons, other translations, or commentaries.] [CHECK words/options for side, because of noise from TB.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="madhob'e "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-01 04:10:57Z" status="Anyone">soft side between ribs and hips; kabake = abdomen (front) ; karasa = ribs (side) ; kakara = chest (human + animal) ; sangasa = (sternum) + collarbone</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="35" />(Ja'a ne'e ka dhu ladhe kèdhi dènge musi madha ku. Ja'a kèdhi aa'i, aa dhu ja'a suri ne lèke tare'a-re'a. Te ja'a ke'a mèu ngaa dhu ja'a lolo ne lèke mola-mola, sèna ka miu bisa parcaya lii padhai ja'a.)<bt>I here was an eye witness. I saw everything, and I write here what is true. Cuz (elaboration) I know what I am telling is really true, so that you-pl can believe/trust what I am saying.)</bt><v n="36" />J'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i j'aj'i, lula Sasuri Ama Lamatua dhu suri, na, &lt;&lt;Rui Na ca laa sa, padhe boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>All these things happened, because the *Scriptures write, saying, “His bones, there was not even one that was broken.”</bt><note reference="19:36" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Kalua nèti Masir 12:46, Sensus 9:12, Lii Sod'a Koa-Kio 34:21</note><v n="37" />Ètu era leo d'ara Sasuri Mola-Mèci ne, suri kahèi, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èèna rèngu ladhe rèdhi dhèu dhu ra kèj'i ne.&gt;&gt;<bt>At another place in those Scriptures, it also writes, saying, “They will look at that person whom they have pierced.”</bt><note reference="19:37" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Sakaria 12:10, Rai-haha Rupa Hiu 1:7</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ra padhane Lamatua Yesus<bt>They bury the Lord Yesus</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 27:57-61; Markus 15:42-47; Lukas 23:50-56)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="38" />Abhu dhèu èci ngara na Yusuf, nèti rae Arimatea. Nèngu ana madhutu Yesus kahèi. Te ngaa na madhutu pahuni-pahuni, lula madha'u dènge ama-ama dhèu Yahudi. Yusuf la'e asa gubernur Pilatus, manèngi ijin sèna ka bisa nèti ngi'u aae Yesus. Gubernur d'èi kahèi. Ka Yusuf la'e papuru ngi'u aae Yesus, hèia ded'e nèti.<bt>There was a person named Yusuf, from the village of Arimatea. He was also Yesus' disciple. But he followed secretly, because he was afraid of the leaders of the Yahudi people. Yusuf went to gubernur Pilatus, requesting permission to take away Yesus' corpse. The gubernur accepted. So Yusuf went and took down Yesus' corpse, and took it away.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="éeren: Joseph was a nobleman, so"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 01:46:07Z" status="Information">éeren: Joseph was a nobleman, so he probably had his servants get the body down off the cross and carry it to the tomb, maybe on a kind of stretcher. There was no casket LITERALLY: Now, Joseph of Arimathea was a secret disciple of Jesus, for fear of the Jews. He asked Pilate if he could take away Jesus' body, and Pilate gave him permission. So he came and took Jesus' body.<span class="Italic">(38) (40) (40) (40) </span>othoníois: pieces of linen cloth. Linen is woven from the fiber taken from flax stalks by beating out the soft stuff aroomátoon: spices, but in this case not used for food. The Greek word means "nice smelling things"LITERALLY: Then they took Jesus body, and wound it up in linen clothes with spices, as the Jewish burial custom is.</Message></Annotation><v n="39" />Nikodemus la'e sama-sama dènge Yusuf kahèi. Nikodemus ne'e ka dhu uru èèna la'e paraga dènge Yesus re mèda. Na hèli rampe ae titu kèna, pe d'ai tèlu nguru tèlu kilo sa, sèna ka tao mi ngi'u aae Yesus.<bt>Nikodemus also went together with Yusuf. Nikodemus was the one who had previously gone to meet Yesus at/by night. He bought a lot of burial.spices, around 33 kilos, to put on Yesus' corpse. [NOTE to daughter translations: TB ‘rempah-rempah’ is spices for food, not for corpses. :) // The weight called ‘kati’ in the TB is not known to educated eastern Indonesians.]</bt><note reference="19:39" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Lii Yunani peka, &lt;cangasu <span class="Italic">litras&gt;,</span> nuka 32,7 kilo. Rampe ne madhutu lii Yunani na, rèngu pab'ali dènge <span class="Italic">smurna</span> (nuka raa aj'u hèu mèngi) dènge <span class="Italic">aloe</span> (nuka raa nèti aj'u hèu mèngi, oe sèmi ai na'a sa). Baca lula-nèti Nikodemus ne ètu <span class="Italic">Yohanis </span>3:1-21.<bt>The Yunani language says, &lt;100 <span class="Italic">litras&gt;, </span>that is 32.7 kilos. Their burial.spices, the Yunani language says they mixed <span class="Italic">smurna</span> (that is the sap from an aromatic tree) and <span class="Italic">aloe</span> (that is the sap from an aromatic plant similar to crocodile tongue). Read about this Nikodemus is Yohanis 3:1-21.</bt></note><v n="40" />Hèia ra hèlu ngi'u aae Yesus dènge bèla halus. Ladhe hèlu ca tèka, ra tao rampe la'a. Rèngu tao sèmi ne'e, madhutu ad'a dhèu Yahudi ladhe padhane dhèu madhe.<bt>Then they wound around Yesus' corpse using fine cloth. Each time they folded/wrapped, they placed burial.spices first. They did that according to the Yahudi people's adat for burying dead people. [EXEG: Morris says “They put the spices between the folds.”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hèlu"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-01 04:26:35Z" status="Anyone">feo, wind, wrap around</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="41" />Kaj'èu boe nèti era Yesus madhe ne, abhu oka bunga cue. Ètu d'ara oka ne, dhèu heka pae rare ro'a dhèu madhe kèna. Ra padhane rèdhi mèka dhèu èci sa ètu d'ara ro'a èèna.<bt>Not far from that place where Yesus died, there was a flower garden/park. In that garden, people had just finished chiselling a grave. They had never buried a corpse in that grave.</bt><v n="42" />Lod'o èèna, lod'o sadia dhèu Yahudi ho soru lod'o sabaj'a ra, oe èle kèna. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu se tèke ngi'u aae Yesus ètu d'ara ro'a èèna, te era èèna kaj'èu boe.<bt>At that time, the Yahudi people's day for preparing to greet their day of worship was almost ended. That's why they stored/put away Yesus' corpse in that grave, cuz (elaboration) that place wasn't far.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus mamuri hari!<bt>The Lord Yesus lives again!</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 28:1-8; Markus 16:1-8; Lukas 24:1-12)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="20" />
      <v n="1" />Hari Migu, nuka lod'o partama ètu d'ara migu èèna. Mad'ae aae era, Maria nèti rae Magdala la'e asa ro'a Yesus. D'ai era èèna, ladhe nèdhi hadhu aae dhu pake katange ro'a, hari eele nèti era na.<bt>Sunday, that is the first day in that week, very early in the morning (around first glimpse of light), Maria from the village of Magdala went to Yesus' grave. Arriving there, she saw the big stone that they had used to close/cover that grave, was already removed from its place.</bt><v n="2" />Hèia na rai lèpa hari la'e paraga dènge Simon Petrus aa dènge ja'a, nuka ana madhutu dhu Yesus sue, ka na peka, &lt;&lt;Dhèu mana'u rèti le Lamatua èdhi nèti ro'a Na! Te'a boe rèngu tèke Ne ètu mia!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then she ran back to meet with Simon Petrus, and me, that is Yesus' disciple whom He loved, and spoke, saying, “People have stolen taken our-inc Lord from His grave! We-exc don't know where they put/placed Him!” [EXEG: Carson, Morris.]</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01852b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Ka ja'a dènge Petrus rai la'a asa era ro'a èèna.<bt>Then I and Petrus ran to the location of that grave.</bt><v n="4" />Ji'i rai palere-lere, te ngaa ja'a malai risi, ka d'ai uuru ro'a èèna.<bt>We-exc ran together, but I ran faster, and arrived at the grave sooner/first.</bt><v n="5" />Te ngaa laku boe asa d'ara ro'a, dhoka patigi nèti li'u di. Ètu d'ara ro'a, ja'a ladhe kèdhi bèla halus dhu ra pake hèlu mi ngi'u aae Yesus.<bt>But I didn't go inside the grave. I only scrutinised (inside) from outside. [NOTE: /patigi/ implies squinting, craning, or bending to scrutinise, often around the edge of a barrier, so the team and UNS's felt that making 'bending' explicit here would be overtranslating.] Inside the grave, I saw the fine cloth which they had used to wrap/wind up Yesus' corpse.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Te ngaa ropa Petrus d'ai, la'e dènge asa d'ara. Nèdhi bèla halus dhu ètu èèna kahèi.<bt>But when Petrus arrived there, he went straight inside. He also saw that fine cloth that was there.</bt><v n="7" />Nèdhi kahèi lesu dhu ra pahutu kètu Yesus. Te ngaa lesu ne dhu lèpe ètu era leo nèti bèla halus ne.<bt>He also saw a handkerchief/square cloth (assimilated Portuguese loan), which they had used to cover Yesus' head. But that handkerchief was separated in a different place from that fine cloth.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lesu "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-02 00:45:43Z" status="Anyone">lencu</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="lèpe"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-02 00:47:56Z" status="Anyone">lipat</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Hèia ja'a, dhu d'ai uuru ro'a, maso madhutu kahèi asa d'ara. Ropa ladhe kèdhi aa'i-aa'i se, ka ja'a parcaya lii padhadha dhu uru èèna Yesus peka mema, na, bèli-camèd'a Nèngu mamuri hari nèti mamadhe Na.<bt>Then I, who earlier had arrived at the grave first, also followed going inside. When I saw all that, I also believed what Yesus had detailed previously, that, later He was going to live again from His death.</bt><v n="9" />Te lod'o èèna, ji'i dhu j'aj'i ana madhutu Na, dhae nge'a mèka sasoa nèti isi Sasuri Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua, dhu suri mema, peka na, Kristus hud'i mamuri hari ku nèti mamadhe Na.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) at that time, we-exc who were His disciples did not yet understand the meaning/significance of the Scriptures which had written beforehand, saying, Kristus must live again from His death.</bt><v n="10" />Èle ka, ji'i dua mi lèpa.<bt>After that, the two of us-exc went home.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pad'elo ngi'u Na mi Maria nèti rae Magdala [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus shows Himself to Maria from the village of Magdala [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 28:9-10; Markus 16:9-11)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Te ngaa Maria titu era ètu li'u ro'a èèna. Nèngu tangi taruu. Ka na patigi asa d'ara ro'a ne, aa na tangi era.<bt>But Maria still stood outside that grave. She kept crying. While she was still crying, she scrutinised into that grave. [NOTE: Again, /patigi/ implies squinting, craning, or bending to scrutinise, so the team and UNS's felt that making 'bending' explicit here would be overtranslating.]</bt><v n="12" />Ladhe nèdhi ana pajuu Ama Lamatua nèti sorga dhèu dua. Ana pajuu se, pake mèdha-papake pudhi. Dua ra madhèdi ètu era dhu ca lod'o ni dhèu paj'unu ngi'u aae Yesus. Ca dhèu madhèdi re era kètu, aa èci hari dhu madhèdi re era haga.<bt>She saw two of God's *angels. They were wearing white clothes. The two of them were sitting in the place where day-before-yesterday people had laid down Yesus' corpse. One was sitting at the place of the head, and the other was sitting at the place of the feet.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ca lod'o ni"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-02 01:09:35Z" status="Anyone">kemaren dolu</Message></Annotation><v n="13" />Ana pajuu se karèi Maria, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka èu tangi?&gt;&gt;<bt>The *angels asked her, saying, “Why are you crying?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Maria dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a tangi, lula dhèu ded'e rèti ngi'u aae Lamatua ja'a. Te ngaa ke'a boe ra tèke Ne ètu mia.&gt;&gt;<bt>So Maria responded, saying, “I am crying, because they have lifted taking my Master's corpse. But I don't know where they have stored Him.”</bt><v n="14" />Ropa na padhai lii nare, nèngu kabib'a asa li'u. Ka ladhe nèdhi ca dhèu dhu titu ètu èèna, te ngaa ne'a boe, na, Dhèu ne, nuka Yesus.<bt>When she finished speaking, she turned to look outside. And she saw there was a person standing there, but she didn't know that Person was Yesus.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Hèia Yesus karèi ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Nga tao ka èu tangi? Te èu tenge cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yesus asked her, saying, “Why are you crying? Cuz (elaboration) who are you (older sister) looking for?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Maria pangee, na, Nèngu ne dhèu madhenga oka. Ka Maria pamako dhèu ne, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama. Ladhe ama ka ded'e mèti ngi'u aae Na, peka ku laa, ama tèke Ne ètu mia. Hud'i laa laku ded'e kèti Ne asa era leo, sèna ka padhane Ne pabe'a-be'a. Sue laa, ama!&gt;&gt;<bt>Maria thought He was just a gardener. So Maria coaxed/pursuaded/urged him, saying, “Father. If you have lifted taking His corpse, na, please tell me where you have stored Him. [+polite imperative] Let me take Him to a different place to bury (Him) well/properly. Please! [Lit: have pity, father]”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ka Yesus paroa ne, peka na, &lt;&lt;Maria.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus called her, saying, “Maria.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia na kabèli ladhe asa Yesus, ka na lii, aku nèngu na, <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Raboni!&gt;&gt;</span> (Lii Aram, sasoa na, &lt;&lt;Mese ja'a!&gt;&gt;)<bt>And she turned to face (bodily) Yesus, saying, <span class="Italic">&lt;&lt;Raboni!&gt;&gt;</span> (In the Aram language, it means, “My Teacher!”) [EXEG: Contrast with 1:38 Rabbi ‘teacher’ vs. Rabboni ‘my teacher’ (LN). It came up because we were challenged on glossing the two. They were the same in an earlier draft.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Baku g'ag'e ku Ja'a, te Ja'a dhae ca'e mèka laku asa Ama Ku ètu sorga. Te ngaa lamu uuru ku peka dènge angalai Ja'a sèra, na, &lt;Ja'a neo ca'e laku asa Ama Ku. Nèngu èèna, Ama miu kahèi. Nèngu èèna, Ama Lamatua Ja'a. De Nèngu, Ama Lamatua miu kahèi.&gt;&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus told her, saying, “Don't touch Me, cuz (elaboration) I have not yet ascended to My Father in heaven. But go now, to tell My friends/companions, saying, ‘I am going to ascend to My Father. He is also your-pl Father. He is My God. So (consequently) He is also your God.’”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Èle ka, Maria, dhèu Magdala èèna, la'e lolo dènge ana madhutu Yesus sèra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a paraga le dènge Lamatua èdhi, Yesus!&gt;&gt; Ka na peka dènge rèngu lii moa Yesus.<bt>After that, Maria of Magdala went to tell/narrate to Yesus disciples, saying, “I have met with our-inc Master, Yesus!” And she told Yesus' message/instructions to them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pad'elo iisi mi ana madhutu Na [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus shows himself to His disciples [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Parallel Passage Reference" usfm="r">(Mateos 28:16-20; Markus 16:14-18; Lukas 24:36-49)</p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Lod'o èèna, lèke dènge hari Migu, nuka lod'o partama ètu d'ara migu èèna. Lod'o heka cèna kèna, ka ana madhutu Yesus pakaboko. Rèngu patèke babèdho èmu ne pa'èra-èra, lula rèngu madha'u dènge ama-ama dhèu Yahudi. Re'a rare boe, na, Yesus titu ètu talora aae rèngu, ka Na lii, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Saloom!&gt;&gt;<bt>That day fell on Sunday, that is the first day in that week. The sun had just gone down, and Yesus' disciples were gathered. They had locked up tight the doors of the house, because they were afraid of the Yahudi peoples' leaders. Then unexpectedly Yesus stood in their midst, and spoke, saying, “Saloom!”</bt><v n="20" />Ropa Yesus padhai lii nare dènge rèngu sèmi èèna, hèia Na pad'elo nu'a dhu ètu kacui-aai dènge karasa Na. Ana madhutu Na karej'e titu kèna, ropa ladhe rèdhi Lamatua rèngu.<bt>When Yesus finished greeted them like that, He showed those wounds which were in His hands and His side/ribs. His disciples were too happy/overjoyed when they saw their Master. [NOTE to daughter translations: Dhao and other lgs here distinguish lexically between ‘fresh wounds’ and ‘old wounds’. Gk in vs. 27 say “put your hand ‘into’ my side”, that leans it toward a fresh wound that does not have skin healed over.]</bt><v n="21" />Ka Yesus peka dènge rèngu, na, &lt;&lt;Hud'i laa miu mamuri dame dènge mera-milu. Sanèd'e, te Ama Ku pua-paleha Ja'a tasamia, na, Ja'a pua-paleha miu sèmi èèna kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told them, saying, “May you-pl be in good relationships and safe/calm. Remember, how My Father sent/commissioned (doublet) Me, na, I also send/commission you-pl like that.” [EXEG: see extensive discussion in Carson. He concludes in the context of John's gospel it is primarily about “unqualified obedience to and dependence upon their Lord”; “Peace” in sense #1 (context of fear and locked doors, not of broken relationships).]</bt><v n="22" />Padhai lii nare sèmi èèna, ka Na ara padètu la'e asa rèngu, hèia Na tiu a'ae Na mi rèngu èci-èci. Hèia Na padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a pangèd'u miu Roh Lamatua dhu Mola-Mèci. Sèmi mere Ne.<bt>After He finished speaking like that, He came nearer/close to them, and blew His breath on each of them. Then He said, “I give God2's Clean/Holy/Pure Spirit to you. Receive Him.</bt><v n="23" />De, ladhe miu pabhèlu eele sasala dhèu, na, sasala ne ele le, te Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala èèna kahèi. Te ngaa ladhe miu mo'o boe pabhèlu eele sasala dhèu, na, Lamatua saku eele boe sasala sèra kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>So (consequently), if/when you completely forget (=deliberate forgiveness1) a person's wrong/sin/fault, na, that wrong is gone (disappeared completely), cuz (elaboration) God2 has already wiped away (forgiveness2) those wrongs. But if you do not want to completely forget a person's wrong, na, God2 also doesn't wipe away that wrong.”</bt><note reference="20:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Mateos 16:19, 18:18</note></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus dènge Tomas [\s2]<bt>The Lord Yesus and Tomas [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ca dhèu nèti ana madhutu Yesus canguru dua sèra, ngara na Tomas. Ra pangare na, &lt;ana kembar&gt; kahèi. Ropa Yesus pad'elo iisi Na dènge ana madhutu dhu leo sèra, Tomas aad'o.<bt>There was one of Yesus' twelve disciples, named Tomas. They also referred to him as ‘twin’ (loan). When Yesus showed himself to the other disciples, Tomas was not there.</bt><v n="25" />Nèti èèna ka, ropa angalai na sèra peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Ji'i paraga le dènge Lamatua èdhi,&gt;&gt; hèia Tomas dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Sèmi ne'e. Ja'a hud'i ladhe kèdhi ku nu'a era paku sèra ètu kacui-aai Na, aa pamaso ai ja'a asa nu'a ètu d'ara karasa Na. Ladhe ja'a tao mèka sèmi èèna, ja'a bisa mèka parcaya, na, Nèngu mamuri hari le.&gt;&gt;<bt>That's why when his friends/companions said to him, “We-exc have met our-inc Master,” Thomas responded, saying, “It's like this. I must first see those wounds from the nail places in His hands. And I must put my finger into that wound in His side. If I have not yet done that, na, I'm not yet able to believe that He has come back to life.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ca migu hari, ka ana madhutu Yesus sama-sama dènge Tomas ètu d'ara èmu cue. Masi ka babèdho dhu patèke, te ngaa Yesus maso asa d'ara, titu ètu talora aae rèngu. Ka Na hia lii maho'o dènge ra, peka na, &lt;&lt;Saloom!&gt;&gt;<bt>One week later, Yesus' disciples were together with Tomas in one house. Even though the doors were locked, nevertheless Yesus entered inside, standing in their midst. He greeted them, saying, “Saloom!” [EXEG: NRSV, CEV, Carson.]</bt><v n="27" />Hèia Na padhai lii dènge Tomas, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;J'ole kacui-aai èu mai, ho g'ag'e kacui-aai Ja'a ne. Aa mai g'ag'e nu'a ètu d'ara karasa Ja'a ne. Parcaya ka, na, Ja'a ne mamuri hari le! Core eele ka d'ara parcaya boe èu èèna.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He spoke to Tomas, saying, “Stretch/scoot your-sg hand here, to touch My hands now/here. Then come (invitation) touch this wound in My side. Believe that I have come back to life [+imperative]! Get rid of that feeling/perception of not believing of yours.” [EXEG: NLT, Carson.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />Tomas dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii, Ama, ee! Ja'a heka lèka tare'a-re'a kèna! Ama ne, Kètu ja'a, aa Ama Lamatua ja'a kahèi!&gt;&gt;<bt>Tomas responded, saying, “Ira ii, Father, ee! [+amazement] Now I really believe! You (Father) here, are my Head, and also my God!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="29" />Ka Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Tomas! Èu parcaya, na, Ja'a mamuri hari le, lula èu mèdhi le Ja'a dènge musi madha èu unu mu. Te ngaa dhu oto risi ka, nuka dhèu dhu rèdhi boe Ja'a, te ngaa ra parcaya.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Yesus told him, saying, “Tomas! You believe that I have come back to life, because you have seen Me with your own eyeballs. But even more fortunate are the people who have not/do not see Me, but they believe.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Naneo Yohanis suri sasuri ne<bt>The purpose of Yohanis writing this book</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="30" />Yesus tao tadha malaa dhu leo ae-ae kahèi, dhu ja'a suri boe ètu d'ara sasuri ne. Ana madhutu Na ladhe rèdhi tadha malaa se'e dènge musi madha rèngu unu ra.<bt>Yesus also did many other amazing signs, that I have not written in this book/writing. His disciples saw those amazing signs with their own eyeballs.</bt><v n="31" />Te ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu ja'a suri ètu d'ara sasuri ne, sèna ka miu parcaya, na,<bt>But all the things/matters/events/issues I have written in this book here, are so that you-pl would/could believe that,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Yesus ne, Kristus dhu Ama Lamatua padhadha tèke hia mai.<bt>Yesus is Kristus whom God had promised beforehand to send coming.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Yesus ne, Ana Ama Lamatua kahèi.<bt>Yesus is also God's Child.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Aa ropa miu parcaya Ne, miu abhu mamuri dhu lèke dhu ma'ète boe, lula miu j'aj'i dhèu unu Nèngu.<bt>And when you-pl believe in Him, you get/obtain real life that never ends, because you have become His people.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus pad'elo iisi mi ana madhutu Na dhèu pidhu<bt>The Lord Yesus shows himself to seven of His disciples</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="21" />
      <v n="1" />Èle pèri-pèri lod'o, ka Yesus pad'elo hari iisi Na ètu sebhe dano Tiberias. Lii lolo na, sèmi ne'e ka:<bt>After several days, Yesus showed himself again at the edge of lake Tiberias. The story is like this:</bt><v n="2" />Lod'o èèna, ana madhutu Yesus, dhèu pidhu dhu pakaboko. Rèngu se, nuka:<bt>At that time seven of Yesus' disciples were gathered. They were:</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Simon Petrus,<bt>Simon Petrus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Tomas, dhu ra pangare ne, &lt;ana kembar&gt;,<bt>Tomas, whom they call/named ‘twin’,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Natanel, nèti rae Kana ètu propensi Galilea,<bt>Natanel, from the village of Kana in the province of Galilea,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">ana dhèu dua nèti Sabadeus,<bt>Sabadeus' two children/offspring,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dènge ana madhutu Yesus dhu leo dhèu dua.<bt>and two of Yesus' other disciples.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Simon Petrus peka dènge angalai na se'e, &lt;&lt;Ja'a neo laku pèku i'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Simon Petrus told his friends/companions, saying, “I'm going to throw out the dragnet.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia angalai na se'e dhaa, aku rèngu na, &lt;&lt;Oo! Ji'i la'a kahèi.&gt;&gt; Ka lasi asa sebhe dano. Hèia ca'e koha lasi tenge i'a. Te ngaa mèda èèna rèngu rara boe ngaa-ngaa.<bt>And his companions responded, saying, “Oo! [+agreement, affirmation] We-exc will go too.” So they went to the edge of the lake. Then they got in a boat to go look for fish. But that night they didn't get anything.</bt><note reference="21:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 5:5</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Asa bèli mad'ae aae èèna, Yesus titu ètu sebhe dano ne. Te ngaa ana madhutu Na sèra re'a boe, na, Nèngu ne, Yesus.<bt>The next morning, Yesus was standing at the edge of the lake. But His disciples didn't know that He was Yesus.</bt><v n="5" />Ka Na pa'oo, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mera i'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He called out/shouted/yelled (message) to ask them, saying, “Did you get fish, or (not)?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia ra dhaa, peka na, &lt;&lt;Mola-mèu lao! Ci'u sa, aad'o hèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>They responded, saying, “Empty (idiom: straight-clear ??)! We didn't even get one tail (counter for fish).”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Ka Yesus peka dènge ra, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Lolo sèku pèku miu asa cabèka koha èèna. Pe miu abhu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Then He told them, saying, “Have a try at letting out the dragnet on the other side of the boat. Then you'll get (some).” [EXEG: “right side” to “other side” (explicit to implicit-naturalness in context). Boats aren't talked about as right and left.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Lolo"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-05-13 03:50:39Z" status="Anyone">lolo1 = ceritera ; lolo2 = 1) ulur (jaring) ; let out ; 2) bentangkan benang</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka rèngu tao madhutu kahèi. Ka ra abhu i'a ae titu kèna, toke rèngu bisa boe ère rare pèku ne asa dedha koha.<bt>Then they did that. And they got a great many fish, to the point that they couldn't pull that dragnet back up into the boat.</bt><note reference="21:6" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lukas 5:6</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Aa ja'a ètu èèna kahèi. Ja'a ne, ana madhutu dhu Yesus sue. Ka ja'a peka dènge Petrus, na, &lt;&lt;Ira ii! Nèngu nèi, Lamatua èdhi!&gt;&gt;<bt>And I was also there. I am the disciple that Yesus loved. So, I told Petrus, saying, “Ira ii! [+amazment, awe] He (yonder) is our-inc Master!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ropa tadèngi nare lii ja'a deo na, hèia Simon Petrus pake hari kodho na, ka ridhu asa d'ara dano, sèna ka nangi asa dae.<bt>Hearing what I just said, Simon Petrus put his shirt/clothes back on, and lept into the lake to swim to shore/land. [DISCOURSE: put back on implies he had taken off, so “naked” is explicit to implicit. CHECKed w/UNS.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pasoa"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-02 03:00:56Z" status="Anyone">lompat ; ridhu = terjun</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te koha ne kaj'èu nèti dae pe d'ai cangasu meter sa. Hèia angalai na kao koha asa dae, todhe dènge pèku dhu pènu dènge i'a deo sa.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) that boat was around only 100 meters from shore/land. So/then his friends paddled the boat back to shore, and they were towing that dragnet which was full of fish.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kao"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-02 03:02:31Z" status="Anyone">1) paddle dayung (pake sehe ‘paddle’); 2) garuk (scratch) ; tuku = row (pulling) (pake tatuku ‘oar’) ; tob'e = push (pake tatob'a ‘pole’) ; todhe = towing ; cabili = purse over shoulder</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Ropa rèngu d'ai dae, hèia rèdhi ai karoo, dènge i'a dhu ra paga. Aa abhu roti kahèi.<bt>When they arrived on land/shore, they saw there was a fire of coals burning there, with fish roasting/broiling on top. And there was also bread.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paga"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-02 03:09:53Z" status="Anyone">panggang ; ai karoo = bara api</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Yesus lii dènge ra, &lt;&lt;Mèti ku i'a osa miu d'ai ciki sa, dhu miu heka pèku mere deo na.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus told them, saying, “Bring some/a few fish from what you-pl just caught.”</bt></p>
    <fig path="Cook\CNT\cn01877b.tif" rtfFormat="width:6.5cm;textWrapping:around;horizontalPosition:right" />
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ka Simon Petrus ca'e hari asa dedha koha, ho ère pa'eta pèku ne asa dae. Pèku ne dhu pènu dènge i'a aae, cangasu lèmi nguru tèlu ngi'u. Masi ka i'a ae sèmi èèna, te ngaa pèku ne mae boe ciki sa hèi.<bt>Then Simon Petrus got back in the boat, to pull/drag net into shore. The dragnet was full of large fish, 153 tails [fish counter]. Even though there were so many fish, nevertheless that dragnet didn't tear at all. [CHECK pa'eta]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'eta "><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-02 03:12:19Z" status="Anyone">kasi kandas ; kaha'i mae boe ciki sa ; kaha'i = 1) kain lap, 2) bagian sisa dari makanan dll</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="12" />Ka Yesus paroa si, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai mi'a ka!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus called/summoned them, saying, “Come on, and (2p) eat!”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Rèngu dhu re'a le, na, Nèngu ne Lamatua rèngu, ka ra bani boe karèi Ne, na, &lt;&lt;Ama ne, cee?&gt;&gt;<bt>They already knew/understood that He was their Master. That is why none of them dared to ask Him, saying, “Who are You, Father?”</bt><v n="13" />Hèia Yesus nare roti dènge i'a, nèti hia si.<bt>Then Yesus took the bread and fish, and went to give (it) to them.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ne'e ne, ka tèlu hari kèna Yesus pad'elo iisi Na mi ana madhutu Na sèra, ropa Na mamuri hari nèti mamadhe Na.<bt>That was the third time Yesus showed Himself to His disciples, when He had come back to life from His death.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Lamatua Yesus padhai lii dènge Petrus<bt>The Lord Yesus speaks with Petrus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Ropa ra'a-rinu rare, Yesus karèi Simon Petrus, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Hee, Simon ana Yohanis. Tasamia? Èu sue Ja'a risi nèti angalai se sue Ja'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>[EXEG: see Carson (on whole passage).] When they had finished eating, Yesus asked Simon Petrus, saying, “Eh, Simon, Yohanis' child. How about it? Do you-sg love Me more than these friends/companions love Me, or (what)?” [CEV]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Petrus dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a Ama! Èu dhu me'a ja'a sue Èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, “True, Father! You know that I love You.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus peka, na, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, na, madhenga paie ana kahib'i-kalèbho Ja'a, sèna ka rèngu abhu ra'a-rinu.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus instructed him, saying, “If that's the case, na, herd/shepherd well My lambs (sheep offspring) so they get food.” [EXEG: agapáais ... philéis: probably not a strong distinction in words for “love”, even though it is possible to read quite a bit into the passage. (See also Carson: on Exegetical Fallacies).]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Hèia Yesus karèi hari, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Simon, ana Yohanis. Tasamia? Èu sue Ja'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus asked him again, saying, “Simon, Yohanis' child. How about it? Do you-sg love Me, or (what)?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka na dhaa, na, &lt;&lt;Tare'a Ama! Èu dhu me'a ja'a sue Èu.&gt;&gt;<bt>He responded, saying, “True, Father! You know that I love You.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Ka Yesus peka hari dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, na, ladhe-leru paie-iie kahib'i-kalèbho Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus spoke to him again, saying, “If that's the case, care for/raise/look after the needs of (doublet) My sheep well.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="17" />Èle èèna ka, Yesus karèi hari Petrus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Simon, ana Yohanis. Tasamia? Èu ne, angalai Ja'a, do?&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus asked Petrus again, saying, “Simon, Yohanis' child. How about it? Are you-sg My friend/companion, or (what)?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia d'ara Petrus susa titu kèna, lula Yesus karèi ne d'ai tèlu hari, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èu sue Ja'a, do?&gt;&gt; Ka na dhaa, aku nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Ama dhu me'a aa'i j'ara. De Ama dhu me'a le, na, ja'a ne angalai Ama.&gt;&gt;<bt>And Petrus' insides were really troubled, because Yesus had asked three time, saying, “Do you love Me, or (what)?” So he responded, saying, “Father, You know everything. So (consequently) You already know that I am Your friend.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus peka dènge ne, &lt;&lt;Ladhe sèmi èèna, na, ladhe-leru paie kahib'i-kalèbho Ja'a se, sèna ka rèngu abhu ra'a-rinu.<bt>Then Yesus told him, saying, “If that's the case, na, look after the needs of (doublet) My sheep well so they get food.</bt><v n="18" />Èu dhane more le naneo Ja'a, do? Ja'a neo peka sèmi ne'e: uru èèna lod'o èu ngèru era, èu tema pake unu mu kodho dènge dhara hake, ho lamu asa mia-mia madhutu dad'èi èu. Te ngaa ètu d'ara heka, èu j'ole kacui-aai ho dhèu èki, pake dhara hake èu unu mu. Hèia ra ère rèti èu asa era dhu èu d'èi boe.&gt;&gt;<bt>Have you caught My meaning/purpose? I also want to tell/explain like this: previously, when you-sg were still young, na, you normally put on clothes, and wore a belt/waist tie, then you went off wherever, according to your desire. But later when you are already old, you will stretch out your hand(s) for (purpose/result) other people to tie/bind them, using your own belt/waist tie. Then they will pull/drag you to a place where you don't want to go.” [EXEG: Carson “stretch out your hands was understood in the ancient world: it widely referred to crucifixion”. Morris “there is evidence that the stretching forth of the hands was held in the early church to refer to crucifixion.”]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="dhane"><Message author="Chuck Grimes" created="2011-04-02 03:40:59Z" status="Anyone">mengerti, camkan</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />(Lii padhai Yesus ne, peka mi Petrus, lula-nèti ngaa dhu j'aj'i bèli-camèd'a mi dedha nèngu. Te èèna na mamadhe Petrus pad'elo dadedha Ama Lamatua.)<bt>(Yesus spoke like that to tell Petrus about what would later happen to him. Cuz (elaboration) later Petrus' death showed God's *glory/high-ness.) [BACKGROUND: Carson “Peter had glorified God by his martyrdom, probably in Rome, under the emperor Nero. Extra-biblical sources for the event are not strong. Clement of Rome (c. AD 96) mentions Peter's martyrdom but does not reveal what form it took (1 Clement 5:4). Writing about AD 212, Tertullian affirms that it was when Peter was bound to the cross that he was girded by someone else ... Later accounts of Peter asking to be crucified upside down, because he felt unworthy to be crucified as his Lord was, are too remote and too infected with legendary accretions to be reliable.” Carlton (TRT) Suggested FOOTNOTE: According to tradition, about 30 years later (around A.D. 64-65) Peter was crucified upside down. He felt unworthy to be crucified in the same position that Jesus was crucified.]</bt><note reference="21:19" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Pe d'ara tèu 96M, ca dhèu ama gareja ngara na Klement nèti kota Roma, dhu suri, na, dhèu pamadhe Petrus. Pe d'ara tèu 212M sa, abhu ca dhèu ama gareja èci hari, ngara na Tertulian, dhu suri, na, rèngu paku Petrus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha. Aa abhu kahèi lii lolo èci nèti gareja dhu peka na, lod'o ra paku Petrus ètu aj'u palolo-palèbha, ele boe d'ara tèu 64-65M, Petrus manèngi sèna ka paku ne kètu asa haha. Na manèngi sèmi èèna, lula nèngu rasa pantas boe madhe kètu asa dedha sama sèmi Yesus.<bt>Around the year 96M (A.D.), there was a church leader, named Klement from the city of Roma, who wrote saying, people had killed Petrus. Around the year 212M, there was another church leader, named Tertulian, who wrote saying, they nailed hanging Petrus on a cross. And there is also another story in the church that says, when they were about to nail hanging Petrus on a cross around the years 64-65M, Petrus asked them to hang him with his head down. That was because he did not feel he was worthy to die with his head above/up, like Yesus.</bt></note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Hèia Yesus lii dènge Petrus, aku Nèngu na, &lt;&lt;Mai sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu Ja'a!&gt;&gt;<bt>Then Yesus told Petrus, saying, “Come and be My person!” [EXEG: Carson, HCE]</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana madhutu dhu j'aj'i ana pasue Yesus<bt>The disciple whom Yesus loved</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Lod'o èèna, Petrus kabib'a asa kabodho. Ka ladhe nèdhi ja'a dhu re limuri madhutu rèngu dua ra. Ja'a ne, nuka ana madhutu dhu Yesus sue. Ja'a dhu madhèdi ètu baboa Yesus, lod'o ji'i nga'a kalela Paska. Ja'a ne ka dhu karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Cee ka dhu neo pahie Ama?&gt;&gt;<bt>At that time, Petrus turned to look back. And he saw me following behind the two of them. I here, am the disciple whom Yesus loved. I am also the one who sat beside Yesus while we-exc were sitting eating the Paska feast. I am the one who asked Him, saying, “Father! Who is it that will sell of (betray) You?”</bt><note reference="21:20" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 13:25</note><v n="21" />Ropa Petrus ladhe nèdhi ja'a, hèia na karèi Yesus, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama! Deo na Ama peka-padhai le lula-nèti ja'a ne. Te ngaa tasamia dènge nèngu hari?&gt;&gt;<bt>When Petrus saw me, he asked Yesus, saying, “Father! You have spoken (doublet) about me earlier. But what about him?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Yesus b'ala lii Petrus, na, &lt;&lt;Urusan èu aad'o ètu èèna. Ladhe Ja'a neo sèna ka nèngu mate mi era ne'e toke Ja'a mai hari, na, sala ngaa? Dhu lèke ka èu hud'i sanèd'e ku lii moa dhu Ja'a peka deo na, nuka: mai sèna ka j'aj'i dhèu Ja'a.&gt;&gt;<bt>Yesus responded to Petrus, saying, “That is not your business. If it is My will for him to just wait here until I come back, what's the problem? The important thing is you must remember what I instructed you earlier, that is, come and be My person.”</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="23" />Lula Yesus padhai lii sèmi èèna, ka ana madhutu Na dhu leo sèra papeka, na, &lt;&lt;Yohanis ne, bèli-camèd'a madhe boe.&gt;&gt; Aa te ngaa Yesus padhai lii boe sèmi èèna. Dhu Na peka, na, &lt;&lt;Urusan èu aad'o ètu èèna. Ladhe Ja'a neo sèna ka nèngu mate mi era ne'e toke Ja'a mai hari, na, sala ngaa?&gt;&gt;<bt>Because Yesus spoke like that, His other disciples began to speak (among themselves), saying, “That Yohanis is not going to die.” Whereas in fact, Yesus did not say that. What He said was, “That is not your business. If it is My will for him to just wait here until I come back, what's the problem?”</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis pa'èle sasuri na<bt>Yohanis closes/ends his writing</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />Ana madhutu dhu Yesus peka èèna, nuka ja'a ne, Yohanis. Ja'a ka lole se aa'i-aa'i hia miu. Ja'a ka dhu kèdhi dènge musi madha ja'a unu ku. Ja'a ka suri aa'i-aa'i se. Ka èdhi te'a, na, ngaa dhu ja'a lole hia miu se, lèke tare'a-re'a.<bt>That disciple whom Yesus was talking about, that was me, Yohanis. I am the one who has told/narrated all these things to you-pl. I am the one who saw (them) with my own eyeballs. so I am the one who wrote everything. And we-inc already know that what I have told you is really true.</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="25" />Abhu j'ara leo ae era dhu Yesus tao. Ladhe dhèu neo suri aa'i mèu-mèu, karèi nèti Yesus pakako sasab'a-la'a Na toke èle, ja'a ngee na buku se pènu risi rai-haha ne.<bt>And there are still many other things that Yesus did. If a person tried to write everything, beginning from Yesus starting to carry out His work until the end/completed, I think/imagine that the books would more than fill the whole world.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">D'ai sange ne'e ka,<bt>That's it up to here,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Yohanis<bt>Yohanis</bt></p>
  </book>
</bible>